(function () {
  var C = {"lh-sec-l1-01":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L1-01: What “security” means at work</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-01</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Define security as managed risk to information and systems, not “locks on everything.”<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Security is a business function; you align controls to impact and regulation.<br><strong>Core ideas:</strong> Threats exploit vulnerabilities; controls reduce likelihood or impact; residual risk remains.<br><strong>Kali lab (10 min):</strong> Open a terminal. Run <code>whoami</code>, <code>id</code>, <code>uname -a</code>. In one paragraph, explain which account type you are using and why admin/root is risky for daily browsing.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-01</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>At Level 1, think like an analyst who must <strong>classify</strong> an event: asset, threat, vulnerability, control, residual risk. If you can narrate those five words for any headline topic, you are aligned with how writers build scenario questions.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 1 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>CVE</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures identifier for a specific flaw—pairs with CVSS severity and vendor advisories for prioritization.</dd><dt><strong>Metrics that matter</strong></dt><dd>Mean time to detect/remediate with quality, coverage of critical assets, and control effectiveness—not vanity ticket counts.</dd><dt><strong>Salt (crypto)</strong></dt><dd>Random input to a password hash to defeat rainbow tables—must be unique per password.</dd><dt><strong>OODA loop (IR)</strong></dt><dd>Observe-orient-decide-act—adversary and defender both iterate; faster, accurate decisions beat hoarding data.</dd><dt><strong>Exploit</strong></dt><dd>A technique or code that takes advantage of a vulnerability to achieve an attacker goal (exfiltration, persistence, disruption).</dd><dt><strong>NAT (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Rewrites addresses/ports for traversal—security relevance includes logging visibility, port forwarding risks, and split tunnel implications for inspection.</dd><dt><strong>Injection</strong></dt><dd>Untrusted input becomes part of a command or query—parameterized queries, input validation, and context escaping are core defenses.</dd><dt><strong>GRC</strong></dt><dd>Governance, risk, and compliance—align security decisions with law, policy, and business appetite; audits test design and operation.</dd><dt><strong>Data loss prevention (DLP)</strong></dt><dd>Content-aware controls to block or alert on sensitive data movement—policy + tech, tuned to avoid blocking work.</dd><dt><strong>NetFlow / IPFIX</strong></dt><dd>Flow metadata for volume and anomaly detection—lighter than PCAP but less payload visibility.</dd><dt><strong>Chain of custody</strong></dt><dd>Documented handling of evidence from collection through presentation—hashing, write blockers, and access logs support admissibility.</dd><dt><strong>Authorization</strong></dt><dd>What an authenticated subject is allowed to do—RBAC/ABAC, scopes, and server-side checks enforce least privilege.</dd><dt><strong>PKI</strong></dt><dd>Public Key Infrastructure—CAs, RAs, CRL/OCSP, and certificate lifecycle; mis-issuance or weak validation breaks trust chains.</dd><dt><strong>IAM least privilege</strong></dt><dd>Grant minimum API/console rights; prefer roles over long-lived keys; audit risky admin-equivalent paths regularly.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>IR phase</th><th>What you do there (exam shorthand)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Prepare</strong></td><td>Playbooks, contacts, tooling, baseline logging—before the pager fires.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detect &amp; analyze</strong></td><td>Scope, timelines, hypotheses—preserve volatile evidence early.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Contain</strong></td><td>Stop spread with minimal evidence damage—network isolation variants matter.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Eradicate &amp; recover</strong></td><td>Remove persistence, patch root cause, restore with verification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Lessons learned</strong></td><td>Metrics, control changes, and communication improvements—close the loop.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>SBOM formats (CycloneDX/SPDX) help inventory components for incident response and licensing—not only security.</li><li>Bug bounty scope must exclude destructive testing—safe harbor language still needs legal review.</li><li>AES-128 is not “half as strong” as AES-256 in practical threat models for many cases—key management quality dominates.</li><li>UDP-based protocols can be abused for amplification DDoS—patch open resolvers and monitor volumetric baselines.</li><li>ISO 27001 is an ISMS standard; it emphasizes risk treatment and continual improvement, not a product checklist.</li><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>SameSite=Lax blocks many CSRF POSTs from cross-site contexts in modern browsers—know the nuance vs Strict.</li><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L1-01: What “security” means at work</em>:</strong> Incident response questions probe containment vs evidence preservation tension, legal escalation, and communication discipline. The exam rewards knowing when to isolate systems, when to involve counsel, and why mass log deletion is catastrophic.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L1-01: What “security” means at work</em>:</strong> Industrial and OT adjacent questions reward knowing <strong>safety vs security</strong> tension: availability may trump confidentiality; testing must avoid breaking physical processes.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L1-01: What “security” means at work</em>:</strong> API keys in mobile apps are often extractable—prefer <strong>short-lived tokens</strong> and server-mediated access to backends.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L1-01: What “security” means at work</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L1-01: What “security” means at work</em>:</strong> Physical security is still on the exam: tailgating, visitor escorts, locks, destruction of media, and environmental controls (fire, HVAC) as availability/confidentiality supports.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L1-01: What “security” means at work</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L1-01: What “security” means at work</em>:</strong> TACACS+ vs RADIUS separation of duties in device admin access—exams may contrast accounting granularity.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L1-01: What “security” means at work</em>:</strong> Cryptography questions reward vocabulary precision: hashing vs encryption vs encoding; symmetric vs asymmetric roles in TLS; what signatures prove; and why key management is usually harder than picking an algorithm. If an answer sounds magical, it is probably wrong.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L1-01: What “security” means at work</em>:</strong> Help desk scenarios test whether you know <strong>identity proofing</strong> vs <strong>account recovery</strong> abuse. The secure path verifies the human through out-of-band channels without teaching attackers how to bypass your process in the stem text.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L1-01: What “security” means at work</em>:</strong> Tabletop exercises test <strong>comms trees</strong>, legal escalation, and customer notification templates—not only technical runbooks.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Purple team wants to simulate abuse of “L1-01: What “security” means at work” next Friday. List <strong>safety gates</strong> (scope, rollback, monitoring) you require before authorizing the exercise.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l1-02":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L1-02: Confidentiality, integrity, availability (CIA)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-02</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Name CIA; give one workplace example of each being violated.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> SLAs and incident severity often map to availability; fraud to integrity; leaks to confidentiality.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> List three services: <code>systemctl list-units --type=service | head</code>. Pick one; describe how its failure hurts <strong>A</strong>, misconfiguration <strong>I</strong>, or exposure <strong>C</strong>.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-02</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Foundations on the exam often pair <strong>policy intent</strong> with <strong>technical examples</strong>—pick answers that show both, not policy theater without enforcement.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 1 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>MFA</strong></dt><dd>Multi-factor authentication—requires two or more independent factors; push fatigue and MFA phishing are real bypass paths.</dd><dt><strong>MITRE ATT&amp;CK</strong></dt><dd>Tactics (why) and techniques (how) adversaries operate—use for detection engineering, gap analysis, and purple team scenarios.</dd><dt><strong>Salt (crypto)</strong></dt><dd>Random input to a password hash to defeat rainbow tables—must be unique per password.</dd><dt><strong>Residual risk</strong></dt><dd>Risk remaining after controls are applied; organizations accept, transfer, mitigate, or avoid it explicitly.</dd><dt><strong>Security misconfiguration</strong></dt><dd>Default creds, debug features on in prod, verbose errors, open directory listings—hardening baselines and drift detection reduce this class.</dd><dt><strong>Forensics basics</strong></dt><dd>Volatile vs non-volatile collection, order of volatility, hashing, and legal escalation paths before deep technical work.</dd><dt><strong>TTP</strong></dt><dd>Tactics, techniques, and procedures—behavioral patterns; harder to change than IOCs, better for resilient detection.</dd><dt><strong>SPF / DKIM / DMARC</strong></dt><dd>Email authenticity stack—SPF authorizes senders, DKIM signs messages, DMARC aligns policies and reporting for abuse handling.</dd><dt><strong>Third-party risk</strong></dt><dd>Vendor access expands attack surface—DPAs, SOC reports, and continuous monitoring for critical suppliers.</dd><dt><strong>Proxy vs reverse proxy</strong></dt><dd>Forward proxy represents clients outbound; reverse proxy fronts servers—different trust and logging points.</dd><dt><strong>Authorization</strong></dt><dd>What an authenticated subject is allowed to do—RBAC/ABAC, scopes, and server-side checks enforce least privilege.</dd><dt><strong>SIEM</strong></dt><dd>Security information and event management—centralize logs, parse fields, correlate alerts; tuning reduces false positives and fatigue.</dd><dt><strong>CRL</strong></dt><dd>Certificate Revocation List—signed list of revoked serials; size/latency issues drove OCSP adoption.</dd><dt><strong>Risk</strong></dt><dd>The intersection of threat, vulnerability, and impact—often assessed qualitatively (high/medium/low) or with scoring frameworks.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Responsible disclosure timelines balance vendor patch readiness with public safety—coordinate, don’t surprise.</li><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li><li>Linux auth.log style entries pair with SSH brute-force detection patterns—velocity and geo anomalies.</li><li>ISO 27001 is an ISMS standard; it emphasizes risk treatment and continual improvement, not a product checklist.</li><li>KMS key policies can deny even root in AWS when configured—explicit deny wins.</li><li>DNS over HTTPS changes visibility for some networks—understand resolver policy and logging tradeoffs.</li><li>HttpOnly does not stop CSRF; it reduces token theft from XSS reading document.cookie in many setups.</li><li>SLSA levels describe increasing supply-chain assurance—useful vocabulary in modern governance questions.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L1-02: Confidentiality, integrity, availability (CIA)</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L1-02: Confidentiality, integrity, availability (CIA)</em>:</strong> Deception tech is not a replacement for <strong>baselines and patching</strong>; it augments detection when mature processes exist.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L1-02: Confidentiality, integrity, availability (CIA)</em>:</strong> Cloud items assume you can articulate <strong>shared responsibility</strong>: what the provider patches vs what the customer must configure (IAM, encryption, network exposure). Misconfiguration beats novel cloud exploits in real incidents and on the exam.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L1-02: Confidentiality, integrity, availability (CIA)</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L1-02: Confidentiality, integrity, availability (CIA)</em>:</strong> LDAP vs Active Directory questions test directory concepts at a high level—binding, searches, and secure transport (LDAPS) appear often.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L1-02: Confidentiality, integrity, availability (CIA)</em>:</strong> Cryptography questions reward vocabulary precision: hashing vs encryption vs encoding; symmetric vs asymmetric roles in TLS; what signatures prove; and why key management is usually harder than picking an algorithm. If an answer sounds magical, it is probably wrong.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L1-02: Confidentiality, integrity, availability (CIA)</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L1-02: Confidentiality, integrity, availability (CIA)</em>:</strong> GraphQL introspection risk is about <strong>schema discovery</strong> aiding attackers—rate limits, authz on fields, and disabling introspection in prod are common answers.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L1-02: Confidentiality, integrity, availability (CIA)</em>:</strong> Defense in depth is not “more products,” it is <strong>independent mechanisms</strong>—if one layer is bypassed, another still limits movement, slows the adversary, or preserves evidence. Be ready to explain why network controls alone cannot compensate for missing app-layer authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L1-02: Confidentiality, integrity, availability (CIA)</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> You are the on-call analyst reviewing an alert tied to “L1-02: Confidentiality, integrity, availability (CIA)”. Leadership wants a <strong>60-second</strong> brief: business impact, evidence gaps, and the <strong>first</strong> containment step that preserves logs. No tool-specific jargon—prioritize scope, evidence, blast radius, then root-cause remediation under change control.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l1-03":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L1-03: Authenticity and non-repudiation</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-03</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Contrast “who you are” (identity) with “proof you said it” (non-repudiation).<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Email signing, audit logs, transaction records.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Run <code>journalctl -b | tail -n 20</code>. Identify one line that supports accountability.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-03</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Level 1 IR literacy means naming <strong>phases</strong> and knowing <strong>never delete logs</strong> as a first reflex; sophistication grows in later levels.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 1 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Full packet capture</strong></dt><dd>High fidelity evidence for investigations—storage, privacy, and legal review constraints apply.</dd><dt><strong>IOC</strong></dt><dd>Indicator of compromise—often ephemeral (IPs, domains); pair with TTP-based detections for durability.</dd><dt><strong>DNS</strong></dt><dd>Name resolution is a trust anchor—DNSSEC, cache poisoning, and malicious resolutions are classic abuse paths; log resolver anomalies.</dd><dt><strong>Exploit</strong></dt><dd>A technique or code that takes advantage of a vulnerability to achieve an attacker goal (exfiltration, persistence, disruption).</dd><dt><strong>Non-repudiation</strong></dt><dd>Prevents a party from credibly denying an action—digital signatures, tamper-evident logs, and time-stamping support it.</dd><dt><strong>Kerberos (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Ticket-based enterprise auth—TGT vs service tickets; golden/silver ticket classes of abuse appear in advanced IR.</dd><dt><strong>Perfect forward secrecy (PFS)</strong></dt><dd>Ephemeral key exchange means past session keys are not compromised if long-term keys leak later—TLS cipher suites can offer this property.</dd><dt><strong>Security misconfiguration</strong></dt><dd>Default creds, debug features on in prod, verbose errors, open directory listings—hardening baselines and drift detection reduce this class.</dd><dt><strong>CWE</strong></dt><dd>Common Weakness Enumeration—taxonomy of software weakness types that help root-cause fixes beyond one CVE instance.</dd><dt><strong>Container security</strong></dt><dd>Image provenance, non-root users, read-only roots, seccomp/AppArmor, and admission control for risky capabilities.</dd><dt><strong>Threat intelligence lifecycle</strong></dt><dd>Planning, collection, processing, analysis, dissemination, feedback—intel must change detections or posture or it is shelf-ware.</dd><dt><strong>Separation of duties (SoD)</strong></dt><dd>No single person can complete a sensitive transaction alone—classic finance control that also limits insider abuse.</dd><dt><strong>Salt (crypto)</strong></dt><dd>Random input to a password hash to defeat rainbow tables—must be unique per password.</dd><dt><strong>Port knocking (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Obscurity-based pre-auth to open firewall—weak alone; exam may present as non-primary control.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Sigma rules are vendor-agnostic detection snippets—tuning required per log source fields.</li><li>Linux auth.log style entries pair with SSH brute-force detection patterns—velocity and geo anomalies.</li><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li><li>Split tunnel VPN can exfil corporate data outside inspection if misconfigured—policy and routing matter.</li><li>Certificate pinning misconfigurations can brick apps—plan rotation and emergency releases.</li><li>JWT alg:none historical vulnerability class—always validate algorithm and signature keys explicitly.</li><li>Server-side template injection is distinct from XSS—context and sinks differ.</li><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L1-03: Authenticity and non-repudiation</em>:</strong> Deception tech is not a replacement for <strong>baselines and patching</strong>; it augments detection when mature processes exist.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L1-03: Authenticity and non-repudiation</em>:</strong> Risk decisions are economic: organizations <strong>accept</strong>, <strong>mitigate</strong>, <strong>transfer</strong> (insurance, outsourcing with contracts), or <strong>avoid</strong> (stop the activity). Controls change likelihood or impact; residual risk should be explicit, not invisible.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L1-03: Authenticity and non-repudiation</em>:</strong> Patching and change management appear as <strong>risk tradeoffs</strong>: emergency patches vs testing rings; compensating monitoring when patching lags; and documenting exceptions for auditors.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L1-03: Authenticity and non-repudiation</em>:</strong> Container escape questions hinge on <strong>kernel boundary</strong> and misconfigured capabilities—namespaces are helpful but not a complete trust boundary without seccomp, AppArmor, and least-privileged service accounts.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L1-03: Authenticity and non-repudiation</em>:</strong> API keys in mobile apps are often extractable—prefer <strong>short-lived tokens</strong> and server-mediated access to backends.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L1-03: Authenticity and non-repudiation</em>:</strong> TPM-backed BitLocker keys illustrate <strong>key protection</strong> binding to platform state—recovery keys must be guarded like crown jewels.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L1-03: Authenticity and non-repudiation</em>:</strong> Vulnerability management is a lifecycle: scanners find candidates, analysts prioritize with exploitability and business context, owners remediate, and verification closes the loop. “Patch everything immediately” is rarely operational; <strong>risk-based SLAs</strong> are the adult answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L1-03: Authenticity and non-repudiation</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L1-03: Authenticity and non-repudiation</em>:</strong> Ransomware stems often pair encryption with <strong>exfiltration</strong>—the correct answer may include legal/notification obligations, not only restoring from backup.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L1-03: Authenticity and non-repudiation</em>:</strong> Certificate pinning failures during rotation teach why <strong>key continuity strategy</strong> must be planned before mobile releases.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> You are the on-call analyst reviewing an alert tied to “L1-03: Authenticity and non-repudiation”. Leadership wants a <strong>60-second</strong> brief: business impact, evidence gaps, and the <strong>first</strong> containment step that preserves logs. No tool-specific jargon—prioritize scope, evidence, blast radius, then root-cause remediation under change control.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l1-04":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L1-04: Privacy vs security</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-04</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Explain that privacy is about people; security protects assets including PII.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> GDPR/CCPA-style rights; data minimization.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Create a dummy file <code>echo &quot;fake PII&quot; &gt; ~/lab-pii.txt</code>; set permissions <code>chmod 600 ~/lab-pii.txt</code>; verify with <code>ls -l</code>.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-04</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Expect “which control type?” questions—administrative vs technical vs physical—tied to realistic workplace moments like contractor onboarding.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 1 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>SSO</strong></dt><dd>Single sign-on federates trust to an IdP—misconfigured SAML/OIDC trusts are high-impact; validate metadata and signing keys.</dd><dt><strong>DevSecOps</strong></dt><dd>Embed security gates in CI/CD with fast feedback—policy-as-code, secret scanning, and SBOMs support supply-chain resilience.</dd><dt><strong>Purple teaming</strong></dt><dd>Collaborative attack/defense exercises to validate detections without surprise production harm—scope and safety first.</dd><dt><strong>Full packet capture</strong></dt><dd>High fidelity evidence for investigations—storage, privacy, and legal review constraints apply.</dd><dt><strong>Compensating control</strong></dt><dd>Alternative control that meets intent when primary control cannot be implemented—must provide equivalent or greater assurance with documentation.</dd><dt><strong>Firewall</strong></dt><dd>Enforces allow/deny rules on traffic—stateful inspection tracks sessions; default-deny with explicit permits is the secure baseline.</dd><dt><strong>SIEM</strong></dt><dd>Security information and event management—centralize logs, parse fields, correlate alerts; tuning reduces false positives and fatigue.</dd><dt><strong>Separation of duties (SoD)</strong></dt><dd>No single person can complete a sensitive transaction alone—classic finance control that also limits insider abuse.</dd><dt><strong>RPO / RTO recap</strong></dt><dd>RPO = max acceptable data loss time; RTO = max acceptable outage—drive backup frequency and HA design.</dd><dt><strong>Exploit</strong></dt><dd>A technique or code that takes advantage of a vulnerability to achieve an attacker goal (exfiltration, persistence, disruption).</dd><dt><strong>Zero Trust (headline)</strong></dt><dd>Assume breach; verify explicitly per request using identity, device posture, and least privilege—not “trust the LAN.”</dd><dt><strong>IAM least privilege</strong></dt><dd>Grant minimum API/console rights; prefer roles over long-lived keys; audit risky admin-equivalent paths regularly.</dd><dt><strong>Token replay</strong></dt><dd>Reusing a stolen token/session artifact—rotation, binding, and short TTLs reduce window.</dd><dt><strong>Kill chain / cyber kill chain</strong></dt><dd>Stages of intrusion—mapping controls and detections to stages clarifies coverage gaps.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Typical exam angle</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Confidentiality</strong></td><td>Who may read? Encryption, ACLs, DLP, classification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Integrity</strong></td><td>Was it modified? Hashing, signatures, change control, backups.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Availability</strong></td><td>Can authorized users work? HA, patching windows, DDoS defense, DR.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authenticity / non-repudiation</strong></td><td>Prove source and intent—signatures, strong issuance, tamper-evident logs.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>KMS key policies can deny even root in AWS when configured—explicit deny wins.</li><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li><li>Sigma rules are vendor-agnostic detection snippets—tuning required per log source fields.</li><li>GraphQL batching can amplify complexity attacks—depth and cost limits are first-class controls.</li><li>Terraform state can hold secrets—remote secure backend and scanning are baseline hygiene.</li><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>Immutable backups mitigate ransomware that tries to delete online copies—air-gapped or WORM patterns.</li><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L1-04: Privacy vs security</em>:</strong> Security operations value <strong>repeatable evidence</strong>: timestamps, authoritative configuration sources, and tamper-aware logs beat heroic memory after an incident. Many exam questions hinge on whether an action preserves integrity and accountability rather than whether it feels fast.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L1-04: Privacy vs security</em>:</strong> Access control stems frequently mix <strong>role</strong> vs <strong>attribute</strong> vs <strong>rule</strong> models; pick the answer that matches the scenario’s constraints (temporary contractor, cross-department data, dynamic tags on resources).</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L1-04: Privacy vs security</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L1-04: Privacy vs security</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L1-04: Privacy vs security</em>:</strong> Certificate pinning failures during rotation teach why <strong>key continuity strategy</strong> must be planned before mobile releases.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L1-04: Privacy vs security</em>:</strong> Social engineering callbacks to <strong>pretexting</strong>, <strong>baiting</strong>, and <strong>vishing</strong>—name the subtype when the stem describes the tactic.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L1-04: Privacy vs security</em>:</strong> Vulnerability management is a lifecycle: scanners find candidates, analysts prioritize with exploitability and business context, owners remediate, and verification closes the loop. “Patch everything immediately” is rarely operational; <strong>risk-based SLAs</strong> are the adult answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L1-04: Privacy vs security</em>:</strong> Business continuity answers should reference <strong>RTO/RPO</strong>, <strong>workarounds</strong>, and <strong>tested restores</strong>; DR without practiced failover is wishful thinking, and exam writers know it.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L1-04: Privacy vs security</em>:</strong> Container escape questions hinge on <strong>kernel boundary</strong> and misconfigured capabilities—namespaces are helpful but not a complete trust boundary without seccomp, AppArmor, and least-privileged service accounts.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L1-04: Privacy vs security</em>:</strong> Evidence bags and write blockers signal <strong>forensics awareness</strong>; touching disks before imaging is a classic wrong answer.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Junior staff proposes a quick fix for “L1-04: Privacy vs security” that disables logging on a noisy host. Walk through why that is unacceptable and propose a <strong>tuning</strong> path that preserves <strong>integrity and retention</strong> commitments.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l1-05":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L1-05: Threat, vulnerability, exploit, control</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-05</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Use each term in a sentence without mixing them up.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Vulnerability management tickets; patch SLAs.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Run <code>apt-cache policy openssl | head -n 15</code>. Note installed vs candidate version language.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-05</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Level 1 physical and operational items return to <strong>tailgating, visitor logs, and media destruction</strong>—do not skip them as “non-technical”; they are fair game.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 1 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Risk</strong></dt><dd>The intersection of threat, vulnerability, and impact—often assessed qualitatively (high/medium/low) or with scoring frameworks.</dd><dt><strong>SSO</strong></dt><dd>Single sign-on federates trust to an IdP—misconfigured SAML/OIDC trusts are high-impact; validate metadata and signing keys.</dd><dt><strong>Encoding (e.g., Base64)</strong></dt><dd>Transforms representation without cryptographic protection—do not confuse with encryption or integrity.</dd><dt><strong>IR phases</strong></dt><dd>Prepare, detect, analyze, contain, eradicate, recover, and lessons learned—legal hold and evidence integrity matter throughout.</dd><dt><strong>Attack surface</strong></dt><dd>The sum of exposure—every service, API, integration, and human workflow that can be reached by a threat; reduction beats perfect monitoring alone.</dd><dt><strong>OCSP stapling (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Server sends fresh revocation info with handshake—reduces client privacy leaks and lookup failures.</dd><dt><strong>Sinkhole (DNS)</strong></dt><dd>Controlled resolution for malicious domains—intel and disruption technique with legal process considerations.</dd><dt><strong>SIEM</strong></dt><dd>Security information and event management—centralize logs, parse fields, correlate alerts; tuning reduces false positives and fatigue.</dd><dt><strong>Availability</strong></dt><dd>Assures timely and reliable access—redundancy, patching, DDoS defenses, and DR planning keep services usable for authorized users.</dd><dt><strong>DNS</strong></dt><dd>Name resolution is a trust anchor—DNSSEC, cache poisoning, and malicious resolutions are classic abuse paths; log resolver anomalies.</dd><dt><strong>XSS</strong></dt><dd>Cross-site scripting injects script in a victim context—CSP, output encoding, HttpOnly cookies, and DOM hygiene reduce blast radius.</dd><dt><strong>Container security</strong></dt><dd>Image provenance, non-root users, read-only roots, seccomp/AppArmor, and admission control for risky capabilities.</dd><dt><strong>Forensics basics</strong></dt><dd>Volatile vs non-volatile collection, order of volatility, hashing, and legal escalation paths before deep technical work.</dd><dt><strong>ECB mode weakness</strong></dt><dd>Identical plaintext blocks yield identical ciphertext—leaks structure; prefer modes with IVs and authentication.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>IR phase</th><th>What you do there (exam shorthand)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Prepare</strong></td><td>Playbooks, contacts, tooling, baseline logging—before the pager fires.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detect &amp; analyze</strong></td><td>Scope, timelines, hypotheses—preserve volatile evidence early.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Contain</strong></td><td>Stop spread with minimal evidence damage—network isolation variants matter.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Eradicate &amp; recover</strong></td><td>Remove persistence, patch root cause, restore with verification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Lessons learned</strong></td><td>Metrics, control changes, and communication improvements—close the loop.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Certificate pinning misconfigurations can brick apps—plan rotation and emergency releases.</li><li>KMS key policies can deny even root in AWS when configured—explicit deny wins.</li><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li><li>Sigma rules are vendor-agnostic detection snippets—tuning required per log source fields.</li><li>GraphQL batching can amplify complexity attacks—depth and cost limits are first-class controls.</li><li>Terraform state can hold secrets—remote secure backend and scanning are baseline hygiene.</li><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>Immutable backups mitigate ransomware that tries to delete online copies—air-gapped or WORM patterns.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L1-05: Threat, vulnerability, exploit, control</em>:</strong> Multicloud complexity increases <strong>identity sprawl</strong>; centralized IdP and consistent conditional access policies reduce human error.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L1-05: Threat, vulnerability, exploit, control</em>:</strong> Advanced topics still return to fundamentals: least privilege, segmentation, logging, and tested recovery. When you see Zero Trust or PQC buzzwords, map them back to concrete controls and threat models rather than treating them as magic shields.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L1-05: Threat, vulnerability, exploit, control</em>:</strong> API keys in mobile apps are often extractable—prefer <strong>short-lived tokens</strong> and server-mediated access to backends.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L1-05: Threat, vulnerability, exploit, control</em>:</strong> Logging questions often test whether you understand <strong>what to log</strong> (who, what, when, where, outcome), <strong>time sync</strong> for correlation, and <strong>tamper resistance</strong> for evidentiary value—not whether you can collect infinite bytes.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L1-05: Threat, vulnerability, exploit, control</em>:</strong> GraphQL introspection risk is about <strong>schema discovery</strong> aiding attackers—rate limits, authz on fields, and disabling introspection in prod are common answers.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L1-05: Threat, vulnerability, exploit, control</em>:</strong> Access control stems frequently mix <strong>role</strong> vs <strong>attribute</strong> vs <strong>rule</strong> models; pick the answer that matches the scenario’s constraints (temporary contractor, cross-department data, dynamic tags on resources).</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L1-05: Threat, vulnerability, exploit, control</em>:</strong> CSP reporting helps tune policy but can leak URLs—<strong>privacy review</strong> of report endpoints matters in regulated environments.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L1-05: Threat, vulnerability, exploit, control</em>:</strong> Wireless and mobility items reward knowing basics: WPA3 improvements conceptually, evil twin risks, captive portals, and why client isolation matters on guest networks—without memorizing obsolete WEP details unless explicitly historical.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L1-05: Threat, vulnerability, exploit, control</em>:</strong> Subresource integrity protects against <strong>CDN compromise</strong> but requires operational discipline when vendors rotate files.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L1-05: Threat, vulnerability, exploit, control</em>:</strong> Physical security is still on the exam: tailgating, visitor escorts, locks, destruction of media, and environmental controls (fire, HVAC) as availability/confidentiality supports.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Internal audit samples “L1-05: Threat, vulnerability, exploit, control” controls and finds screenshots instead of config exports. Explain why <strong>authoritative evidence</strong> matters and what you would collect instead.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l1-06":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L1-06: Risk = likelihood × impact (qualitative)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-06</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Plot a simple 3×3 risk matrix story for one asset.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Risk registers; “accept vs mitigate.”<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Write a 5-row markdown table in <code>~/risk-example.md</code>: asset, threat, vuln, control, residual risk.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-06</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Level 1 maps to Security+ <strong>foundations</strong>: risk vocabulary, CIA, control families, common attack classes, physical basics, and early IR literacy. Stems reward <strong>definitions you can apply</strong>, not memorizing obscure RFC numbers unless the question names them.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 1 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>WAF vs IPS</strong></dt><dd>WAF focuses on application-layer attacks; IPS often line-rate network signatures—overlap exists but priorities differ.</dd><dt><strong>Vulnerability</strong></dt><dd>A weakness in design, implementation, configuration, or process that could be exploited to violate a security policy.</dd><dt><strong>SPF / DKIM / DMARC</strong></dt><dd>Email authenticity stack—SPF authorizes senders, DKIM signs messages, DMARC aligns policies and reporting for abuse handling.</dd><dt><strong>Shared responsibility model</strong></dt><dd>Cloud provider secures the platform; customer secures configuration, identities, data, and app code in their scope.</dd><dt><strong>Data loss prevention (DLP)</strong></dt><dd>Content-aware controls to block or alert on sensitive data movement—policy + tech, tuned to avoid blocking work.</dd><dt><strong>Diamond model</strong></dt><dd>Adversary, infrastructure, capability, victim—useful for pivoting investigations and intel fusion.</dd><dt><strong>Availability</strong></dt><dd>Assures timely and reliable access—redundancy, patching, DDoS defenses, and DR planning keep services usable for authorized users.</dd><dt><strong>Encoding (e.g., Base64)</strong></dt><dd>Transforms representation without cryptographic protection—do not confuse with encryption or integrity.</dd><dt><strong>Third-party risk</strong></dt><dd>Vendor access expands attack surface—DPAs, SOC reports, and continuous monitoring for critical suppliers.</dd><dt><strong>Collision (hash)</strong></dt><dd>Two inputs produce same hash—breaks integrity assumptions; choose strong hash families for security use.</dd><dt><strong>CWE</strong></dt><dd>Common Weakness Enumeration—taxonomy of software weakness types that help root-cause fixes beyond one CVE instance.</dd><dt><strong>Password policy</strong></dt><dd>Modern guidance favors long passphrases, breach-banned lists, and vaults over rotation-for-its-own-sake complexity theater.</dd><dt><strong>Security headers</strong></dt><dd>HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options/Frame-ancestors, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy—reduce browser-driven attack surface.</dd><dt><strong>Confidential computing</strong></dt><dd>Use of hardware enclaves/TEEs to reduce exposure to privileged operators—threat model still required.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>S3 bucket policies and ACLs layer with IAM—effective permissions require understanding intersection.</li><li>Sigma rules are vendor-agnostic detection snippets—tuning required per log source fields.</li><li>SBOM formats (CycloneDX/SPDX) help inventory components for incident response and licensing—not only security.</li><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li><li>JWT alg:none historical vulnerability class—always validate algorithm and signature keys explicitly.</li><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L1-06: Risk = likelihood × impact (qualitative)</em>:</strong> Certificate pinning failures during rotation teach why <strong>key continuity strategy</strong> must be planned before mobile releases.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L1-06: Risk = likelihood × impact (qualitative)</em>:</strong> Incident response questions probe containment vs evidence preservation tension, legal escalation, and communication discipline. The exam rewards knowing when to isolate systems, when to involve counsel, and why mass log deletion is catastrophic.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L1-06: Risk = likelihood × impact (qualitative)</em>:</strong> KMS keys are not “magic secrecy dust”—<strong>who can invoke decrypt</strong> and from which contexts (VPC endpoint policies, IAM conditions) is what exams probe.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L1-06: Risk = likelihood × impact (qualitative)</em>:</strong> BIOS/UEFI passwords and secure boot reduce some pre-boot attacks but do not stop <strong>evil maid</strong> classes without additional controls.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L1-06: Risk = likelihood × impact (qualitative)</em>:</strong> Patching and change management appear as <strong>risk tradeoffs</strong>: emergency patches vs testing rings; compensating monitoring when patching lags; and documenting exceptions for auditors.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L1-06: Risk = likelihood × impact (qualitative)</em>:</strong> Tabletop exercises test <strong>comms trees</strong>, legal escalation, and customer notification templates—not only technical runbooks.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L1-06: Risk = likelihood × impact (qualitative)</em>:</strong> Defense in depth is not “more products,” it is <strong>independent mechanisms</strong>—if one layer is bypassed, another still limits movement, slows the adversary, or preserves evidence. Be ready to explain why network controls alone cannot compensate for missing app-layer authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L1-06: Risk = likelihood × impact (qualitative)</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L1-06: Risk = likelihood × impact (qualitative)</em>:</strong> LDAP vs Active Directory questions test directory concepts at a high level—binding, searches, and secure transport (LDAPS) appear often.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L1-06: Risk = likelihood × impact (qualitative)</em>:</strong> Cloud items assume you can articulate <strong>shared responsibility</strong>: what the provider patches vs what the customer must configure (IAM, encryption, network exposure). Misconfiguration beats novel cloud exploits in real incidents and on the exam.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Legal asks whether “L1-06: Risk = likelihood × impact (qualitative)” artifacts require <strong>hold</strong> before deletion. Describe how you would <strong>tag systems</strong>, <strong>freeze backups</strong> appropriately, and <strong>escalate</strong> without tipping external actors.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l1-07":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L1-07: Least privilege and separation of duties</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-07</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Define both; give a finance + IT example.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> SoD for payment approval; break-glass accounts.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Run <code>groups</code>. List one group you would remove from a normal user in production.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-07</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Level 1 physical and operational items return to <strong>tailgating, visitor logs, and media destruction</strong>—do not skip them as “non-technical”; they are fair game.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 1 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Full packet capture</strong></dt><dd>High fidelity evidence for investigations—storage, privacy, and legal review constraints apply.</dd><dt><strong>Policy vs standard vs procedure</strong></dt><dd>Policy states intent; standards define mandatory requirements; procedures are step-by-step how-to for operators.</dd><dt><strong>Kerberos (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Ticket-based enterprise auth—TGT vs service tickets; golden/silver ticket classes of abuse appear in advanced IR.</dd><dt><strong>Secure SDLC</strong></dt><dd>Requirements, threat modeling, secure design, code review, SAST/DAST, dependency scanning, and hardened deployment pipelines.</dd><dt><strong>PQC</strong></dt><dd>Post-quantum cryptography migration—hybrid schemes and crypto-agility for long-lived secrets exposed to harvest-now/decrypt-later risk.</dd><dt><strong>MITM</strong></dt><dd>Man-in-the-middle intercepts or alters traffic—TLS with proper validation mitigates; corporate SSL inspection is its own trust zone.</dd><dt><strong>Control</strong></dt><dd>Administrative, technical, or physical safeguards that reduce likelihood or impact of a security event (prevent, detect, correct).</dd><dt><strong>MFA</strong></dt><dd>Multi-factor authentication—requires two or more independent factors; push fatigue and MFA phishing are real bypass paths.</dd><dt><strong>Injection</strong></dt><dd>Untrusted input becomes part of a command or query—parameterized queries, input validation, and context escaping are core defenses.</dd><dt><strong>Supply chain security</strong></dt><dd>SBOM, provenance signing (SLSA-style thinking), and dependency pinning reduce “update from upstream” surprises.</dd><dt><strong>ECB mode weakness</strong></dt><dd>Identical plaintext blocks yield identical ciphertext—leaks structure; prefer modes with IVs and authentication.</dd><dt><strong>Quantitative vs qualitative risk</strong></dt><dd>Qualitative uses scales (high/medium/low); quantitative uses dollar or probability estimates—both need consistent assumptions and reviewer judgment.</dd><dt><strong>Privacy</strong></dt><dd>Protection of personal information and individual rights—overlaps with security but adds legal/regulatory obligations (GDPR-style).</dd><dt><strong>Key management</strong></dt><dd>Generation, storage, rotation, and destruction—HSM/KMS patterns reduce exposure compared to software-only secrets.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>KMS key policies can deny even root in AWS when configured—explicit deny wins.</li><li>PCI DSS scope reduction via segmentation is a recurring theme—if it is not in scope, it cannot drag you into assessment.</li><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li><li>Linux auth.log style entries pair with SSH brute-force detection patterns—velocity and geo anomalies.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L1-07: Least privilege and separation of duties</em>:</strong> Ransomware stems often pair encryption with <strong>exfiltration</strong>—the correct answer may include legal/notification obligations, not only restoring from backup.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L1-07: Least privilege and separation of duties</em>:</strong> Evidence bags and write blockers signal <strong>forensics awareness</strong>; touching disks before imaging is a classic wrong answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L1-07: Least privilege and separation of duties</em>:</strong> LDAP vs Active Directory questions test directory concepts at a high level—binding, searches, and secure transport (LDAPS) appear often.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L1-07: Least privilege and separation of duties</em>:</strong> BIOS/UEFI passwords and secure boot reduce some pre-boot attacks but do not stop <strong>evil maid</strong> classes without additional controls.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L1-07: Least privilege and separation of duties</em>:</strong> Controls fail in three predictable ways: <strong>misconfiguration</strong>, <strong>missing coverage</strong> (gaps between tools), and <strong>human process</strong> breakdown (exceptions, shared accounts, emergency access). When you read a scenario, ask which failure mode is most plausible before picking an answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L1-07: Least privilege and separation of duties</em>:</strong> Vulnerability management is a lifecycle: scanners find candidates, analysts prioritize with exploitability and business context, owners remediate, and verification closes the loop. “Patch everything immediately” is rarely operational; <strong>risk-based SLAs</strong> are the adult answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L1-07: Least privilege and separation of duties</em>:</strong> Wireless and mobility items reward knowing basics: WPA3 improvements conceptually, evil twin risks, captive portals, and why client isolation matters on guest networks—without memorizing obsolete WEP details unless explicitly historical.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L1-07: Least privilege and separation of duties</em>:</strong> Engineers often optimize for speed; attackers optimize for <strong>cheap reuse</strong> of stolen creds and known exploits. The winning answer bridges both: ship fast with guardrails—feature flags, staged rollouts, and automated security checks in CI.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L1-07: Least privilege and separation of duties</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L1-07: Least privilege and separation of duties</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> You are the on-call analyst reviewing an alert tied to “L1-07: Least privilege and separation of duties”. Leadership wants a <strong>60-second</strong> brief: business impact, evidence gaps, and the <strong>first</strong> containment step that preserves logs. No tool-specific jargon—prioritize scope, evidence, blast radius, then root-cause remediation under change control.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l1-08":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L1-08: Passwords and password managers</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-08</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Explain length &gt; complexity; MFA as the real control.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Enterprise IdP; banned password lists.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Install <code>keepassxc</code> if allowed, or document why corp policy uses vault X. Hash a test string: <code>echo -n &quot;lab&quot; | sha256sum</code>.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-08</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Foundations on the exam often pair <strong>policy intent</strong> with <strong>technical examples</strong>—pick answers that show both, not policy theater without enforcement.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 1 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Threat modeling (STRIDE)</strong></dt><dd>Spoofing, tampering, repudiation, information disclosure, denial of service, elevation of privilege—drive controls early.</dd><dt><strong>Token replay</strong></dt><dd>Reusing a stolen token/session artifact—rotation, binding, and short TTLs reduce window.</dd><dt><strong>ECB mode weakness</strong></dt><dd>Identical plaintext blocks yield identical ciphertext—leaks structure; prefer modes with IVs and authentication.</dd><dt><strong>NetFlow / IPFIX</strong></dt><dd>Flow metadata for volume and anomaly detection—lighter than PCAP but less payload visibility.</dd><dt><strong>TTP</strong></dt><dd>Tactics, techniques, and procedures—behavioral patterns; harder to change than IOCs, better for resilient detection.</dd><dt><strong>PKI</strong></dt><dd>Public Key Infrastructure—CAs, RAs, CRL/OCSP, and certificate lifecycle; mis-issuance or weak validation breaks trust chains.</dd><dt><strong>Control</strong></dt><dd>Administrative, technical, or physical safeguards that reduce likelihood or impact of a security event (prevent, detect, correct).</dd><dt><strong>Privacy</strong></dt><dd>Protection of personal information and individual rights—overlaps with security but adds legal/regulatory obligations (GDPR-style).</dd><dt><strong>NAT (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Rewrites addresses/ports for traversal—security relevance includes logging visibility, port forwarding risks, and split tunnel implications for inspection.</dd><dt><strong>Certificate pinning (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Client remembers expected server key material—reduces MITM from rogue CAs but complicates rotation; mostly seen in mobile/API hardening patterns.</dd><dt><strong>OWASP Top 10</strong></dt><dd>High-prevalence web risks—broken access control and crypto failures often dominate; study each category with one workplace example.</dd><dt><strong>Vulnerability management</strong></dt><dd>Discover, prioritize, remediate, verify, and report—SLAs differ by exposure, exploitability, and asset criticality.</dd><dt><strong>Serverless blast radius</strong></dt><dd>One broad execution role affects every invocation—scope IAM per function and watch environment variable leaks.</dd><dt><strong>Attack surface</strong></dt><dd>The sum of exposure—every service, API, integration, and human workflow that can be reached by a threat; reduction beats perfect monitoring alone.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Cloud responsibility</th><th>Who typically owns it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Patching the hypervisor</strong></td><td>Provider responsibility in major IaaS models—customer still patches guests.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>IAM policy and keys</strong></td><td>Customer-owned configuration—misconfigurations dominate incidents.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Data encryption at rest</strong></td><td>Often customer-controlled keys/KMS policies with provider primitives.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Network exposure (SGs/NACLs)</strong></td><td>Customer configures; default-deny patterns are exam favorites.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Application vulnerabilities</strong></td><td>Customer code and dependencies—shared model does not absolve secure SDLC.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>AEAD</strong></td><td>Confidentiality + integrity together—misuse of IV/nonce still breaks security.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Linux auth.log style entries pair with SSH brute-force detection patterns—velocity and geo anomalies.</li><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li><li>Split tunnel VPN can exfil corporate data outside inspection if misconfigured—policy and routing matter.</li><li>Certificate pinning misconfigurations can brick apps—plan rotation and emergency releases.</li><li>JWT alg:none historical vulnerability class—always validate algorithm and signature keys explicitly.</li><li>Server-side template injection is distinct from XSS—context and sinks differ.</li><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li><li>Admission controllers can block privileged pods—policy-as-code integrates with GitOps reviews.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L1-08: Passwords and password managers</em>:</strong> Clean desk pairs with <strong>screen privacy</strong> and <strong>clear desk checks</strong> for regulated spaces—physical + procedural controls together.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L1-08: Passwords and password managers</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L1-08: Passwords and password managers</em>:</strong> GraphQL introspection risk is about <strong>schema discovery</strong> aiding attackers—rate limits, authz on fields, and disabling introspection in prod are common answers.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L1-08: Passwords and password managers</em>:</strong> Cryptography questions reward vocabulary precision: hashing vs encryption vs encoding; symmetric vs asymmetric roles in TLS; what signatures prove; and why key management is usually harder than picking an algorithm. If an answer sounds magical, it is probably wrong.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L1-08: Passwords and password managers</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L1-08: Passwords and password managers</em>:</strong> Deception tech is not a replacement for <strong>baselines and patching</strong>; it augments detection when mature processes exist.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L1-08: Passwords and password managers</em>:</strong> Access control stems frequently mix <strong>role</strong> vs <strong>attribute</strong> vs <strong>rule</strong> models; pick the answer that matches the scenario’s constraints (temporary contractor, cross-department data, dynamic tags on resources).</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L1-08: Passwords and password managers</em>:</strong> SAST finds issues early but produces false positives; <strong>triage workflows</strong> and developer feedback loops are part of a mature program, not “run tool once.”</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L1-08: Passwords and password managers</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L1-08: Passwords and password managers</em>:</strong> Engineers often optimize for speed; attackers optimize for <strong>cheap reuse</strong> of stolen creds and known exploits. The winning answer bridges both: ship fast with guardrails—feature flags, staged rollouts, and automated security checks in CI.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> A vendor integration project mentions “L1-08: Passwords and password managers” as out-of-scope for pen testing. Explain what <strong>residual risk</strong> remains, what <strong>compensating monitoring</strong> you would demand, and how you would <strong>document acceptance</strong>.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l1-09":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L1-09: Multi-factor authentication (MFA) patterns</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-09</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> List factors (knowledge, possession, inherence); recognize MFA bypass tricks at high level.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Conditional access; phishing-resistant FIDO2.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Research (read-only) <code>man pam_unix</code> skim — note “authentication stack” idea; 3-bullet summary.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-09</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Level 1 physical and operational items return to <strong>tailgating, visitor logs, and media destruction</strong>—do not skip them as “non-technical”; they are fair game.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 1 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Authentication</strong></dt><dd>Proving identity—something you know, have, or are; combine factors for MFA; never equate login with authorization alone.</dd><dt><strong>DevSecOps</strong></dt><dd>Embed security gates in CI/CD with fast feedback—policy-as-code, secret scanning, and SBOMs support supply-chain resilience.</dd><dt><strong>Job rotation</strong></dt><dd>Reduces collusion and fraud risk; also surfaces “tribal knowledge” silos before an employee leaves.</dd><dt><strong>TTP</strong></dt><dd>Tactics, techniques, and procedures—behavioral patterns; harder to change than IOCs, better for resilient detection.</dd><dt><strong>FIDO2 / WebAuthn</strong></dt><dd>Phishing-resistant possession factors using asymmetric crypto and origin binding; preferred where supported.</dd><dt><strong>CWE</strong></dt><dd>Common Weakness Enumeration—taxonomy of software weakness types that help root-cause fixes beyond one CVE instance.</dd><dt><strong>Data loss prevention (DLP)</strong></dt><dd>Content-aware controls to block or alert on sensitive data movement—policy + tech, tuned to avoid blocking work.</dd><dt><strong>Data residency</strong></dt><dd>Legal requirement for where data lives—impacts cloud region selection and key custody.</dd><dt><strong>SSO</strong></dt><dd>Single sign-on federates trust to an IdP—misconfigured SAML/OIDC trusts are high-impact; validate metadata and signing keys.</dd><dt><strong>MITRE ATT&amp;CK</strong></dt><dd>Tactics (why) and techniques (how) adversaries operate—use for detection engineering, gap analysis, and purple team scenarios.</dd><dt><strong>Downgrade attack</strong></dt><dd>Forcing weaker crypto or protocols—HSTS and modern TLS config reduce browser downgrade paths.</dd><dt><strong>Authorization</strong></dt><dd>What an authenticated subject is allowed to do—RBAC/ABAC, scopes, and server-side checks enforce least privilege.</dd><dt><strong>DDoS</strong></dt><dd>Distributed denial of service—volumetric, protocol, or application-layer floods; mitigations include scrubbing, anycast, rate limits, and architecture elasticity.</dd><dt><strong>Shared responsibility model</strong></dt><dd>Cloud provider secures the platform; customer secures configuration, identities, data, and app code in their scope.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>IR phase</th><th>What you do there (exam shorthand)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Prepare</strong></td><td>Playbooks, contacts, tooling, baseline logging—before the pager fires.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detect &amp; analyze</strong></td><td>Scope, timelines, hypotheses—preserve volatile evidence early.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Contain</strong></td><td>Stop spread with minimal evidence damage—network isolation variants matter.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Eradicate &amp; recover</strong></td><td>Remove persistence, patch root cause, restore with verification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Lessons learned</strong></td><td>Metrics, control changes, and communication improvements—close the loop.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Certificate pinning misconfigurations can brick apps—plan rotation and emergency releases.</li><li>Bug bounty scope must exclude destructive testing—safe harbor language still needs legal review.</li><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li><li>S3 bucket policies and ACLs layer with IAM—effective permissions require understanding intersection.</li><li>SameSite=Lax blocks many CSRF POSTs from cross-site contexts in modern browsers—know the nuance vs Strict.</li><li>GraphQL batching can amplify complexity attacks—depth and cost limits are first-class controls.</li><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L1-09: Multi-factor authentication (MFA) patterns</em>:</strong> Industrial and OT adjacent questions reward knowing <strong>safety vs security</strong> tension: availability may trump confidentiality; testing must avoid breaking physical processes.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L1-09: Multi-factor authentication (MFA) patterns</em>:</strong> API keys in mobile apps are often extractable—prefer <strong>short-lived tokens</strong> and server-mediated access to backends.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L1-09: Multi-factor authentication (MFA) patterns</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L1-09: Multi-factor authentication (MFA) patterns</em>:</strong> Physical security is still on the exam: tailgating, visitor escorts, locks, destruction of media, and environmental controls (fire, HVAC) as availability/confidentiality supports.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L1-09: Multi-factor authentication (MFA) patterns</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L1-09: Multi-factor authentication (MFA) patterns</em>:</strong> TACACS+ vs RADIUS separation of duties in device admin access—exams may contrast accounting granularity.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L1-09: Multi-factor authentication (MFA) patterns</em>:</strong> Cryptography questions reward vocabulary precision: hashing vs encryption vs encoding; symmetric vs asymmetric roles in TLS; what signatures prove; and why key management is usually harder than picking an algorithm. If an answer sounds magical, it is probably wrong.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L1-09: Multi-factor authentication (MFA) patterns</em>:</strong> Help desk scenarios test whether you know <strong>identity proofing</strong> vs <strong>account recovery</strong> abuse. The secure path verifies the human through out-of-band channels without teaching attackers how to bypass your process in the stem text.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L1-09: Multi-factor authentication (MFA) patterns</em>:</strong> Tabletop exercises test <strong>comms trees</strong>, legal escalation, and customer notification templates—not only technical runbooks.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L1-09: Multi-factor authentication (MFA) patterns</em>:</strong> Sanitization vs wiping vs destruction: exams like knowing which media needs <strong>degaussing, shredding, or crypto erase</strong> per policy.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Marketing launches a campaign referencing “L1-09: Multi-factor authentication (MFA) patterns” with a new subdomain. Security review finds DNS delegated to an unknown party. Explain <strong>trust chain</strong> risks and the <strong>minimum fixes</strong> before go-live.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l1-10":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L1-10: Phishing and social engineering basics</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-10</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> List red flags; know reporting path.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> SOC email triage; user awareness metrics.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Open a <strong>local</strong> HTML file you author with a benign “fake login” — describe 3 UX cues that differ from real SSO pages.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-10</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>At Level 1, think like an analyst who must <strong>classify</strong> an event: asset, threat, vulnerability, control, residual risk. If you can narrate those five words for any headline topic, you are aligned with how writers build scenario questions.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 1 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Encoding (e.g., Base64)</strong></dt><dd>Transforms representation without cryptographic protection—do not confuse with encryption or integrity.</dd><dt><strong>CVE</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures identifier for a specific flaw—pairs with CVSS severity and vendor advisories for prioritization.</dd><dt><strong>Container security</strong></dt><dd>Image provenance, non-root users, read-only roots, seccomp/AppArmor, and admission control for risky capabilities.</dd><dt><strong>Zero Trust architecture</strong></dt><dd>Identity-centric access with continuous verification—policy enforcement points for users, devices, and workloads.</dd><dt><strong>Data loss prevention (DLP)</strong></dt><dd>Content-aware controls to block or alert on sensitive data movement—policy + tech, tuned to avoid blocking work.</dd><dt><strong>IV / nonce</strong></dt><dd>Initialization vector or number-used-once—must be unique per encryption under a key for many modes.</dd><dt><strong>BGP prefix hijack</strong></dt><dd>Unauthorized route advertisement—RPKI ROV reduces impact but does not replace monitoring.</dd><dt><strong>NAT (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Rewrites addresses/ports for traversal—security relevance includes logging visibility, port forwarding risks, and split tunnel implications for inspection.</dd><dt><strong>Asset</strong></dt><dd>Anything of value to the organization—data, systems, people, reputation, or services—that security controls protect.</dd><dt><strong>Authenticity</strong></dt><dd>Verifies that users, devices, or data are genuine—cryptographic identity, attestation, and strong issuance processes matter.</dd><dt><strong>Asymmetric encryption</strong></dt><dd>Key pairs for key agreement/signing—RSA/ECC; hybrid TLS uses asymmetric to establish symmetric session keys.</dd><dt><strong>IDOR</strong></dt><dd>Insecure direct object reference—missing object-level authorization; test horizontal/vertical access with different accounts.</dd><dt><strong>IAM least privilege</strong></dt><dd>Grant minimum API/console rights; prefer roles over long-lived keys; audit risky admin-equivalent paths regularly.</dd><dt><strong>Supply chain security</strong></dt><dd>SBOM, provenance signing (SLSA-style thinking), and dependency pinning reduce “update from upstream” surprises.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Cloud responsibility</th><th>Who typically owns it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Patching the hypervisor</strong></td><td>Provider responsibility in major IaaS models—customer still patches guests.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>IAM policy and keys</strong></td><td>Customer-owned configuration—misconfigurations dominate incidents.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Data encryption at rest</strong></td><td>Often customer-controlled keys/KMS policies with provider primitives.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Network exposure (SGs/NACLs)</strong></td><td>Customer configures; default-deny patterns are exam favorites.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Application vulnerabilities</strong></td><td>Customer code and dependencies—shared model does not absolve secure SDLC.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>AES-128 is not “half as strong” as AES-256 in practical threat models for many cases—key management quality dominates.</li><li>SBOM formats (CycloneDX/SPDX) help inventory components for incident response and licensing—not only security.</li><li>KMS key policies can deny even root in AWS when configured—explicit deny wins.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li><li>GraphQL batching can amplify complexity attacks—depth and cost limits are first-class controls.</li><li>DNS over HTTPS changes visibility for some networks—understand resolver policy and logging tradeoffs.</li><li>Immutable backups mitigate ransomware that tries to delete online copies—air-gapped or WORM patterns.</li><li>ATT&CK technique IDs are stable references for detection content—good for purple team reporting.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L1-10: Phishing and social engineering basics</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L1-10: Phishing and social engineering basics</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L1-10: Phishing and social engineering basics</em>:</strong> Container escape questions hinge on <strong>kernel boundary</strong> and misconfigured capabilities—namespaces are helpful but not a complete trust boundary without seccomp, AppArmor, and least-privileged service accounts.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L1-10: Phishing and social engineering basics</em>:</strong> For the Security+ mindset, translate every control into <strong>who</strong> it protects, <strong>what</strong> asset is at risk, and <strong>how</strong> you would detect failure. Interview and exam items often reward practical prioritization over buzzwords—choose the mitigation that reduces realistic loss first.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L1-10: Phishing and social engineering basics</em>:</strong> Serverless cold start is not a security control; <strong>per-function IAM</strong> and least-privilege API scopes are. Watch for attractive nonsense distractors tied to performance tuning.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L1-10: Phishing and social engineering basics</em>:</strong> Controls fail in three predictable ways: <strong>misconfiguration</strong>, <strong>missing coverage</strong> (gaps between tools), and <strong>human process</strong> breakdown (exceptions, shared accounts, emergency access). When you read a scenario, ask which failure mode is most plausible before picking an answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L1-10: Phishing and social engineering basics</em>:</strong> KMS keys are not “magic secrecy dust”—<strong>who can invoke decrypt</strong> and from which contexts (VPC endpoint policies, IAM conditions) is what exams probe.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L1-10: Phishing and social engineering basics</em>:</strong> Defense in depth is not “more products,” it is <strong>independent mechanisms</strong>—if one layer is bypassed, another still limits movement, slows the adversary, or preserves evidence. Be ready to explain why network controls alone cannot compensate for missing app-layer authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L1-10: Phishing and social engineering basics</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L1-10: Phishing and social engineering basics</em>:</strong> Security operations value <strong>repeatable evidence</strong>: timestamps, authoritative configuration sources, and tamper-aware logs beat heroic memory after an incident. Many exam questions hinge on whether an action preserves integrity and accountability rather than whether it feels fast.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Marketing launches a campaign referencing “L1-10: Phishing and social engineering basics” with a new subdomain. Security review finds DNS delegated to an unknown party. Explain <strong>trust chain</strong> risks and the <strong>minimum fixes</strong> before go-live.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l1-11":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L1-11: Malware families at a glance</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-11</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Distinguish virus, worm, trojan, ransomware, cryptominer, spyware.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> EDR alerts often use these buckets.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>ls /usr/share/metasploit-framework/modules/payloads 2&gt;/dev/null | head</code> — <strong>do not</strong> generate traffic; note organization of payloads as a taxonomy exercise.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-11</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Expect “which control type?” questions—administrative vs technical vs physical—tied to realistic workplace moments like contractor onboarding.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 1 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Container security</strong></dt><dd>Image provenance, non-root users, read-only roots, seccomp/AppArmor, and admission control for risky capabilities.</dd><dt><strong>Insider threat</strong></dt><dd>Malicious or negligent insiders—monitor with proportionality, separation of duties, and HR/legal partnership.</dd><dt><strong>PQC</strong></dt><dd>Post-quantum cryptography migration—hybrid schemes and crypto-agility for long-lived secrets exposed to harvest-now/decrypt-later risk.</dd><dt><strong>SOC triage order</strong></dt><dd>Scope → impact → evidence → containment hypothesis; avoid fixing symptoms before you know blast radius.</dd><dt><strong>Replay attack</strong></dt><dd>Valid data maliciously re-sent—nonces, timestamps, and session freshness mitigate.</dd><dt><strong>Rainbow table</strong></dt><dd>Precomputed hash chains for fast password cracking—salting and modern KDFs are the defense.</dd><dt><strong>Diffie-Hellman (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Key agreement over insecure channel—combine with authentication to prevent MITM.</dd><dt><strong>NetFlow / IPFIX</strong></dt><dd>Flow metadata for volume and anomaly detection—lighter than PCAP but less payload visibility.</dd><dt><strong>OODA loop (IR)</strong></dt><dd>Observe-orient-decide-act—adversary and defender both iterate; faster, accurate decisions beat hoarding data.</dd><dt><strong>Data residency</strong></dt><dd>Legal requirement for where data lives—impacts cloud region selection and key custody.</dd><dt><strong>Digital signature</strong></dt><dd>Proves origin and integrity using private key to sign and public key to verify—non-repudiation when keys are well governed.</dd><dt><strong>Quantitative vs qualitative risk</strong></dt><dd>Qualitative uses scales (high/medium/low); quantitative uses dollar or probability estimates—both need consistent assumptions and reviewer judgment.</dd><dt><strong>Residual risk</strong></dt><dd>Risk remaining after controls are applied; organizations accept, transfer, mitigate, or avoid it explicitly.</dd><dt><strong>Authenticity</strong></dt><dd>Verifies that users, devices, or data are genuine—cryptographic identity, attestation, and strong issuance processes matter.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>AEAD</strong></td><td>Confidentiality + integrity together—misuse of IV/nonce still breaks security.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>ATT&CK technique IDs are stable references for detection content—good for purple team reporting.</li><li>HttpOnly does not stop CSRF; it reduces token theft from XSS reading document.cookie in many setups.</li><li>PCI DSS scope reduction via segmentation is a recurring theme—if it is not in scope, it cannot drag you into assessment.</li><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li><li>SLSA levels describe increasing supply-chain assurance—useful vocabulary in modern governance questions.</li><li>Azure AD / Entra conditional access is analogous to risk-based policies—device compliance signals matter.</li><li>Admission controllers can block privileged pods—policy-as-code integrates with GitOps reviews.</li><li>Server-side template injection is distinct from XSS—context and sinks differ.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L1-11: Malware families at a glance</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L1-11: Malware families at a glance</em>:</strong> Air gapped networks still need <strong>patching via sneaker-net</strong> and insider controls—physical isolation is not logical isolation.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L1-11: Malware families at a glance</em>:</strong> Incident response questions probe containment vs evidence preservation tension, legal escalation, and communication discipline. The exam rewards knowing when to isolate systems, when to involve counsel, and why mass log deletion is catastrophic.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L1-11: Malware families at a glance</em>:</strong> Industrial and OT adjacent questions reward knowing <strong>safety vs security</strong> tension: availability may trump confidentiality; testing must avoid breaking physical processes.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L1-11: Malware families at a glance</em>:</strong> API keys in mobile apps are often extractable—prefer <strong>short-lived tokens</strong> and server-mediated access to backends.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L1-11: Malware families at a glance</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L1-11: Malware families at a glance</em>:</strong> Physical security is still on the exam: tailgating, visitor escorts, locks, destruction of media, and environmental controls (fire, HVAC) as availability/confidentiality supports.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L1-11: Malware families at a glance</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L1-11: Malware families at a glance</em>:</strong> TACACS+ vs RADIUS separation of duties in device admin access—exams may contrast accounting granularity.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L1-11: Malware families at a glance</em>:</strong> Cryptography questions reward vocabulary precision: hashing vs encryption vs encoding; symmetric vs asymmetric roles in TLS; what signatures prove; and why key management is usually harder than picking an algorithm. If an answer sounds magical, it is probably wrong.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> A cloud bill spike correlates with traffic about “L1-11: Malware families at a glance”. Differentiate <strong>misconfiguration</strong> vs <strong>abuse</strong> in your first triage questions and what logs prove each hypothesis.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l1-12":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L1-12: Physical security and clean desk</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-12</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Tailgating, badge cloning (concept), device locks.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Data center access; visitor logs.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Set screen lock timeout in desktop settings; screenshot policy note (redact).</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-12</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>At Level 1, think like an analyst who must <strong>classify</strong> an event: asset, threat, vulnerability, control, residual risk. If you can narrate those five words for any headline topic, you are aligned with how writers build scenario questions.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 1 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Certificate pinning (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Client remembers expected server key material—reduces MITM from rogue CAs but complicates rotation; mostly seen in mobile/API hardening patterns.</dd><dt><strong>Secure SDLC</strong></dt><dd>Requirements, threat modeling, secure design, code review, SAST/DAST, dependency scanning, and hardened deployment pipelines.</dd><dt><strong>CASB / SaaS governance</strong></dt><dd>Visibility and policy for sanctioned vs shadow SaaS—OAuth consent attacks and guest sharing are common gaps.</dd><dt><strong>Forensics basics</strong></dt><dd>Volatile vs non-volatile collection, order of volatility, hashing, and legal escalation paths before deep technical work.</dd><dt><strong>Collision (hash)</strong></dt><dd>Two inputs produce same hash—breaks integrity assumptions; choose strong hash families for security use.</dd><dt><strong>RPO / RTO recap</strong></dt><dd>RPO = max acceptable data loss time; RTO = max acceptable outage—drive backup frequency and HA design.</dd><dt><strong>Vulnerability</strong></dt><dd>A weakness in design, implementation, configuration, or process that could be exploited to violate a security policy.</dd><dt><strong>Authorization</strong></dt><dd>What an authenticated subject is allowed to do—RBAC/ABAC, scopes, and server-side checks enforce least privilege.</dd><dt><strong>Perfect forward secrecy (PFS)</strong></dt><dd>Ephemeral key exchange means past session keys are not compromised if long-term keys leak later—TLS cipher suites can offer this property.</dd><dt><strong>Security headers</strong></dt><dd>HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options/Frame-ancestors, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy—reduce browser-driven attack surface.</dd><dt><strong>Serverless blast radius</strong></dt><dd>One broad execution role affects every invocation—scope IAM per function and watch environment variable leaks.</dd><dt><strong>Purple / red / blue</strong></dt><dd>Red emulates adversaries, blue defends, purple bridges—authorization and logging are mandatory for any simulation.</dd><dt><strong>Rainbow table</strong></dt><dd>Precomputed hash chains for fast password cracking—salting and modern KDFs are the defense.</dd><dt><strong>BGP prefix hijack</strong></dt><dd>Unauthorized route advertisement—RPKI ROV reduces impact but does not replace monitoring.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Typical exam angle</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Confidentiality</strong></td><td>Who may read? Encryption, ACLs, DLP, classification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Integrity</strong></td><td>Was it modified? Hashing, signatures, change control, backups.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Availability</strong></td><td>Can authorized users work? HA, patching windows, DDoS defense, DR.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authenticity / non-repudiation</strong></td><td>Prove source and intent—signatures, strong issuance, tamper-evident logs.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li><li>AES-128 is not “half as strong” as AES-256 in practical threat models for many cases—key management quality dominates.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>PCI DSS scope reduction via segmentation is a recurring theme—if it is not in scope, it cannot drag you into assessment.</li><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li><li>KMS key policies can deny even root in AWS when configured—explicit deny wins.</li><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L1-12: Physical security and clean desk</em>:</strong> Industrial and OT adjacent questions reward knowing <strong>safety vs security</strong> tension: availability may trump confidentiality; testing must avoid breaking physical processes.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L1-12: Physical security and clean desk</em>:</strong> API keys in mobile apps are often extractable—prefer <strong>short-lived tokens</strong> and server-mediated access to backends.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L1-12: Physical security and clean desk</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L1-12: Physical security and clean desk</em>:</strong> Physical security is still on the exam: tailgating, visitor escorts, locks, destruction of media, and environmental controls (fire, HVAC) as availability/confidentiality supports.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L1-12: Physical security and clean desk</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L1-12: Physical security and clean desk</em>:</strong> TACACS+ vs RADIUS separation of duties in device admin access—exams may contrast accounting granularity.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L1-12: Physical security and clean desk</em>:</strong> Cryptography questions reward vocabulary precision: hashing vs encryption vs encoding; symmetric vs asymmetric roles in TLS; what signatures prove; and why key management is usually harder than picking an algorithm. If an answer sounds magical, it is probably wrong.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L1-12: Physical security and clean desk</em>:</strong> Help desk scenarios test whether you know <strong>identity proofing</strong> vs <strong>account recovery</strong> abuse. The secure path verifies the human through out-of-band channels without teaching attackers how to bypass your process in the stem text.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L1-12: Physical security and clean desk</em>:</strong> Tabletop exercises test <strong>comms trees</strong>, legal escalation, and customer notification templates—not only technical runbooks.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L1-12: Physical security and clean desk</em>:</strong> Sanitization vs wiping vs destruction: exams like knowing which media needs <strong>degaussing, shredding, or crypto erase</strong> per policy.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> During a tabletop, the CFO asks how “L1-12: Physical security and clean desk” could become a material incident. Answer with <strong>one plausible attack path</strong>, <strong>one detective control</strong> you already have, and <strong>one preventive gap</strong> you would fund next quarter.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l1-13":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L1-13: Backups and recovery goals (RPO/RTO)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-13</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Define RPO/RTO; 3-2-1 rule.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> DR tabletop exercises.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>tar czf ~/lab-backup.tgz ~/lab-pii.txt</code>; verify <code>tar tzf ~/lab-backup.tgz</code>.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-13</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Expect “which control type?” questions—administrative vs technical vs physical—tied to realistic workplace moments like contractor onboarding.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 1 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Confidentiality</strong></dt><dd>Assures that information is not disclosed to unauthorized subjects—encryption, access control, and data minimization support it.</dd><dt><strong>Security headers</strong></dt><dd>HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options/Frame-ancestors, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy—reduce browser-driven attack surface.</dd><dt><strong>Token replay</strong></dt><dd>Reusing a stolen token/session artifact—rotation, binding, and short TTLs reduce window.</dd><dt><strong>Vulnerability</strong></dt><dd>A weakness in design, implementation, configuration, or process that could be exploited to violate a security policy.</dd><dt><strong>VPN</strong></dt><dd>Creates an encrypted tunnel; split tunneling can bypass corporate inspection; VPN is not anonymity or a substitute for app-layer auth.</dd><dt><strong>Security awareness</strong></dt><dd>Training plus culture—measure reporting rates, not shame metrics; phishing simulations should reinforce reporting.</dd><dt><strong>NetFlow / IPFIX</strong></dt><dd>Flow metadata for volume and anomaly detection—lighter than PCAP but less payload visibility.</dd><dt><strong>Integrity</strong></dt><dd>Assures accuracy and trustworthiness—hashing, signatures, change control, and backups protect against unauthorized modification.</dd><dt><strong>Secure SDLC</strong></dt><dd>Requirements, threat modeling, secure design, code review, SAST/DAST, dependency scanning, and hardened deployment pipelines.</dd><dt><strong>Replay attack</strong></dt><dd>Valid data maliciously re-sent—nonces, timestamps, and session freshness mitigate.</dd><dt><strong>Exploit</strong></dt><dd>A technique or code that takes advantage of a vulnerability to achieve an attacker goal (exfiltration, persistence, disruption).</dd><dt><strong>SPF / DKIM / DMARC</strong></dt><dd>Email authenticity stack—SPF authorizes senders, DKIM signs messages, DMARC aligns policies and reporting for abuse handling.</dd><dt><strong>Insider threat</strong></dt><dd>Malicious or negligent insiders—monitor with proportionality, separation of duties, and HR/legal partnership.</dd><dt><strong>Sinkhole (DNS)</strong></dt><dd>Controlled resolution for malicious domains—intel and disruption technique with legal process considerations.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>GCP service account keys are long-lived secrets—prefer workload identity federation from CI where possible.</li><li>Linux auth.log style entries pair with SSH brute-force detection patterns—velocity and geo anomalies.</li><li>SLSA levels describe increasing supply-chain assurance—useful vocabulary in modern governance questions.</li><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li><li>AES-128 is not “half as strong” as AES-256 in practical threat models for many cases—key management quality dominates.</li><li>Certificate pinning misconfigurations can brick apps—plan rotation and emergency releases.</li><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li><li>GraphQL batching can amplify complexity attacks—depth and cost limits are first-class controls.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L1-13: Backups and recovery goals (RPO/RTO)</em>:</strong> TACACS+ vs RADIUS separation of duties in device admin access—exams may contrast accounting granularity.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L1-13: Backups and recovery goals (RPO/RTO)</em>:</strong> Data handling questions often hinge on <strong>classification</strong>, <strong>least data</strong>, and <strong>retention</strong>: collect only what you need, keep it only as long as allowed, and destroy securely when done.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L1-13: Backups and recovery goals (RPO/RTO)</em>:</strong> Honeypots can generate high-signal alerts but carry <strong>legal and operational</strong> risk if touched by real users; scope carefully.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L1-13: Backups and recovery goals (RPO/RTO)</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L1-13: Backups and recovery goals (RPO/RTO)</em>:</strong> Deception tech is not a replacement for <strong>baselines and patching</strong>; it augments detection when mature processes exist.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L1-13: Backups and recovery goals (RPO/RTO)</em>:</strong> Engineers often optimize for speed; attackers optimize for <strong>cheap reuse</strong> of stolen creds and known exploits. The winning answer bridges both: ship fast with guardrails—feature flags, staged rollouts, and automated security checks in CI.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L1-13: Backups and recovery goals (RPO/RTO)</em>:</strong> Air gapped networks still need <strong>patching via sneaker-net</strong> and insider controls—physical isolation is not logical isolation.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L1-13: Backups and recovery goals (RPO/RTO)</em>:</strong> Help desk scenarios test whether you know <strong>identity proofing</strong> vs <strong>account recovery</strong> abuse. The secure path verifies the human through out-of-band channels without teaching attackers how to bypass your process in the stem text.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L1-13: Backups and recovery goals (RPO/RTO)</em>:</strong> Virtualization risks include <strong>snapshot sprawl</strong> containing secrets and stale VM images drifting from hardened baselines.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L1-13: Backups and recovery goals (RPO/RTO)</em>:</strong> Wireless assessments should mention <strong>rogue AP</strong> discovery, client isolation, and guest segmentation—not just “use WPA2” as a slogan. Exam writers like the distinction between personal and enterprise authentication modes at a conceptual level.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Purple team wants to simulate abuse of “L1-13: Backups and recovery goals (RPO/RTO)” next Friday. List <strong>safety gates</strong> (scope, rollback, monitoring) you require before authorizing the exercise.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l1-14":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L1-14: Patching and secure configuration</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-14</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Why delay windows exist; test rings.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Change management; CAB.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>apt list --upgradable 2&gt;/dev/null | head</code>; document one package and one risk of upgrading without testing.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-14</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Level 1 physical and operational items return to <strong>tailgating, visitor logs, and media destruction</strong>—do not skip them as “non-technical”; they are fair game.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 1 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Proxy vs reverse proxy</strong></dt><dd>Forward proxy represents clients outbound; reverse proxy fronts servers—different trust and logging points.</dd><dt><strong>Security control categories</strong></dt><dd>Technical (firewalls, encryption), administrative (policies, training), and physical (badges, locks)—exam items often ask which category fits a scenario.</dd><dt><strong>PII</strong></dt><dd>Personally identifiable information—names, government IDs, biometrics, account numbers; triggers handling, retention, and breach rules.</dd><dt><strong>Network segmentation</strong></dt><dd>VLANs, micro-segmentation, and east-west controls limit lateral movement after an initial foothold.</dd><dt><strong>Secure SDLC</strong></dt><dd>Requirements, threat modeling, secure design, code review, SAST/DAST, dependency scanning, and hardened deployment pipelines.</dd><dt><strong>BCP / DR</strong></dt><dd>Business continuity and disaster recovery—RTO/RPO drive architecture; test restores, not just backups on paper.</dd><dt><strong>Job rotation</strong></dt><dd>Reduces collusion and fraud risk; also surfaces “tribal knowledge” silos before an employee leaves.</dd><dt><strong>Diffie-Hellman (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Key agreement over insecure channel—combine with authentication to prevent MITM.</dd><dt><strong>SOAR</strong></dt><dd>Security orchestration, automation, response—playbooks must have human gates for destructive actions.</dd><dt><strong>Availability</strong></dt><dd>Assures timely and reliable access—redundancy, patching, DDoS defenses, and DR planning keep services usable for authorized users.</dd><dt><strong>DNS</strong></dt><dd>Name resolution is a trust anchor—DNSSEC, cache poisoning, and malicious resolutions are classic abuse paths; log resolver anomalies.</dd><dt><strong>XSS</strong></dt><dd>Cross-site scripting injects script in a victim context—CSP, output encoding, HttpOnly cookies, and DOM hygiene reduce blast radius.</dd><dt><strong>Container security</strong></dt><dd>Image provenance, non-root users, read-only roots, seccomp/AppArmor, and admission control for risky capabilities.</dd><dt><strong>Forensics basics</strong></dt><dd>Volatile vs non-volatile collection, order of volatility, hashing, and legal escalation paths before deep technical work.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Typical exam angle</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Confidentiality</strong></td><td>Who may read? Encryption, ACLs, DLP, classification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Integrity</strong></td><td>Was it modified? Hashing, signatures, change control, backups.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Availability</strong></td><td>Can authorized users work? HA, patching windows, DDoS defense, DR.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authenticity / non-repudiation</strong></td><td>Prove source and intent—signatures, strong issuance, tamper-evident logs.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>S3 bucket policies and ACLs layer with IAM—effective permissions require understanding intersection.</li><li>Certificate pinning misconfigurations can brick apps—plan rotation and emergency releases.</li><li>EPSS (concept) scores exploitation probability—useful alongside CVSS for prioritization in mature programs.</li><li>UDP-based protocols can be abused for amplification DDoS—patch open resolvers and monitor volumetric baselines.</li><li>KMS key policies can deny even root in AWS when configured—explicit deny wins.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>ATT&CK technique IDs are stable references for detection content—good for purple team reporting.</li><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L1-14: Patching and secure configuration</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L1-14: Patching and secure configuration</em>:</strong> When logs “mysteriously stop,” think <strong>time sync failure</strong>, collector saturation, retention misconfiguration, or attacker tampering—in that diagnostic order for a fair exam narrative.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L1-14: Patching and secure configuration</em>:</strong> Cryptojacking still appears: high CPU, unexpected mining pools, and cloud billing spikes—detection plus credential hygiene beats chasing miner signatures alone.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L1-14: Patching and secure configuration</em>:</strong> Multicloud complexity increases <strong>identity sprawl</strong>; centralized IdP and consistent conditional access policies reduce human error.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L1-14: Patching and secure configuration</em>:</strong> RADIUS is still referenced for <strong>network access control</strong> integrations; know it as a AAA component in enterprise Wi-Fi contexts.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L1-14: Patching and secure configuration</em>:</strong> TPM-backed BitLocker keys illustrate <strong>key protection</strong> binding to platform state—recovery keys must be guarded like crown jewels.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L1-14: Patching and secure configuration</em>:</strong> Defense in depth is not “more products,” it is <strong>independent mechanisms</strong>—if one layer is bypassed, another still limits movement, slows the adversary, or preserves evidence. Be ready to explain why network controls alone cannot compensate for missing app-layer authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L1-14: Patching and secure configuration</em>:</strong> Incident response questions probe containment vs evidence preservation tension, legal escalation, and communication discipline. The exam rewards knowing when to isolate systems, when to involve counsel, and why mass log deletion is catastrophic.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L1-14: Patching and secure configuration</em>:</strong> Physical security is still on the exam: tailgating, visitor escorts, locks, destruction of media, and environmental controls (fire, HVAC) as availability/confidentiality supports.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L1-14: Patching and secure configuration</em>:</strong> Help desk scenarios test whether you know <strong>identity proofing</strong> vs <strong>account recovery</strong> abuse. The secure path verifies the human through out-of-band channels without teaching attackers how to bypass your process in the stem text.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> A vendor integration project mentions “L1-14: Patching and secure configuration” as out-of-scope for pen testing. Explain what <strong>residual risk</strong> remains, what <strong>compensating monitoring</strong> you would demand, and how you would <strong>document acceptance</strong>.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l1-15":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L1-15: Security policies you will actually read</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-15</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> AUP, acceptable encryption, incident reporting, data classification.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Onboarding; insider risk.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Draft a 1-page “lab RoE” for yourself: allowed targets (your VM only), forbidden actions, logging expectations.</p>\n<h2>Lab pack — Level 1 (Kali VM, isolated network)</h2>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Identity baseline:</strong> Document users/groups; enable lock screen; remove unnecessary services from startup list (read-only survey).  </li>\n<li><strong>Evidence hygiene:</strong> Create <code>~/cases/2026-lab-01/</code>; copy one log excerpt with hash: <code>sha256sum</code> the file.  </li>\n<li><strong>Network sanity:</strong> <code>ip a</code>, <code>ip r</code>; draw ASCII diagram host → gateway → internet (or host-only).  </li>\n<li><strong>Update discipline:</strong> Simulate CAB: write test plan for one security update before <code>apt upgrade</code> (or document why withheld).  </li>\n<li><strong>Phishing response:</strong> Write a 10-line employee-facing “report suspicious email” procedure.</li>\n</ol>\n<h2>Question bank — Level 1</h2>\n<p><strong>Q1.</strong> Which pillar of CIA is most directly harmed by ransomware encrypting files?<br><strong>Q2.</strong> Non-repudiation is primarily supported by: (a) longer passwords (b) audit trails and signatures (c) RAID.<br><strong>Q3.</strong> Least privilege means: (a) everyone is admin (b) minimum rights to do the job (c) maximum logging.<br><strong>Q4.</strong> A vulnerability is: (a) a threat actor (b) a weakness that can be exploited (c) a firewall rule.<br><strong>Q5.</strong> RPO measures: (a) max downtime (b) max acceptable data loss window (c) password rotation.<br><strong>Q6.</strong> MFA requires at least: (a) one factor (b) two independent factors (c) biometrics only.<br><strong>Q7.</strong> 3-2-1 backups refer partly to: (a) three admins (b) copies across media and off-site (c) three firewalls.<br><strong>Q8.</strong> Tailgating is a: (a) network scan (b) physical access tactic (c) SQL attack.<br><strong>Q9.</strong> Privacy differs from security because: (a) they are identical (b) privacy centers on personal data rights (c) privacy ignores law.<br><strong>Q10.</strong> Separation of duties reduces: (a) availability (b) fraud and error by collusion (c) encryption strength.<br><strong>Q11.</strong> A trojan’s hallmark is: (a) self-propagation without user (b) disguised malicious payload (c) only physical damage.<br><strong>Q12.</strong> Integrity violation example: (a) DDoS (b) unauthorized ledger edit (c) stolen laptop only if powered off.<br><strong>Q13.</strong> <code>chmod 600</code> on a key file helps: (a) availability (b) confidentiality on a multi-user system (c) routing.<br><strong>Q14.</strong> Risk treatment “accept” means: (a) ignore forever (b) documented decision to tolerate risk (c) delete asset.<br><strong>Q15.</strong> Incident “first response” often includes: (a) silent deletion of logs (b) preserve evidence and notify chain (c) pay ransom immediately.<br><strong>Q16.</strong> Patch testing rings commonly: (a) skip dev (b) dev → test → prod (c) prod only.<br><strong>Q17.</strong> PII examples include: (a) public weather (b) government ID numbers (c) anonymous aggregate stats.<br><strong>Q18.</strong> Security policy’s role: (a) replace technical controls (b) set expectations and requirements (c) block all email.<br><strong>Q19.</strong> A worm differs from a virus mainly by: (a) color (b) autonomous spreading (c) needing paper.<br><strong>Q20.</strong> Availability control example: (a) RAID + redundant power (b) posting passwords (c) disabling backups.</p>\n<h3>Answer key — Level 1</h3>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Availability</strong> — encryption that denies access to data is primarily an availability hit (integrity of plaintext can also be argued; in workplace triage, “cannot work” is <strong>A</strong>).<br>2–5: B / B / B / B<br>6–10: B / B / B / B / B<br>11–15: B / B / B / B / B<br>16–20: B / B / B / B / B</li>\n</ol>\n<hr>\n<h1>Level 2 — Intermediate (networks, crypto vocabulary, common attacks)</h1>\n<p><strong>Workplace outcomes:</strong> You can read firewall tickets, TLS errors, and basic vuln scan output; you know OWASP names at a headline level.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-15</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Foundations on the exam often pair <strong>policy intent</strong> with <strong>technical examples</strong>—pick answers that show both, not policy theater without enforcement.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 1 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Serverless blast radius</strong></dt><dd>One broad execution role affects every invocation—scope IAM per function and watch environment variable leaks.</dd><dt><strong>CRL</strong></dt><dd>Certificate Revocation List—signed list of revoked serials; size/latency issues drove OCSP adoption.</dd><dt><strong>Data residency</strong></dt><dd>Legal requirement for where data lives—impacts cloud region selection and key custody.</dd><dt><strong>PII</strong></dt><dd>Personally identifiable information—names, government IDs, biometrics, account numbers; triggers handling, retention, and breach rules.</dd><dt><strong>Security misconfiguration</strong></dt><dd>Default creds, debug features on in prod, verbose errors, open directory listings—hardening baselines and drift detection reduce this class.</dd><dt><strong>Supply chain security</strong></dt><dd>SBOM, provenance signing (SLSA-style thinking), and dependency pinning reduce “update from upstream” surprises.</dd><dt><strong>MAC</strong></dt><dd>Message authentication code—integrity with a secret key; differs from digital signature which uses asymmetric keys.</dd><dt><strong>IDOR</strong></dt><dd>Insecure direct object reference—missing object-level authorization; test horizontal/vertical access with different accounts.</dd><dt><strong>SSO</strong></dt><dd>Single sign-on federates trust to an IdP—misconfigured SAML/OIDC trusts are high-impact; validate metadata and signing keys.</dd><dt><strong>DevSecOps</strong></dt><dd>Embed security gates in CI/CD with fast feedback—policy-as-code, secret scanning, and SBOMs support supply-chain resilience.</dd><dt><strong>Purple teaming</strong></dt><dd>Collaborative attack/defense exercises to validate detections without surprise production harm—scope and safety first.</dd><dt><strong>Full packet capture</strong></dt><dd>High fidelity evidence for investigations—storage, privacy, and legal review constraints apply.</dd><dt><strong>Threat</strong></dt><dd>Any circumstance or actor with the potential to cause harm by exploiting a vulnerability (malware, insider, natural disaster).</dd><dt><strong>VPN</strong></dt><dd>Creates an encrypted tunnel; split tunneling can bypass corporate inspection; VPN is not anonymity or a substitute for app-layer auth.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authorization</strong></td><td>Server-side object checks—headers and TLS do not replace this.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li><li>CVSS base does not include your asset criticality—environmental metrics exist for a reason.</li><li>OAuth access tokens are not a replacement for server-side authorization checks on every sensitive action.</li><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li><li>Responsible disclosure timelines balance vendor patch readiness with public safety—coordinate, don’t surprise.</li><li>Terraform state can hold secrets—remote secure backend and scanning are baseline hygiene.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L1-15: Security policies you will actually read</em>:</strong> Governance and awareness questions tie policy to behavior: acceptable use, clean desk, travel security, and vendor due diligence. Pick answers that reduce <strong>realistic</strong> human failure modes, not answers that maximize surveillance without process support.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L1-15: Security policies you will actually read</em>:</strong> When logs “mysteriously stop,” think <strong>time sync failure</strong>, collector saturation, retention misconfiguration, or attacker tampering—in that diagnostic order for a fair exam narrative.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L1-15: Security policies you will actually read</em>:</strong> CSP reporting helps tune policy but can leak URLs—<strong>privacy review</strong> of report endpoints matters in regulated environments.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L1-15: Security policies you will actually read</em>:</strong> Controls fail in three predictable ways: <strong>misconfiguration</strong>, <strong>missing coverage</strong> (gaps between tools), and <strong>human process</strong> breakdown (exceptions, shared accounts, emergency access). When you read a scenario, ask which failure mode is most plausible before picking an answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L1-15: Security policies you will actually read</em>:</strong> Third-party and supply chain answers should emphasize <strong>contracts</strong>, <strong>evidence</strong>, and <strong>continuous monitoring</strong>—not “trust the SOC 2 logo” without scope review.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L1-15: Security policies you will actually read</em>:</strong> Cryptojacking still appears: high CPU, unexpected mining pools, and cloud billing spikes—detection plus credential hygiene beats chasing miner signatures alone.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L1-15: Security policies you will actually read</em>:</strong> Deception tech is not a replacement for <strong>baselines and patching</strong>; it augments detection when mature processes exist.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L1-15: Security policies you will actually read</em>:</strong> Vulnerability management is a lifecycle: scanners find candidates, analysts prioritize with exploitability and business context, owners remediate, and verification closes the loop. “Patch everything immediately” is rarely operational; <strong>risk-based SLAs</strong> are the adult answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L1-15: Security policies you will actually read</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L1-15: Security policies you will actually read</em>:</strong> Multicloud complexity increases <strong>identity sprawl</strong>; centralized IdP and consistent conditional access policies reduce human error.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Internal audit samples “L1-15: Security policies you will actually read” controls and finds screenshots instead of config exports. Explain why <strong>authoritative evidence</strong> matters and what you would collect instead.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l2-01":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L2-01: TCP/IP model and trust boundaries</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-01</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Map segments, subnets, DMZ, zero trust hint.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>ss -tuln | head -n 30</code>; identify three listening ports and likely services.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-01</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Level 2 tracks Security+ <strong>architecture and hybrid environments</strong>: trust boundaries, TLS/certificates, DNS/email controls, VPN caveats, and headline application flaws. Explain <em>why</em> a control exists and <em>what misconfiguration breaks</em>.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 2 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>TLS</strong></dt><dd>Encrypts data in motion and authenticates endpoints when certificates and hostnames are validated; termination points affect trust boundaries.</dd><dt><strong>Compensating control</strong></dt><dd>Alternative control that meets intent when primary control cannot be implemented—must provide equivalent or greater assurance with documentation.</dd><dt><strong>Risk</strong></dt><dd>The intersection of threat, vulnerability, and impact—often assessed qualitatively (high/medium/low) or with scoring frameworks.</dd><dt><strong>Availability</strong></dt><dd>Assures timely and reliable access—redundancy, patching, DDoS defenses, and DR planning keep services usable for authorized users.</dd><dt><strong>Authorization</strong></dt><dd>What an authenticated subject is allowed to do—RBAC/ABAC, scopes, and server-side checks enforce least privilege.</dd><dt><strong>NAT (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Rewrites addresses/ports for traversal—security relevance includes logging visibility, port forwarding risks, and split tunnel implications for inspection.</dd><dt><strong>SPF / DKIM / DMARC</strong></dt><dd>Email authenticity stack—SPF authorizes senders, DKIM signs messages, DMARC aligns policies and reporting for abuse handling.</dd><dt><strong>Hashing</strong></dt><dd>One-way fingerprint for integrity verification—SHA-256 family; not secrecy; used with HMAC for keyed integrity.</dd><dt><strong>Security misconfiguration</strong></dt><dd>Default creds, debug features on in prod, verbose errors, open directory listings—hardening baselines and drift detection reduce this class.</dd><dt><strong>Secure SDLC</strong></dt><dd>Requirements, threat modeling, secure design, code review, SAST/DAST, dependency scanning, and hardened deployment pipelines.</dd><dt><strong>MITRE ATT&amp;CK</strong></dt><dd>Tactics (why) and techniques (how) adversaries operate—use for detection engineering, gap analysis, and purple team scenarios.</dd><dt><strong>Encryption at rest / in transit</strong></dt><dd>KMS/HSM-backed keys, envelope encryption, and TLS everywhere for administrative and user paths.</dd><dt><strong>Security awareness</strong></dt><dd>Training plus culture—measure reporting rates, not shame metrics; phishing simulations should reinforce reporting.</dd><dt><strong>Zero Trust architecture</strong></dt><dd>Identity-centric access with continuous verification—policy enforcement points for users, devices, and workloads.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>DNS over HTTPS changes visibility for some networks—understand resolver policy and logging tradeoffs.</li><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li><li>GCP service account keys are long-lived secrets—prefer workload identity federation from CI where possible.</li><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li><li>SameSite=Lax blocks many CSRF POSTs from cross-site contexts in modern browsers—know the nuance vs Strict.</li><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li><li>Certificate pinning misconfigurations can brick apps—plan rotation and emergency releases.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L2-01: TCP/IP model and trust boundaries</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L2-01: TCP/IP model and trust boundaries</em>:</strong> Third-party and supply chain answers should emphasize <strong>contracts</strong>, <strong>evidence</strong>, and <strong>continuous monitoring</strong>—not “trust the SOC 2 logo” without scope review.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L2-01: TCP/IP model and trust boundaries</em>:</strong> SAST finds issues early but produces false positives; <strong>triage workflows</strong> and developer feedback loops are part of a mature program, not “run tool once.”</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L2-01: TCP/IP model and trust boundaries</em>:</strong> TPM-backed BitLocker keys illustrate <strong>key protection</strong> binding to platform state—recovery keys must be guarded like crown jewels.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L2-01: TCP/IP model and trust boundaries</em>:</strong> Access control stems frequently mix <strong>role</strong> vs <strong>attribute</strong> vs <strong>rule</strong> models; pick the answer that matches the scenario’s constraints (temporary contractor, cross-department data, dynamic tags on resources).</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L2-01: TCP/IP model and trust boundaries</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L2-01: TCP/IP model and trust boundaries</em>:</strong> Deception tech is not a replacement for <strong>baselines and patching</strong>; it augments detection when mature processes exist.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L2-01: TCP/IP model and trust boundaries</em>:</strong> Cloud items assume you can articulate <strong>shared responsibility</strong>: what the provider patches vs what the customer must configure (IAM, encryption, network exposure). Misconfiguration beats novel cloud exploits in real incidents and on the exam.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L2-01: TCP/IP model and trust boundaries</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L2-01: TCP/IP model and trust boundaries</em>:</strong> LDAP vs Active Directory questions test directory concepts at a high level—binding, searches, and secure transport (LDAPS) appear often.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Internal audit samples “L2-01: TCP/IP model and trust boundaries” controls and finds screenshots instead of config exports. Explain why <strong>authoritative evidence</strong> matters and what you would collect instead.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l2-02":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L2-02: Firewalls, ports, and allowlists</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-02</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Default-deny; stateful inspection concept.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> If <code>ufw</code> present: <code>ufw status</code>; otherwise document <code>iptables -S 2&gt;/dev/null | head</code>.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-02</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Application-layer stems sneak in early: know where <strong>authorization</strong> must be enforced even if TLS is perfect.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 2 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Job rotation</strong></dt><dd>Reduces collusion and fraud risk; also surfaces “tribal knowledge” silos before an employee leaves.</dd><dt><strong>PBKDF2 / Argon2 (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Key derivation functions that slow brute force—work factors must track attacker economics.</dd><dt><strong>Jump server / bastion</strong></dt><dd>Hardened administrative entry point—centralizes session recording and access policy for admins.</dd><dt><strong>OODA loop (IR)</strong></dt><dd>Observe-orient-decide-act—adversary and defender both iterate; faster, accurate decisions beat hoarding data.</dd><dt><strong>Quantitative vs qualitative risk</strong></dt><dd>Qualitative uses scales (high/medium/low); quantitative uses dollar or probability estimates—both need consistent assumptions and reviewer judgment.</dd><dt><strong>Confidentiality</strong></dt><dd>Assures that information is not disclosed to unauthorized subjects—encryption, access control, and data minimization support it.</dd><dt><strong>FIDO2 / WebAuthn</strong></dt><dd>Phishing-resistant possession factors using asymmetric crypto and origin binding; preferred where supported.</dd><dt><strong>VPN</strong></dt><dd>Creates an encrypted tunnel; split tunneling can bypass corporate inspection; VPN is not anonymity or a substitute for app-layer auth.</dd><dt><strong>Encoding (e.g., Base64)</strong></dt><dd>Transforms representation without cryptographic protection—do not confuse with encryption or integrity.</dd><dt><strong>Secure SDLC</strong></dt><dd>Requirements, threat modeling, secure design, code review, SAST/DAST, dependency scanning, and hardened deployment pipelines.</dd><dt><strong>IAM least privilege</strong></dt><dd>Grant minimum API/console rights; prefer roles over long-lived keys; audit risky admin-equivalent paths regularly.</dd><dt><strong>Insider threat</strong></dt><dd>Malicious or negligent insiders—monitor with proportionality, separation of duties, and HR/legal partnership.</dd><dt><strong>Purple / red / blue</strong></dt><dd>Red emulates adversaries, blue defends, purple bridges—authorization and logging are mandatory for any simulation.</dd><dt><strong>Downgrade attack</strong></dt><dd>Forcing weaker crypto or protocols—HSTS and modern TLS config reduce browser downgrade paths.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Sigma rules are vendor-agnostic detection snippets—tuning required per log source fields.</li><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li><li>OAuth access tokens are not a replacement for server-side authorization checks on every sensitive action.</li><li>JWT alg:none historical vulnerability class—always validate algorithm and signature keys explicitly.</li><li>AES-128 is not “half as strong” as AES-256 in practical threat models for many cases—key management quality dominates.</li><li>Immutable backups mitigate ransomware that tries to delete online copies—air-gapped or WORM patterns.</li><li>Azure AD / Entra conditional access is analogous to risk-based policies—device compliance signals matter.</li><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L2-02: Firewalls, ports, and allowlists</em>:</strong> Deception tech is not a replacement for <strong>baselines and patching</strong>; it augments detection when mature processes exist.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L2-02: Firewalls, ports, and allowlists</em>:</strong> Engineers often optimize for speed; attackers optimize for <strong>cheap reuse</strong> of stolen creds and known exploits. The winning answer bridges both: ship fast with guardrails—feature flags, staged rollouts, and automated security checks in CI.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L2-02: Firewalls, ports, and allowlists</em>:</strong> Air gapped networks still need <strong>patching via sneaker-net</strong> and insider controls—physical isolation is not logical isolation.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L2-02: Firewalls, ports, and allowlists</em>:</strong> Help desk scenarios test whether you know <strong>identity proofing</strong> vs <strong>account recovery</strong> abuse. The secure path verifies the human through out-of-band channels without teaching attackers how to bypass your process in the stem text.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L2-02: Firewalls, ports, and allowlists</em>:</strong> Virtualization risks include <strong>snapshot sprawl</strong> containing secrets and stale VM images drifting from hardened baselines.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L2-02: Firewalls, ports, and allowlists</em>:</strong> Wireless assessments should mention <strong>rogue AP</strong> discovery, client isolation, and guest segmentation—not just “use WPA2” as a slogan. Exam writers like the distinction between personal and enterprise authentication modes at a conceptual level.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L2-02: Firewalls, ports, and allowlists</em>:</strong> BIOS/UEFI passwords and secure boot reduce some pre-boot attacks but do not stop <strong>evil maid</strong> classes without additional controls.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L2-02: Firewalls, ports, and allowlists</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L2-02: Firewalls, ports, and allowlists</em>:</strong> TPM-backed BitLocker keys illustrate <strong>key protection</strong> binding to platform state—recovery keys must be guarded like crown jewels.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L2-02: Firewalls, ports, and allowlists</em>:</strong> Industrial and OT adjacent questions reward knowing <strong>safety vs security</strong> tension: availability may trump confidentiality; testing must avoid breaking physical processes.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> You are the on-call analyst reviewing an alert tied to “L2-02: Firewalls, ports, and allowlists”. Leadership wants a <strong>60-second</strong> brief: business impact, evidence gaps, and the <strong>first</strong> containment step that preserves logs. No tool-specific jargon—prioritize scope, evidence, blast radius, then root-cause remediation under change control.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l2-03":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L2-03: TLS/HTTPS — certificates, chain, hostname check</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-03</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Why TLS termination matters; common misconfigurations.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>openssl s_client -connect example.com:443 -servername example.com &lt;/dev/null 2&gt;/dev/null | openssl x509 -noout -subject -dates</code> (read-only to public site).</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-03</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Email authenticity (SPF/DKIM/DMARC) is a frequent multi-part stem—read whether the failure is <strong>alignment</strong>, <strong>policy</strong>, or <strong>operator error</strong>.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 2 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Key management</strong></dt><dd>Generation, storage, rotation, and destruction—HSM/KMS patterns reduce exposure compared to software-only secrets.</dd><dt><strong>Misconfiguration</strong></dt><dd>Top cloud incident driver—public buckets, open security groups, permissive trust policies; IaC scanning catches drift early.</dd><dt><strong>SOC triage order</strong></dt><dd>Scope → impact → evidence → containment hypothesis; avoid fixing symptoms before you know blast radius.</dd><dt><strong>Port knocking (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Obscurity-based pre-auth to open firewall—weak alone; exam may present as non-primary control.</dd><dt><strong>Defense in depth</strong></dt><dd>Layered controls so one failure does not equal total failure—network, host, app, identity, and monitoring each contribute.</dd><dt><strong>Availability</strong></dt><dd>Assures timely and reliable access—redundancy, patching, DDoS defenses, and DR planning keep services usable for authorized users.</dd><dt><strong>Network segmentation</strong></dt><dd>VLANs, micro-segmentation, and east-west controls limit lateral movement after an initial foothold.</dd><dt><strong>CWE</strong></dt><dd>Common Weakness Enumeration—taxonomy of software weakness types that help root-cause fixes beyond one CVE instance.</dd><dt><strong>Attack surface</strong></dt><dd>The sum of exposure—every service, API, integration, and human workflow that can be reached by a threat; reduction beats perfect monitoring alone.</dd><dt><strong>Rainbow table</strong></dt><dd>Precomputed hash chains for fast password cracking—salting and modern KDFs are the defense.</dd><dt><strong>Kill chain / cyber kill chain</strong></dt><dd>Stages of intrusion—mapping controls and detections to stages clarifies coverage gaps.</dd><dt><strong>Exploit</strong></dt><dd>A technique or code that takes advantage of a vulnerability to achieve an attacker goal (exfiltration, persistence, disruption).</dd><dt><strong>NAT (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Rewrites addresses/ports for traversal—security relevance includes logging visibility, port forwarding risks, and split tunnel implications for inspection.</dd><dt><strong>Injection</strong></dt><dd>Untrusted input becomes part of a command or query—parameterized queries, input validation, and context escaping are core defenses.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Cloud responsibility</th><th>Who typically owns it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Patching the hypervisor</strong></td><td>Provider responsibility in major IaaS models—customer still patches guests.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>IAM policy and keys</strong></td><td>Customer-owned configuration—misconfigurations dominate incidents.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Data encryption at rest</strong></td><td>Often customer-controlled keys/KMS policies with provider primitives.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Network exposure (SGs/NACLs)</strong></td><td>Customer configures; default-deny patterns are exam favorites.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Application vulnerabilities</strong></td><td>Customer code and dependencies—shared model does not absolve secure SDLC.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>AES-128 is not “half as strong” as AES-256 in practical threat models for many cases—key management quality dominates.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>PCI DSS scope reduction via segmentation is a recurring theme—if it is not in scope, it cannot drag you into assessment.</li><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li><li>KMS key policies can deny even root in AWS when configured—explicit deny wins.</li><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li><li>SLSA levels describe increasing supply-chain assurance—useful vocabulary in modern governance questions.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L2-03: TLS/HTTPS — certificates, chain, hostname check</em>:</strong> API keys in mobile apps are often extractable—prefer <strong>short-lived tokens</strong> and server-mediated access to backends.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L2-03: TLS/HTTPS — certificates, chain, hostname check</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L2-03: TLS/HTTPS — certificates, chain, hostname check</em>:</strong> Physical security is still on the exam: tailgating, visitor escorts, locks, destruction of media, and environmental controls (fire, HVAC) as availability/confidentiality supports.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L2-03: TLS/HTTPS — certificates, chain, hostname check</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L2-03: TLS/HTTPS — certificates, chain, hostname check</em>:</strong> TACACS+ vs RADIUS separation of duties in device admin access—exams may contrast accounting granularity.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L2-03: TLS/HTTPS — certificates, chain, hostname check</em>:</strong> Cryptography questions reward vocabulary precision: hashing vs encryption vs encoding; symmetric vs asymmetric roles in TLS; what signatures prove; and why key management is usually harder than picking an algorithm. If an answer sounds magical, it is probably wrong.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L2-03: TLS/HTTPS — certificates, chain, hostname check</em>:</strong> Help desk scenarios test whether you know <strong>identity proofing</strong> vs <strong>account recovery</strong> abuse. The secure path verifies the human through out-of-band channels without teaching attackers how to bypass your process in the stem text.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L2-03: TLS/HTTPS — certificates, chain, hostname check</em>:</strong> Tabletop exercises test <strong>comms trees</strong>, legal escalation, and customer notification templates—not only technical runbooks.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L2-03: TLS/HTTPS — certificates, chain, hostname check</em>:</strong> Sanitization vs wiping vs destruction: exams like knowing which media needs <strong>degaussing, shredding, or crypto erase</strong> per policy.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L2-03: TLS/HTTPS — certificates, chain, hostname check</em>:</strong> Logging questions often test whether you understand <strong>what to log</strong> (who, what, when, where, outcome), <strong>time sync</strong> for correlation, and <strong>tamper resistance</strong> for evidentiary value—not whether you can collect infinite bytes.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> During a tabletop, the CFO asks how “L2-03: TLS/HTTPS — certificates, chain, hostname check” could become a material incident. Answer with <strong>one plausible attack path</strong>, <strong>one detective control</strong> you already have, and <strong>one preventive gap</strong> you would fund next quarter.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l2-04":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L2-04: DNS basics and DNS abuse (spoofing, cache poison — concept)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-04</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Describe how wrong DNS breaks trust.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>dig +short A example.com</code> and <code>dig +short TXT _dmarc.example.com</code> — interpret DMARC presence.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-04</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Application-layer stems sneak in early: know where <strong>authorization</strong> must be enforced even if TLS is perfect.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 2 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Authorization</strong></dt><dd>What an authenticated subject is allowed to do—RBAC/ABAC, scopes, and server-side checks enforce least privilege.</dd><dt><strong>XSS</strong></dt><dd>Cross-site scripting injects script in a victim context—CSP, output encoding, HttpOnly cookies, and DOM hygiene reduce blast radius.</dd><dt><strong>Attack surface</strong></dt><dd>The sum of exposure—every service, API, integration, and human workflow that can be reached by a threat; reduction beats perfect monitoring alone.</dd><dt><strong>MITM</strong></dt><dd>Man-in-the-middle intercepts or alters traffic—TLS with proper validation mitigates; corporate SSL inspection is its own trust zone.</dd><dt><strong>Network segmentation</strong></dt><dd>VLANs, micro-segmentation, and east-west controls limit lateral movement after an initial foothold.</dd><dt><strong>DDoS</strong></dt><dd>Distributed denial of service—volumetric, protocol, or application-layer floods; mitigations include scrubbing, anycast, rate limits, and architecture elasticity.</dd><dt><strong>CWE</strong></dt><dd>Common Weakness Enumeration—taxonomy of software weakness types that help root-cause fixes beyond one CVE instance.</dd><dt><strong>Business continuity testing</strong></dt><dd>Tabletops and technical failover drills reveal gaps in comms, dependencies, and vendor SLAs.</dd><dt><strong>Sinkhole (routing)</strong></dt><dd>Different meaning in BGP—be careful with homonyms on exams; read the stem’s context.</dd><dt><strong>Control</strong></dt><dd>Administrative, technical, or physical safeguards that reduce likelihood or impact of a security event (prevent, detect, correct).</dd><dt><strong>Logging &amp; monitoring</strong></dt><dd>CloudTrail-style management events differ from data-plane logs—enable central export, immutability, and alerting.</dd><dt><strong>Replay attack</strong></dt><dd>Valid data maliciously re-sent—nonces, timestamps, and session freshness mitigate.</dd><dt><strong>IOC</strong></dt><dd>Indicator of compromise—often ephemeral (IPs, domains); pair with TTP-based detections for durability.</dd><dt><strong>Availability</strong></dt><dd>Assures timely and reliable access—redundancy, patching, DDoS defenses, and DR planning keep services usable for authorized users.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Typical exam angle</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Confidentiality</strong></td><td>Who may read? Encryption, ACLs, DLP, classification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Integrity</strong></td><td>Was it modified? Hashing, signatures, change control, backups.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Availability</strong></td><td>Can authorized users work? HA, patching windows, DDoS defense, DR.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authenticity / non-repudiation</strong></td><td>Prove source and intent—signatures, strong issuance, tamper-evident logs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li><li>EPSS (concept) scores exploitation probability—useful alongside CVSS for prioritization in mature programs.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>Azure AD / Entra conditional access is analogous to risk-based policies—device compliance signals matter.</li><li>ISO 27001 is an ISMS standard; it emphasizes risk treatment and continual improvement, not a product checklist.</li><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li><li>Server-side template injection is distinct from XSS—context and sinks differ.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L2-04: DNS basics and DNS abuse (spoofing, cache poison — concept)</em>:</strong> Application security scenarios often test whether you know <strong>where</strong> enforcement belongs—browser controls supplement but do not replace server-side checks. SameSite cookies, CSP, and HttpOnly mitigate classes of issues; they do not fix broken object-level authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L2-04: DNS basics and DNS abuse (spoofing, cache poison — concept)</em>:</strong> Data handling questions often hinge on <strong>classification</strong>, <strong>least data</strong>, and <strong>retention</strong>: collect only what you need, keep it only as long as allowed, and destroy securely when done.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L2-04: DNS basics and DNS abuse (spoofing, cache poison — concept)</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L2-04: DNS basics and DNS abuse (spoofing, cache poison — concept)</em>:</strong> Subresource integrity protects against <strong>CDN compromise</strong> but requires operational discipline when vendors rotate files.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L2-04: DNS basics and DNS abuse (spoofing, cache poison — concept)</em>:</strong> Clean desk pairs with <strong>screen privacy</strong> and <strong>clear desk checks</strong> for regulated spaces—physical + procedural controls together.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L2-04: DNS basics and DNS abuse (spoofing, cache poison — concept)</em>:</strong> Governance and awareness questions tie policy to behavior: acceptable use, clean desk, travel security, and vendor due diligence. Pick answers that reduce <strong>realistic</strong> human failure modes, not answers that maximize surveillance without process support.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L2-04: DNS basics and DNS abuse (spoofing, cache poison — concept)</em>:</strong> Wireless assessments should mention <strong>rogue AP</strong> discovery, client isolation, and guest segmentation—not just “use WPA2” as a slogan. Exam writers like the distinction between personal and enterprise authentication modes at a conceptual level.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L2-04: DNS basics and DNS abuse (spoofing, cache poison — concept)</em>:</strong> SAST finds issues early but produces false positives; <strong>triage workflows</strong> and developer feedback loops are part of a mature program, not “run tool once.”</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L2-04: DNS basics and DNS abuse (spoofing, cache poison — concept)</em>:</strong> TACACS+ vs RADIUS separation of duties in device admin access—exams may contrast accounting granularity.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L2-04: DNS basics and DNS abuse (spoofing, cache poison — concept)</em>:</strong> Defense in depth is not “more products,” it is <strong>independent mechanisms</strong>—if one layer is bypassed, another still limits movement, slows the adversary, or preserves evidence. Be ready to explain why network controls alone cannot compensate for missing app-layer authorization.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> A vendor integration project mentions “L2-04: DNS basics and DNS abuse (spoofing, cache poison — concept)” as out-of-scope for pen testing. Explain what <strong>residual risk</strong> remains, what <strong>compensating monitoring</strong> you would demand, and how you would <strong>document acceptance</strong>.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l2-05":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L2-05: VPN goals and limits (“VPN is not anonymity by default”)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-05</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Tunnel vs policy enforcement; split tunnel risks.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Document your VM’s default route and MTU: <code>ip r</code>; <code>ping -c 3 1.1.1.1</code>.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-05</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Level 2 tracks Security+ <strong>architecture and hybrid environments</strong>: trust boundaries, TLS/certificates, DNS/email controls, VPN caveats, and headline application flaws. Explain <em>why</em> a control exists and <em>what misconfiguration breaks</em>.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 2 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Certificate transparency (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Public logs of issued certs help detect mis-issued certificates for your domains.</dd><dt><strong>Zero Trust (headline)</strong></dt><dd>Assume breach; verify explicitly per request using identity, device posture, and least privilege—not “trust the LAN.”</dd><dt><strong>Symmetric encryption</strong></dt><dd>Same key encrypts and decrypts—fast for bulk data (AES-GCM); key distribution is the hard problem.</dd><dt><strong>Attack surface</strong></dt><dd>The sum of exposure—every service, API, integration, and human workflow that can be reached by a threat; reduction beats perfect monitoring alone.</dd><dt><strong>MTTD / MTTR</strong></dt><dd>Mean time to detect / remediate—quality matters; gaming metrics by closing tickets inflates false success.</dd><dt><strong>MFA</strong></dt><dd>Multi-factor authentication—requires two or more independent factors; push fatigue and MFA phishing are real bypass paths.</dd><dt><strong>Chain of custody</strong></dt><dd>Documented handling of evidence from collection through presentation—hashing, write blockers, and access logs support admissibility.</dd><dt><strong>Block cipher vs stream</strong></dt><dd>Block operates on fixed-size chunks; stream on bits/bytes—misuse modes (e.g., ECB) create patterns.</dd><dt><strong>Vulnerability</strong></dt><dd>A weakness in design, implementation, configuration, or process that could be exploited to violate a security policy.</dd><dt><strong>AEAD</strong></dt><dd>Authenticated encryption with associated data—confidentiality plus integrity in one primitive (e.g., AES-GCM) when used correctly.</dd><dt><strong>Forensics basics</strong></dt><dd>Volatile vs non-volatile collection, order of volatility, hashing, and legal escalation paths before deep technical work.</dd><dt><strong>UEBA</strong></dt><dd>User and entity behavior analytics—baseline deviations; tune to avoid HR/privacy backlash.</dd><dt><strong>DDoS</strong></dt><dd>Distributed denial of service—volumetric, protocol, or application-layer floods; mitigations include scrubbing, anycast, rate limits, and architecture elasticity.</dd><dt><strong>Serverless blast radius</strong></dt><dd>One broad execution role affects every invocation—scope IAM per function and watch environment variable leaks.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Cloud responsibility</th><th>Who typically owns it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Patching the hypervisor</strong></td><td>Provider responsibility in major IaaS models—customer still patches guests.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>IAM policy and keys</strong></td><td>Customer-owned configuration—misconfigurations dominate incidents.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Data encryption at rest</strong></td><td>Often customer-controlled keys/KMS policies with provider primitives.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Network exposure (SGs/NACLs)</strong></td><td>Customer configures; default-deny patterns are exam favorites.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Application vulnerabilities</strong></td><td>Customer code and dependencies—shared model does not absolve secure SDLC.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>SLSA levels describe increasing supply-chain assurance—useful vocabulary in modern governance questions.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li><li>Split tunnel VPN can exfil corporate data outside inspection if misconfigured—policy and routing matter.</li><li>CVSS base does not include your asset criticality—environmental metrics exist for a reason.</li><li>UDP-based protocols can be abused for amplification DDoS—patch open resolvers and monitor volumetric baselines.</li><li>Azure AD / Entra conditional access is analogous to risk-based policies—device compliance signals matter.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L2-05: VPN goals and limits (“VPN is not anonymity by default”)</em>:</strong> Data handling questions often hinge on <strong>classification</strong>, <strong>least data</strong>, and <strong>retention</strong>: collect only what you need, keep it only as long as allowed, and destroy securely when done.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L2-05: VPN goals and limits (“VPN is not anonymity by default”)</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L2-05: VPN goals and limits (“VPN is not anonymity by default”)</em>:</strong> Subresource integrity protects against <strong>CDN compromise</strong> but requires operational discipline when vendors rotate files.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L2-05: VPN goals and limits (“VPN is not anonymity by default”)</em>:</strong> Clean desk pairs with <strong>screen privacy</strong> and <strong>clear desk checks</strong> for regulated spaces—physical + procedural controls together.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L2-05: VPN goals and limits (“VPN is not anonymity by default”)</em>:</strong> Governance and awareness questions tie policy to behavior: acceptable use, clean desk, travel security, and vendor due diligence. Pick answers that reduce <strong>realistic</strong> human failure modes, not answers that maximize surveillance without process support.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L2-05: VPN goals and limits (“VPN is not anonymity by default”)</em>:</strong> Wireless assessments should mention <strong>rogue AP</strong> discovery, client isolation, and guest segmentation—not just “use WPA2” as a slogan. Exam writers like the distinction between personal and enterprise authentication modes at a conceptual level.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L2-05: VPN goals and limits (“VPN is not anonymity by default”)</em>:</strong> SAST finds issues early but produces false positives; <strong>triage workflows</strong> and developer feedback loops are part of a mature program, not “run tool once.”</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L2-05: VPN goals and limits (“VPN is not anonymity by default”)</em>:</strong> TACACS+ vs RADIUS separation of duties in device admin access—exams may contrast accounting granularity.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L2-05: VPN goals and limits (“VPN is not anonymity by default”)</em>:</strong> Defense in depth is not “more products,” it is <strong>independent mechanisms</strong>—if one layer is bypassed, another still limits movement, slows the adversary, or preserves evidence. Be ready to explain why network controls alone cannot compensate for missing app-layer authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L2-05: VPN goals and limits (“VPN is not anonymity by default”)</em>:</strong> Wireless and mobility items reward knowing basics: WPA3 improvements conceptually, evil twin risks, captive portals, and why client isolation matters on guest networks—without memorizing obsolete WEP details unless explicitly historical.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> An engineer wants emergency access to production to debug “L2-05: VPN goals and limits (“VPN is not anonymity by default”)” during change freeze. Outline <strong>break-glass</strong> steps: who approves, how sessions are recorded, and how credentials are rotated after.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l2-06":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L2-06: Email security (SPF, DKIM, DMARC) at SOC level</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-06</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> What each solves; alignment failures.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Pick <strong>your</strong> domain if authorized, else <code>example.com</code> headers in received email (sanitized screenshot).</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-06</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Application-layer stems sneak in early: know where <strong>authorization</strong> must be enforced even if TLS is perfect.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 2 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Due care</strong></dt><dd>The effort a prudent person would take to meet a duty; in security, reasonable steps to protect assets and stakeholders.</dd><dt><strong>Non-repudiation</strong></dt><dd>Prevents a party from credibly denying an action—digital signatures, tamper-evident logs, and time-stamping support it.</dd><dt><strong>FIDO2 / WebAuthn</strong></dt><dd>Phishing-resistant possession factors using asymmetric crypto and origin binding; preferred where supported.</dd><dt><strong>Defense in depth</strong></dt><dd>Layered controls so one failure does not equal total failure—network, host, app, identity, and monitoring each contribute.</dd><dt><strong>Network segmentation</strong></dt><dd>VLANs, micro-segmentation, and east-west controls limit lateral movement after an initial foothold.</dd><dt><strong>PKI</strong></dt><dd>Public Key Infrastructure—CAs, RAs, CRL/OCSP, and certificate lifecycle; mis-issuance or weak validation breaks trust chains.</dd><dt><strong>Injection</strong></dt><dd>Untrusted input becomes part of a command or query—parameterized queries, input validation, and context escaping are core defenses.</dd><dt><strong>CVE</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures identifier for a specific flaw—pairs with CVSS severity and vendor advisories for prioritization.</dd><dt><strong>Chain of custody</strong></dt><dd>Documented handling of evidence from collection through presentation—hashing, write blockers, and access logs support admissibility.</dd><dt><strong>Serverless blast radius</strong></dt><dd>One broad execution role affects every invocation—scope IAM per function and watch environment variable leaks.</dd><dt><strong>Data retention</strong></dt><dd>Shorter retention reduces exposure and cost—legal holds override routine deletion when investigations require preservation.</dd><dt><strong>Confidential computing</strong></dt><dd>Use of hardware enclaves/TEEs to reduce exposure to privileged operators—threat model still required.</dd><dt><strong>Separation of duties (SoD)</strong></dt><dd>No single person can complete a sensitive transaction alone—classic finance control that also limits insider abuse.</dd><dt><strong>Downgrade attack</strong></dt><dd>Forcing weaker crypto or protocols—HSTS and modern TLS config reduce browser downgrade paths.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>IR phase</th><th>What you do there (exam shorthand)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Prepare</strong></td><td>Playbooks, contacts, tooling, baseline logging—before the pager fires.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detect &amp; analyze</strong></td><td>Scope, timelines, hypotheses—preserve volatile evidence early.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Contain</strong></td><td>Stop spread with minimal evidence damage—network isolation variants matter.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Eradicate &amp; recover</strong></td><td>Remove persistence, patch root cause, restore with verification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Lessons learned</strong></td><td>Metrics, control changes, and communication improvements—close the loop.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authorization</strong></td><td>Server-side object checks—headers and TLS do not replace this.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li><li>SameSite=Lax blocks many CSRF POSTs from cross-site contexts in modern browsers—know the nuance vs Strict.</li><li>Bug bounty scope must exclude destructive testing—safe harbor language still needs legal review.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li><li>HttpOnly does not stop CSRF; it reduces token theft from XSS reading document.cookie in many setups.</li><li>Responsible disclosure timelines balance vendor patch readiness with public safety—coordinate, don’t surprise.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L2-06: Email security (SPF, DKIM, DMARC) at SOC level</em>:</strong> Defense in depth is not “more products,” it is <strong>independent mechanisms</strong>—if one layer is bypassed, another still limits movement, slows the adversary, or preserves evidence. Be ready to explain why network controls alone cannot compensate for missing app-layer authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L2-06: Email security (SPF, DKIM, DMARC) at SOC level</em>:</strong> API keys in mobile apps are often extractable—prefer <strong>short-lived tokens</strong> and server-mediated access to backends.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L2-06: Email security (SPF, DKIM, DMARC) at SOC level</em>:</strong> Help desk scenarios test whether you know <strong>identity proofing</strong> vs <strong>account recovery</strong> abuse. The secure path verifies the human through out-of-band channels without teaching attackers how to bypass your process in the stem text.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L2-06: Email security (SPF, DKIM, DMARC) at SOC level</em>:</strong> Security operations value <strong>repeatable evidence</strong>: timestamps, authoritative configuration sources, and tamper-aware logs beat heroic memory after an incident. Many exam questions hinge on whether an action preserves integrity and accountability rather than whether it feels fast.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L2-06: Email security (SPF, DKIM, DMARC) at SOC level</em>:</strong> GraphQL introspection risk is about <strong>schema discovery</strong> aiding attackers—rate limits, authz on fields, and disabling introspection in prod are common answers.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L2-06: Email security (SPF, DKIM, DMARC) at SOC level</em>:</strong> Wireless assessments should mention <strong>rogue AP</strong> discovery, client isolation, and guest segmentation—not just “use WPA2” as a slogan. Exam writers like the distinction between personal and enterprise authentication modes at a conceptual level.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L2-06: Email security (SPF, DKIM, DMARC) at SOC level</em>:</strong> Risk decisions are economic: organizations <strong>accept</strong>, <strong>mitigate</strong>, <strong>transfer</strong> (insurance, outsourcing with contracts), or <strong>avoid</strong> (stop the activity). Controls change likelihood or impact; residual risk should be explicit, not invisible.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L2-06: Email security (SPF, DKIM, DMARC) at SOC level</em>:</strong> CSP reporting helps tune policy but can leak URLs—<strong>privacy review</strong> of report endpoints matters in regulated environments.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L2-06: Email security (SPF, DKIM, DMARC) at SOC level</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L2-06: Email security (SPF, DKIM, DMARC) at SOC level</em>:</strong> Identity is the new perimeter: credentials, tokens, and sessions are stolen more often than novel zero-days are burned. Expect Security+ items on MFA bypass awareness, phishing-resistant factors, and why <strong>authorization</strong> must be enforced server-side.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> A cloud bill spike correlates with traffic about “L2-06: Email security (SPF, DKIM, DMARC) at SOC level”. Differentiate <strong>misconfiguration</strong> vs <strong>abuse</strong> in your first triage questions and what logs prove each hypothesis.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l2-07":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L2-07: Hashing vs encryption vs encoding</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-07</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> One-way vs reversible vs representation.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>echo -n test | md5sum</code> vs <code>openssl enc -aes-256-cbc -pbkdf2 -pass pass:lab -in /etc/hosts -out ~/enc.bin</code> then explain which is reversible.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-07</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Level 2 tracks Security+ <strong>architecture and hybrid environments</strong>: trust boundaries, TLS/certificates, DNS/email controls, VPN caveats, and headline application flaws. Explain <em>why</em> a control exists and <em>what misconfiguration breaks</em>.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 2 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>NAT (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Rewrites addresses/ports for traversal—security relevance includes logging visibility, port forwarding risks, and split tunnel implications for inspection.</dd><dt><strong>Asymmetric encryption</strong></dt><dd>Key pairs for key agreement/signing—RSA/ECC; hybrid TLS uses asymmetric to establish symmetric session keys.</dd><dt><strong>IDOR</strong></dt><dd>Insecure direct object reference—missing object-level authorization; test horizontal/vertical access with different accounts.</dd><dt><strong>IAM least privilege</strong></dt><dd>Grant minimum API/console rights; prefer roles over long-lived keys; audit risky admin-equivalent paths regularly.</dd><dt><strong>Supply chain security</strong></dt><dd>SBOM, provenance signing (SLSA-style thinking), and dependency pinning reduce “update from upstream” surprises.</dd><dt><strong>Separation of duties (SoD)</strong></dt><dd>No single person can complete a sensitive transaction alone—classic finance control that also limits insider abuse.</dd><dt><strong>Rainbow table</strong></dt><dd>Precomputed hash chains for fast password cracking—salting and modern KDFs are the defense.</dd><dt><strong>Full packet capture</strong></dt><dd>High fidelity evidence for investigations—storage, privacy, and legal review constraints apply.</dd><dt><strong>SOAR</strong></dt><dd>Security orchestration, automation, response—playbooks must have human gates for destructive actions.</dd><dt><strong>AEAD</strong></dt><dd>Authenticated encryption with associated data—confidentiality plus integrity in one primitive (e.g., AES-GCM) when used correctly.</dd><dt><strong>Policy vs standard vs procedure</strong></dt><dd>Policy states intent; standards define mandatory requirements; procedures are step-by-step how-to for operators.</dd><dt><strong>Password policy</strong></dt><dd>Modern guidance favors long passphrases, breach-banned lists, and vaults over rotation-for-its-own-sake complexity theater.</dd><dt><strong>Network segmentation</strong></dt><dd>VLANs, micro-segmentation, and east-west controls limit lateral movement after an initial foothold.</dd><dt><strong>OWASP Top 10</strong></dt><dd>High-prevalence web risks—broken access control and crypto failures often dominate; study each category with one workplace example.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>IR phase</th><th>What you do there (exam shorthand)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Prepare</strong></td><td>Playbooks, contacts, tooling, baseline logging—before the pager fires.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detect &amp; analyze</strong></td><td>Scope, timelines, hypotheses—preserve volatile evidence early.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Contain</strong></td><td>Stop spread with minimal evidence damage—network isolation variants matter.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Eradicate &amp; recover</strong></td><td>Remove persistence, patch root cause, restore with verification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Lessons learned</strong></td><td>Metrics, control changes, and communication improvements—close the loop.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>AEAD</strong></td><td>Confidentiality + integrity together—misuse of IV/nonce still breaks security.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>SBOM formats (CycloneDX/SPDX) help inventory components for incident response and licensing—not only security.</li><li>HttpOnly does not stop CSRF; it reduces token theft from XSS reading document.cookie in many setups.</li><li>Certificate pinning misconfigurations can brick apps—plan rotation and emergency releases.</li><li>GCP service account keys are long-lived secrets—prefer workload identity federation from CI where possible.</li><li>OAuth access tokens are not a replacement for server-side authorization checks on every sensitive action.</li><li>Split tunnel VPN can exfil corporate data outside inspection if misconfigured—policy and routing matter.</li><li>KMS key policies can deny even root in AWS when configured—explicit deny wins.</li><li>PCI DSS scope reduction via segmentation is a recurring theme—if it is not in scope, it cannot drag you into assessment.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L2-07: Hashing vs encryption vs encoding</em>:</strong> Incident response questions probe containment vs evidence preservation tension, legal escalation, and communication discipline. The exam rewards knowing when to isolate systems, when to involve counsel, and why mass log deletion is catastrophic.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L2-07: Hashing vs encryption vs encoding</em>:</strong> DAST exercises running apps but misses authz logic without credentials; combine with <strong>manual review</strong> for business-rule flaws.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L2-07: Hashing vs encryption vs encoding</em>:</strong> Cryptography questions reward vocabulary precision: hashing vs encryption vs encoding; symmetric vs asymmetric roles in TLS; what signatures prove; and why key management is usually harder than picking an algorithm. If an answer sounds magical, it is probably wrong.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L2-07: Hashing vs encryption vs encoding</em>:</strong> Cryptojacking still appears: high CPU, unexpected mining pools, and cloud billing spikes—detection plus credential hygiene beats chasing miner signatures alone.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L2-07: Hashing vs encryption vs encoding</em>:</strong> Security operations value <strong>repeatable evidence</strong>: timestamps, authoritative configuration sources, and tamper-aware logs beat heroic memory after an incident. Many exam questions hinge on whether an action preserves integrity and accountability rather than whether it feels fast.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L2-07: Hashing vs encryption vs encoding</em>:</strong> KMS keys are not “magic secrecy dust”—<strong>who can invoke decrypt</strong> and from which contexts (VPC endpoint policies, IAM conditions) is what exams probe.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L2-07: Hashing vs encryption vs encoding</em>:</strong> For the Security+ mindset, translate every control into <strong>who</strong> it protects, <strong>what</strong> asset is at risk, and <strong>how</strong> you would detect failure. Interview and exam items often reward practical prioritization over buzzwords—choose the mitigation that reduces realistic loss first.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L2-07: Hashing vs encryption vs encoding</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L2-07: Hashing vs encryption vs encoding</em>:</strong> Social engineering callbacks to <strong>pretexting</strong>, <strong>baiting</strong>, and <strong>vishing</strong>—name the subtype when the stem describes the tactic.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L2-07: Hashing vs encryption vs encoding</em>:</strong> Industrial and OT adjacent questions reward knowing <strong>safety vs security</strong> tension: availability may trump confidentiality; testing must avoid breaking physical processes.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Marketing launches a campaign referencing “L2-07: Hashing vs encryption vs encoding” with a new subdomain. Security review finds DNS delegated to an unknown party. Explain <strong>trust chain</strong> risks and the <strong>minimum fixes</strong> before go-live.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l2-08":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L2-08: Symmetric vs asymmetric crypto</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-08</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Speed, key distribution, hybrid TLS.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>openssl pkey -in /etc/ssl/certs/ssl-cert-snakeoil.pem 2&gt;/dev/null</code> (may fail) — instead <code>ls /etc/ssl/certs | head</code> and note PEM as text format.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-08</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Application-layer stems sneak in early: know where <strong>authorization</strong> must be enforced even if TLS is perfect.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 2 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>TLS</strong></dt><dd>Encrypts data in motion and authenticates endpoints when certificates and hostnames are validated; termination points affect trust boundaries.</dd><dt><strong>Vulnerability</strong></dt><dd>A weakness in design, implementation, configuration, or process that could be exploited to violate a security policy.</dd><dt><strong>Authenticity</strong></dt><dd>Verifies that users, devices, or data are genuine—cryptographic identity, attestation, and strong issuance processes matter.</dd><dt><strong>SSO</strong></dt><dd>Single sign-on federates trust to an IdP—misconfigured SAML/OIDC trusts are high-impact; validate metadata and signing keys.</dd><dt><strong>Network segmentation</strong></dt><dd>VLANs, micro-segmentation, and east-west controls limit lateral movement after an initial foothold.</dd><dt><strong>Input validation vs output encoding</strong></dt><dd>Validation rejects bad input early; encoding neutralizes dangerous characters in the right output context—both are needed across HTML, SQL, OS, and LDAP channels.</dd><dt><strong>CVSS</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerability Scoring System—base metrics describe technical severity; environmental and temporal modifiers refine priority.</dd><dt><strong>Encryption at rest / in transit</strong></dt><dd>KMS/HSM-backed keys, envelope encryption, and TLS everywhere for administrative and user paths.</dd><dt><strong>Metrics that matter</strong></dt><dd>Mean time to detect/remediate with quality, coverage of critical assets, and control effectiveness—not vanity ticket counts.</dd><dt><strong>SOC triage order</strong></dt><dd>Scope → impact → evidence → containment hypothesis; avoid fixing symptoms before you know blast radius.</dd><dt><strong>CRL</strong></dt><dd>Certificate Revocation List—signed list of revoked serials; size/latency issues drove OCSP adoption.</dd><dt><strong>MITM</strong></dt><dd>Man-in-the-middle intercepts or alters traffic—TLS with proper validation mitigates; corporate SSL inspection is its own trust zone.</dd><dt><strong>Warm site / cold site</strong></dt><dd>Warm has partial hardware ready; cold is space only—cost vs recovery speed tradeoff.</dd><dt><strong>NAT (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Rewrites addresses/ports for traversal—security relevance includes logging visibility, port forwarding risks, and split tunnel implications for inspection.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Sigma rules are vendor-agnostic detection snippets—tuning required per log source fields.</li><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>UDP-based protocols can be abused for amplification DDoS—patch open resolvers and monitor volumetric baselines.</li><li>Bug bounty scope must exclude destructive testing—safe harbor language still needs legal review.</li><li>GCP service account keys are long-lived secrets—prefer workload identity federation from CI where possible.</li><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li><li>Race conditions in web apps can undermine authorization—sequential logic tests in secure design reviews.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L2-08: Symmetric vs asymmetric crypto</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L2-08: Symmetric vs asymmetric crypto</em>:</strong> Security operations value <strong>repeatable evidence</strong>: timestamps, authoritative configuration sources, and tamper-aware logs beat heroic memory after an incident. Many exam questions hinge on whether an action preserves integrity and accountability rather than whether it feels fast.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L2-08: Symmetric vs asymmetric crypto</em>:</strong> Subresource integrity protects against <strong>CDN compromise</strong> but requires operational discipline when vendors rotate files.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L2-08: Symmetric vs asymmetric crypto</em>:</strong> When logs “mysteriously stop,” think <strong>time sync failure</strong>, collector saturation, retention misconfiguration, or attacker tampering—in that diagnostic order for a fair exam narrative.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L2-08: Symmetric vs asymmetric crypto</em>:</strong> Cloud items assume you can articulate <strong>shared responsibility</strong>: what the provider patches vs what the customer must configure (IAM, encryption, network exposure). Misconfiguration beats novel cloud exploits in real incidents and on the exam.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L2-08: Symmetric vs asymmetric crypto</em>:</strong> Air gapped networks still need <strong>patching via sneaker-net</strong> and insider controls—physical isolation is not logical isolation.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L2-08: Symmetric vs asymmetric crypto</em>:</strong> Cryptojacking still appears: high CPU, unexpected mining pools, and cloud billing spikes—detection plus credential hygiene beats chasing miner signatures alone.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L2-08: Symmetric vs asymmetric crypto</em>:</strong> Patching and change management appear as <strong>risk tradeoffs</strong>: emergency patches vs testing rings; compensating monitoring when patching lags; and documenting exceptions for auditors.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L2-08: Symmetric vs asymmetric crypto</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L2-08: Symmetric vs asymmetric crypto</em>:</strong> Multicloud complexity increases <strong>identity sprawl</strong>; centralized IdP and consistent conditional access policies reduce human error.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Marketing launches a campaign referencing “L2-08: Symmetric vs asymmetric crypto” with a new subdomain. Security review finds DNS delegated to an unknown party. Explain <strong>trust chain</strong> risks and the <strong>minimum fixes</strong> before go-live.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l2-09":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L2-09: Digital signatures and PKI roles (CA, RA, subscriber)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-09</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Why private keys must stay protected.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>ls -l /etc/ssl/private 2&gt;/dev/null</code> — note permissions pattern.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-09</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Level 2 tracks Security+ <strong>architecture and hybrid environments</strong>: trust boundaries, TLS/certificates, DNS/email controls, VPN caveats, and headline application flaws. Explain <em>why</em> a control exists and <em>what misconfiguration breaks</em>.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 2 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Metrics that matter</strong></dt><dd>Mean time to detect/remediate with quality, coverage of critical assets, and control effectiveness—not vanity ticket counts.</dd><dt><strong>Salt (crypto)</strong></dt><dd>Random input to a password hash to defeat rainbow tables—must be unique per password.</dd><dt><strong>OODA loop (IR)</strong></dt><dd>Observe-orient-decide-act—adversary and defender both iterate; faster, accurate decisions beat hoarding data.</dd><dt><strong>Threat</strong></dt><dd>Any circumstance or actor with the potential to cause harm by exploiting a vulnerability (malware, insider, natural disaster).</dd><dt><strong>SSO</strong></dt><dd>Single sign-on federates trust to an IdP—misconfigured SAML/OIDC trusts are high-impact; validate metadata and signing keys.</dd><dt><strong>Security misconfiguration</strong></dt><dd>Default creds, debug features on in prod, verbose errors, open directory listings—hardening baselines and drift detection reduce this class.</dd><dt><strong>Serverless blast radius</strong></dt><dd>One broad execution role affects every invocation—scope IAM per function and watch environment variable leaks.</dd><dt><strong>Mandatory vacation</strong></dt><dd>Forces handover and review of another employee’s work—can uncover fraud or backdoors.</dd><dt><strong>WAF vs IPS</strong></dt><dd>WAF focuses on application-layer attacks; IPS often line-rate network signatures—overlap exists but priorities differ.</dd><dt><strong>Digital signature</strong></dt><dd>Proves origin and integrity using private key to sign and public key to verify—non-repudiation when keys are well governed.</dd><dt><strong>Privacy</strong></dt><dd>Protection of personal information and individual rights—overlaps with security but adds legal/regulatory obligations (GDPR-style).</dd><dt><strong>Symmetric encryption</strong></dt><dd>Same key encrypts and decrypts—fast for bulk data (AES-GCM); key distribution is the hard problem.</dd><dt><strong>MITRE ATT&amp;CK</strong></dt><dd>Tactics (why) and techniques (how) adversaries operate—use for detection engineering, gap analysis, and purple team scenarios.</dd><dt><strong>Confidential computing</strong></dt><dd>Use of hardware enclaves/TEEs to reduce exposure to privileged operators—threat model still required.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Cloud responsibility</th><th>Who typically owns it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Patching the hypervisor</strong></td><td>Provider responsibility in major IaaS models—customer still patches guests.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>IAM policy and keys</strong></td><td>Customer-owned configuration—misconfigurations dominate incidents.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Data encryption at rest</strong></td><td>Often customer-controlled keys/KMS policies with provider primitives.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Network exposure (SGs/NACLs)</strong></td><td>Customer configures; default-deny patterns are exam favorites.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Application vulnerabilities</strong></td><td>Customer code and dependencies—shared model does not absolve secure SDLC.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>AEAD</strong></td><td>Confidentiality + integrity together—misuse of IV/nonce still breaks security.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li><li>EPSS (concept) scores exploitation probability—useful alongside CVSS for prioritization in mature programs.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>Azure AD / Entra conditional access is analogous to risk-based policies—device compliance signals matter.</li><li>ISO 27001 is an ISMS standard; it emphasizes risk treatment and continual improvement, not a product checklist.</li><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li><li>Server-side template injection is distinct from XSS—context and sinks differ.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L2-09: Digital signatures and PKI roles (CA, RA, subscriber)</em>:</strong> Application security scenarios often test whether you know <strong>where</strong> enforcement belongs—browser controls supplement but do not replace server-side checks. SameSite cookies, CSP, and HttpOnly mitigate classes of issues; they do not fix broken object-level authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L2-09: Digital signatures and PKI roles (CA, RA, subscriber)</em>:</strong> Third-party and supply chain answers should emphasize <strong>contracts</strong>, <strong>evidence</strong>, and <strong>continuous monitoring</strong>—not “trust the SOC 2 logo” without scope review.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L2-09: Digital signatures and PKI roles (CA, RA, subscriber)</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L2-09: Digital signatures and PKI roles (CA, RA, subscriber)</em>:</strong> Tabletop exercises test <strong>comms trees</strong>, legal escalation, and customer notification templates—not only technical runbooks.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L2-09: Digital signatures and PKI roles (CA, RA, subscriber)</em>:</strong> Honeypots can generate high-signal alerts but carry <strong>legal and operational</strong> risk if touched by real users; scope carefully.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L2-09: Digital signatures and PKI roles (CA, RA, subscriber)</em>:</strong> Controls fail in three predictable ways: <strong>misconfiguration</strong>, <strong>missing coverage</strong> (gaps between tools), and <strong>human process</strong> breakdown (exceptions, shared accounts, emergency access). When you read a scenario, ask which failure mode is most plausible before picking an answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L2-09: Digital signatures and PKI roles (CA, RA, subscriber)</em>:</strong> Advanced topics still return to fundamentals: least privilege, segmentation, logging, and tested recovery. When you see Zero Trust or PQC buzzwords, map them back to concrete controls and threat models rather than treating them as magic shields.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L2-09: Digital signatures and PKI roles (CA, RA, subscriber)</em>:</strong> Help desk scenarios test whether you know <strong>identity proofing</strong> vs <strong>account recovery</strong> abuse. The secure path verifies the human through out-of-band channels without teaching attackers how to bypass your process in the stem text.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L2-09: Digital signatures and PKI roles (CA, RA, subscriber)</em>:</strong> Ransomware stems often pair encryption with <strong>exfiltration</strong>—the correct answer may include legal/notification obligations, not only restoring from backup.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L2-09: Digital signatures and PKI roles (CA, RA, subscriber)</em>:</strong> CSP reporting helps tune policy but can leak URLs—<strong>privacy review</strong> of report endpoints matters in regulated environments.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> A cloud bill spike correlates with traffic about “L2-09: Digital signatures and PKI roles (CA, RA, subscriber)”. Differentiate <strong>misconfiguration</strong> vs <strong>abuse</strong> in your first triage questions and what logs prove each hypothesis.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l2-10":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L2-10: OWASP Top 10 recognition (2021)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-10</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Name 5 categories with one-line meaning.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Offline reading of OWASP page PDF save in <code>~/refs/</code> + 10 bullet summary.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-10</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Hybrid identity and remote access scenarios appear here—know when <strong>split tunneling</strong> changes what your security tools can see.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 2 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Block cipher vs stream</strong></dt><dd>Block operates on fixed-size chunks; stream on bits/bytes—misuse modes (e.g., ECB) create patterns.</dd><dt><strong>TTP</strong></dt><dd>Tactics, techniques, and procedures—behavioral patterns; harder to change than IOCs, better for resilient detection.</dd><dt><strong>Risk</strong></dt><dd>The intersection of threat, vulnerability, and impact—often assessed qualitatively (high/medium/low) or with scoring frameworks.</dd><dt><strong>Defense in depth</strong></dt><dd>Layered controls so one failure does not equal total failure—network, host, app, identity, and monitoring each contribute.</dd><dt><strong>CSRF</strong></dt><dd>Cross-site request forgery rides ambient auth—anti-CSRF tokens, SameSite cookies, and re-auth for sensitive actions help.</dd><dt><strong>Third-party risk</strong></dt><dd>Vendor access expands attack surface—DPAs, SOC reports, and continuous monitoring for critical suppliers.</dd><dt><strong>Replay attack</strong></dt><dd>Valid data maliciously re-sent—nonces, timestamps, and session freshness mitigate.</dd><dt><strong>Sinkhole (routing)</strong></dt><dd>Different meaning in BGP—be careful with homonyms on exams; read the stem’s context.</dd><dt><strong>DevSecOps</strong></dt><dd>Embed security gates in CI/CD with fast feedback—policy-as-code, secret scanning, and SBOMs support supply-chain resilience.</dd><dt><strong>Authorization</strong></dt><dd>What an authenticated subject is allowed to do—RBAC/ABAC, scopes, and server-side checks enforce least privilege.</dd><dt><strong>PKI</strong></dt><dd>Public Key Infrastructure—CAs, RAs, CRL/OCSP, and certificate lifecycle; mis-issuance or weak validation breaks trust chains.</dd><dt><strong>IAM least privilege</strong></dt><dd>Grant minimum API/console rights; prefer roles over long-lived keys; audit risky admin-equivalent paths regularly.</dd><dt><strong>Forensics basics</strong></dt><dd>Volatile vs non-volatile collection, order of volatility, hashing, and legal escalation paths before deep technical work.</dd><dt><strong>Diffie-Hellman (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Key agreement over insecure channel—combine with authentication to prevent MITM.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authorization</strong></td><td>Server-side object checks—headers and TLS do not replace this.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li><li>Linux auth.log style entries pair with SSH brute-force detection patterns—velocity and geo anomalies.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li><li>Sigma rules are vendor-agnostic detection snippets—tuning required per log source fields.</li><li>Race conditions in web apps can undermine authorization—sequential logic tests in secure design reviews.</li><li>Responsible disclosure timelines balance vendor patch readiness with public safety—coordinate, don’t surprise.</li><li>EPSS (concept) scores exploitation probability—useful alongside CVSS for prioritization in mature programs.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L2-10: OWASP Top 10 recognition (2021)</em>:</strong> Data handling questions often hinge on <strong>classification</strong>, <strong>least data</strong>, and <strong>retention</strong>: collect only what you need, keep it only as long as allowed, and destroy securely when done.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L2-10: OWASP Top 10 recognition (2021)</em>:</strong> Serverless cold start is not a security control; <strong>per-function IAM</strong> and least-privilege API scopes are. Watch for attractive nonsense distractors tied to performance tuning.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L2-10: OWASP Top 10 recognition (2021)</em>:</strong> Multicloud complexity increases <strong>identity sprawl</strong>; centralized IdP and consistent conditional access policies reduce human error.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L2-10: OWASP Top 10 recognition (2021)</em>:</strong> Air gapped networks still need <strong>patching via sneaker-net</strong> and insider controls—physical isolation is not logical isolation.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L2-10: OWASP Top 10 recognition (2021)</em>:</strong> Security operations value <strong>repeatable evidence</strong>: timestamps, authoritative configuration sources, and tamper-aware logs beat heroic memory after an incident. Many exam questions hinge on whether an action preserves integrity and accountability rather than whether it feels fast.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L2-10: OWASP Top 10 recognition (2021)</em>:</strong> Access control stems frequently mix <strong>role</strong> vs <strong>attribute</strong> vs <strong>rule</strong> models; pick the answer that matches the scenario’s constraints (temporary contractor, cross-department data, dynamic tags on resources).</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L2-10: OWASP Top 10 recognition (2021)</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L2-10: OWASP Top 10 recognition (2021)</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L2-10: OWASP Top 10 recognition (2021)</em>:</strong> Certificate pinning failures during rotation teach why <strong>key continuity strategy</strong> must be planned before mobile releases.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L2-10: OWASP Top 10 recognition (2021)</em>:</strong> Social engineering callbacks to <strong>pretexting</strong>, <strong>baiting</strong>, and <strong>vishing</strong>—name the subtype when the stem describes the tactic.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> An engineer wants emergency access to production to debug “L2-10: OWASP Top 10 recognition (2021)” during change freeze. Outline <strong>break-glass</strong> steps: who approves, how sessions are recorded, and how credentials are rotated after.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l2-11":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L2-11: Injection (SQLi) concept and defense</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-11</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Parameterized queries, ORM pitfalls.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> On <strong>local</strong> DVWA if installed with auth; <strong>otherwise</strong> write 2 safe vs 2 unsafe pseudo-queries in <code>sqli-notes.md</code> — no live exploitation outside scope.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-11</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Application-layer stems sneak in early: know where <strong>authorization</strong> must be enforced even if TLS is perfect.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 2 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Purple / red / blue</strong></dt><dd>Red emulates adversaries, blue defends, purple bridges—authorization and logging are mandatory for any simulation.</dd><dt><strong>WAF vs IPS</strong></dt><dd>WAF focuses on application-layer attacks; IPS often line-rate network signatures—overlap exists but priorities differ.</dd><dt><strong>Compensating control</strong></dt><dd>Alternative control that meets intent when primary control cannot be implemented—must provide equivalent or greater assurance with documentation.</dd><dt><strong>DDoS</strong></dt><dd>Distributed denial of service—volumetric, protocol, or application-layer floods; mitigations include scrubbing, anycast, rate limits, and architecture elasticity.</dd><dt><strong>CVE</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures identifier for a specific flaw—pairs with CVSS severity and vendor advisories for prioritization.</dd><dt><strong>Threat modeling (STRIDE)</strong></dt><dd>Spoofing, tampering, repudiation, information disclosure, denial of service, elevation of privilege—drive controls early.</dd><dt><strong>Jump server / bastion</strong></dt><dd>Hardened administrative entry point—centralizes session recording and access policy for admins.</dd><dt><strong>DevSecOps</strong></dt><dd>Embed security gates in CI/CD with fast feedback—policy-as-code, secret scanning, and SBOMs support supply-chain resilience.</dd><dt><strong>Kerberos (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Ticket-based enterprise auth—TGT vs service tickets; golden/silver ticket classes of abuse appear in advanced IR.</dd><dt><strong>Secure SDLC</strong></dt><dd>Requirements, threat modeling, secure design, code review, SAST/DAST, dependency scanning, and hardened deployment pipelines.</dd><dt><strong>PQC</strong></dt><dd>Post-quantum cryptography migration—hybrid schemes and crypto-agility for long-lived secrets exposed to harvest-now/decrypt-later risk.</dd><dt><strong>MITM</strong></dt><dd>Man-in-the-middle intercepts or alters traffic—TLS with proper validation mitigates; corporate SSL inspection is its own trust zone.</dd><dt><strong>Security headers</strong></dt><dd>HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options/Frame-ancestors, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy—reduce browser-driven attack surface.</dd><dt><strong>Session management</strong></dt><dd>Server-side session IDs or tokens must rotate on privilege change, bind to channel, and expire predictably.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authorization</strong></td><td>Server-side object checks—headers and TLS do not replace this.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>DNS over HTTPS changes visibility for some networks—understand resolver policy and logging tradeoffs.</li><li>Azure AD / Entra conditional access is analogous to risk-based policies—device compliance signals matter.</li><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li><li>S3 bucket policies and ACLs layer with IAM—effective permissions require understanding intersection.</li><li>ISO 27001 is an ISMS standard; it emphasizes risk treatment and continual improvement, not a product checklist.</li><li>Immutable backups mitigate ransomware that tries to delete online copies—air-gapped or WORM patterns.</li><li>Admission controllers can block privileged pods—policy-as-code integrates with GitOps reviews.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L2-11: Injection (SQLi) concept and defense</em>:</strong> When logs “mysteriously stop,” think <strong>time sync failure</strong>, collector saturation, retention misconfiguration, or attacker tampering—in that diagnostic order for a fair exam narrative.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L2-11: Injection (SQLi) concept and defense</em>:</strong> CSP reporting helps tune policy but can leak URLs—<strong>privacy review</strong> of report endpoints matters in regulated environments.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L2-11: Injection (SQLi) concept and defense</em>:</strong> Controls fail in three predictable ways: <strong>misconfiguration</strong>, <strong>missing coverage</strong> (gaps between tools), and <strong>human process</strong> breakdown (exceptions, shared accounts, emergency access). When you read a scenario, ask which failure mode is most plausible before picking an answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L2-11: Injection (SQLi) concept and defense</em>:</strong> Third-party and supply chain answers should emphasize <strong>contracts</strong>, <strong>evidence</strong>, and <strong>continuous monitoring</strong>—not “trust the SOC 2 logo” without scope review.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L2-11: Injection (SQLi) concept and defense</em>:</strong> Cryptojacking still appears: high CPU, unexpected mining pools, and cloud billing spikes—detection plus credential hygiene beats chasing miner signatures alone.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L2-11: Injection (SQLi) concept and defense</em>:</strong> Deception tech is not a replacement for <strong>baselines and patching</strong>; it augments detection when mature processes exist.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L2-11: Injection (SQLi) concept and defense</em>:</strong> Vulnerability management is a lifecycle: scanners find candidates, analysts prioritize with exploitability and business context, owners remediate, and verification closes the loop. “Patch everything immediately” is rarely operational; <strong>risk-based SLAs</strong> are the adult answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L2-11: Injection (SQLi) concept and defense</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L2-11: Injection (SQLi) concept and defense</em>:</strong> Multicloud complexity increases <strong>identity sprawl</strong>; centralized IdP and consistent conditional access policies reduce human error.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L2-11: Injection (SQLi) concept and defense</em>:</strong> Clean desk pairs with <strong>screen privacy</strong> and <strong>clear desk checks</strong> for regulated spaces—physical + procedural controls together.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> You are the on-call analyst reviewing an alert tied to “L2-11: Injection (SQLi) concept and defense”. Leadership wants a <strong>60-second</strong> brief: business impact, evidence gaps, and the <strong>first</strong> containment step that preserves logs. No tool-specific jargon—prioritize scope, evidence, blast radius, then root-cause remediation under change control.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l2-12":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L2-12: XSS (stored/reflected/DOM) and CSP as mitigation</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-12</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Explain trust of input vs output encoding.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Minimal <code>index.html</code> echoing <code>location.hash</code> — describe attack line without hosting publicly.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-12</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Email authenticity (SPF/DKIM/DMARC) is a frequent multi-part stem—read whether the failure is <strong>alignment</strong>, <strong>policy</strong>, or <strong>operator error</strong>.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 2 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Session management</strong></dt><dd>Server-side session IDs or tokens must rotate on privilege change, bind to channel, and expire predictably.</dd><dt><strong>Logging &amp; monitoring</strong></dt><dd>CloudTrail-style management events differ from data-plane logs—enable central export, immutability, and alerting.</dd><dt><strong>MAC</strong></dt><dd>Message authentication code—integrity with a secret key; differs from digital signature which uses asymmetric keys.</dd><dt><strong>Risk</strong></dt><dd>The intersection of threat, vulnerability, and impact—often assessed qualitatively (high/medium/low) or with scoring frameworks.</dd><dt><strong>OWASP Top 10</strong></dt><dd>High-prevalence web risks—broken access control and crypto failures often dominate; study each category with one workplace example.</dd><dt><strong>Separation of duties (SoD)</strong></dt><dd>No single person can complete a sensitive transaction alone—classic finance control that also limits insider abuse.</dd><dt><strong>Input validation vs output encoding</strong></dt><dd>Validation rejects bad input early; encoding neutralizes dangerous characters in the right output context—both are needed across HTML, SQL, OS, and LDAP channels.</dd><dt><strong>TLS</strong></dt><dd>Encrypts data in motion and authenticates endpoints when certificates and hostnames are validated; termination points affect trust boundaries.</dd><dt><strong>BCP / DR</strong></dt><dd>Business continuity and disaster recovery—RTO/RPO drive architecture; test restores, not just backups on paper.</dd><dt><strong>WAF vs IPS</strong></dt><dd>WAF focuses on application-layer attacks; IPS often line-rate network signatures—overlap exists but priorities differ.</dd><dt><strong>Availability</strong></dt><dd>Assures timely and reliable access—redundancy, patching, DDoS defenses, and DR planning keep services usable for authorized users.</dd><dt><strong>DevSecOps</strong></dt><dd>Embed security gates in CI/CD with fast feedback—policy-as-code, secret scanning, and SBOMs support supply-chain resilience.</dd><dt><strong>Downgrade attack</strong></dt><dd>Forcing weaker crypto or protocols—HSTS and modern TLS config reduce browser downgrade paths.</dd><dt><strong>Security headers</strong></dt><dd>HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options/Frame-ancestors, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy—reduce browser-driven attack surface.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authorization</strong></td><td>Server-side object checks—headers and TLS do not replace this.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>JWT alg:none historical vulnerability class—always validate algorithm and signature keys explicitly.</li><li>GCP service account keys are long-lived secrets—prefer workload identity federation from CI where possible.</li><li>PCI DSS scope reduction via segmentation is a recurring theme—if it is not in scope, it cannot drag you into assessment.</li><li>Linux auth.log style entries pair with SSH brute-force detection patterns—velocity and geo anomalies.</li><li>Race conditions in web apps can undermine authorization—sequential logic tests in secure design reviews.</li><li>SLSA levels describe increasing supply-chain assurance—useful vocabulary in modern governance questions.</li><li>SameSite=Lax blocks many CSRF POSTs from cross-site contexts in modern browsers—know the nuance vs Strict.</li><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L2-12: XSS (stored/reflected/DOM) and CSP as mitigation</em>:</strong> CSP reporting helps tune policy but can leak URLs—<strong>privacy review</strong> of report endpoints matters in regulated environments.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L2-12: XSS (stored/reflected/DOM) and CSP as mitigation</em>:</strong> Email security stems often combine SPF alignment failures with <strong>look-alike domains</strong>. The best answer addresses user training plus technical authenticity controls, not only one or the other.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L2-12: XSS (stored/reflected/DOM) and CSP as mitigation</em>:</strong> Incident response questions probe containment vs evidence preservation tension, legal escalation, and communication discipline. The exam rewards knowing when to isolate systems, when to involve counsel, and why mass log deletion is catastrophic.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L2-12: XSS (stored/reflected/DOM) and CSP as mitigation</em>:</strong> Deception tech is not a replacement for <strong>baselines and patching</strong>; it augments detection when mature processes exist.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L2-12: XSS (stored/reflected/DOM) and CSP as mitigation</em>:</strong> Ransomware stems often pair encryption with <strong>exfiltration</strong>—the correct answer may include legal/notification obligations, not only restoring from backup.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L2-12: XSS (stored/reflected/DOM) and CSP as mitigation</em>:</strong> Physical security is still on the exam: tailgating, visitor escorts, locks, destruction of media, and environmental controls (fire, HVAC) as availability/confidentiality supports.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L2-12: XSS (stored/reflected/DOM) and CSP as mitigation</em>:</strong> Clean desk pairs with <strong>screen privacy</strong> and <strong>clear desk checks</strong> for regulated spaces—physical + procedural controls together.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L2-12: XSS (stored/reflected/DOM) and CSP as mitigation</em>:</strong> Evidence bags and write blockers signal <strong>forensics awareness</strong>; touching disks before imaging is a classic wrong answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L2-12: XSS (stored/reflected/DOM) and CSP as mitigation</em>:</strong> Help desk scenarios test whether you know <strong>identity proofing</strong> vs <strong>account recovery</strong> abuse. The secure path verifies the human through out-of-band channels without teaching attackers how to bypass your process in the stem text.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L2-12: XSS (stored/reflected/DOM) and CSP as mitigation</em>:</strong> Identity is the new perimeter: credentials, tokens, and sessions are stolen more often than novel zero-days are burned. Expect Security+ items on MFA bypass awareness, phishing-resistant factors, and why <strong>authorization</strong> must be enforced server-side.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Purple team wants to simulate abuse of “L2-12: XSS (stored/reflected/DOM) and CSP as mitigation” next Friday. List <strong>safety gates</strong> (scope, rollback, monitoring) you require before authorizing the exercise.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l2-13":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L2-13: CSRF and anti-CSRF tokens</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-13</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Why state-changing POSTs need protection.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Diagram cookie + cross-site POST flow in ASCII.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-13</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>TLS questions separate <strong>confidentiality channel</strong> from <strong>server authentication</strong>—certificate validation and hostname checks matter in the answer set.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 2 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Vulnerability</strong></dt><dd>A weakness in design, implementation, configuration, or process that could be exploited to violate a security policy.</dd><dt><strong>DNS</strong></dt><dd>Name resolution is a trust anchor—DNSSEC, cache poisoning, and malicious resolutions are classic abuse paths; log resolver anomalies.</dd><dt><strong>SIEM</strong></dt><dd>Security information and event management—centralize logs, parse fields, correlate alerts; tuning reduces false positives and fatigue.</dd><dt><strong>Business continuity testing</strong></dt><dd>Tabletops and technical failover drills reveal gaps in comms, dependencies, and vendor SLAs.</dd><dt><strong>NetFlow / IPFIX</strong></dt><dd>Flow metadata for volume and anomaly detection—lighter than PCAP but less payload visibility.</dd><dt><strong>Asset</strong></dt><dd>Anything of value to the organization—data, systems, people, reputation, or services—that security controls protect.</dd><dt><strong>Firewall</strong></dt><dd>Enforces allow/deny rules on traffic—stateful inspection tracks sessions; default-deny with explicit permits is the secure baseline.</dd><dt><strong>CWE</strong></dt><dd>Common Weakness Enumeration—taxonomy of software weakness types that help root-cause fixes beyond one CVE instance.</dd><dt><strong>Purple / red / blue</strong></dt><dd>Red emulates adversaries, blue defends, purple bridges—authorization and logging are mandatory for any simulation.</dd><dt><strong>WAF vs IPS</strong></dt><dd>WAF focuses on application-layer attacks; IPS often line-rate network signatures—overlap exists but priorities differ.</dd><dt><strong>Compensating control</strong></dt><dd>Alternative control that meets intent when primary control cannot be implemented—must provide equivalent or greater assurance with documentation.</dd><dt><strong>DDoS</strong></dt><dd>Distributed denial of service—volumetric, protocol, or application-layer floods; mitigations include scrubbing, anycast, rate limits, and architecture elasticity.</dd><dt><strong>CVE</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures identifier for a specific flaw—pairs with CVSS severity and vendor advisories for prioritization.</dd><dt><strong>Threat modeling (STRIDE)</strong></dt><dd>Spoofing, tampering, repudiation, information disclosure, denial of service, elevation of privilege—drive controls early.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authorization</strong></td><td>Server-side object checks—headers and TLS do not replace this.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Immutable backups mitigate ransomware that tries to delete online copies—air-gapped or WORM patterns.</li><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li><li>DNS over HTTPS changes visibility for some networks—understand resolver policy and logging tradeoffs.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>GraphQL batching can amplify complexity attacks—depth and cost limits are first-class controls.</li><li>Race conditions in web apps can undermine authorization—sequential logic tests in secure design reviews.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L2-13: CSRF and anti-CSRF tokens</em>:</strong> Identity is the new perimeter: credentials, tokens, and sessions are stolen more often than novel zero-days are burned. Expect Security+ items on MFA bypass awareness, phishing-resistant factors, and why <strong>authorization</strong> must be enforced server-side.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L2-13: CSRF and anti-CSRF tokens</em>:</strong> Advanced topics still return to fundamentals: least privilege, segmentation, logging, and tested recovery. When you see Zero Trust or PQC buzzwords, map them back to concrete controls and threat models rather than treating them as magic shields.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L2-13: CSRF and anti-CSRF tokens</em>:</strong> Business continuity answers should reference <strong>RTO/RPO</strong>, <strong>workarounds</strong>, and <strong>tested restores</strong>; DR without practiced failover is wishful thinking, and exam writers know it.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L2-13: CSRF and anti-CSRF tokens</em>:</strong> Industrial and OT adjacent questions reward knowing <strong>safety vs security</strong> tension: availability may trump confidentiality; testing must avoid breaking physical processes.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L2-13: CSRF and anti-CSRF tokens</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L2-13: CSRF and anti-CSRF tokens</em>:</strong> Tabletop exercises test <strong>comms trees</strong>, legal escalation, and customer notification templates—not only technical runbooks.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L2-13: CSRF and anti-CSRF tokens</em>:</strong> Certificate pinning failures during rotation teach why <strong>key continuity strategy</strong> must be planned before mobile releases.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L2-13: CSRF and anti-CSRF tokens</em>:</strong> Virtualization risks include <strong>snapshot sprawl</strong> containing secrets and stale VM images drifting from hardened baselines.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L2-13: CSRF and anti-CSRF tokens</em>:</strong> For the Security+ mindset, translate every control into <strong>who</strong> it protects, <strong>what</strong> asset is at risk, and <strong>how</strong> you would detect failure. Interview and exam items often reward practical prioritization over buzzwords—choose the mitigation that reduces realistic loss first.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L2-13: CSRF and anti-CSRF tokens</em>:</strong> Application security scenarios often test whether you know <strong>where</strong> enforcement belongs—browser controls supplement but do not replace server-side checks. SameSite cookies, CSP, and HttpOnly mitigate classes of issues; they do not fix broken object-level authorization.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Marketing launches a campaign referencing “L2-13: CSRF and anti-CSRF tokens” with a new subdomain. Security review finds DNS delegated to an unknown party. Explain <strong>trust chain</strong> risks and the <strong>minimum fixes</strong> before go-live.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l2-14":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L2-14: Authentication vs session fixation/hijacking</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-14</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Rotate session on login; Secure/HttpOnly/SameSite cookies.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>curl -I https://example.com 2&gt;/dev/null | grep -i set-cookie</code> — note flags if any.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-14</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Email authenticity (SPF/DKIM/DMARC) is a frequent multi-part stem—read whether the failure is <strong>alignment</strong>, <strong>policy</strong>, or <strong>operator error</strong>.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 2 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>ECB mode weakness</strong></dt><dd>Identical plaintext blocks yield identical ciphertext—leaks structure; prefer modes with IVs and authentication.</dd><dt><strong>MTTD / MTTR</strong></dt><dd>Mean time to detect / remediate—quality matters; gaming metrics by closing tickets inflates false success.</dd><dt><strong>Security headers</strong></dt><dd>HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options/Frame-ancestors, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy—reduce browser-driven attack surface.</dd><dt><strong>Integrity</strong></dt><dd>Assures accuracy and trustworthiness—hashing, signatures, change control, and backups protect against unauthorized modification.</dd><dt><strong>Defense in depth</strong></dt><dd>Layered controls so one failure does not equal total failure—network, host, app, identity, and monitoring each contribute.</dd><dt><strong>AEAD</strong></dt><dd>Authenticated encryption with associated data—confidentiality plus integrity in one primitive (e.g., AES-GCM) when used correctly.</dd><dt><strong>IR phases</strong></dt><dd>Prepare, detect, analyze, contain, eradicate, recover, and lessons learned—legal hold and evidence integrity matter throughout.</dd><dt><strong>Metrics that matter</strong></dt><dd>Mean time to detect/remediate with quality, coverage of critical assets, and control effectiveness—not vanity ticket counts.</dd><dt><strong>Token replay</strong></dt><dd>Reusing a stolen token/session artifact—rotation, binding, and short TTLs reduce window.</dd><dt><strong>Port knocking (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Obscurity-based pre-auth to open firewall—weak alone; exam may present as non-primary control.</dd><dt><strong>SOAR</strong></dt><dd>Security orchestration, automation, response—playbooks must have human gates for destructive actions.</dd><dt><strong>Asset</strong></dt><dd>Anything of value to the organization—data, systems, people, reputation, or services—that security controls protect.</dd><dt><strong>Data classification</strong></dt><dd>Labels (public, internal, confidential, restricted) drive storage, encryption, sharing, and disposal requirements.</dd><dt><strong>Zero Trust (headline)</strong></dt><dd>Assume breach; verify explicitly per request using identity, device posture, and least privilege—not “trust the LAN.”</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authorization</strong></td><td>Server-side object checks—headers and TLS do not replace this.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>S3 bucket policies and ACLs layer with IAM—effective permissions require understanding intersection.</li><li>UDP-based protocols can be abused for amplification DDoS—patch open resolvers and monitor volumetric baselines.</li><li>ATT&CK technique IDs are stable references for detection content—good for purple team reporting.</li><li>JWT alg:none historical vulnerability class—always validate algorithm and signature keys explicitly.</li><li>GCP service account keys are long-lived secrets—prefer workload identity federation from CI where possible.</li><li>PCI DSS scope reduction via segmentation is a recurring theme—if it is not in scope, it cannot drag you into assessment.</li><li>Linux auth.log style entries pair with SSH brute-force detection patterns—velocity and geo anomalies.</li><li>Race conditions in web apps can undermine authorization—sequential logic tests in secure design reviews.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L2-14: Authentication vs session fixation/hijacking</em>:</strong> Cryptography questions reward vocabulary precision: hashing vs encryption vs encoding; symmetric vs asymmetric roles in TLS; what signatures prove; and why key management is usually harder than picking an algorithm. If an answer sounds magical, it is probably wrong.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L2-14: Authentication vs session fixation/hijacking</em>:</strong> Help desk scenarios test whether you know <strong>identity proofing</strong> vs <strong>account recovery</strong> abuse. The secure path verifies the human through out-of-band channels without teaching attackers how to bypass your process in the stem text.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L2-14: Authentication vs session fixation/hijacking</em>:</strong> Tabletop exercises test <strong>comms trees</strong>, legal escalation, and customer notification templates—not only technical runbooks.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L2-14: Authentication vs session fixation/hijacking</em>:</strong> Sanitization vs wiping vs destruction: exams like knowing which media needs <strong>degaussing, shredding, or crypto erase</strong> per policy.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L2-14: Authentication vs session fixation/hijacking</em>:</strong> Logging questions often test whether you understand <strong>what to log</strong> (who, what, when, where, outcome), <strong>time sync</strong> for correlation, and <strong>tamper resistance</strong> for evidentiary value—not whether you can collect infinite bytes.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L2-14: Authentication vs session fixation/hijacking</em>:</strong> Container escape questions hinge on <strong>kernel boundary</strong> and misconfigured capabilities—namespaces are helpful but not a complete trust boundary without seccomp, AppArmor, and least-privileged service accounts.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L2-14: Authentication vs session fixation/hijacking</em>:</strong> Certificate pinning failures during rotation teach why <strong>key continuity strategy</strong> must be planned before mobile releases.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L2-14: Authentication vs session fixation/hijacking</em>:</strong> Security operations value <strong>repeatable evidence</strong>: timestamps, authoritative configuration sources, and tamper-aware logs beat heroic memory after an incident. Many exam questions hinge on whether an action preserves integrity and accountability rather than whether it feels fast.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L2-14: Authentication vs session fixation/hijacking</em>:</strong> Data handling questions often hinge on <strong>classification</strong>, <strong>least data</strong>, and <strong>retention</strong>: collect only what you need, keep it only as long as allowed, and destroy securely when done.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L2-14: Authentication vs session fixation/hijacking</em>:</strong> SAST finds issues early but produces false positives; <strong>triage workflows</strong> and developer feedback loops are part of a mature program, not “run tool once.”</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Junior staff proposes a quick fix for “L2-14: Authentication vs session fixation/hijacking” that disables logging on a noisy host. Walk through why that is unacceptable and propose a <strong>tuning</strong> path that preserves <strong>integrity and retention</strong> commitments.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l2-15":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L2-15: Security headers (HSTS, X-Frame-Options, CSP)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-15</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Map header to attack class.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>curl -sI https://example.com | egrep -i &#39;strict-transport|content-security|x-frame|x-content-type&#39;</code>.</p>\n<h2>Lab pack — Level 2</h2>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Passive footprinting (authorized):</strong> On domains you own or <code>example.com</code>, collect DNS, TLS cert dates, HTTP headers; 1-page OSINT-style report (ethical).  </li>\n<li><strong>Service inventory:</strong> Map listeners to purpose; mark “unnecessary” candidates.  </li>\n<li><strong>TLS inspection:</strong> Document chain depth for one SaaS API your org uses (if permitted).  </li>\n<li><strong>Cookie policy review:</strong> Find SameSite defaults in framework docs you use at work.  </li>\n<li><strong>Secure coding fix:</strong> Rewrite one dynamic SQL into parameterized pseudocode.</li>\n</ol>\n<h2>Question bank — Level 2</h2>\n<p><strong>Q1.</strong> Stateful firewall primarily tracks: (a) only MAC (b) connection state (c) CPU temperature.<br><strong>Q2.</strong> TLS provides primarily: (a) disk compression (b) confidentiality + integrity on the wire (c) physical locks.<br><strong>Q3.</strong> SPF validates: (a) HTML (b) sending IP for domain (c) TLS cipher.<br><strong>Q4.</strong> DKIM proves: (a) message tampering detection via signing (b) password strength (c) disk free space.<br><strong>Q5.</strong> DMARC builds on: (a) SPF and/or DKIM alignment (b) RAID (c) BIOS passwords only.<br><strong>Q6.</strong> Hashing is mainly: (a) reversible (b) one-way fingerprinting (c) same as encoding.<br><strong>Q7.</strong> Asymmetric keys help with: (a) faster bulk disk wipe (b) key agreement/signing without shared secret (c) RAID parity.<br><strong>Q8.</strong> SQLi safest fix pattern: (a) more regex (b) parameterized queries (c) longer passwords only.<br><strong>Q9.</strong> Stored XSS executes in: (a) DNS resolver (b) victim browser context (c) printer firmware only.<br><strong>Q10.</strong> CSRF abuses: (a) victim’s ambient auth to forge actions (b) weak TLS (c) RAID 0.<br><strong>Q11.</strong> <code>HttpOnly</code> cookies mitigate: (a) XSS token theft from JS (b) SQLi (c) BGP hijacks.<br><strong>Q12.</strong> HSTS mitigates: (a) SSLstrip/downgrade (b) SQLi (c) weak BIOS.<br><strong>Q13.</strong> CSP primarily reduces: (a) XSS impact (b) disk failure (c) power outages.<br><strong>Q14.</strong> Default-deny firewall means: (a) allow all then block (b) block unless explicitly allowed (c) no logging.<br><strong>Q15.</strong> VPN primarily provides: (a) cryptographic tunnel between endpoints (b) guaranteed malware removal (c) immutable logs.<br><strong>Q16.</strong> DNS cache poisoning conceptually: (a) wrong answers cached (b) stronger passwords (c) TPM attestation.<br><strong>Q17.</strong> Hybrid TLS uses asymmetric for: (a) bulk data only (b) key exchange/signatures then symmetric session keys (c) printing.<br><strong>Q18.</strong> Session fixation defense includes: (a) reusing pre-auth session IDs (b) rotate session ID after successful login (c) disable HTTPS.<br><strong>Q19.</strong> <code>SameSite=Lax/Strict</code> reduces: (a) some cross-site cookie sends (b) disk encryption (c) RAID overhead.<br><strong>Q20.</strong> Encoding (e.g., Base64) provides: (a) confidentiality (b) representation, not security (c) integrity.</p>\n<h3>Answer key — Level 2</h3>\n<p>1–5: B/B/B/A/A<br>6–10: B/B/B/B/A<br>11–15: A/A/A/B/A<br>16–20: A/B/B/B/B  </p>\n<hr>\n<h1>Level 3 — Advanced (assessment, logging, IAM, vuln lifecycle)</h1>\n<p><strong>Workplace outcomes:</strong> You can support vulnerability management, parse scanner findings, explain IAM policies, and follow IR hygiene.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-15</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>TLS questions separate <strong>confidentiality channel</strong> from <strong>server authentication</strong>—certificate validation and hostname checks matter in the answer set.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 2 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Logging &amp; monitoring</strong></dt><dd>CloudTrail-style management events differ from data-plane logs—enable central export, immutability, and alerting.</dd><dt><strong>BCP / DR</strong></dt><dd>Business continuity and disaster recovery—RTO/RPO drive architecture; test restores, not just backups on paper.</dd><dt><strong>Threat intelligence lifecycle</strong></dt><dd>Planning, collection, processing, analysis, dissemination, feedback—intel must change detections or posture or it is shelf-ware.</dd><dt><strong>Purple / red / blue</strong></dt><dd>Red emulates adversaries, blue defends, purple bridges—authorization and logging are mandatory for any simulation.</dd><dt><strong>Need to know</strong></dt><dd>Finer than least privilege for data—access only to the minimum subset required for the current task.</dd><dt><strong>CRL</strong></dt><dd>Certificate Revocation List—signed list of revoked serials; size/latency issues drove OCSP adoption.</dd><dt><strong>IV / nonce</strong></dt><dd>Initialization vector or number-used-once—must be unique per encryption under a key for many modes.</dd><dt><strong>Proxy vs reverse proxy</strong></dt><dd>Forward proxy represents clients outbound; reverse proxy fronts servers—different trust and logging points.</dd><dt><strong>RPO / RTO recap</strong></dt><dd>RPO = max acceptable data loss time; RTO = max acceptable outage—drive backup frequency and HA design.</dd><dt><strong>TTP</strong></dt><dd>Tactics, techniques, and procedures—behavioral patterns; harder to change than IOCs, better for resilient detection.</dd><dt><strong>OWASP Top 10</strong></dt><dd>High-prevalence web risks—broken access control and crypto failures often dominate; study each category with one workplace example.</dd><dt><strong>DevSecOps</strong></dt><dd>Embed security gates in CI/CD with fast feedback—policy-as-code, secret scanning, and SBOMs support supply-chain resilience.</dd><dt><strong>Exploit</strong></dt><dd>A technique or code that takes advantage of a vulnerability to achieve an attacker goal (exfiltration, persistence, disruption).</dd><dt><strong>Confidentiality</strong></dt><dd>Assures that information is not disclosed to unauthorized subjects—encryption, access control, and data minimization support it.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authorization</strong></td><td>Server-side object checks—headers and TLS do not replace this.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>AES-128 is not “half as strong” as AES-256 in practical threat models for many cases—key management quality dominates.</li><li>OAuth access tokens are not a replacement for server-side authorization checks on every sensitive action.</li><li>Sigma rules are vendor-agnostic detection snippets—tuning required per log source fields.</li><li>DNS over HTTPS changes visibility for some networks—understand resolver policy and logging tradeoffs.</li><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li><li>GCP service account keys are long-lived secrets—prefer workload identity federation from CI where possible.</li><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li><li>SameSite=Lax blocks many CSRF POSTs from cross-site contexts in modern browsers—know the nuance vs Strict.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L2-15: Security headers (HSTS, X-Frame-Options, CSP)</em>:</strong> Serverless cold start is not a security control; <strong>per-function IAM</strong> and least-privilege API scopes are. Watch for attractive nonsense distractors tied to performance tuning.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L2-15: Security headers (HSTS, X-Frame-Options, CSP)</em>:</strong> Governance and awareness questions tie policy to behavior: acceptable use, clean desk, travel security, and vendor due diligence. Pick answers that reduce <strong>realistic</strong> human failure modes, not answers that maximize surveillance without process support.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L2-15: Security headers (HSTS, X-Frame-Options, CSP)</em>:</strong> Deception tech is not a replacement for <strong>baselines and patching</strong>; it augments detection when mature processes exist.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L2-15: Security headers (HSTS, X-Frame-Options, CSP)</em>:</strong> KMS keys are not “magic secrecy dust”—<strong>who can invoke decrypt</strong> and from which contexts (VPC endpoint policies, IAM conditions) is what exams probe.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L2-15: Security headers (HSTS, X-Frame-Options, CSP)</em>:</strong> Advanced topics still return to fundamentals: least privilege, segmentation, logging, and tested recovery. When you see Zero Trust or PQC buzzwords, map them back to concrete controls and threat models rather than treating them as magic shields.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L2-15: Security headers (HSTS, X-Frame-Options, CSP)</em>:</strong> Air gapped networks still need <strong>patching via sneaker-net</strong> and insider controls—physical isolation is not logical isolation.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L2-15: Security headers (HSTS, X-Frame-Options, CSP)</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L2-15: Security headers (HSTS, X-Frame-Options, CSP)</em>:</strong> Logging questions often test whether you understand <strong>what to log</strong> (who, what, when, where, outcome), <strong>time sync</strong> for correlation, and <strong>tamper resistance</strong> for evidentiary value—not whether you can collect infinite bytes.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L2-15: Security headers (HSTS, X-Frame-Options, CSP)</em>:</strong> Virtualization risks include <strong>snapshot sprawl</strong> containing secrets and stale VM images drifting from hardened baselines.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L2-15: Security headers (HSTS, X-Frame-Options, CSP)</em>:</strong> Ransomware stems often pair encryption with <strong>exfiltration</strong>—the correct answer may include legal/notification obligations, not only restoring from backup.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Legal asks whether “L2-15: Security headers (HSTS, X-Frame-Options, CSP)” artifacts require <strong>hold</strong> before deletion. Describe how you would <strong>tag systems</strong>, <strong>freeze backups</strong> appropriately, and <strong>escalate</strong> without tipping external actors.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l3-01":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L3-01: Vulnerability management lifecycle</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-01</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Discover → prioritize → remediate → verify → report.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Install/read <code>man debsecan</code> or run <code>sudo apt-get install -y debsecan</code> in lab VM only; <code>debsecan --suite bookworm 2&gt;/dev/null | head</code> (suite must match).</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-01</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Operations answers should show <strong>measurable process</strong>: SLAs, verification steps, and feedback loops—not heroic one-off fixes.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 3 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Port knocking (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Obscurity-based pre-auth to open firewall—weak alone; exam may present as non-primary control.</dd><dt><strong>Due care</strong></dt><dd>The effort a prudent person would take to meet a duty; in security, reasonable steps to protect assets and stakeholders.</dd><dt><strong>Symmetric encryption</strong></dt><dd>Same key encrypts and decrypts—fast for bulk data (AES-GCM); key distribution is the hard problem.</dd><dt><strong>Container security</strong></dt><dd>Image provenance, non-root users, read-only roots, seccomp/AppArmor, and admission control for risky capabilities.</dd><dt><strong>OCSP stapling (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Server sends fresh revocation info with handshake—reduces client privacy leaks and lookup failures.</dd><dt><strong>UEBA</strong></dt><dd>User and entity behavior analytics—baseline deviations; tune to avoid HR/privacy backlash.</dd><dt><strong>Kerberos (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Ticket-based enterprise auth—TGT vs service tickets; golden/silver ticket classes of abuse appear in advanced IR.</dd><dt><strong>CVE</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures identifier for a specific flaw—pairs with CVSS severity and vendor advisories for prioritization.</dd><dt><strong>Purple / red / blue</strong></dt><dd>Red emulates adversaries, blue defends, purple bridges—authorization and logging are mandatory for any simulation.</dd><dt><strong>NetFlow / IPFIX</strong></dt><dd>Flow metadata for volume and anomaly detection—lighter than PCAP but less payload visibility.</dd><dt><strong>Availability</strong></dt><dd>Assures timely and reliable access—redundancy, patching, DDoS defenses, and DR planning keep services usable for authorized users.</dd><dt><strong>Encoding (e.g., Base64)</strong></dt><dd>Transforms representation without cryptographic protection—do not confuse with encryption or integrity.</dd><dt><strong>Third-party risk</strong></dt><dd>Vendor access expands attack surface—DPAs, SOC reports, and continuous monitoring for critical suppliers.</dd><dt><strong>Collision (hash)</strong></dt><dd>Two inputs produce same hash—breaks integrity assumptions; choose strong hash families for security use.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Cloud responsibility</th><th>Who typically owns it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Patching the hypervisor</strong></td><td>Provider responsibility in major IaaS models—customer still patches guests.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>IAM policy and keys</strong></td><td>Customer-owned configuration—misconfigurations dominate incidents.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Data encryption at rest</strong></td><td>Often customer-controlled keys/KMS policies with provider primitives.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Network exposure (SGs/NACLs)</strong></td><td>Customer configures; default-deny patterns are exam favorites.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Application vulnerabilities</strong></td><td>Customer code and dependencies—shared model does not absolve secure SDLC.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Responsible disclosure timelines balance vendor patch readiness with public safety—coordinate, don’t surprise.</li><li>Terraform state can hold secrets—remote secure backend and scanning are baseline hygiene.</li><li>S3 bucket policies and ACLs layer with IAM—effective permissions require understanding intersection.</li><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li><li>JWT alg:none historical vulnerability class—always validate algorithm and signature keys explicitly.</li><li>Split tunnel VPN can exfil corporate data outside inspection if misconfigured—policy and routing matter.</li><li>Linux auth.log style entries pair with SSH brute-force detection patterns—velocity and geo anomalies.</li><li>EPSS (concept) scores exploitation probability—useful alongside CVSS for prioritization in mature programs.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L3-01: Vulnerability management lifecycle</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L3-01: Vulnerability management lifecycle</em>:</strong> GraphQL introspection risk is about <strong>schema discovery</strong> aiding attackers—rate limits, authz on fields, and disabling introspection in prod are common answers.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L3-01: Vulnerability management lifecycle</em>:</strong> BIOS/UEFI passwords and secure boot reduce some pre-boot attacks but do not stop <strong>evil maid</strong> classes without additional controls.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L3-01: Vulnerability management lifecycle</em>:</strong> Identity is the new perimeter: credentials, tokens, and sessions are stolen more often than novel zero-days are burned. Expect Security+ items on MFA bypass awareness, phishing-resistant factors, and why <strong>authorization</strong> must be enforced server-side.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L3-01: Vulnerability management lifecycle</em>:</strong> Physical security is still on the exam: tailgating, visitor escorts, locks, destruction of media, and environmental controls (fire, HVAC) as availability/confidentiality supports.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L3-01: Vulnerability management lifecycle</em>:</strong> Email security stems often combine SPF alignment failures with <strong>look-alike domains</strong>. The best answer addresses user training plus technical authenticity controls, not only one or the other.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L3-01: Vulnerability management lifecycle</em>:</strong> DAST exercises running apps but misses authz logic without credentials; combine with <strong>manual review</strong> for business-rule flaws.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L3-01: Vulnerability management lifecycle</em>:</strong> RADIUS is still referenced for <strong>network access control</strong> integrations; know it as a AAA component in enterprise Wi-Fi contexts.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L3-01: Vulnerability management lifecycle</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L3-01: Vulnerability management lifecycle</em>:</strong> Cloud items assume you can articulate <strong>shared responsibility</strong>: what the provider patches vs what the customer must configure (IAM, encryption, network exposure). Misconfiguration beats novel cloud exploits in real incidents and on the exam.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Marketing launches a campaign referencing “L3-01: Vulnerability management lifecycle” with a new subdomain. Security review finds DNS delegated to an unknown party. Explain <strong>trust chain</strong> risks and the <strong>minimum fixes</strong> before go-live.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l3-02":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L3-02: CVE, CWE, CVSS v3 at a glance</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-02</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Read base score metrics (AV, AC, PR, UI, S, C, I, A).<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Pick one CVE from <a href=\"https://nvd.nist.gov/\">https://nvd.nist.gov/</a> (offline copy OK); fill CVSS vector string meaning in your words.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-02</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Threat modeling at this level stays <strong>STRIDE-shaped</strong>—name the abuse, then map a proportional control.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 3 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Security headers</strong></dt><dd>HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options/Frame-ancestors, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy—reduce browser-driven attack surface.</dd><dt><strong>Insider threat</strong></dt><dd>Malicious or negligent insiders—monitor with proportionality, separation of duties, and HR/legal partnership.</dd><dt><strong>Certificate transparency (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Public logs of issued certs help detect mis-issued certificates for your domains.</dd><dt><strong>RPO / RTO recap</strong></dt><dd>RPO = max acceptable data loss time; RTO = max acceptable outage—drive backup frequency and HA design.</dd><dt><strong>Asset</strong></dt><dd>Anything of value to the organization—data, systems, people, reputation, or services—that security controls protect.</dd><dt><strong>Session management</strong></dt><dd>Server-side session IDs or tokens must rotate on privilege change, bind to channel, and expire predictably.</dd><dt><strong>Input validation vs output encoding</strong></dt><dd>Validation rejects bad input early; encoding neutralizes dangerous characters in the right output context—both are needed across HTML, SQL, OS, and LDAP channels.</dd><dt><strong>Container security</strong></dt><dd>Image provenance, non-root users, read-only roots, seccomp/AppArmor, and admission control for risky capabilities.</dd><dt><strong>Job rotation</strong></dt><dd>Reduces collusion and fraud risk; also surfaces “tribal knowledge” silos before an employee leaves.</dd><dt><strong>Proxy vs reverse proxy</strong></dt><dd>Forward proxy represents clients outbound; reverse proxy fronts servers—different trust and logging points.</dd><dt><strong>SIEM</strong></dt><dd>Security information and event management—centralize logs, parse fields, correlate alerts; tuning reduces false positives and fatigue.</dd><dt><strong>PII</strong></dt><dd>Personally identifiable information—names, government IDs, biometrics, account numbers; triggers handling, retention, and breach rules.</dd><dt><strong>Asymmetric encryption</strong></dt><dd>Key pairs for key agreement/signing—RSA/ECC; hybrid TLS uses asymmetric to establish symmetric session keys.</dd><dt><strong>IR phases</strong></dt><dd>Prepare, detect, analyze, contain, eradicate, recover, and lessons learned—legal hold and evidence integrity matter throughout.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li><li>CVSS base does not include your asset criticality—environmental metrics exist for a reason.</li><li>Azure AD / Entra conditional access is analogous to risk-based policies—device compliance signals matter.</li><li>Linux auth.log style entries pair with SSH brute-force detection patterns—velocity and geo anomalies.</li><li>Bug bounty scope must exclude destructive testing—safe harbor language still needs legal review.</li><li>DNS over HTTPS changes visibility for some networks—understand resolver policy and logging tradeoffs.</li><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L3-02: CVE, CWE, CVSS v3 at a glance</em>:</strong> Third-party and supply chain answers should emphasize <strong>contracts</strong>, <strong>evidence</strong>, and <strong>continuous monitoring</strong>—not “trust the SOC 2 logo” without scope review.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L3-02: CVE, CWE, CVSS v3 at a glance</em>:</strong> Clean desk pairs with <strong>screen privacy</strong> and <strong>clear desk checks</strong> for regulated spaces—physical + procedural controls together.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L3-02: CVE, CWE, CVSS v3 at a glance</em>:</strong> Penetration tests require <strong>written authorization</strong>, defined scope, and rules of engagement—even in internal labs for professional conduct.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L3-02: CVE, CWE, CVSS v3 at a glance</em>:</strong> Business continuity answers should reference <strong>RTO/RPO</strong>, <strong>workarounds</strong>, and <strong>tested restores</strong>; DR without practiced failover is wishful thinking, and exam writers know it.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L3-02: CVE, CWE, CVSS v3 at a glance</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L3-02: CVE, CWE, CVSS v3 at a glance</em>:</strong> Tabletop exercises test <strong>comms trees</strong>, legal escalation, and customer notification templates—not only technical runbooks.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L3-02: CVE, CWE, CVSS v3 at a glance</em>:</strong> Data handling questions often hinge on <strong>classification</strong>, <strong>least data</strong>, and <strong>retention</strong>: collect only what you need, keep it only as long as allowed, and destroy securely when done.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L3-02: CVE, CWE, CVSS v3 at a glance</em>:</strong> For the Security+ mindset, translate every control into <strong>who</strong> it protects, <strong>what</strong> asset is at risk, and <strong>how</strong> you would detect failure. Interview and exam items often reward practical prioritization over buzzwords—choose the mitigation that reduces realistic loss first.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L3-02: CVE, CWE, CVSS v3 at a glance</em>:</strong> Evidence bags and write blockers signal <strong>forensics awareness</strong>; touching disks before imaging is a classic wrong answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L3-02: CVE, CWE, CVSS v3 at a glance</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> A cloud bill spike correlates with traffic about “L3-02: CVE, CWE, CVSS v3 at a glance”. Differentiate <strong>misconfiguration</strong> vs <strong>abuse</strong> in your first triage questions and what logs prove each hypothesis.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l3-03":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L3-03: Secure baselines and CIS benchmarks</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-03</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Hardening vs functionality tradeoffs.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Download CIS PDF summary table (if licensed) or public STIG overview; 10 control bullets for SSH.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-03</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Vulnerability prioritization is not “CVSS only”—think <strong>exposure</strong>, <strong>exploitability</strong>, and <strong>asset value</strong> together.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 3 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>IOC</strong></dt><dd>Indicator of compromise—often ephemeral (IPs, domains); pair with TTP-based detections for durability.</dd><dt><strong>MFA</strong></dt><dd>Multi-factor authentication—requires two or more independent factors; push fatigue and MFA phishing are real bypass paths.</dd><dt><strong>Injection</strong></dt><dd>Untrusted input becomes part of a command or query—parameterized queries, input validation, and context escaping are core defenses.</dd><dt><strong>Supply chain security</strong></dt><dd>SBOM, provenance signing (SLSA-style thinking), and dependency pinning reduce “update from upstream” surprises.</dd><dt><strong>ECB mode weakness</strong></dt><dd>Identical plaintext blocks yield identical ciphertext—leaks structure; prefer modes with IVs and authentication.</dd><dt><strong>Quantitative vs qualitative risk</strong></dt><dd>Qualitative uses scales (high/medium/low); quantitative uses dollar or probability estimates—both need consistent assumptions and reviewer judgment.</dd><dt><strong>Defense in depth</strong></dt><dd>Layered controls so one failure does not equal total failure—network, host, app, identity, and monitoring each contribute.</dd><dt><strong>CVSS</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerability Scoring System—base metrics describe technical severity; environmental and temporal modifiers refine priority.</dd><dt><strong>Purple teaming</strong></dt><dd>Collaborative attack/defense exercises to validate detections without surprise production harm—scope and safety first.</dd><dt><strong>Proxy vs reverse proxy</strong></dt><dd>Forward proxy represents clients outbound; reverse proxy fronts servers—different trust and logging points.</dd><dt><strong>Due care</strong></dt><dd>The effort a prudent person would take to meet a duty; in security, reasonable steps to protect assets and stakeholders.</dd><dt><strong>Perfect forward secrecy (PFS)</strong></dt><dd>Ephemeral key exchange means past session keys are not compromised if long-term keys leak later—TLS cipher suites can offer this property.</dd><dt><strong>IAM least privilege</strong></dt><dd>Grant minimum API/console rights; prefer roles over long-lived keys; audit risky admin-equivalent paths regularly.</dd><dt><strong>Need to know</strong></dt><dd>Finer than least privilege for data—access only to the minimum subset required for the current task.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>SameSite=Lax blocks many CSRF POSTs from cross-site contexts in modern browsers—know the nuance vs Strict.</li><li>GCP service account keys are long-lived secrets—prefer workload identity federation from CI where possible.</li><li>DNS over HTTPS changes visibility for some networks—understand resolver policy and logging tradeoffs.</li><li>OAuth access tokens are not a replacement for server-side authorization checks on every sensitive action.</li><li>Azure AD / Entra conditional access is analogous to risk-based policies—device compliance signals matter.</li><li>Split tunnel VPN can exfil corporate data outside inspection if misconfigured—policy and routing matter.</li><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>KMS key policies can deny even root in AWS when configured—explicit deny wins.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L3-03: Secure baselines and CIS benchmarks</em>:</strong> Deception tech is not a replacement for <strong>baselines and patching</strong>; it augments detection when mature processes exist.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L3-03: Secure baselines and CIS benchmarks</em>:</strong> Access control stems frequently mix <strong>role</strong> vs <strong>attribute</strong> vs <strong>rule</strong> models; pick the answer that matches the scenario’s constraints (temporary contractor, cross-department data, dynamic tags on resources).</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L3-03: Secure baselines and CIS benchmarks</em>:</strong> SAST finds issues early but produces false positives; <strong>triage workflows</strong> and developer feedback loops are part of a mature program, not “run tool once.”</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L3-03: Secure baselines and CIS benchmarks</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L3-03: Secure baselines and CIS benchmarks</em>:</strong> Engineers often optimize for speed; attackers optimize for <strong>cheap reuse</strong> of stolen creds and known exploits. The winning answer bridges both: ship fast with guardrails—feature flags, staged rollouts, and automated security checks in CI.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L3-03: Secure baselines and CIS benchmarks</em>:</strong> CSP reporting helps tune policy but can leak URLs—<strong>privacy review</strong> of report endpoints matters in regulated environments.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L3-03: Secure baselines and CIS benchmarks</em>:</strong> Application security scenarios often test whether you know <strong>where</strong> enforcement belongs—browser controls supplement but do not replace server-side checks. SameSite cookies, CSP, and HttpOnly mitigate classes of issues; they do not fix broken object-level authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L3-03: Secure baselines and CIS benchmarks</em>:</strong> Container escape questions hinge on <strong>kernel boundary</strong> and misconfigured capabilities—namespaces are helpful but not a complete trust boundary without seccomp, AppArmor, and least-privileged service accounts.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L3-03: Secure baselines and CIS benchmarks</em>:</strong> Air gapped networks still need <strong>patching via sneaker-net</strong> and insider controls—physical isolation is not logical isolation.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L3-03: Secure baselines and CIS benchmarks</em>:</strong> Wireless and mobility items reward knowing basics: WPA3 improvements conceptually, evil twin risks, captive portals, and why client isolation matters on guest networks—without memorizing obsolete WEP details unless explicitly historical.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Junior staff proposes a quick fix for “L3-03: Secure baselines and CIS benchmarks” that disables logging on a noisy host. Walk through why that is unacceptable and propose a <strong>tuning</strong> path that preserves <strong>integrity and retention</strong> commitments.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l3-04":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L3-04: SSH hardening checklist</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-04</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Key-based auth, PermitRootLogin, ciphers, AllowUsers.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>grep -E &#39;^(PermitRootLogin|PasswordAuthentication|AllowUsers)&#39; /etc/ssh/sshd_config</code> — document current values (do not lock yourself out).</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-04</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Level 3 aligns with Security+ <strong>operations and engineering</strong>: vuln management, logging/SIEM concepts, IAM patterns, threat modeling, and IR mechanics. Writers blend domains—patch urgency plus change window is a classic pair.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 3 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Digital signature</strong></dt><dd>Proves origin and integrity using private key to sign and public key to verify—non-repudiation when keys are well governed.</dd><dt><strong>Secure SDLC</strong></dt><dd>Requirements, threat modeling, secure design, code review, SAST/DAST, dependency scanning, and hardened deployment pipelines.</dd><dt><strong>Misconfiguration</strong></dt><dd>Top cloud incident driver—public buckets, open security groups, permissive trust policies; IaC scanning catches drift early.</dd><dt><strong>Threat intelligence lifecycle</strong></dt><dd>Planning, collection, processing, analysis, dissemination, feedback—intel must change detections or posture or it is shelf-ware.</dd><dt><strong>Mandatory vacation</strong></dt><dd>Forces handover and review of another employee’s work—can uncover fraud or backdoors.</dd><dt><strong>Block cipher vs stream</strong></dt><dd>Block operates on fixed-size chunks; stream on bits/bytes—misuse modes (e.g., ECB) create patterns.</dd><dt><strong>Sinkhole (DNS)</strong></dt><dd>Controlled resolution for malicious domains—intel and disruption technique with legal process considerations.</dd><dt><strong>Data residency</strong></dt><dd>Legal requirement for where data lives—impacts cloud region selection and key custody.</dd><dt><strong>Compensating control</strong></dt><dd>Alternative control that meets intent when primary control cannot be implemented—must provide equivalent or greater assurance with documentation.</dd><dt><strong>Integrity</strong></dt><dd>Assures accuracy and trustworthiness—hashing, signatures, change control, and backups protect against unauthorized modification.</dd><dt><strong>SSO</strong></dt><dd>Single sign-on federates trust to an IdP—misconfigured SAML/OIDC trusts are high-impact; validate metadata and signing keys.</dd><dt><strong>Certificate pinning (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Client remembers expected server key material—reduces MITM from rogue CAs but complicates rotation; mostly seen in mobile/API hardening patterns.</dd><dt><strong>XSS</strong></dt><dd>Cross-site scripting injects script in a victim context—CSP, output encoding, HttpOnly cookies, and DOM hygiene reduce blast radius.</dd><dt><strong>Chain of custody</strong></dt><dd>Documented handling of evidence from collection through presentation—hashing, write blockers, and access logs support admissibility.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>HttpOnly does not stop CSRF; it reduces token theft from XSS reading document.cookie in many setups.</li><li>Responsible disclosure timelines balance vendor patch readiness with public safety—coordinate, don’t surprise.</li><li>Admission controllers can block privileged pods—policy-as-code integrates with GitOps reviews.</li><li>Split tunnel VPN can exfil corporate data outside inspection if misconfigured—policy and routing matter.</li><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li><li>AES-128 is not “half as strong” as AES-256 in practical threat models for many cases—key management quality dominates.</li><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li><li>DNS over HTTPS changes visibility for some networks—understand resolver policy and logging tradeoffs.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L3-04: SSH hardening checklist</em>:</strong> API keys in mobile apps are often extractable—prefer <strong>short-lived tokens</strong> and server-mediated access to backends.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L3-04: SSH hardening checklist</em>:</strong> Identity is the new perimeter: credentials, tokens, and sessions are stolen more often than novel zero-days are burned. Expect Security+ items on MFA bypass awareness, phishing-resistant factors, and why <strong>authorization</strong> must be enforced server-side.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L3-04: SSH hardening checklist</em>:</strong> When logs “mysteriously stop,” think <strong>time sync failure</strong>, collector saturation, retention misconfiguration, or attacker tampering—in that diagnostic order for a fair exam narrative.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L3-04: SSH hardening checklist</em>:</strong> Honeypots can generate high-signal alerts but carry <strong>legal and operational</strong> risk if touched by real users; scope carefully.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L3-04: SSH hardening checklist</em>:</strong> Logging questions often test whether you understand <strong>what to log</strong> (who, what, when, where, outcome), <strong>time sync</strong> for correlation, and <strong>tamper resistance</strong> for evidentiary value—not whether you can collect infinite bytes.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L3-04: SSH hardening checklist</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L3-04: SSH hardening checklist</em>:</strong> Clean desk pairs with <strong>screen privacy</strong> and <strong>clear desk checks</strong> for regulated spaces—physical + procedural controls together.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L3-04: SSH hardening checklist</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L3-04: SSH hardening checklist</em>:</strong> GraphQL introspection risk is about <strong>schema discovery</strong> aiding attackers—rate limits, authz on fields, and disabling introspection in prod are common answers.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L3-04: SSH hardening checklist</em>:</strong> Cryptography questions reward vocabulary precision: hashing vs encryption vs encoding; symmetric vs asymmetric roles in TLS; what signatures prove; and why key management is usually harder than picking an algorithm. If an answer sounds magical, it is probably wrong.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Internal audit samples “L3-04: SSH hardening checklist” controls and finds screenshots instead of config exports. Explain why <strong>authoritative evidence</strong> matters and what you would collect instead.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l3-05":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L3-05: Linux file permissions and ACLs (concept)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-05</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> <code>rwx</code>, special bits high level, <code>getfacl</code> when needed.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>touch ~/acltest &amp;&amp; chmod 640 ~/acltest &amp;&amp; ls -l ~/acltest</code>; explain group read risk on shared hosts.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-05</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>IR stems test <strong>containment vs evidence</strong> tension—choose actions that preserve hashes and legal escalation paths.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 3 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Input validation vs output encoding</strong></dt><dd>Validation rejects bad input early; encoding neutralizes dangerous characters in the right output context—both are needed across HTML, SQL, OS, and LDAP channels.</dd><dt><strong>Data retention</strong></dt><dd>Shorter retention reduces exposure and cost—legal holds override routine deletion when investigations require preservation.</dd><dt><strong>IV / nonce</strong></dt><dd>Initialization vector or number-used-once—must be unique per encryption under a key for many modes.</dd><dt><strong>MITRE ATT&amp;CK</strong></dt><dd>Tactics (why) and techniques (how) adversaries operate—use for detection engineering, gap analysis, and purple team scenarios.</dd><dt><strong>Kerberos (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Ticket-based enterprise auth—TGT vs service tickets; golden/silver ticket classes of abuse appear in advanced IR.</dd><dt><strong>CVE</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures identifier for a specific flaw—pairs with CVSS severity and vendor advisories for prioritization.</dd><dt><strong>Purple / red / blue</strong></dt><dd>Red emulates adversaries, blue defends, purple bridges—authorization and logging are mandatory for any simulation.</dd><dt><strong>NetFlow / IPFIX</strong></dt><dd>Flow metadata for volume and anomaly detection—lighter than PCAP but less payload visibility.</dd><dt><strong>Control</strong></dt><dd>Administrative, technical, or physical safeguards that reduce likelihood or impact of a security event (prevent, detect, correct).</dd><dt><strong>Network segmentation</strong></dt><dd>VLANs, micro-segmentation, and east-west controls limit lateral movement after an initial foothold.</dd><dt><strong>Logging &amp; monitoring</strong></dt><dd>CloudTrail-style management events differ from data-plane logs—enable central export, immutability, and alerting.</dd><dt><strong>Replay attack</strong></dt><dd>Valid data maliciously re-sent—nonces, timestamps, and session freshness mitigate.</dd><dt><strong>IOC</strong></dt><dd>Indicator of compromise—often ephemeral (IPs, domains); pair with TTP-based detections for durability.</dd><dt><strong>Non-repudiation</strong></dt><dd>Prevents a party from credibly denying an action—digital signatures, tamper-evident logs, and time-stamping support it.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Cloud responsibility</th><th>Who typically owns it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Patching the hypervisor</strong></td><td>Provider responsibility in major IaaS models—customer still patches guests.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>IAM policy and keys</strong></td><td>Customer-owned configuration—misconfigurations dominate incidents.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Data encryption at rest</strong></td><td>Often customer-controlled keys/KMS policies with provider primitives.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Network exposure (SGs/NACLs)</strong></td><td>Customer configures; default-deny patterns are exam favorites.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Application vulnerabilities</strong></td><td>Customer code and dependencies—shared model does not absolve secure SDLC.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>PCI DSS scope reduction via segmentation is a recurring theme—if it is not in scope, it cannot drag you into assessment.</li><li>Certificate pinning misconfigurations can brick apps—plan rotation and emergency releases.</li><li>Bug bounty scope must exclude destructive testing—safe harbor language still needs legal review.</li><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li><li>S3 bucket policies and ACLs layer with IAM—effective permissions require understanding intersection.</li><li>SameSite=Lax blocks many CSRF POSTs from cross-site contexts in modern browsers—know the nuance vs Strict.</li><li>GraphQL batching can amplify complexity attacks—depth and cost limits are first-class controls.</li><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L3-05: Linux file permissions and ACLs (concept)</em>:</strong> Certificate pinning failures during rotation teach why <strong>key continuity strategy</strong> must be planned before mobile releases.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L3-05: Linux file permissions and ACLs (concept)</em>:</strong> Help desk scenarios test whether you know <strong>identity proofing</strong> vs <strong>account recovery</strong> abuse. The secure path verifies the human through out-of-band channels without teaching attackers how to bypass your process in the stem text.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L3-05: Linux file permissions and ACLs (concept)</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L3-05: Linux file permissions and ACLs (concept)</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L3-05: Linux file permissions and ACLs (concept)</em>:</strong> Advanced topics still return to fundamentals: least privilege, segmentation, logging, and tested recovery. When you see Zero Trust or PQC buzzwords, map them back to concrete controls and threat models rather than treating them as magic shields.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L3-05: Linux file permissions and ACLs (concept)</em>:</strong> RADIUS is still referenced for <strong>network access control</strong> integrations; know it as a AAA component in enterprise Wi-Fi contexts.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L3-05: Linux file permissions and ACLs (concept)</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L3-05: Linux file permissions and ACLs (concept)</em>:</strong> Controls fail in three predictable ways: <strong>misconfiguration</strong>, <strong>missing coverage</strong> (gaps between tools), and <strong>human process</strong> breakdown (exceptions, shared accounts, emergency access). When you read a scenario, ask which failure mode is most plausible before picking an answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L3-05: Linux file permissions and ACLs (concept)</em>:</strong> DAST exercises running apps but misses authz logic without credentials; combine with <strong>manual review</strong> for business-rule flaws.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L3-05: Linux file permissions and ACLs (concept)</em>:</strong> Access control stems frequently mix <strong>role</strong> vs <strong>attribute</strong> vs <strong>rule</strong> models; pick the answer that matches the scenario’s constraints (temporary contractor, cross-department data, dynamic tags on resources).</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> During a tabletop, the CFO asks how “L3-05: Linux file permissions and ACLs (concept)” could become a material incident. Answer with <strong>one plausible attack path</strong>, <strong>one detective control</strong> you already have, and <strong>one preventive gap</strong> you would fund next quarter.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l3-06":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L3-06: `sudo` and privilege escalation mindset (defender view)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-06</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Why unrestricted sudo is dangerous; logging to central SIEM.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>sudo -l</code> — list allowed commands; write one abuse scenario <strong>without</strong> executing it.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-06</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Level 3 aligns with Security+ <strong>operations and engineering</strong>: vuln management, logging/SIEM concepts, IAM patterns, threat modeling, and IR mechanics. Writers blend domains—patch urgency plus change window is a classic pair.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 3 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Purple / red / blue</strong></dt><dd>Red emulates adversaries, blue defends, purple bridges—authorization and logging are mandatory for any simulation.</dd><dt><strong>WAF vs IPS</strong></dt><dd>WAF focuses on application-layer attacks; IPS often line-rate network signatures—overlap exists but priorities differ.</dd><dt><strong>Due diligence</strong></dt><dd>Investigation and verification before decisions (vendor risk, M&amp;A) to ensure claims about controls are credible.</dd><dt><strong>Certificate pinning (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Client remembers expected server key material—reduces MITM from rogue CAs but complicates rotation; mostly seen in mobile/API hardening patterns.</dd><dt><strong>Logging &amp; monitoring</strong></dt><dd>CloudTrail-style management events differ from data-plane logs—enable central export, immutability, and alerting.</dd><dt><strong>Data loss prevention (DLP)</strong></dt><dd>Content-aware controls to block or alert on sensitive data movement—policy + tech, tuned to avoid blocking work.</dd><dt><strong>MTTD / MTTR</strong></dt><dd>Mean time to detect / remediate—quality matters; gaming metrics by closing tickets inflates false success.</dd><dt><strong>PII</strong></dt><dd>Personally identifiable information—names, government IDs, biometrics, account numbers; triggers handling, retention, and breach rules.</dd><dt><strong>AEAD</strong></dt><dd>Authenticated encryption with associated data—confidentiality plus integrity in one primitive (e.g., AES-GCM) when used correctly.</dd><dt><strong>Third-party risk</strong></dt><dd>Vendor access expands attack surface—DPAs, SOC reports, and continuous monitoring for critical suppliers.</dd><dt><strong>PBKDF2 / Argon2 (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Key derivation functions that slow brute force—work factors must track attacker economics.</dd><dt><strong>Data residency</strong></dt><dd>Legal requirement for where data lives—impacts cloud region selection and key custody.</dd><dt><strong>SSO</strong></dt><dd>Single sign-on federates trust to an IdP—misconfigured SAML/OIDC trusts are high-impact; validate metadata and signing keys.</dd><dt><strong>Security headers</strong></dt><dd>HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options/Frame-ancestors, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy—reduce browser-driven attack surface.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Typical exam angle</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Confidentiality</strong></td><td>Who may read? Encryption, ACLs, DLP, classification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Integrity</strong></td><td>Was it modified? Hashing, signatures, change control, backups.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Availability</strong></td><td>Can authorized users work? HA, patching windows, DDoS defense, DR.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authenticity / non-repudiation</strong></td><td>Prove source and intent—signatures, strong issuance, tamper-evident logs.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Admission controllers can block privileged pods—policy-as-code integrates with GitOps reviews.</li><li>SameSite=Lax blocks many CSRF POSTs from cross-site contexts in modern browsers—know the nuance vs Strict.</li><li>Race conditions in web apps can undermine authorization—sequential logic tests in secure design reviews.</li><li>PCI DSS scope reduction via segmentation is a recurring theme—if it is not in scope, it cannot drag you into assessment.</li><li>JWT alg:none historical vulnerability class—always validate algorithm and signature keys explicitly.</li><li>UDP-based protocols can be abused for amplification DDoS—patch open resolvers and monitor volumetric baselines.</li><li>DNS over HTTPS changes visibility for some networks—understand resolver policy and logging tradeoffs.</li><li>Responsible disclosure timelines balance vendor patch readiness with public safety—coordinate, don’t surprise.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L3-06: `sudo` and privilege escalation mindset (defender view)</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L3-06: `sudo` and privilege escalation mindset (defender view)</em>:</strong> Risk decisions are economic: organizations <strong>accept</strong>, <strong>mitigate</strong>, <strong>transfer</strong> (insurance, outsourcing with contracts), or <strong>avoid</strong> (stop the activity). Controls change likelihood or impact; residual risk should be explicit, not invisible.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L3-06: `sudo` and privilege escalation mindset (defender view)</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L3-06: `sudo` and privilege escalation mindset (defender view)</em>:</strong> Controls fail in three predictable ways: <strong>misconfiguration</strong>, <strong>missing coverage</strong> (gaps between tools), and <strong>human process</strong> breakdown (exceptions, shared accounts, emergency access). When you read a scenario, ask which failure mode is most plausible before picking an answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L3-06: `sudo` and privilege escalation mindset (defender view)</em>:</strong> Container escape questions hinge on <strong>kernel boundary</strong> and misconfigured capabilities—namespaces are helpful but not a complete trust boundary without seccomp, AppArmor, and least-privileged service accounts.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L3-06: `sudo` and privilege escalation mindset (defender view)</em>:</strong> Clean desk pairs with <strong>screen privacy</strong> and <strong>clear desk checks</strong> for regulated spaces—physical + procedural controls together.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L3-06: `sudo` and privilege escalation mindset (defender view)</em>:</strong> Email security stems often combine SPF alignment failures with <strong>look-alike domains</strong>. The best answer addresses user training plus technical authenticity controls, not only one or the other.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L3-06: `sudo` and privilege escalation mindset (defender view)</em>:</strong> TPM-backed BitLocker keys illustrate <strong>key protection</strong> binding to platform state—recovery keys must be guarded like crown jewels.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L3-06: `sudo` and privilege escalation mindset (defender view)</em>:</strong> Wireless assessments should mention <strong>rogue AP</strong> discovery, client isolation, and guest segmentation—not just “use WPA2” as a slogan. Exam writers like the distinction between personal and enterprise authentication modes at a conceptual level.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L3-06: `sudo` and privilege escalation mindset (defender view)</em>:</strong> Air gapped networks still need <strong>patching via sneaker-net</strong> and insider controls—physical isolation is not logical isolation.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> You are the on-call analyst reviewing an alert tied to “L3-06: `sudo` and privilege escalation mindset (defender view)”. Leadership wants a <strong>60-second</strong> brief: business impact, evidence gaps, and the <strong>first</strong> containment step that preserves logs. No tool-specific jargon—prioritize scope, evidence, blast radius, then root-cause remediation under change control.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l3-07":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L3-07: Syslog/journald and remote log shipping idea</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-07</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Tamper-aware logging; time sync (NTP) for correlation.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>timedatectl status</code>; <code>journalctl -u ssh --since &quot;1 hour ago&quot; | tail -n 15</code>.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-07</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>IR stems test <strong>containment vs evidence</strong> tension—choose actions that preserve hashes and legal escalation paths.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 3 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>CVE</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures identifier for a specific flaw—pairs with CVSS severity and vendor advisories for prioritization.</dd><dt><strong>Security awareness</strong></dt><dd>Training plus culture—measure reporting rates, not shame metrics; phishing simulations should reinforce reporting.</dd><dt><strong>Need to know</strong></dt><dd>Finer than least privilege for data—access only to the minimum subset required for the current task.</dd><dt><strong>Port knocking (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Obscurity-based pre-auth to open firewall—weak alone; exam may present as non-primary control.</dd><dt><strong>Data residency</strong></dt><dd>Legal requirement for where data lives—impacts cloud region selection and key custody.</dd><dt><strong>Control</strong></dt><dd>Administrative, technical, or physical safeguards that reduce likelihood or impact of a security event (prevent, detect, correct).</dd><dt><strong>Session management</strong></dt><dd>Server-side session IDs or tokens must rotate on privilege change, bind to channel, and expire predictably.</dd><dt><strong>PKI</strong></dt><dd>Public Key Infrastructure—CAs, RAs, CRL/OCSP, and certificate lifecycle; mis-issuance or weak validation breaks trust chains.</dd><dt><strong>MITRE ATT&amp;CK</strong></dt><dd>Tactics (why) and techniques (how) adversaries operate—use for detection engineering, gap analysis, and purple team scenarios.</dd><dt><strong>Threat intelligence lifecycle</strong></dt><dd>Planning, collection, processing, analysis, dissemination, feedback—intel must change detections or posture or it is shelf-ware.</dd><dt><strong>Certificate transparency (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Public logs of issued certs help detect mis-issued certificates for your domains.</dd><dt><strong>NetFlow / IPFIX</strong></dt><dd>Flow metadata for volume and anomaly detection—lighter than PCAP but less payload visibility.</dd><dt><strong>Firewall</strong></dt><dd>Enforces allow/deny rules on traffic—stateful inspection tracks sessions; default-deny with explicit permits is the secure baseline.</dd><dt><strong>Policy vs standard vs procedure</strong></dt><dd>Policy states intent; standards define mandatory requirements; procedures are step-by-step how-to for operators.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li><li>Certificate pinning misconfigurations can brick apps—plan rotation and emergency releases.</li><li>AES-128 is not “half as strong” as AES-256 in practical threat models for many cases—key management quality dominates.</li><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li><li>SLSA levels describe increasing supply-chain assurance—useful vocabulary in modern governance questions.</li><li>Linux auth.log style entries pair with SSH brute-force detection patterns—velocity and geo anomalies.</li><li>GCP service account keys are long-lived secrets—prefer workload identity federation from CI where possible.</li><li>ATT&CK technique IDs are stable references for detection content—good for purple team reporting.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L3-07: Syslog/journald and remote log shipping idea</em>:</strong> Tabletop exercises test <strong>comms trees</strong>, legal escalation, and customer notification templates—not only technical runbooks.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L3-07: Syslog/journald and remote log shipping idea</em>:</strong> Certificate pinning failures during rotation teach why <strong>key continuity strategy</strong> must be planned before mobile releases.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L3-07: Syslog/journald and remote log shipping idea</em>:</strong> Virtualization risks include <strong>snapshot sprawl</strong> containing secrets and stale VM images drifting from hardened baselines.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L3-07: Syslog/journald and remote log shipping idea</em>:</strong> For the Security+ mindset, translate every control into <strong>who</strong> it protects, <strong>what</strong> asset is at risk, and <strong>how</strong> you would detect failure. Interview and exam items often reward practical prioritization over buzzwords—choose the mitigation that reduces realistic loss first.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L3-07: Syslog/journald and remote log shipping idea</em>:</strong> Application security scenarios often test whether you know <strong>where</strong> enforcement belongs—browser controls supplement but do not replace server-side checks. SameSite cookies, CSP, and HttpOnly mitigate classes of issues; they do not fix broken object-level authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L3-07: Syslog/journald and remote log shipping idea</em>:</strong> Access control stems frequently mix <strong>role</strong> vs <strong>attribute</strong> vs <strong>rule</strong> models; pick the answer that matches the scenario’s constraints (temporary contractor, cross-department data, dynamic tags on resources).</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L3-07: Syslog/journald and remote log shipping idea</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L3-07: Syslog/journald and remote log shipping idea</em>:</strong> When logs “mysteriously stop,” think <strong>time sync failure</strong>, collector saturation, retention misconfiguration, or attacker tampering—in that diagnostic order for a fair exam narrative.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L3-07: Syslog/journald and remote log shipping idea</em>:</strong> Cryptojacking still appears: high CPU, unexpected mining pools, and cloud billing spikes—detection plus credential hygiene beats chasing miner signatures alone.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L3-07: Syslog/journald and remote log shipping idea</em>:</strong> Multicloud complexity increases <strong>identity sprawl</strong>; centralized IdP and consistent conditional access policies reduce human error.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Marketing launches a campaign referencing “L3-07: Syslog/journald and remote log shipping idea” with a new subdomain. Security review finds DNS delegated to an unknown party. Explain <strong>trust chain</strong> risks and the <strong>minimum fixes</strong> before go-live.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l3-08":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L3-08: SIEM concepts — parsing, correlation rules, noise</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-08</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Detection vs prevention; false positives.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Write three Sigma-style pseudo-rules (plaintext) for: brute force SSH, new user added, outbound connection to rare port.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-08</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Detection engineering stems want you to connect <strong>data sources</strong> to <strong>hypothesis</strong>—what log field proves the story?</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 3 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>SSO</strong></dt><dd>Single sign-on federates trust to an IdP—misconfigured SAML/OIDC trusts are high-impact; validate metadata and signing keys.</dd><dt><strong>DNS</strong></dt><dd>Name resolution is a trust anchor—DNSSEC, cache poisoning, and malicious resolutions are classic abuse paths; log resolver anomalies.</dd><dt><strong>Symmetric encryption</strong></dt><dd>Same key encrypts and decrypts—fast for bulk data (AES-GCM); key distribution is the hard problem.</dd><dt><strong>AEAD</strong></dt><dd>Authenticated encryption with associated data—confidentiality plus integrity in one primitive (e.g., AES-GCM) when used correctly.</dd><dt><strong>IDOR</strong></dt><dd>Insecure direct object reference—missing object-level authorization; test horizontal/vertical access with different accounts.</dd><dt><strong>Vulnerability management</strong></dt><dd>Discover, prioritize, remediate, verify, and report—SLAs differ by exposure, exploitability, and asset criticality.</dd><dt><strong>Logging &amp; monitoring</strong></dt><dd>CloudTrail-style management events differ from data-plane logs—enable central export, immutability, and alerting.</dd><dt><strong>BCP / DR</strong></dt><dd>Business continuity and disaster recovery—RTO/RPO drive architecture; test restores, not just backups on paper.</dd><dt><strong>Threat intelligence lifecycle</strong></dt><dd>Planning, collection, processing, analysis, dissemination, feedback—intel must change detections or posture or it is shelf-ware.</dd><dt><strong>Purple / red / blue</strong></dt><dd>Red emulates adversaries, blue defends, purple bridges—authorization and logging are mandatory for any simulation.</dd><dt><strong>Need to know</strong></dt><dd>Finer than least privilege for data—access only to the minimum subset required for the current task.</dd><dt><strong>CRL</strong></dt><dd>Certificate Revocation List—signed list of revoked serials; size/latency issues drove OCSP adoption.</dd><dt><strong>IV / nonce</strong></dt><dd>Initialization vector or number-used-once—must be unique per encryption under a key for many modes.</dd><dt><strong>Proxy vs reverse proxy</strong></dt><dd>Forward proxy represents clients outbound; reverse proxy fronts servers—different trust and logging points.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li><li>Admission controllers can block privileged pods—policy-as-code integrates with GitOps reviews.</li><li>S3 bucket policies and ACLs layer with IAM—effective permissions require understanding intersection.</li><li>Azure AD / Entra conditional access is analogous to risk-based policies—device compliance signals matter.</li><li>Terraform state can hold secrets—remote secure backend and scanning are baseline hygiene.</li><li>SLSA levels describe increasing supply-chain assurance—useful vocabulary in modern governance questions.</li><li>Responsible disclosure timelines balance vendor patch readiness with public safety—coordinate, don’t surprise.</li><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L3-08: SIEM concepts — parsing, correlation rules, noise</em>:</strong> TPM-backed BitLocker keys illustrate <strong>key protection</strong> binding to platform state—recovery keys must be guarded like crown jewels.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L3-08: SIEM concepts — parsing, correlation rules, noise</em>:</strong> DAST exercises running apps but misses authz logic without credentials; combine with <strong>manual review</strong> for business-rule flaws.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L3-08: SIEM concepts — parsing, correlation rules, noise</em>:</strong> Data handling questions often hinge on <strong>classification</strong>, <strong>least data</strong>, and <strong>retention</strong>: collect only what you need, keep it only as long as allowed, and destroy securely when done.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L3-08: SIEM concepts — parsing, correlation rules, noise</em>:</strong> Defense in depth is not “more products,” it is <strong>independent mechanisms</strong>—if one layer is bypassed, another still limits movement, slows the adversary, or preserves evidence. Be ready to explain why network controls alone cannot compensate for missing app-layer authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L3-08: SIEM concepts — parsing, correlation rules, noise</em>:</strong> CSP reporting helps tune policy but can leak URLs—<strong>privacy review</strong> of report endpoints matters in regulated environments.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L3-08: SIEM concepts — parsing, correlation rules, noise</em>:</strong> Email security stems often combine SPF alignment failures with <strong>look-alike domains</strong>. The best answer addresses user training plus technical authenticity controls, not only one or the other.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L3-08: SIEM concepts — parsing, correlation rules, noise</em>:</strong> Incident response questions probe containment vs evidence preservation tension, legal escalation, and communication discipline. The exam rewards knowing when to isolate systems, when to involve counsel, and why mass log deletion is catastrophic.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L3-08: SIEM concepts — parsing, correlation rules, noise</em>:</strong> Deception tech is not a replacement for <strong>baselines and patching</strong>; it augments detection when mature processes exist.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L3-08: SIEM concepts — parsing, correlation rules, noise</em>:</strong> Ransomware stems often pair encryption with <strong>exfiltration</strong>—the correct answer may include legal/notification obligations, not only restoring from backup.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L3-08: SIEM concepts — parsing, correlation rules, noise</em>:</strong> Physical security is still on the exam: tailgating, visitor escorts, locks, destruction of media, and environmental controls (fire, HVAC) as availability/confidentiality supports.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> During a tabletop, the CFO asks how “L3-08: SIEM concepts — parsing, correlation rules, noise” could become a material incident. Answer with <strong>one plausible attack path</strong>, <strong>one detective control</strong> you already have, and <strong>one preventive gap</strong> you would fund next quarter.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l3-09":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L3-09: IDS/IPS placement and TLS visibility problem</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-09</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> East-west vs north-south; decryption ethics/legal.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> ASCII diagram with tap, IPS inline, and TLS bump caveats.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-09</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Operations answers should show <strong>measurable process</strong>: SLAs, verification steps, and feedback loops—not heroic one-off fixes.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 3 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Rainbow table</strong></dt><dd>Precomputed hash chains for fast password cracking—salting and modern KDFs are the defense.</dd><dt><strong>Warm site / cold site</strong></dt><dd>Warm has partial hardware ready; cold is space only—cost vs recovery speed tradeoff.</dd><dt><strong>Zero Trust (headline)</strong></dt><dd>Assume breach; verify explicitly per request using identity, device posture, and least privilege—not “trust the LAN.”</dd><dt><strong>Non-repudiation</strong></dt><dd>Prevents a party from credibly denying an action—digital signatures, tamper-evident logs, and time-stamping support it.</dd><dt><strong>SPF / DKIM / DMARC</strong></dt><dd>Email authenticity stack—SPF authorizes senders, DKIM signs messages, DMARC aligns policies and reporting for abuse handling.</dd><dt><strong>IDOR</strong></dt><dd>Insecure direct object reference—missing object-level authorization; test horizontal/vertical access with different accounts.</dd><dt><strong>CASB / SaaS governance</strong></dt><dd>Visibility and policy for sanctioned vs shadow SaaS—OAuth consent attacks and guest sharing are common gaps.</dd><dt><strong>SOC triage order</strong></dt><dd>Scope → impact → evidence → containment hypothesis; avoid fixing symptoms before you know blast radius.</dd><dt><strong>MAC</strong></dt><dd>Message authentication code—integrity with a secret key; differs from digital signature which uses asymmetric keys.</dd><dt><strong>IOC</strong></dt><dd>Indicator of compromise—often ephemeral (IPs, domains); pair with TTP-based detections for durability.</dd><dt><strong>Asset</strong></dt><dd>Anything of value to the organization—data, systems, people, reputation, or services—that security controls protect.</dd><dt><strong>Authorization</strong></dt><dd>What an authenticated subject is allowed to do—RBAC/ABAC, scopes, and server-side checks enforce least privilege.</dd><dt><strong>Symmetric encryption</strong></dt><dd>Same key encrypts and decrypts—fast for bulk data (AES-GCM); key distribution is the hard problem.</dd><dt><strong>CVSS</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerability Scoring System—base metrics describe technical severity; environmental and temporal modifiers refine priority.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Typical exam angle</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Confidentiality</strong></td><td>Who may read? Encryption, ACLs, DLP, classification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Integrity</strong></td><td>Was it modified? Hashing, signatures, change control, backups.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Availability</strong></td><td>Can authorized users work? HA, patching windows, DDoS defense, DR.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authenticity / non-repudiation</strong></td><td>Prove source and intent—signatures, strong issuance, tamper-evident logs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Server-side template injection is distinct from XSS—context and sinks differ.</li><li>Sigma rules are vendor-agnostic detection snippets—tuning required per log source fields.</li><li>UDP-based protocols can be abused for amplification DDoS—patch open resolvers and monitor volumetric baselines.</li><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li><li>OAuth access tokens are not a replacement for server-side authorization checks on every sensitive action.</li><li>Terraform state can hold secrets—remote secure backend and scanning are baseline hygiene.</li><li>JWT alg:none historical vulnerability class—always validate algorithm and signature keys explicitly.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L3-09: IDS/IPS placement and TLS visibility problem</em>:</strong> Risk decisions are economic: organizations <strong>accept</strong>, <strong>mitigate</strong>, <strong>transfer</strong> (insurance, outsourcing with contracts), or <strong>avoid</strong> (stop the activity). Controls change likelihood or impact; residual risk should be explicit, not invisible.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L3-09: IDS/IPS placement and TLS visibility problem</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L3-09: IDS/IPS placement and TLS visibility problem</em>:</strong> Controls fail in three predictable ways: <strong>misconfiguration</strong>, <strong>missing coverage</strong> (gaps between tools), and <strong>human process</strong> breakdown (exceptions, shared accounts, emergency access). When you read a scenario, ask which failure mode is most plausible before picking an answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L3-09: IDS/IPS placement and TLS visibility problem</em>:</strong> Container escape questions hinge on <strong>kernel boundary</strong> and misconfigured capabilities—namespaces are helpful but not a complete trust boundary without seccomp, AppArmor, and least-privileged service accounts.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L3-09: IDS/IPS placement and TLS visibility problem</em>:</strong> Clean desk pairs with <strong>screen privacy</strong> and <strong>clear desk checks</strong> for regulated spaces—physical + procedural controls together.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L3-09: IDS/IPS placement and TLS visibility problem</em>:</strong> Email security stems often combine SPF alignment failures with <strong>look-alike domains</strong>. The best answer addresses user training plus technical authenticity controls, not only one or the other.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L3-09: IDS/IPS placement and TLS visibility problem</em>:</strong> TPM-backed BitLocker keys illustrate <strong>key protection</strong> binding to platform state—recovery keys must be guarded like crown jewels.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L3-09: IDS/IPS placement and TLS visibility problem</em>:</strong> Wireless assessments should mention <strong>rogue AP</strong> discovery, client isolation, and guest segmentation—not just “use WPA2” as a slogan. Exam writers like the distinction between personal and enterprise authentication modes at a conceptual level.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L3-09: IDS/IPS placement and TLS visibility problem</em>:</strong> Air gapped networks still need <strong>patching via sneaker-net</strong> and insider controls—physical isolation is not logical isolation.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L3-09: IDS/IPS placement and TLS visibility problem</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> You are the on-call analyst reviewing an alert tied to “L3-09: IDS/IPS placement and TLS visibility problem”. Leadership wants a <strong>60-second</strong> brief: business impact, evidence gaps, and the <strong>first</strong> containment step that preserves logs. No tool-specific jargon—prioritize scope, evidence, blast radius, then root-cause remediation under change control.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l3-10":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L3-10: MITRE ATT&amp;CK as a common language</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-10</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Tactics vs techniques; sub-techniques; procedures.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Pick technique <code>T1059</code> (read site); map to one log source you have in lab.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-10</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Operations answers should show <strong>measurable process</strong>: SLAs, verification steps, and feedback loops—not heroic one-off fixes.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 3 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Security headers</strong></dt><dd>HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options/Frame-ancestors, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy—reduce browser-driven attack surface.</dd><dt><strong>Token replay</strong></dt><dd>Reusing a stolen token/session artifact—rotation, binding, and short TTLs reduce window.</dd><dt><strong>MITRE ATT&amp;CK</strong></dt><dd>Tactics (why) and techniques (how) adversaries operate—use for detection engineering, gap analysis, and purple team scenarios.</dd><dt><strong>Certificate pinning (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Client remembers expected server key material—reduces MITM from rogue CAs but complicates rotation; mostly seen in mobile/API hardening patterns.</dd><dt><strong>Threat intelligence lifecycle</strong></dt><dd>Planning, collection, processing, analysis, dissemination, feedback—intel must change detections or posture or it is shelf-ware.</dd><dt><strong>Warm site / cold site</strong></dt><dd>Warm has partial hardware ready; cold is space only—cost vs recovery speed tradeoff.</dd><dt><strong>FIDO2 / WebAuthn</strong></dt><dd>Phishing-resistant possession factors using asymmetric crypto and origin binding; preferred where supported.</dd><dt><strong>Shared responsibility model</strong></dt><dd>Cloud provider secures the platform; customer secures configuration, identities, data, and app code in their scope.</dd><dt><strong>ECB mode weakness</strong></dt><dd>Identical plaintext blocks yield identical ciphertext—leaks structure; prefer modes with IVs and authentication.</dd><dt><strong>Risk</strong></dt><dd>The intersection of threat, vulnerability, and impact—often assessed qualitatively (high/medium/low) or with scoring frameworks.</dd><dt><strong>OWASP Top 10</strong></dt><dd>High-prevalence web risks—broken access control and crypto failures often dominate; study each category with one workplace example.</dd><dt><strong>Separation of duties (SoD)</strong></dt><dd>No single person can complete a sensitive transaction alone—classic finance control that also limits insider abuse.</dd><dt><strong>CVE</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures identifier for a specific flaw—pairs with CVSS severity and vendor advisories for prioritization.</dd><dt><strong>VPN</strong></dt><dd>Creates an encrypted tunnel; split tunneling can bypass corporate inspection; VPN is not anonymity or a substitute for app-layer auth.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>GCP service account keys are long-lived secrets—prefer workload identity federation from CI where possible.</li><li>CVSS base does not include your asset criticality—environmental metrics exist for a reason.</li><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li><li>ISO 27001 is an ISMS standard; it emphasizes risk treatment and continual improvement, not a product checklist.</li><li>DNS over HTTPS changes visibility for some networks—understand resolver policy and logging tradeoffs.</li><li>SLSA levels describe increasing supply-chain assurance—useful vocabulary in modern governance questions.</li><li>Sigma rules are vendor-agnostic detection snippets—tuning required per log source fields.</li><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L3-10: MITRE ATT&amp;CK as a common language</em>:</strong> BIOS/UEFI passwords and secure boot reduce some pre-boot attacks but do not stop <strong>evil maid</strong> classes without additional controls.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L3-10: MITRE ATT&amp;CK as a common language</em>:</strong> Controls fail in three predictable ways: <strong>misconfiguration</strong>, <strong>missing coverage</strong> (gaps between tools), and <strong>human process</strong> breakdown (exceptions, shared accounts, emergency access). When you read a scenario, ask which failure mode is most plausible before picking an answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L3-10: MITRE ATT&amp;CK as a common language</em>:</strong> Vulnerability management is a lifecycle: scanners find candidates, analysts prioritize with exploitability and business context, owners remediate, and verification closes the loop. “Patch everything immediately” is rarely operational; <strong>risk-based SLAs</strong> are the adult answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L3-10: MITRE ATT&amp;CK as a common language</em>:</strong> Wireless and mobility items reward knowing basics: WPA3 improvements conceptually, evil twin risks, captive portals, and why client isolation matters on guest networks—without memorizing obsolete WEP details unless explicitly historical.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L3-10: MITRE ATT&amp;CK as a common language</em>:</strong> Engineers often optimize for speed; attackers optimize for <strong>cheap reuse</strong> of stolen creds and known exploits. The winning answer bridges both: ship fast with guardrails—feature flags, staged rollouts, and automated security checks in CI.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L3-10: MITRE ATT&amp;CK as a common language</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L3-10: MITRE ATT&amp;CK as a common language</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L3-10: MITRE ATT&amp;CK as a common language</em>:</strong> API keys in mobile apps are often extractable—prefer <strong>short-lived tokens</strong> and server-mediated access to backends.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L3-10: MITRE ATT&amp;CK as a common language</em>:</strong> TACACS+ vs RADIUS separation of duties in device admin access—exams may contrast accounting granularity.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L3-10: MITRE ATT&amp;CK as a common language</em>:</strong> Sanitization vs wiping vs destruction: exams like knowing which media needs <strong>degaussing, shredding, or crypto erase</strong> per policy.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Internal audit samples “L3-10: MITRE ATT&amp;CK as a common language” controls and finds screenshots instead of config exports. Explain why <strong>authoritative evidence</strong> matters and what you would collect instead.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l3-11":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L3-11: Threat modeling STRIDE (developer collaboration)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-11</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Spoofing, Tampering, Repudiation, Information disclosure, DoS, Elevation.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> STRIDE table for “password reset” feature with one mitigation per row.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-11</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Detection engineering stems want you to connect <strong>data sources</strong> to <strong>hypothesis</strong>—what log field proves the story?</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 3 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>MITRE ATT&amp;CK</strong></dt><dd>Tactics (why) and techniques (how) adversaries operate—use for detection engineering, gap analysis, and purple team scenarios.</dd><dt><strong>GRC</strong></dt><dd>Governance, risk, and compliance—align security decisions with law, policy, and business appetite; audits test design and operation.</dd><dt><strong>PQC</strong></dt><dd>Post-quantum cryptography migration—hybrid schemes and crypto-agility for long-lived secrets exposed to harvest-now/decrypt-later risk.</dd><dt><strong>Need to know</strong></dt><dd>Finer than least privilege for data—access only to the minimum subset required for the current task.</dd><dt><strong>Collision (hash)</strong></dt><dd>Two inputs produce same hash—breaks integrity assumptions; choose strong hash families for security use.</dd><dt><strong>WAF vs IPS</strong></dt><dd>WAF focuses on application-layer attacks; IPS often line-rate network signatures—overlap exists but priorities differ.</dd><dt><strong>Kill chain / cyber kill chain</strong></dt><dd>Stages of intrusion—mapping controls and detections to stages clarifies coverage gaps.</dd><dt><strong>Confidential computing</strong></dt><dd>Use of hardware enclaves/TEEs to reduce exposure to privileged operators—threat model still required.</dd><dt><strong>Vulnerability</strong></dt><dd>A weakness in design, implementation, configuration, or process that could be exploited to violate a security policy.</dd><dt><strong>Authenticity</strong></dt><dd>Verifies that users, devices, or data are genuine—cryptographic identity, attestation, and strong issuance processes matter.</dd><dt><strong>SSO</strong></dt><dd>Single sign-on federates trust to an IdP—misconfigured SAML/OIDC trusts are high-impact; validate metadata and signing keys.</dd><dt><strong>Network segmentation</strong></dt><dd>VLANs, micro-segmentation, and east-west controls limit lateral movement after an initial foothold.</dd><dt><strong>Input validation vs output encoding</strong></dt><dd>Validation rejects bad input early; encoding neutralizes dangerous characters in the right output context—both are needed across HTML, SQL, OS, and LDAP channels.</dd><dt><strong>CVSS</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerability Scoring System—base metrics describe technical severity; environmental and temporal modifiers refine priority.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>IR phase</th><th>What you do there (exam shorthand)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Prepare</strong></td><td>Playbooks, contacts, tooling, baseline logging—before the pager fires.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detect &amp; analyze</strong></td><td>Scope, timelines, hypotheses—preserve volatile evidence early.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Contain</strong></td><td>Stop spread with minimal evidence damage—network isolation variants matter.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Eradicate &amp; recover</strong></td><td>Remove persistence, patch root cause, restore with verification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Lessons learned</strong></td><td>Metrics, control changes, and communication improvements—close the loop.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>SLSA levels describe increasing supply-chain assurance—useful vocabulary in modern governance questions.</li><li>Azure AD / Entra conditional access is analogous to risk-based policies—device compliance signals matter.</li><li>Admission controllers can block privileged pods—policy-as-code integrates with GitOps reviews.</li><li>Server-side template injection is distinct from XSS—context and sinks differ.</li><li>Certificate pinning misconfigurations can brick apps—plan rotation and emergency releases.</li><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li><li>Sigma rules are vendor-agnostic detection snippets—tuning required per log source fields.</li><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L3-11: Threat modeling STRIDE (developer collaboration)</em>:</strong> Container escape questions hinge on <strong>kernel boundary</strong> and misconfigured capabilities—namespaces are helpful but not a complete trust boundary without seccomp, AppArmor, and least-privileged service accounts.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L3-11: Threat modeling STRIDE (developer collaboration)</em>:</strong> For the Security+ mindset, translate every control into <strong>who</strong> it protects, <strong>what</strong> asset is at risk, and <strong>how</strong> you would detect failure. Interview and exam items often reward practical prioritization over buzzwords—choose the mitigation that reduces realistic loss first.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L3-11: Threat modeling STRIDE (developer collaboration)</em>:</strong> Serverless cold start is not a security control; <strong>per-function IAM</strong> and least-privilege API scopes are. Watch for attractive nonsense distractors tied to performance tuning.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L3-11: Threat modeling STRIDE (developer collaboration)</em>:</strong> Controls fail in three predictable ways: <strong>misconfiguration</strong>, <strong>missing coverage</strong> (gaps between tools), and <strong>human process</strong> breakdown (exceptions, shared accounts, emergency access). When you read a scenario, ask which failure mode is most plausible before picking an answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L3-11: Threat modeling STRIDE (developer collaboration)</em>:</strong> KMS keys are not “magic secrecy dust”—<strong>who can invoke decrypt</strong> and from which contexts (VPC endpoint policies, IAM conditions) is what exams probe.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L3-11: Threat modeling STRIDE (developer collaboration)</em>:</strong> Defense in depth is not “more products,” it is <strong>independent mechanisms</strong>—if one layer is bypassed, another still limits movement, slows the adversary, or preserves evidence. Be ready to explain why network controls alone cannot compensate for missing app-layer authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L3-11: Threat modeling STRIDE (developer collaboration)</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L3-11: Threat modeling STRIDE (developer collaboration)</em>:</strong> Security operations value <strong>repeatable evidence</strong>: timestamps, authoritative configuration sources, and tamper-aware logs beat heroic memory after an incident. Many exam questions hinge on whether an action preserves integrity and accountability rather than whether it feels fast.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L3-11: Threat modeling STRIDE (developer collaboration)</em>:</strong> Ransomware stems often pair encryption with <strong>exfiltration</strong>—the correct answer may include legal/notification obligations, not only restoring from backup.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L3-11: Threat modeling STRIDE (developer collaboration)</em>:</strong> Risk decisions are economic: organizations <strong>accept</strong>, <strong>mitigate</strong>, <strong>transfer</strong> (insurance, outsourcing with contracts), or <strong>avoid</strong> (stop the activity). Controls change likelihood or impact; residual risk should be explicit, not invisible.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> During a tabletop, the CFO asks how “L3-11: Threat modeling STRIDE (developer collaboration)” could become a material incident. Answer with <strong>one plausible attack path</strong>, <strong>one detective control</strong> you already have, and <strong>one preventive gap</strong> you would fund next quarter.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l3-12":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L3-12: IAM — RBAC vs ABAC</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-12</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> When attributes beat static roles.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Sketch AWS-style JSON policy allowing <code>s3:GetObject</code> only on <code>arn:.../prefix/${aws:PrincipalTag/team}</code>.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-12</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Operations answers should show <strong>measurable process</strong>: SLAs, verification steps, and feedback loops—not heroic one-off fixes.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 3 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Kerberos (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Ticket-based enterprise auth—TGT vs service tickets; golden/silver ticket classes of abuse appear in advanced IR.</dd><dt><strong>VPN</strong></dt><dd>Creates an encrypted tunnel; split tunneling can bypass corporate inspection; VPN is not anonymity or a substitute for app-layer auth.</dd><dt><strong>Asymmetric encryption</strong></dt><dd>Key pairs for key agreement/signing—RSA/ECC; hybrid TLS uses asymmetric to establish symmetric session keys.</dd><dt><strong>Input validation vs output encoding</strong></dt><dd>Validation rejects bad input early; encoding neutralizes dangerous characters in the right output context—both are needed across HTML, SQL, OS, and LDAP channels.</dd><dt><strong>Security headers</strong></dt><dd>HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options/Frame-ancestors, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy—reduce browser-driven attack surface.</dd><dt><strong>SIEM</strong></dt><dd>Security information and event management—centralize logs, parse fields, correlate alerts; tuning reduces false positives and fatigue.</dd><dt><strong>Misconfiguration</strong></dt><dd>Top cloud incident driver—public buckets, open security groups, permissive trust policies; IaC scanning catches drift early.</dd><dt><strong>Third-party risk</strong></dt><dd>Vendor access expands attack surface—DPAs, SOC reports, and continuous monitoring for critical suppliers.</dd><dt><strong>Attack surface</strong></dt><dd>The sum of exposure—every service, API, integration, and human workflow that can be reached by a threat; reduction beats perfect monitoring alone.</dd><dt><strong>Forensics basics</strong></dt><dd>Volatile vs non-volatile collection, order of volatility, hashing, and legal escalation paths before deep technical work.</dd><dt><strong>Data loss prevention (DLP)</strong></dt><dd>Content-aware controls to block or alert on sensitive data movement—policy + tech, tuned to avoid blocking work.</dd><dt><strong>Salt (crypto)</strong></dt><dd>Random input to a password hash to defeat rainbow tables—must be unique per password.</dd><dt><strong>MAC</strong></dt><dd>Message authentication code—integrity with a secret key; differs from digital signature which uses asymmetric keys.</dd><dt><strong>WAF vs IPS</strong></dt><dd>WAF focuses on application-layer attacks; IPS often line-rate network signatures—overlap exists but priorities differ.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>ISO 27001 is an ISMS standard; it emphasizes risk treatment and continual improvement, not a product checklist.</li><li>PCI DSS scope reduction via segmentation is a recurring theme—if it is not in scope, it cannot drag you into assessment.</li><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>OAuth access tokens are not a replacement for server-side authorization checks on every sensitive action.</li><li>SameSite=Lax blocks many CSRF POSTs from cross-site contexts in modern browsers—know the nuance vs Strict.</li><li>HttpOnly does not stop CSRF; it reduces token theft from XSS reading document.cookie in many setups.</li><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li><li>CVSS base does not include your asset criticality—environmental metrics exist for a reason.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L3-12: IAM — RBAC vs ABAC</em>:</strong> Security operations value <strong>repeatable evidence</strong>: timestamps, authoritative configuration sources, and tamper-aware logs beat heroic memory after an incident. Many exam questions hinge on whether an action preserves integrity and accountability rather than whether it feels fast.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L3-12: IAM — RBAC vs ABAC</em>:</strong> Physical security is still on the exam: tailgating, visitor escorts, locks, destruction of media, and environmental controls (fire, HVAC) as availability/confidentiality supports.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L3-12: IAM — RBAC vs ABAC</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L3-12: IAM — RBAC vs ABAC</em>:</strong> Multicloud complexity increases <strong>identity sprawl</strong>; centralized IdP and consistent conditional access policies reduce human error.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L3-12: IAM — RBAC vs ABAC</em>:</strong> BIOS/UEFI passwords and secure boot reduce some pre-boot attacks but do not stop <strong>evil maid</strong> classes without additional controls.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L3-12: IAM — RBAC vs ABAC</em>:</strong> Application security scenarios often test whether you know <strong>where</strong> enforcement belongs—browser controls supplement but do not replace server-side checks. SameSite cookies, CSP, and HttpOnly mitigate classes of issues; they do not fix broken object-level authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L3-12: IAM — RBAC vs ABAC</em>:</strong> Data handling questions often hinge on <strong>classification</strong>, <strong>least data</strong>, and <strong>retention</strong>: collect only what you need, keep it only as long as allowed, and destroy securely when done.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L3-12: IAM — RBAC vs ABAC</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L3-12: IAM — RBAC vs ABAC</em>:</strong> Subresource integrity protects against <strong>CDN compromise</strong> but requires operational discipline when vendors rotate files.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L3-12: IAM — RBAC vs ABAC</em>:</strong> Clean desk pairs with <strong>screen privacy</strong> and <strong>clear desk checks</strong> for regulated spaces—physical + procedural controls together.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> A vendor integration project mentions “L3-12: IAM — RBAC vs ABAC” as out-of-scope for pen testing. Explain what <strong>residual risk</strong> remains, what <strong>compensating monitoring</strong> you would demand, and how you would <strong>document acceptance</strong>.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l3-13":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L3-13: OAuth2 / OIDC flows (authorization code + PKCE)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-13</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Tokens, audiences, scopes; common misconfigurations.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Sequence diagram: user, browser, IdP, client, resource server — 6 numbered steps.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-13</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Threat modeling at this level stays <strong>STRIDE-shaped</strong>—name the abuse, then map a proportional control.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 3 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Port knocking (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Obscurity-based pre-auth to open firewall—weak alone; exam may present as non-primary control.</dd><dt><strong>Due care</strong></dt><dd>The effort a prudent person would take to meet a duty; in security, reasonable steps to protect assets and stakeholders.</dd><dt><strong>Symmetric encryption</strong></dt><dd>Same key encrypts and decrypts—fast for bulk data (AES-GCM); key distribution is the hard problem.</dd><dt><strong>Container security</strong></dt><dd>Image provenance, non-root users, read-only roots, seccomp/AppArmor, and admission control for risky capabilities.</dd><dt><strong>OCSP stapling (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Server sends fresh revocation info with handshake—reduces client privacy leaks and lookup failures.</dd><dt><strong>UEBA</strong></dt><dd>User and entity behavior analytics—baseline deviations; tune to avoid HR/privacy backlash.</dd><dt><strong>Kerberos (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Ticket-based enterprise auth—TGT vs service tickets; golden/silver ticket classes of abuse appear in advanced IR.</dd><dt><strong>CVE</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures identifier for a specific flaw—pairs with CVSS severity and vendor advisories for prioritization.</dd><dt><strong>Purple / red / blue</strong></dt><dd>Red emulates adversaries, blue defends, purple bridges—authorization and logging are mandatory for any simulation.</dd><dt><strong>NetFlow / IPFIX</strong></dt><dd>Flow metadata for volume and anomaly detection—lighter than PCAP but less payload visibility.</dd><dt><strong>Availability</strong></dt><dd>Assures timely and reliable access—redundancy, patching, DDoS defenses, and DR planning keep services usable for authorized users.</dd><dt><strong>Encoding (e.g., Base64)</strong></dt><dd>Transforms representation without cryptographic protection—do not confuse with encryption or integrity.</dd><dt><strong>Third-party risk</strong></dt><dd>Vendor access expands attack surface—DPAs, SOC reports, and continuous monitoring for critical suppliers.</dd><dt><strong>Collision (hash)</strong></dt><dd>Two inputs produce same hash—breaks integrity assumptions; choose strong hash families for security use.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Bug bounty scope must exclude destructive testing—safe harbor language still needs legal review.</li><li>GCP service account keys are long-lived secrets—prefer workload identity federation from CI where possible.</li><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li><li>Race conditions in web apps can undermine authorization—sequential logic tests in secure design reviews.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li><li>CVSS base does not include your asset criticality—environmental metrics exist for a reason.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L3-13: OAuth2 / OIDC flows (authorization code + PKCE)</em>:</strong> For the Security+ mindset, for “L3-13: OAuth2 / OIDC flows (authorization code + PKCE)”, translate every control into <strong>who</strong> it protects, <strong>what</strong> asset is at risk, and <strong>how</strong> you would detect failure. Interview and exam items often reward practical prioritization over buzzwords—choose the mitigation that reduces realistic loss first.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L3-13: OAuth2 / OIDC flows (authorization code + PKCE)</em>:</strong> SAST finds issues early but produces false positives; <strong>triage workflows</strong> and developer feedback loops are part of a mature program, not “run tool once.”</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L3-13: OAuth2 / OIDC flows (authorization code + PKCE)</em>:</strong> Logging questions often test whether you understand <strong>what to log</strong> (who, what, when, where, outcome), <strong>time sync</strong> for correlation, and <strong>tamper resistance</strong> for evidentiary value—not whether you can collect infinite bytes.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L3-13: OAuth2 / OIDC flows (authorization code + PKCE)</em>:</strong> TACACS+ vs RADIUS separation of duties in device admin access—exams may contrast accounting granularity.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L3-13: OAuth2 / OIDC flows (authorization code + PKCE)</em>:</strong> Industrial and OT adjacent questions reward knowing <strong>safety vs security</strong> tension: availability may trump confidentiality; testing must avoid breaking physical processes.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L3-13: OAuth2 / OIDC flows (authorization code + PKCE)</em>:</strong> Defense in depth is not “more products,” it is <strong>independent mechanisms</strong>—if one layer is bypassed, another still limits movement, slows the adversary, or preserves evidence. Be ready to explain why network controls alone cannot compensate for missing app-layer authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L3-13: OAuth2 / OIDC flows (authorization code + PKCE)</em>:</strong> Penetration tests require <strong>written authorization</strong>, defined scope, and rules of engagement—even in internal labs for professional conduct.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L3-13: OAuth2 / OIDC flows (authorization code + PKCE)</em>:</strong> Wireless and mobility items reward knowing basics: WPA3 improvements conceptually, evil twin risks, captive portals, and why client isolation matters on guest networks—without memorizing obsolete WEP details unless explicitly historical.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L3-13: OAuth2 / OIDC flows (authorization code + PKCE)</em>:</strong> Deception tech is not a replacement for <strong>baselines and patching</strong>; it augments detection when mature processes exist.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L3-13: OAuth2 / OIDC flows (authorization code + PKCE)</em>:</strong> When logs “mysteriously stop,” think <strong>time sync failure</strong>, collector saturation, retention misconfiguration, or attacker tampering—in that diagnostic order for a fair exam narrative.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Legal asks whether “L3-13: OAuth2 / OIDC flows (authorization code + PKCE)” artifacts require <strong>hold</strong> before deletion. Describe how you would <strong>tag systems</strong>, <strong>freeze backups</strong> appropriately, and <strong>escalate</strong> without tipping external actors.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l3-14":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L3-14: Secrets management (vaults, rotation, no keys in git)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-14</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Short-lived credentials; break-glass.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>git log --all --full-history -- &quot;*.env&quot; 2&gt;/dev/null | head</code> on a dummy repo — explain blast radius.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-14</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Vulnerability prioritization is not “CVSS only”—think <strong>exposure</strong>, <strong>exploitability</strong>, and <strong>asset value</strong> together.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 3 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Injection</strong></dt><dd>Untrusted input becomes part of a command or query—parameterized queries, input validation, and context escaping are core defenses.</dd><dt><strong>Logging &amp; monitoring</strong></dt><dd>CloudTrail-style management events differ from data-plane logs—enable central export, immutability, and alerting.</dd><dt><strong>PQC</strong></dt><dd>Post-quantum cryptography migration—hybrid schemes and crypto-agility for long-lived secrets exposed to harvest-now/decrypt-later risk.</dd><dt><strong>OCSP stapling (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Server sends fresh revocation info with handshake—reduces client privacy leaks and lookup failures.</dd><dt><strong>Full packet capture</strong></dt><dd>High fidelity evidence for investigations—storage, privacy, and legal review constraints apply.</dd><dt><strong>CVE</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures identifier for a specific flaw—pairs with CVSS severity and vendor advisories for prioritization.</dd><dt><strong>Residual risk</strong></dt><dd>Risk remaining after controls are applied; organizations accept, transfer, mitigate, or avoid it explicitly.</dd><dt><strong>Session management</strong></dt><dd>Server-side session IDs or tokens must rotate on privilege change, bind to channel, and expire predictably.</dd><dt><strong>Hashing</strong></dt><dd>One-way fingerprint for integrity verification—SHA-256 family; not secrecy; used with HMAC for keyed integrity.</dd><dt><strong>CVSS</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerability Scoring System—base metrics describe technical severity; environmental and temporal modifiers refine priority.</dd><dt><strong>Third-party risk</strong></dt><dd>Vendor access expands attack surface—DPAs, SOC reports, and continuous monitoring for critical suppliers.</dd><dt><strong>Separation of duties (SoD)</strong></dt><dd>No single person can complete a sensitive transaction alone—classic finance control that also limits insider abuse.</dd><dt><strong>IV / nonce</strong></dt><dd>Initialization vector or number-used-once—must be unique per encryption under a key for many modes.</dd><dt><strong>OODA loop (IR)</strong></dt><dd>Observe-orient-decide-act—adversary and defender both iterate; faster, accurate decisions beat hoarding data.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Typical exam angle</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Confidentiality</strong></td><td>Who may read? Encryption, ACLs, DLP, classification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Integrity</strong></td><td>Was it modified? Hashing, signatures, change control, backups.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Availability</strong></td><td>Can authorized users work? HA, patching windows, DDoS defense, DR.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authenticity / non-repudiation</strong></td><td>Prove source and intent—signatures, strong issuance, tamper-evident logs.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>DNS over HTTPS changes visibility for some networks—understand resolver policy and logging tradeoffs.</li><li>SLSA levels describe increasing supply-chain assurance—useful vocabulary in modern governance questions.</li><li>Sigma rules are vendor-agnostic detection snippets—tuning required per log source fields.</li><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li><li>OAuth access tokens are not a replacement for server-side authorization checks on every sensitive action.</li><li>JWT alg:none historical vulnerability class—always validate algorithm and signature keys explicitly.</li><li>AES-128 is not “half as strong” as AES-256 in practical threat models for many cases—key management quality dominates.</li><li>Immutable backups mitigate ransomware that tries to delete online copies—air-gapped or WORM patterns.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L3-14: Secrets management (vaults, rotation, no keys in git)</em>:</strong> SAST finds issues early but produces false positives; <strong>triage workflows</strong> and developer feedback loops are part of a mature program, not “run tool once.”</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L3-14: Secrets management (vaults, rotation, no keys in git)</em>:</strong> Virtualization risks include <strong>snapshot sprawl</strong> containing secrets and stale VM images drifting from hardened baselines.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L3-14: Secrets management (vaults, rotation, no keys in git)</em>:</strong> Cloud items assume you can articulate <strong>shared responsibility</strong>: what the provider patches vs what the customer must configure (IAM, encryption, network exposure). Misconfiguration beats novel cloud exploits in real incidents and on the exam.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L3-14: Secrets management (vaults, rotation, no keys in git)</em>:</strong> Email security stems often combine SPF alignment failures with <strong>look-alike domains</strong>. The best answer addresses user training plus technical authenticity controls, not only one or the other.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L3-14: Secrets management (vaults, rotation, no keys in git)</em>:</strong> GraphQL introspection risk is about <strong>schema discovery</strong> aiding attackers—rate limits, authz on fields, and disabling introspection in prod are common answers.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L3-14: Secrets management (vaults, rotation, no keys in git)</em>:</strong> For the Security+ mindset, translate every control into <strong>who</strong> it protects, <strong>what</strong> asset is at risk, and <strong>how</strong> you would detect failure. Interview and exam items often reward practical prioritization over buzzwords—choose the mitigation that reduces realistic loss first.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L3-14: Secrets management (vaults, rotation, no keys in git)</em>:</strong> Patching and change management appear as <strong>risk tradeoffs</strong>: emergency patches vs testing rings; compensating monitoring when patching lags; and documenting exceptions for auditors.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L3-14: Secrets management (vaults, rotation, no keys in git)</em>:</strong> Ransomware stems often pair encryption with <strong>exfiltration</strong>—the correct answer may include legal/notification obligations, not only restoring from backup.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L3-14: Secrets management (vaults, rotation, no keys in git)</em>:</strong> Honeypots can generate high-signal alerts but carry <strong>legal and operational</strong> risk if touched by real users; scope carefully.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L3-14: Secrets management (vaults, rotation, no keys in git)</em>:</strong> Application security scenarios often test whether you know <strong>where</strong> enforcement belongs—browser controls supplement but do not replace server-side checks. SameSite cookies, CSP, and HttpOnly mitigate classes of issues; they do not fix broken object-level authorization.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Junior staff proposes a quick fix for “L3-14: Secrets management (vaults, rotation, no keys in git)” that disables logging on a noisy host. Walk through why that is unacceptable and propose a <strong>tuning</strong> path that preserves <strong>integrity and retention</strong> commitments.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l3-15":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L3-15: Incident response phases (NIST-style)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-15</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Prepare, detect, analyze, contain, eradicate, recover, post-incident.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Create <code>~/ir-playbook-mini.md</code> with roles: IC, tech lead, comms, legal — RACI snippet.</p>\n<h2>Lab pack — Level 3</h2>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Vuln triage simulation:</strong> Given 5 fake CVE rows (make up), assign priority using CVSS + exploitability + asset criticality table.  </li>\n<li><strong>SSH review:</strong> Export sanitized <code>sshd -T</code> effective config if available; circle 5 hardening opportunities.  </li>\n<li><strong>Log correlation:</strong> Merge SSH logs + <code>auth.log</code> style entries; write one timeline paragraph.  </li>\n<li><strong>ATT&amp;CK navigator export (optional):</strong> Build tiny layer JSON for 10 techniques relevant to your org’s stack (concept).  </li>\n<li><strong>Secret scan:</strong> Run <code>trufflehog filesystem --directory .</code> only on a <strong>synthetic</strong> repo you create with fake keys — verify detection.</li>\n</ol>\n<h2>Question bank — Level 3</h2>\n<p><strong>Q1.</strong> CVSS base score communicates: (a) legal liability (b) technical severity snapshot (c) stock price.<br><strong>Q2.</strong> CVE identifies: (a) a specific vulnerability instance (b) a standardized ID for a vuln (c) a firewall SKU.<br><strong>Q3.</strong> CIS benchmarks are: (a) malware (b) configuration hardening guidance (c) TLS cipher lists only.<br><strong>Q4.</strong> <code>PermitRootLogin no</code> primarily reduces: (a) DNS leaks (b) high-impact credential abuse (c) GPU theft.<br><strong>Q5.</strong> SIEM correlation aims to: (a) replace firewalls (b) detect multi-event patterns (c) encrypt disks.<br><strong>Q6.</strong> IDS vs IPS: (a) IPS can actively block inline (b) identical always (c) IDS only for Wi-Fi.<br><strong>Q7.</strong> MITRE technique vs tactic: (a) same (b) tactic is goal; technique is how (c) tactic is CVE.<br><strong>Q8.</strong> STRIDE “Spoofing” mitigations often include: (a) weaker TLS (b) authentication (c) deleting logs.<br><strong>Q9.</strong> RBAC maps permissions to: (a) job function/role (b) CPU stepping (c) DHCP lease time.<br><strong>Q10.</strong> PKCE mainly protects: (a) public OAuth clients in code flow (b) RAID (c) BIOS.<br><strong>Q11.</strong> Vault rotation reduces: (a) blast radius of leaked creds (b) need for MFA (c) RAM size.<br><strong>Q12.</strong> NTP importance for logs: (a) pretty fonts (b) correlation across systems (c) GPU render.<br><strong>Q13.</strong> <code>sudo -l</code> helps auditors see: (a) kernel modules only (b) permitted privilege commands (c) Wi-Fi SSID.<br><strong>Q14.</strong> Remote syslog goal: (a) slower apps (b) attacker cannot cover tracks on host only (c) replace MFA.<br><strong>Q15.</strong> Threat modeling timing: (a) only after breach (b) design phase and changes (c) never for APIs.<br><strong>Q16.</strong> ABAC can use: (a) attributes like department, clearance, resource tags (b) only usernames (c) only file size.<br><strong>Q17.</strong> Incident “containment” means: (a) press release only (b) limit spread/damage (c) delete all servers.<br><strong>Q18.</strong> TLS inspection appliances raise: (a) privacy and legal considerations (b) no issues (c) only GPU issues.<br><strong>Q19.</strong> CWE helps: (a) classify weakness types (b) assign stock tickers (c) replace CVSS.<br><strong>Q20.</strong> Principle “verify remediation” means: (a) rescan/retest after fix (b) assume fixed (c) hide tickets.</p>\n<h3>Answer key — Level 3</h3>\n<p>1–5: B/B/B/B/B<br>6–10: B/B/B/B/A<br>11–15: B/B/B/B/A<br>16–20: A/B/A/A/A  </p>\n<hr>\n<h1>Level 4 — Expert (enterprise identity, cloud, detection engineering, forensics hygiene)</h1>\n<p><strong>Workplace outcomes:</strong> You can discuss AD/Azure patterns, cloud IAM guardrails, detection as code, and evidence handling with IT/legal.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-15</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Detection engineering stems want you to connect <strong>data sources</strong> to <strong>hypothesis</strong>—what log field proves the story?</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 3 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>TLS</strong></dt><dd>Encrypts data in motion and authenticates endpoints when certificates and hostnames are validated; termination points affect trust boundaries.</dd><dt><strong>Injection</strong></dt><dd>Untrusted input becomes part of a command or query—parameterized queries, input validation, and context escaping are core defenses.</dd><dt><strong>Encryption at rest / in transit</strong></dt><dd>KMS/HSM-backed keys, envelope encryption, and TLS everywhere for administrative and user paths.</dd><dt><strong>Purple / red / blue</strong></dt><dd>Red emulates adversaries, blue defends, purple bridges—authorization and logging are mandatory for any simulation.</dd><dt><strong>Block cipher vs stream</strong></dt><dd>Block operates on fixed-size chunks; stream on bits/bytes—misuse modes (e.g., ECB) create patterns.</dd><dt><strong>OODA loop (IR)</strong></dt><dd>Observe-orient-decide-act—adversary and defender both iterate; faster, accurate decisions beat hoarding data.</dd><dt><strong>Security control categories</strong></dt><dd>Technical (firewalls, encryption), administrative (policies, training), and physical (badges, locks)—exam items often ask which category fits a scenario.</dd><dt><strong>PII</strong></dt><dd>Personally identifiable information—names, government IDs, biometrics, account numbers; triggers handling, retention, and breach rules.</dd><dt><strong>Network segmentation</strong></dt><dd>VLANs, micro-segmentation, and east-west controls limit lateral movement after an initial foothold.</dd><dt><strong>Secure SDLC</strong></dt><dd>Requirements, threat modeling, secure design, code review, SAST/DAST, dependency scanning, and hardened deployment pipelines.</dd><dt><strong>BCP / DR</strong></dt><dd>Business continuity and disaster recovery—RTO/RPO drive architecture; test restores, not just backups on paper.</dd><dt><strong>Job rotation</strong></dt><dd>Reduces collusion and fraud risk; also surfaces “tribal knowledge” silos before an employee leaves.</dd><dt><strong>Diffie-Hellman (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Key agreement over insecure channel—combine with authentication to prevent MITM.</dd><dt><strong>SOAR</strong></dt><dd>Security orchestration, automation, response—playbooks must have human gates for destructive actions.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Linux auth.log style entries pair with SSH brute-force detection patterns—velocity and geo anomalies.</li><li>Bug bounty scope must exclude destructive testing—safe harbor language still needs legal review.</li><li>DNS over HTTPS changes visibility for some networks—understand resolver policy and logging tradeoffs.</li><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li><li>Server-side template injection is distinct from XSS—context and sinks differ.</li><li>SameSite=Lax blocks many CSRF POSTs from cross-site contexts in modern browsers—know the nuance vs Strict.</li><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li><li>ATT&CK technique IDs are stable references for detection content—good for purple team reporting.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L3-15: Incident response phases (NIST-style)</em>:</strong> Ransomware stems often pair encryption with <strong>exfiltration</strong>—the correct answer may include legal/notification obligations, not only restoring from backup.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L3-15: Incident response phases (NIST-style)</em>:</strong> Risk decisions are economic: organizations <strong>accept</strong>, <strong>mitigate</strong>, <strong>transfer</strong> (insurance, outsourcing with contracts), or <strong>avoid</strong> (stop the activity). Controls change likelihood or impact; residual risk should be explicit, not invisible.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L3-15: Incident response phases (NIST-style)</em>:</strong> Cryptojacking still appears: high CPU, unexpected mining pools, and cloud billing spikes—detection plus credential hygiene beats chasing miner signatures alone.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L3-15: Incident response phases (NIST-style)</em>:</strong> Identity is the new perimeter: credentials, tokens, and sessions are stolen more often than novel zero-days are burned. Expect Security+ items on MFA bypass awareness, phishing-resistant factors, and why <strong>authorization</strong> must be enforced server-side.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L3-15: Incident response phases (NIST-style)</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L3-15: Incident response phases (NIST-style)</em>:</strong> Cryptography questions reward vocabulary precision: hashing vs encryption vs encoding; symmetric vs asymmetric roles in TLS; what signatures prove; and why key management is usually harder than picking an algorithm. If an answer sounds magical, it is probably wrong.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L3-15: Incident response phases (NIST-style)</em>:</strong> SAST finds issues early but produces false positives; <strong>triage workflows</strong> and developer feedback loops are part of a mature program, not “run tool once.”</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L3-15: Incident response phases (NIST-style)</em>:</strong> Application security scenarios often test whether you know <strong>where</strong> enforcement belongs—browser controls supplement but do not replace server-side checks. SameSite cookies, CSP, and HttpOnly mitigate classes of issues; they do not fix broken object-level authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L3-15: Incident response phases (NIST-style)</em>:</strong> DAST exercises running apps but misses authz logic without credentials; combine with <strong>manual review</strong> for business-rule flaws.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L3-15: Incident response phases (NIST-style)</em>:</strong> Vulnerability management is a lifecycle: scanners find candidates, analysts prioritize with exploitability and business context, owners remediate, and verification closes the loop. “Patch everything immediately” is rarely operational; <strong>risk-based SLAs</strong> are the adult answer.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Purple team wants to simulate abuse of “L3-15: Incident response phases (NIST-style)” next Friday. List <strong>safety gates</strong> (scope, rollback, monitoring) you require before authorizing the exercise.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l4-01":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L4-01: Active Directory basics for defenders</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-01</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> DC, Kerberos tickets concept, LDAP, GPO.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Read-only lab: if you have authorized AD lab, enumerate <strong>with tool policy</strong>; else write 10-term glossary with relationships.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-01</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Level 4 mirrors Security+ <strong>enterprise and cloud</strong>: identity governance, conditional access patterns, evidence handling, purple collaboration, and vendor/SaaS risk. Show you understand <strong>scope</strong> and <strong>blast radius</strong> across accounts and tenants.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 4 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>DDoS</strong></dt><dd>Distributed denial of service—volumetric, protocol, or application-layer floods; mitigations include scrubbing, anycast, rate limits, and architecture elasticity.</dd><dt><strong>Integrity</strong></dt><dd>Assures accuracy and trustworthiness—hashing, signatures, change control, and backups protect against unauthorized modification.</dd><dt><strong>Zero Trust (headline)</strong></dt><dd>Assume breach; verify explicitly per request using identity, device posture, and least privilege—not “trust the LAN.”</dd><dt><strong>CVSS</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerability Scoring System—base metrics describe technical severity; environmental and temporal modifiers refine priority.</dd><dt><strong>Threat intelligence lifecycle</strong></dt><dd>Planning, collection, processing, analysis, dissemination, feedback—intel must change detections or posture or it is shelf-ware.</dd><dt><strong>PBKDF2 / Argon2 (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Key derivation functions that slow brute force—work factors must track attacker economics.</dd><dt><strong>Diamond model</strong></dt><dd>Adversary, infrastructure, capability, victim—useful for pivoting investigations and intel fusion.</dd><dt><strong>Vulnerability</strong></dt><dd>A weakness in design, implementation, configuration, or process that could be exploited to violate a security policy.</dd><dt><strong>Kerberos (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Ticket-based enterprise auth—TGT vs service tickets; golden/silver ticket classes of abuse appear in advanced IR.</dd><dt><strong>OWASP Top 10</strong></dt><dd>High-prevalence web risks—broken access control and crypto failures often dominate; study each category with one workplace example.</dd><dt><strong>CASB / SaaS governance</strong></dt><dd>Visibility and policy for sanctioned vs shadow SaaS—OAuth consent attacks and guest sharing are common gaps.</dd><dt><strong>Need to know</strong></dt><dd>Finer than least privilege for data—access only to the minimum subset required for the current task.</dd><dt><strong>Full packet capture</strong></dt><dd>High fidelity evidence for investigations—storage, privacy, and legal review constraints apply.</dd><dt><strong>VPN</strong></dt><dd>Creates an encrypted tunnel; split tunneling can bypass corporate inspection; VPN is not anonymity or a substitute for app-layer auth.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Typical exam angle</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Confidentiality</strong></td><td>Who may read? Encryption, ACLs, DLP, classification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Integrity</strong></td><td>Was it modified? Hashing, signatures, change control, backups.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Availability</strong></td><td>Can authorized users work? HA, patching windows, DDoS defense, DR.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authenticity / non-repudiation</strong></td><td>Prove source and intent—signatures, strong issuance, tamper-evident logs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li><li>Server-side template injection is distinct from XSS—context and sinks differ.</li><li>SBOM formats (CycloneDX/SPDX) help inventory components for incident response and licensing—not only security.</li><li>OAuth access tokens are not a replacement for server-side authorization checks on every sensitive action.</li><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li><li>Responsible disclosure timelines balance vendor patch readiness with public safety—coordinate, don’t surprise.</li><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L4-01: Active Directory basics for defenders</em>:</strong> LDAP vs Active Directory questions test directory concepts at a high level—binding, searches, and secure transport (LDAPS) appear often.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L4-01: Active Directory basics for defenders</em>:</strong> Third-party and supply chain answers should emphasize <strong>contracts</strong>, <strong>evidence</strong>, and <strong>continuous monitoring</strong>—not “trust the SOC 2 logo” without scope review.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L4-01: Active Directory basics for defenders</em>:</strong> RADIUS is still referenced for <strong>network access control</strong> integrations; know it as a AAA component in enterprise Wi-Fi contexts.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L4-01: Active Directory basics for defenders</em>:</strong> Business continuity answers should reference <strong>RTO/RPO</strong>, <strong>workarounds</strong>, and <strong>tested restores</strong>; DR without practiced failover is wishful thinking, and exam writers know it.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L4-01: Active Directory basics for defenders</em>:</strong> TACACS+ vs RADIUS separation of duties in device admin access—exams may contrast accounting granularity.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L4-01: Active Directory basics for defenders</em>:</strong> Data handling questions often hinge on <strong>classification</strong>, <strong>least data</strong>, and <strong>retention</strong>: collect only what you need, keep it only as long as allowed, and destroy securely when done.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L4-01: Active Directory basics for defenders</em>:</strong> Honeypots can generate high-signal alerts but carry <strong>legal and operational</strong> risk if touched by real users; scope carefully.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L4-01: Active Directory basics for defenders</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L4-01: Active Directory basics for defenders</em>:</strong> Deception tech is not a replacement for <strong>baselines and patching</strong>; it augments detection when mature processes exist.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L4-01: Active Directory basics for defenders</em>:</strong> Engineers often optimize for speed; attackers optimize for <strong>cheap reuse</strong> of stolen creds and known exploits. The winning answer bridges both: ship fast with guardrails—feature flags, staged rollouts, and automated security checks in CI.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Purple team wants to simulate abuse of “L4-01: Active Directory basics for defenders” next Friday. List <strong>safety gates</strong> (scope, rollback, monitoring) you require before authorizing the exercise.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l4-02":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L4-02: Kerberoasting / AS-REP roasting (detection angle)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-02</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> What noisy events look like; service account hygiene.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> List detections: weak RC4 usage, unusual TGS requests — no offensive execution without lab DC + permission.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-02</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Purple team references test <strong>authorization to simulate</strong> and <strong>logging of exercises</strong>—safety and auditability matter.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 4 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>BCP / DR</strong></dt><dd>Business continuity and disaster recovery—RTO/RPO drive architecture; test restores, not just backups on paper.</dd><dt><strong>Jump server / bastion</strong></dt><dd>Hardened administrative entry point—centralizes session recording and access policy for admins.</dd><dt><strong>Confidentiality</strong></dt><dd>Assures that information is not disclosed to unauthorized subjects—encryption, access control, and data minimization support it.</dd><dt><strong>CSRF</strong></dt><dd>Cross-site request forgery rides ambient auth—anti-CSRF tokens, SameSite cookies, and re-auth for sensitive actions help.</dd><dt><strong>Job rotation</strong></dt><dd>Reduces collusion and fraud risk; also surfaces “tribal knowledge” silos before an employee leaves.</dd><dt><strong>Right to be forgotten (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Privacy request to delete data—may conflict with legal hold; counsel resolves precedence.</dd><dt><strong>Firewall</strong></dt><dd>Enforces allow/deny rules on traffic—stateful inspection tracks sessions; default-deny with explicit permits is the secure baseline.</dd><dt><strong>Serverless blast radius</strong></dt><dd>One broad execution role affects every invocation—scope IAM per function and watch environment variable leaks.</dd><dt><strong>Diffie-Hellman (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Key agreement over insecure channel—combine with authentication to prevent MITM.</dd><dt><strong>Due care</strong></dt><dd>The effort a prudent person would take to meet a duty; in security, reasonable steps to protect assets and stakeholders.</dd><dt><strong>OWASP Top 10</strong></dt><dd>High-prevalence web risks—broken access control and crypto failures often dominate; study each category with one workplace example.</dd><dt><strong>Business continuity testing</strong></dt><dd>Tabletops and technical failover drills reveal gaps in comms, dependencies, and vendor SLAs.</dd><dt><strong>SOAR</strong></dt><dd>Security orchestration, automation, response—playbooks must have human gates for destructive actions.</dd><dt><strong>NAT (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Rewrites addresses/ports for traversal—security relevance includes logging visibility, port forwarding risks, and split tunnel implications for inspection.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>IR phase</th><th>What you do there (exam shorthand)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Prepare</strong></td><td>Playbooks, contacts, tooling, baseline logging—before the pager fires.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detect &amp; analyze</strong></td><td>Scope, timelines, hypotheses—preserve volatile evidence early.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Contain</strong></td><td>Stop spread with minimal evidence damage—network isolation variants matter.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Eradicate &amp; recover</strong></td><td>Remove persistence, patch root cause, restore with verification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Lessons learned</strong></td><td>Metrics, control changes, and communication improvements—close the loop.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>KMS key policies can deny even root in AWS when configured—explicit deny wins.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>ATT&CK technique IDs are stable references for detection content—good for purple team reporting.</li><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li><li>Azure AD / Entra conditional access is analogous to risk-based policies—device compliance signals matter.</li><li>JWT alg:none historical vulnerability class—always validate algorithm and signature keys explicitly.</li><li>Sigma rules are vendor-agnostic detection snippets—tuning required per log source fields.</li><li>ISO 27001 is an ISMS standard; it emphasizes risk treatment and continual improvement, not a product checklist.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L4-02: Kerberoasting / AS-REP roasting (detection angle)</em>:</strong> Application security scenarios often test whether you know <strong>where</strong> enforcement belongs—browser controls supplement but do not replace server-side checks. SameSite cookies, CSP, and HttpOnly mitigate classes of issues; they do not fix broken object-level authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L4-02: Kerberoasting / AS-REP roasting (detection angle)</em>:</strong> Access control stems frequently mix <strong>role</strong> vs <strong>attribute</strong> vs <strong>rule</strong> models; pick the answer that matches the scenario’s constraints (temporary contractor, cross-department data, dynamic tags on resources).</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L4-02: Kerberoasting / AS-REP roasting (detection angle)</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L4-02: Kerberoasting / AS-REP roasting (detection angle)</em>:</strong> When logs “mysteriously stop,” think <strong>time sync failure</strong>, collector saturation, retention misconfiguration, or attacker tampering—in that diagnostic order for a fair exam narrative.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L4-02: Kerberoasting / AS-REP roasting (detection angle)</em>:</strong> Cryptojacking still appears: high CPU, unexpected mining pools, and cloud billing spikes—detection plus credential hygiene beats chasing miner signatures alone.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L4-02: Kerberoasting / AS-REP roasting (detection angle)</em>:</strong> Multicloud complexity increases <strong>identity sprawl</strong>; centralized IdP and consistent conditional access policies reduce human error.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L4-02: Kerberoasting / AS-REP roasting (detection angle)</em>:</strong> RADIUS is still referenced for <strong>network access control</strong> integrations; know it as a AAA component in enterprise Wi-Fi contexts.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L4-02: Kerberoasting / AS-REP roasting (detection angle)</em>:</strong> TPM-backed BitLocker keys illustrate <strong>key protection</strong> binding to platform state—recovery keys must be guarded like crown jewels.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L4-02: Kerberoasting / AS-REP roasting (detection angle)</em>:</strong> Defense in depth is not “more products,” it is <strong>independent mechanisms</strong>—if one layer is bypassed, another still limits movement, slows the adversary, or preserves evidence. Be ready to explain why network controls alone cannot compensate for missing app-layer authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L4-02: Kerberoasting / AS-REP roasting (detection angle)</em>:</strong> Incident response questions probe containment vs evidence preservation tension, legal escalation, and communication discipline. The exam rewards knowing when to isolate systems, when to involve counsel, and why mass log deletion is catastrophic.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> An engineer wants emergency access to production to debug “L4-02: Kerberoasting / AS-REP roasting (detection angle)” during change freeze. Outline <strong>break-glass</strong> steps: who approves, how sessions are recorded, and how credentials are rotated after.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l4-03":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L4-03: Pass-the-hash mitigations (tiering, LAPS, Protected Users)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-03</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Why credential theft is endemic on Windows estates.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Microsoft docs summary 15 lines + your org’s equivalent controls field.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-03</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>SaaS governance (CASB-style thinking) pairs technical visibility with <strong>OAuth consent</strong> and <strong>guest sharing</strong> policy.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 4 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Key management</strong></dt><dd>Generation, storage, rotation, and destruction—HSM/KMS patterns reduce exposure compared to software-only secrets.</dd><dt><strong>Vulnerability</strong></dt><dd>A weakness in design, implementation, configuration, or process that could be exploited to violate a security policy.</dd><dt><strong>Policy vs standard vs procedure</strong></dt><dd>Policy states intent; standards define mandatory requirements; procedures are step-by-step how-to for operators.</dd><dt><strong>PII</strong></dt><dd>Personally identifiable information—names, government IDs, biometrics, account numbers; triggers handling, retention, and breach rules.</dd><dt><strong>Session management</strong></dt><dd>Server-side session IDs or tokens must rotate on privilege change, bind to channel, and expire predictably.</dd><dt><strong>TLS</strong></dt><dd>Encrypts data in motion and authenticates endpoints when certificates and hostnames are validated; termination points affect trust boundaries.</dd><dt><strong>Certificate pinning (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Client remembers expected server key material—reduces MITM from rogue CAs but complicates rotation; mostly seen in mobile/API hardening patterns.</dd><dt><strong>CSRF</strong></dt><dd>Cross-site request forgery rides ambient auth—anti-CSRF tokens, SameSite cookies, and re-auth for sensitive actions help.</dd><dt><strong>CWE</strong></dt><dd>Common Weakness Enumeration—taxonomy of software weakness types that help root-cause fixes beyond one CVE instance.</dd><dt><strong>IAM least privilege</strong></dt><dd>Grant minimum API/console rights; prefer roles over long-lived keys; audit risky admin-equivalent paths regularly.</dd><dt><strong>GRC</strong></dt><dd>Governance, risk, and compliance—align security decisions with law, policy, and business appetite; audits test design and operation.</dd><dt><strong>Metrics that matter</strong></dt><dd>Mean time to detect/remediate with quality, coverage of critical assets, and control effectiveness—not vanity ticket counts.</dd><dt><strong>Purple teaming</strong></dt><dd>Collaborative attack/defense exercises to validate detections without surprise production harm—scope and safety first.</dd><dt><strong>Mandatory vacation</strong></dt><dd>Forces handover and review of another employee’s work—can uncover fraud or backdoors.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>AEAD</strong></td><td>Confidentiality + integrity together—misuse of IV/nonce still breaks security.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Admission controllers can block privileged pods—policy-as-code integrates with GitOps reviews.</li><li>Server-side template injection is distinct from XSS—context and sinks differ.</li><li>Certificate pinning misconfigurations can brick apps—plan rotation and emergency releases.</li><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li><li>Sigma rules are vendor-agnostic detection snippets—tuning required per log source fields.</li><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>UDP-based protocols can be abused for amplification DDoS—patch open resolvers and monitor volumetric baselines.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L4-03: Pass-the-hash mitigations (tiering, LAPS, Protected Users)</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L4-03: Pass-the-hash mitigations (tiering, LAPS, Protected Users)</em>:</strong> Governance and awareness questions tie policy to behavior: acceptable use, clean desk, travel security, and vendor due diligence. Pick answers that reduce <strong>realistic</strong> human failure modes, not answers that maximize surveillance without process support.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L4-03: Pass-the-hash mitigations (tiering, LAPS, Protected Users)</em>:</strong> Virtualization risks include <strong>snapshot sprawl</strong> containing secrets and stale VM images drifting from hardened baselines.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L4-03: Pass-the-hash mitigations (tiering, LAPS, Protected Users)</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L4-03: Pass-the-hash mitigations (tiering, LAPS, Protected Users)</em>:</strong> Third-party and supply chain answers should emphasize <strong>contracts</strong>, <strong>evidence</strong>, and <strong>continuous monitoring</strong>—not “trust the SOC 2 logo” without scope review.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L4-03: Pass-the-hash mitigations (tiering, LAPS, Protected Users)</em>:</strong> For the Security+ mindset, translate every control into <strong>who</strong> it protects, <strong>what</strong> asset is at risk, and <strong>how</strong> you would detect failure. Interview and exam items often reward practical prioritization over buzzwords—choose the mitigation that reduces realistic loss first.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L4-03: Pass-the-hash mitigations (tiering, LAPS, Protected Users)</em>:</strong> API keys in mobile apps are often extractable—prefer <strong>short-lived tokens</strong> and server-mediated access to backends.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L4-03: Pass-the-hash mitigations (tiering, LAPS, Protected Users)</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L4-03: Pass-the-hash mitigations (tiering, LAPS, Protected Users)</em>:</strong> Application security scenarios often test whether you know <strong>where</strong> enforcement belongs—browser controls supplement but do not replace server-side checks. SameSite cookies, CSP, and HttpOnly mitigate classes of issues; they do not fix broken object-level authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L4-03: Pass-the-hash mitigations (tiering, LAPS, Protected Users)</em>:</strong> TACACS+ vs RADIUS separation of duties in device admin access—exams may contrast accounting granularity.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> A cloud bill spike correlates with traffic about “L4-03: Pass-the-hash mitigations (tiering, LAPS, Protected Users)”. Differentiate <strong>misconfiguration</strong> vs <strong>abuse</strong> in your first triage questions and what logs prove each hypothesis.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l4-04":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L4-04: Azure AD / Entra ID concepts (tenant, CA policies, PIM)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-04</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Conditional Access signals; break-glass accounts monitored.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Portal walkthrough on <strong>personal</strong> tenant or screenshots from training — no customer data.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-04</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Purple team references test <strong>authorization to simulate</strong> and <strong>logging of exercises</strong>—safety and auditability matter.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 4 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Purple teaming</strong></dt><dd>Collaborative attack/defense exercises to validate detections without surprise production harm—scope and safety first.</dd><dt><strong>Certificate transparency (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Public logs of issued certs help detect mis-issued certificates for your domains.</dd><dt><strong>MITM</strong></dt><dd>Man-in-the-middle intercepts or alters traffic—TLS with proper validation mitigates; corporate SSL inspection is its own trust zone.</dd><dt><strong>OODA loop (IR)</strong></dt><dd>Observe-orient-decide-act—adversary and defender both iterate; faster, accurate decisions beat hoarding data.</dd><dt><strong>TLS</strong></dt><dd>Encrypts data in motion and authenticates endpoints when certificates and hostnames are validated; termination points affect trust boundaries.</dd><dt><strong>Control</strong></dt><dd>Administrative, technical, or physical safeguards that reduce likelihood or impact of a security event (prevent, detect, correct).</dd><dt><strong>Data classification</strong></dt><dd>Labels (public, internal, confidential, restricted) drive storage, encryption, sharing, and disposal requirements.</dd><dt><strong>Encoding (e.g., Base64)</strong></dt><dd>Transforms representation without cryptographic protection—do not confuse with encryption or integrity.</dd><dt><strong>CVE</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures identifier for a specific flaw—pairs with CVSS severity and vendor advisories for prioritization.</dd><dt><strong>Container security</strong></dt><dd>Image provenance, non-root users, read-only roots, seccomp/AppArmor, and admission control for risky capabilities.</dd><dt><strong>Zero Trust architecture</strong></dt><dd>Identity-centric access with continuous verification—policy enforcement points for users, devices, and workloads.</dd><dt><strong>Data loss prevention (DLP)</strong></dt><dd>Content-aware controls to block or alert on sensitive data movement—policy + tech, tuned to avoid blocking work.</dd><dt><strong>IV / nonce</strong></dt><dd>Initialization vector or number-used-once—must be unique per encryption under a key for many modes.</dd><dt><strong>BGP prefix hijack</strong></dt><dd>Unauthorized route advertisement—RPKI ROV reduces impact but does not replace monitoring.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Cloud responsibility</th><th>Who typically owns it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Patching the hypervisor</strong></td><td>Provider responsibility in major IaaS models—customer still patches guests.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>IAM policy and keys</strong></td><td>Customer-owned configuration—misconfigurations dominate incidents.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Data encryption at rest</strong></td><td>Often customer-controlled keys/KMS policies with provider primitives.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Network exposure (SGs/NACLs)</strong></td><td>Customer configures; default-deny patterns are exam favorites.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Application vulnerabilities</strong></td><td>Customer code and dependencies—shared model does not absolve secure SDLC.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Sigma rules are vendor-agnostic detection snippets—tuning required per log source fields.</li><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>Bug bounty scope must exclude destructive testing—safe harbor language still needs legal review.</li><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li><li>OAuth access tokens are not a replacement for server-side authorization checks on every sensitive action.</li><li>Responsible disclosure timelines balance vendor patch readiness with public safety—coordinate, don’t surprise.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L4-04: Azure AD / Entra ID concepts (tenant, CA policies, PIM)</em>:</strong> LDAP vs Active Directory questions test directory concepts at a high level—binding, searches, and secure transport (LDAPS) appear often.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L4-04: Azure AD / Entra ID concepts (tenant, CA policies, PIM)</em>:</strong> Clean desk pairs with <strong>screen privacy</strong> and <strong>clear desk checks</strong> for regulated spaces—physical + procedural controls together.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L4-04: Azure AD / Entra ID concepts (tenant, CA policies, PIM)</em>:</strong> Incident response questions probe containment vs evidence preservation tension, legal escalation, and communication discipline. The exam rewards knowing when to isolate systems, when to involve counsel, and why mass log deletion is catastrophic.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L4-04: Azure AD / Entra ID concepts (tenant, CA policies, PIM)</em>:</strong> Data handling questions often hinge on <strong>classification</strong>, <strong>least data</strong>, and <strong>retention</strong>: collect only what you need, keep it only as long as allowed, and destroy securely when done.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L4-04: Azure AD / Entra ID concepts (tenant, CA policies, PIM)</em>:</strong> Serverless cold start is not a security control; <strong>per-function IAM</strong> and least-privilege API scopes are. Watch for attractive nonsense distractors tied to performance tuning.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L4-04: Azure AD / Entra ID concepts (tenant, CA policies, PIM)</em>:</strong> Multicloud complexity increases <strong>identity sprawl</strong>; centralized IdP and consistent conditional access policies reduce human error.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L4-04: Azure AD / Entra ID concepts (tenant, CA policies, PIM)</em>:</strong> Air gapped networks still need <strong>patching via sneaker-net</strong> and insider controls—physical isolation is not logical isolation.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L4-04: Azure AD / Entra ID concepts (tenant, CA policies, PIM)</em>:</strong> Security operations value <strong>repeatable evidence</strong>: timestamps, authoritative configuration sources, and tamper-aware logs beat heroic memory after an incident. Many exam questions hinge on whether an action preserves integrity and accountability rather than whether it feels fast.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L4-04: Azure AD / Entra ID concepts (tenant, CA policies, PIM)</em>:</strong> Access control stems frequently mix <strong>role</strong> vs <strong>attribute</strong> vs <strong>rule</strong> models; pick the answer that matches the scenario’s constraints (temporary contractor, cross-department data, dynamic tags on resources).</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L4-04: Azure AD / Entra ID concepts (tenant, CA policies, PIM)</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Marketing launches a campaign referencing “L4-04: Azure AD / Entra ID concepts (tenant, CA policies, PIM)” with a new subdomain. Security review finds DNS delegated to an unknown party. Explain <strong>trust chain</strong> risks and the <strong>minimum fixes</strong> before go-live.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l4-05":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L4-05: AWS IAM policy evaluation mental model</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-05</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Explicit deny wins; SCP vs identity vs resource policy (high level).<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Write a policy that <strong>denies</strong> <code>s3:*</code> without <code>aws:MultiFactorAuthPresent=true</code> for <code>DenyExceptWithMFA</code> pattern (pseudo-json).</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-05</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Level 4 mirrors Security+ <strong>enterprise and cloud</strong>: identity governance, conditional access patterns, evidence handling, purple collaboration, and vendor/SaaS risk. Show you understand <strong>scope</strong> and <strong>blast radius</strong> across accounts and tenants.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 4 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Jump server / bastion</strong></dt><dd>Hardened administrative entry point—centralizes session recording and access policy for admins.</dd><dt><strong>OODA loop (IR)</strong></dt><dd>Observe-orient-decide-act—adversary and defender both iterate; faster, accurate decisions beat hoarding data.</dd><dt><strong>Logging &amp; monitoring</strong></dt><dd>CloudTrail-style management events differ from data-plane logs—enable central export, immutability, and alerting.</dd><dt><strong>Vulnerability</strong></dt><dd>A weakness in design, implementation, configuration, or process that could be exploited to violate a security policy.</dd><dt><strong>Authenticity</strong></dt><dd>Verifies that users, devices, or data are genuine—cryptographic identity, attestation, and strong issuance processes matter.</dd><dt><strong>SSO</strong></dt><dd>Single sign-on federates trust to an IdP—misconfigured SAML/OIDC trusts are high-impact; validate metadata and signing keys.</dd><dt><strong>Network segmentation</strong></dt><dd>VLANs, micro-segmentation, and east-west controls limit lateral movement after an initial foothold.</dd><dt><strong>Input validation vs output encoding</strong></dt><dd>Validation rejects bad input early; encoding neutralizes dangerous characters in the right output context—both are needed across HTML, SQL, OS, and LDAP channels.</dd><dt><strong>CVSS</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerability Scoring System—base metrics describe technical severity; environmental and temporal modifiers refine priority.</dd><dt><strong>Encryption at rest / in transit</strong></dt><dd>KMS/HSM-backed keys, envelope encryption, and TLS everywhere for administrative and user paths.</dd><dt><strong>Metrics that matter</strong></dt><dd>Mean time to detect/remediate with quality, coverage of critical assets, and control effectiveness—not vanity ticket counts.</dd><dt><strong>SOC triage order</strong></dt><dd>Scope → impact → evidence → containment hypothesis; avoid fixing symptoms before you know blast radius.</dd><dt><strong>CRL</strong></dt><dd>Certificate Revocation List—signed list of revoked serials; size/latency issues drove OCSP adoption.</dd><dt><strong>MITM</strong></dt><dd>Man-in-the-middle intercepts or alters traffic—TLS with proper validation mitigates; corporate SSL inspection is its own trust zone.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>AES-128 is not “half as strong” as AES-256 in practical threat models for many cases—key management quality dominates.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>PCI DSS scope reduction via segmentation is a recurring theme—if it is not in scope, it cannot drag you into assessment.</li><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li><li>KMS key policies can deny even root in AWS when configured—explicit deny wins.</li><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li><li>SLSA levels describe increasing supply-chain assurance—useful vocabulary in modern governance questions.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L4-05: AWS IAM policy evaluation mental model</em>:</strong> Advanced topics still return to fundamentals: least privilege, segmentation, logging, and tested recovery. When you see Zero Trust or PQC buzzwords, map them back to concrete controls and threat models rather than treating them as magic shields.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L4-05: AWS IAM policy evaluation mental model</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L4-05: AWS IAM policy evaluation mental model</em>:</strong> Subresource integrity protects against <strong>CDN compromise</strong> but requires operational discipline when vendors rotate files.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L4-05: AWS IAM policy evaluation mental model</em>:</strong> Defense in depth is not “more products,” it is <strong>independent mechanisms</strong>—if one layer is bypassed, another still limits movement, slows the adversary, or preserves evidence. Be ready to explain why network controls alone cannot compensate for missing app-layer authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L4-05: AWS IAM policy evaluation mental model</em>:</strong> Business continuity answers should reference <strong>RTO/RPO</strong>, <strong>workarounds</strong>, and <strong>tested restores</strong>; DR without practiced failover is wishful thinking, and exam writers know it.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L4-05: AWS IAM policy evaluation mental model</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L4-05: AWS IAM policy evaluation mental model</em>:</strong> Air gapped networks still need <strong>patching via sneaker-net</strong> and insider controls—physical isolation is not logical isolation.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L4-05: AWS IAM policy evaluation mental model</em>:</strong> Incident response questions probe containment vs evidence preservation tension, legal escalation, and communication discipline. The exam rewards knowing when to isolate systems, when to involve counsel, and why mass log deletion is catastrophic.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L4-05: AWS IAM policy evaluation mental model</em>:</strong> Industrial and OT adjacent questions reward knowing <strong>safety vs security</strong> tension: availability may trump confidentiality; testing must avoid breaking physical processes.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L4-05: AWS IAM policy evaluation mental model</em>:</strong> API keys in mobile apps are often extractable—prefer <strong>short-lived tokens</strong> and server-mediated access to backends.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> You are the on-call analyst reviewing an alert tied to “L4-05: AWS IAM policy evaluation mental model”. Leadership wants a <strong>60-second</strong> brief: business impact, evidence gaps, and the <strong>first</strong> containment step that preserves logs. No tool-specific jargon—prioritize scope, evidence, blast radius, then root-cause remediation under change control.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l4-06":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L4-06: Cloud logging — CloudTrail / Azure Activity / GCP Audit Logs</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-06</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Who changed IAM when; immutability options.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Table comparing “control plane” vs “data plane” logs for one service (S3/Azure Blob).</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-06</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Evidence handling in regulated orgs may invoke <strong>legal hold</strong>—do not pick answers that “clean up” data prematurely.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 4 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Privacy</strong></dt><dd>Protection of personal information and individual rights—overlaps with security but adds legal/regulatory obligations (GDPR-style).</dd><dt><strong>VPN</strong></dt><dd>Creates an encrypted tunnel; split tunneling can bypass corporate inspection; VPN is not anonymity or a substitute for app-layer auth.</dd><dt><strong>Injection</strong></dt><dd>Untrusted input becomes part of a command or query—parameterized queries, input validation, and context escaping are core defenses.</dd><dt><strong>Logging &amp; monitoring</strong></dt><dd>CloudTrail-style management events differ from data-plane logs—enable central export, immutability, and alerting.</dd><dt><strong>PQC</strong></dt><dd>Post-quantum cryptography migration—hybrid schemes and crypto-agility for long-lived secrets exposed to harvest-now/decrypt-later risk.</dd><dt><strong>OCSP stapling (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Server sends fresh revocation info with handshake—reduces client privacy leaks and lookup failures.</dd><dt><strong>Full packet capture</strong></dt><dd>High fidelity evidence for investigations—storage, privacy, and legal review constraints apply.</dd><dt><strong>CVE</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures identifier for a specific flaw—pairs with CVSS severity and vendor advisories for prioritization.</dd><dt><strong>Residual risk</strong></dt><dd>Risk remaining after controls are applied; organizations accept, transfer, mitigate, or avoid it explicitly.</dd><dt><strong>Session management</strong></dt><dd>Server-side session IDs or tokens must rotate on privilege change, bind to channel, and expire predictably.</dd><dt><strong>Hashing</strong></dt><dd>One-way fingerprint for integrity verification—SHA-256 family; not secrecy; used with HMAC for keyed integrity.</dd><dt><strong>CVSS</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerability Scoring System—base metrics describe technical severity; environmental and temporal modifiers refine priority.</dd><dt><strong>Third-party risk</strong></dt><dd>Vendor access expands attack surface—DPAs, SOC reports, and continuous monitoring for critical suppliers.</dd><dt><strong>Separation of duties (SoD)</strong></dt><dd>No single person can complete a sensitive transaction alone—classic finance control that also limits insider abuse.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>UDP-based protocols can be abused for amplification DDoS—patch open resolvers and monitor volumetric baselines.</li><li>DNS over HTTPS changes visibility for some networks—understand resolver policy and logging tradeoffs.</li><li>Responsible disclosure timelines balance vendor patch readiness with public safety—coordinate, don’t surprise.</li><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li><li>SBOM formats (CycloneDX/SPDX) help inventory components for incident response and licensing—not only security.</li><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li><li>Azure AD / Entra conditional access is analogous to risk-based policies—device compliance signals matter.</li><li>EPSS (concept) scores exploitation probability—useful alongside CVSS for prioritization in mature programs.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L4-06: Cloud logging — CloudTrail / Azure Activity / GCP Audit Logs</em>:</strong> Data handling questions often hinge on <strong>classification</strong>, <strong>least data</strong>, and <strong>retention</strong>: collect only what you need, keep it only as long as allowed, and destroy securely when done.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L4-06: Cloud logging — CloudTrail / Azure Activity / GCP Audit Logs</em>:</strong> Email security stems often combine SPF alignment failures with <strong>look-alike domains</strong>. The best answer addresses user training plus technical authenticity controls, not only one or the other.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L4-06: Cloud logging — CloudTrail / Azure Activity / GCP Audit Logs</em>:</strong> Ransomware stems often pair encryption with <strong>exfiltration</strong>—the correct answer may include legal/notification obligations, not only restoring from backup.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L4-06: Cloud logging — CloudTrail / Azure Activity / GCP Audit Logs</em>:</strong> Evidence bags and write blockers signal <strong>forensics awareness</strong>; touching disks before imaging is a classic wrong answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L4-06: Cloud logging — CloudTrail / Azure Activity / GCP Audit Logs</em>:</strong> LDAP vs Active Directory questions test directory concepts at a high level—binding, searches, and secure transport (LDAPS) appear often.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L4-06: Cloud logging — CloudTrail / Azure Activity / GCP Audit Logs</em>:</strong> BIOS/UEFI passwords and secure boot reduce some pre-boot attacks but do not stop <strong>evil maid</strong> classes without additional controls.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L4-06: Cloud logging — CloudTrail / Azure Activity / GCP Audit Logs</em>:</strong> Controls fail in three predictable ways: <strong>misconfiguration</strong>, <strong>missing coverage</strong> (gaps between tools), and <strong>human process</strong> breakdown (exceptions, shared accounts, emergency access). When you read a scenario, ask which failure mode is most plausible before picking an answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L4-06: Cloud logging — CloudTrail / Azure Activity / GCP Audit Logs</em>:</strong> Vulnerability management is a lifecycle: scanners find candidates, analysts prioritize with exploitability and business context, owners remediate, and verification closes the loop. “Patch everything immediately” is rarely operational; <strong>risk-based SLAs</strong> are the adult answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L4-06: Cloud logging — CloudTrail / Azure Activity / GCP Audit Logs</em>:</strong> Wireless and mobility items reward knowing basics: WPA3 improvements conceptually, evil twin risks, captive portals, and why client isolation matters on guest networks—without memorizing obsolete WEP details unless explicitly historical.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L4-06: Cloud logging — CloudTrail / Azure Activity / GCP Audit Logs</em>:</strong> Engineers often optimize for speed; attackers optimize for <strong>cheap reuse</strong> of stolen creds and known exploits. The winning answer bridges both: ship fast with guardrails—feature flags, staged rollouts, and automated security checks in CI.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Junior staff proposes a quick fix for “L4-06: Cloud logging — CloudTrail / Azure Activity / GCP Audit Logs” that disables logging on a noisy host. Walk through why that is unacceptable and propose a <strong>tuning</strong> path that preserves <strong>integrity and retention</strong> commitments.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l4-07":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L4-07: Container and Kubernetes risk surface (not full CKA)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-07</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Image trust, root in container, seccomp/AppArmor, network policies idea.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>docker info 2&gt;/dev/null | head</code> or <code>podman info</code>; note rootless mode if present.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-07</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>SaaS governance (CASB-style thinking) pairs technical visibility with <strong>OAuth consent</strong> and <strong>guest sharing</strong> policy.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 4 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Proxy vs reverse proxy</strong></dt><dd>Forward proxy represents clients outbound; reverse proxy fronts servers—different trust and logging points.</dd><dt><strong>Risk</strong></dt><dd>The intersection of threat, vulnerability, and impact—often assessed qualitatively (high/medium/low) or with scoring frameworks.</dd><dt><strong>PKI</strong></dt><dd>Public Key Infrastructure—CAs, RAs, CRL/OCSP, and certificate lifecycle; mis-issuance or weak validation breaks trust chains.</dd><dt><strong>Metrics that matter</strong></dt><dd>Mean time to detect/remediate with quality, coverage of critical assets, and control effectiveness—not vanity ticket counts.</dd><dt><strong>WAF vs IPS</strong></dt><dd>WAF focuses on application-layer attacks; IPS often line-rate network signatures—overlap exists but priorities differ.</dd><dt><strong>Residual risk</strong></dt><dd>Risk remaining after controls are applied; organizations accept, transfer, mitigate, or avoid it explicitly.</dd><dt><strong>Encoding (e.g., Base64)</strong></dt><dd>Transforms representation without cryptographic protection—do not confuse with encryption or integrity.</dd><dt><strong>Threat intelligence lifecycle</strong></dt><dd>Planning, collection, processing, analysis, dissemination, feedback—intel must change detections or posture or it is shelf-ware.</dd><dt><strong>Full packet capture</strong></dt><dd>High fidelity evidence for investigations—storage, privacy, and legal review constraints apply.</dd><dt><strong>Due care</strong></dt><dd>The effort a prudent person would take to meet a duty; in security, reasonable steps to protect assets and stakeholders.</dd><dt><strong>Key management</strong></dt><dd>Generation, storage, rotation, and destruction—HSM/KMS patterns reduce exposure compared to software-only secrets.</dd><dt><strong>Attack surface</strong></dt><dd>The sum of exposure—every service, API, integration, and human workflow that can be reached by a threat; reduction beats perfect monitoring alone.</dd><dt><strong>NetFlow / IPFIX</strong></dt><dd>Flow metadata for volume and anomaly detection—lighter than PCAP but less payload visibility.</dd><dt><strong>Due diligence</strong></dt><dd>Investigation and verification before decisions (vendor risk, M&amp;A) to ensure claims about controls are credible.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Typical exam angle</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Confidentiality</strong></td><td>Who may read? Encryption, ACLs, DLP, classification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Integrity</strong></td><td>Was it modified? Hashing, signatures, change control, backups.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Availability</strong></td><td>Can authorized users work? HA, patching windows, DDoS defense, DR.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authenticity / non-repudiation</strong></td><td>Prove source and intent—signatures, strong issuance, tamper-evident logs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>EPSS (concept) scores exploitation probability—useful alongside CVSS for prioritization in mature programs.</li><li>Sigma rules are vendor-agnostic detection snippets—tuning required per log source fields.</li><li>Linux auth.log style entries pair with SSH brute-force detection patterns—velocity and geo anomalies.</li><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li><li>Split tunnel VPN can exfil corporate data outside inspection if misconfigured—policy and routing matter.</li><li>Certificate pinning misconfigurations can brick apps—plan rotation and emergency releases.</li><li>JWT alg:none historical vulnerability class—always validate algorithm and signature keys explicitly.</li><li>Server-side template injection is distinct from XSS—context and sinks differ.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L4-07: Container and Kubernetes risk surface (not full CKA)</em>:</strong> Subresource integrity protects against <strong>CDN compromise</strong> but requires operational discipline when vendors rotate files.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L4-07: Container and Kubernetes risk surface (not full CKA)</em>:</strong> Air gapped networks still need <strong>patching via sneaker-net</strong> and insider controls—physical isolation is not logical isolation.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L4-07: Container and Kubernetes risk surface (not full CKA)</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L4-07: Container and Kubernetes risk surface (not full CKA)</em>:</strong> Cryptography questions reward vocabulary precision: hashing vs encryption vs encoding; symmetric vs asymmetric roles in TLS; what signatures prove; and why key management is usually harder than picking an algorithm. If an answer sounds magical, it is probably wrong.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L4-07: Container and Kubernetes risk surface (not full CKA)</em>:</strong> Logging questions often test whether you understand <strong>what to log</strong> (who, what, when, where, outcome), <strong>time sync</strong> for correlation, and <strong>tamper resistance</strong> for evidentiary value—not whether you can collect infinite bytes.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L4-07: Container and Kubernetes risk surface (not full CKA)</em>:</strong> Data handling questions often hinge on <strong>classification</strong>, <strong>least data</strong>, and <strong>retention</strong>: collect only what you need, keep it only as long as allowed, and destroy securely when done.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L4-07: Container and Kubernetes risk surface (not full CKA)</em>:</strong> Email security stems often combine SPF alignment failures with <strong>look-alike domains</strong>. The best answer addresses user training plus technical authenticity controls, not only one or the other.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L4-07: Container and Kubernetes risk surface (not full CKA)</em>:</strong> Ransomware stems often pair encryption with <strong>exfiltration</strong>—the correct answer may include legal/notification obligations, not only restoring from backup.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L4-07: Container and Kubernetes risk surface (not full CKA)</em>:</strong> Evidence bags and write blockers signal <strong>forensics awareness</strong>; touching disks before imaging is a classic wrong answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L4-07: Container and Kubernetes risk surface (not full CKA)</em>:</strong> LDAP vs Active Directory questions test directory concepts at a high level—binding, searches, and secure transport (LDAPS) appear often.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> An engineer wants emergency access to production to debug “L4-07: Container and Kubernetes risk surface (not full CKA)” during change freeze. Outline <strong>break-glass</strong> steps: who approves, how sessions are recorded, and how credentials are rotated after.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l4-08":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L4-08: Supply chain security (SBOM, SLSA, signing)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-08</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Why hashes aren’t enough; provenance.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>syft packages dir:/usr/share/doc -o json 2&gt;/dev/null | head</code> (if installed) or document manual SBOM fields.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-08</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Purple team references test <strong>authorization to simulate</strong> and <strong>logging of exercises</strong>—safety and auditability matter.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 4 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>UEBA</strong></dt><dd>User and entity behavior analytics—baseline deviations; tune to avoid HR/privacy backlash.</dd><dt><strong>Network segmentation</strong></dt><dd>VLANs, micro-segmentation, and east-west controls limit lateral movement after an initial foothold.</dd><dt><strong>Insider threat</strong></dt><dd>Malicious or negligent insiders—monitor with proportionality, separation of duties, and HR/legal partnership.</dd><dt><strong>Full packet capture</strong></dt><dd>High fidelity evidence for investigations—storage, privacy, and legal review constraints apply.</dd><dt><strong>FIDO2 / WebAuthn</strong></dt><dd>Phishing-resistant possession factors using asymmetric crypto and origin binding; preferred where supported.</dd><dt><strong>IR phases</strong></dt><dd>Prepare, detect, analyze, contain, eradicate, recover, and lessons learned—legal hold and evidence integrity matter throughout.</dd><dt><strong>PBKDF2 / Argon2 (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Key derivation functions that slow brute force—work factors must track attacker economics.</dd><dt><strong>Due care</strong></dt><dd>The effort a prudent person would take to meet a duty; in security, reasonable steps to protect assets and stakeholders.</dd><dt><strong>OWASP Top 10</strong></dt><dd>High-prevalence web risks—broken access control and crypto failures often dominate; study each category with one workplace example.</dd><dt><strong>Business continuity testing</strong></dt><dd>Tabletops and technical failover drills reveal gaps in comms, dependencies, and vendor SLAs.</dd><dt><strong>SOAR</strong></dt><dd>Security orchestration, automation, response—playbooks must have human gates for destructive actions.</dd><dt><strong>Zero Trust (headline)</strong></dt><dd>Assume breach; verify explicitly per request using identity, device posture, and least privilege—not “trust the LAN.”</dd><dt><strong>Security awareness</strong></dt><dd>Training plus culture—measure reporting rates, not shame metrics; phishing simulations should reinforce reporting.</dd><dt><strong>WAF vs IPS</strong></dt><dd>WAF focuses on application-layer attacks; IPS often line-rate network signatures—overlap exists but priorities differ.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Typical exam angle</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Confidentiality</strong></td><td>Who may read? Encryption, ACLs, DLP, classification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Integrity</strong></td><td>Was it modified? Hashing, signatures, change control, backups.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Availability</strong></td><td>Can authorized users work? HA, patching windows, DDoS defense, DR.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authenticity / non-repudiation</strong></td><td>Prove source and intent—signatures, strong issuance, tamper-evident logs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>AEAD</strong></td><td>Confidentiality + integrity together—misuse of IV/nonce still breaks security.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li><li>JWT alg:none historical vulnerability class—always validate algorithm and signature keys explicitly.</li><li>ISO 27001 is an ISMS standard; it emphasizes risk treatment and continual improvement, not a product checklist.</li><li>GraphQL batching can amplify complexity attacks—depth and cost limits are first-class controls.</li><li>PCI DSS scope reduction via segmentation is a recurring theme—if it is not in scope, it cannot drag you into assessment.</li><li>Server-side template injection is distinct from XSS—context and sinks differ.</li><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>Race conditions in web apps can undermine authorization—sequential logic tests in secure design reviews.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L4-08: Supply chain security (SBOM, SLSA, signing)</em>:</strong> Defense in depth is not “more products,” it is <strong>independent mechanisms</strong>—if one layer is bypassed, another still limits movement, slows the adversary, or preserves evidence. Be ready to explain why network controls alone cannot compensate for missing app-layer authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L4-08: Supply chain security (SBOM, SLSA, signing)</em>:</strong> Business continuity answers should reference <strong>RTO/RPO</strong>, <strong>workarounds</strong>, and <strong>tested restores</strong>; DR without practiced failover is wishful thinking, and exam writers know it.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L4-08: Supply chain security (SBOM, SLSA, signing)</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L4-08: Supply chain security (SBOM, SLSA, signing)</em>:</strong> Air gapped networks still need <strong>patching via sneaker-net</strong> and insider controls—physical isolation is not logical isolation.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L4-08: Supply chain security (SBOM, SLSA, signing)</em>:</strong> Incident response questions probe containment vs evidence preservation tension, legal escalation, and communication discipline. The exam rewards knowing when to isolate systems, when to involve counsel, and why mass log deletion is catastrophic.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L4-08: Supply chain security (SBOM, SLSA, signing)</em>:</strong> Industrial and OT adjacent questions reward knowing <strong>safety vs security</strong> tension: availability may trump confidentiality; testing must avoid breaking physical processes.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L4-08: Supply chain security (SBOM, SLSA, signing)</em>:</strong> API keys in mobile apps are often extractable—prefer <strong>short-lived tokens</strong> and server-mediated access to backends.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L4-08: Supply chain security (SBOM, SLSA, signing)</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L4-08: Supply chain security (SBOM, SLSA, signing)</em>:</strong> Physical security is still on the exam: tailgating, visitor escorts, locks, destruction of media, and environmental controls (fire, HVAC) as availability/confidentiality supports.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L4-08: Supply chain security (SBOM, SLSA, signing)</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Purple team wants to simulate abuse of “L4-08: Supply chain security (SBOM, SLSA, signing)” next Friday. List <strong>safety gates</strong> (scope, rollback, monitoring) you require before authorizing the exercise.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l4-09":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L4-09: Detection engineering — data quality, observability, unit tests for rules</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-09</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Detection is software engineering.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Pick one atomic test from Atomic Red Team <strong>read-only</strong>; write expected log field + rule pseudocode.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-09</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Vendor risk items reward <strong>continuous monitoring</strong> and <strong>contractual evidence</strong>, not one-time PDF collection.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 4 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Exploit</strong></dt><dd>A technique or code that takes advantage of a vulnerability to achieve an attacker goal (exfiltration, persistence, disruption).</dd><dt><strong>Confidentiality</strong></dt><dd>Assures that information is not disclosed to unauthorized subjects—encryption, access control, and data minimization support it.</dd><dt><strong>Data classification</strong></dt><dd>Labels (public, internal, confidential, restricted) drive storage, encryption, sharing, and disposal requirements.</dd><dt><strong>SSO</strong></dt><dd>Single sign-on federates trust to an IdP—misconfigured SAML/OIDC trusts are high-impact; validate metadata and signing keys.</dd><dt><strong>DNS</strong></dt><dd>Name resolution is a trust anchor—DNSSEC, cache poisoning, and malicious resolutions are classic abuse paths; log resolver anomalies.</dd><dt><strong>Symmetric encryption</strong></dt><dd>Same key encrypts and decrypts—fast for bulk data (AES-GCM); key distribution is the hard problem.</dd><dt><strong>AEAD</strong></dt><dd>Authenticated encryption with associated data—confidentiality plus integrity in one primitive (e.g., AES-GCM) when used correctly.</dd><dt><strong>IDOR</strong></dt><dd>Insecure direct object reference—missing object-level authorization; test horizontal/vertical access with different accounts.</dd><dt><strong>Vulnerability management</strong></dt><dd>Discover, prioritize, remediate, verify, and report—SLAs differ by exposure, exploitability, and asset criticality.</dd><dt><strong>Logging &amp; monitoring</strong></dt><dd>CloudTrail-style management events differ from data-plane logs—enable central export, immutability, and alerting.</dd><dt><strong>BCP / DR</strong></dt><dd>Business continuity and disaster recovery—RTO/RPO drive architecture; test restores, not just backups on paper.</dd><dt><strong>Threat intelligence lifecycle</strong></dt><dd>Planning, collection, processing, analysis, dissemination, feedback—intel must change detections or posture or it is shelf-ware.</dd><dt><strong>Purple / red / blue</strong></dt><dd>Red emulates adversaries, blue defends, purple bridges—authorization and logging are mandatory for any simulation.</dd><dt><strong>Need to know</strong></dt><dd>Finer than least privilege for data—access only to the minimum subset required for the current task.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>DNS over HTTPS changes visibility for some networks—understand resolver policy and logging tradeoffs.</li><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li><li>Responsible disclosure timelines balance vendor patch readiness with public safety—coordinate, don’t surprise.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li><li>OAuth access tokens are not a replacement for server-side authorization checks on every sensitive action.</li><li>SBOM formats (CycloneDX/SPDX) help inventory components for incident response and licensing—not only security.</li><li>Server-side template injection is distinct from XSS—context and sinks differ.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L4-09: Detection engineering — data quality, observability, unit tests for rules</em>:</strong> Defense in depth is not “more products,” it is <strong>independent mechanisms</strong>—if one layer is bypassed, another still limits movement, slows the adversary, or preserves evidence. Be ready to explain why network controls alone cannot compensate for missing app-layer authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L4-09: Detection engineering — data quality, observability, unit tests for rules</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L4-09: Detection engineering — data quality, observability, unit tests for rules</em>:</strong> Tabletop exercises test <strong>comms trees</strong>, legal escalation, and customer notification templates—not only technical runbooks.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L4-09: Detection engineering — data quality, observability, unit tests for rules</em>:</strong> Clean desk pairs with <strong>screen privacy</strong> and <strong>clear desk checks</strong> for regulated spaces—physical + procedural controls together.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L4-09: Detection engineering — data quality, observability, unit tests for rules</em>:</strong> Patching and change management appear as <strong>risk tradeoffs</strong>: emergency patches vs testing rings; compensating monitoring when patching lags; and documenting exceptions for auditors.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L4-09: Detection engineering — data quality, observability, unit tests for rules</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L4-09: Detection engineering — data quality, observability, unit tests for rules</em>:</strong> BIOS/UEFI passwords and secure boot reduce some pre-boot attacks but do not stop <strong>evil maid</strong> classes without additional controls.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L4-09: Detection engineering — data quality, observability, unit tests for rules</em>:</strong> Logging questions often test whether you understand <strong>what to log</strong> (who, what, when, where, outcome), <strong>time sync</strong> for correlation, and <strong>tamper resistance</strong> for evidentiary value—not whether you can collect infinite bytes.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L4-09: Detection engineering — data quality, observability, unit tests for rules</em>:</strong> KMS keys are not “magic secrecy dust”—<strong>who can invoke decrypt</strong> and from which contexts (VPC endpoint policies, IAM conditions) is what exams probe.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L4-09: Detection engineering — data quality, observability, unit tests for rules</em>:</strong> Honeypots can generate high-signal alerts but carry <strong>legal and operational</strong> risk if touched by real users; scope carefully.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> A vendor integration project mentions “L4-09: Detection engineering — data quality, observability, unit tests for rules” as out-of-scope for pen testing. Explain what <strong>residual risk</strong> remains, what <strong>compensating monitoring</strong> you would demand, and how you would <strong>document acceptance</strong>.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l4-10":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L4-10: Purple teaming and tabletop exercises</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-10</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Hypothesis-driven detection validation.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> 1-page scenario: ransomware via stolen VPN session — detection points + comms checklist.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-10</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Level 4 mirrors Security+ <strong>enterprise and cloud</strong>: identity governance, conditional access patterns, evidence handling, purple collaboration, and vendor/SaaS risk. Show you understand <strong>scope</strong> and <strong>blast radius</strong> across accounts and tenants.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 4 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Network segmentation</strong></dt><dd>VLANs, micro-segmentation, and east-west controls limit lateral movement after an initial foothold.</dd><dt><strong>Policy vs standard vs procedure</strong></dt><dd>Policy states intent; standards define mandatory requirements; procedures are step-by-step how-to for operators.</dd><dt><strong>Password policy</strong></dt><dd>Modern guidance favors long passphrases, breach-banned lists, and vaults over rotation-for-its-own-sake complexity theater.</dd><dt><strong>OWASP Top 10</strong></dt><dd>High-prevalence web risks—broken access control and crypto failures often dominate; study each category with one workplace example.</dd><dt><strong>MITRE ATT&amp;CK</strong></dt><dd>Tactics (why) and techniques (how) adversaries operate—use for detection engineering, gap analysis, and purple team scenarios.</dd><dt><strong>Third-party risk</strong></dt><dd>Vendor access expands attack surface—DPAs, SOC reports, and continuous monitoring for critical suppliers.</dd><dt><strong>Purple / red / blue</strong></dt><dd>Red emulates adversaries, blue defends, purple bridges—authorization and logging are mandatory for any simulation.</dd><dt><strong>OCSP stapling (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Server sends fresh revocation info with handshake—reduces client privacy leaks and lookup failures.</dd><dt><strong>Port knocking (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Obscurity-based pre-auth to open firewall—weak alone; exam may present as non-primary control.</dd><dt><strong>Diamond model</strong></dt><dd>Adversary, infrastructure, capability, victim—useful for pivoting investigations and intel fusion.</dd><dt><strong>DNS</strong></dt><dd>Name resolution is a trust anchor—DNSSEC, cache poisoning, and malicious resolutions are classic abuse paths; log resolver anomalies.</dd><dt><strong>Risk</strong></dt><dd>The intersection of threat, vulnerability, and impact—often assessed qualitatively (high/medium/low) or with scoring frameworks.</dd><dt><strong>Authentication</strong></dt><dd>Proving identity—something you know, have, or are; combine factors for MFA; never equate login with authorization alone.</dd><dt><strong>Key management</strong></dt><dd>Generation, storage, rotation, and destruction—HSM/KMS patterns reduce exposure compared to software-only secrets.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Typical exam angle</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Confidentiality</strong></td><td>Who may read? Encryption, ACLs, DLP, classification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Integrity</strong></td><td>Was it modified? Hashing, signatures, change control, backups.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Availability</strong></td><td>Can authorized users work? HA, patching windows, DDoS defense, DR.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authenticity / non-repudiation</strong></td><td>Prove source and intent—signatures, strong issuance, tamper-evident logs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Terraform state can hold secrets—remote secure backend and scanning are baseline hygiene.</li><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li><li>AES-128 is not “half as strong” as AES-256 in practical threat models for many cases—key management quality dominates.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>PCI DSS scope reduction via segmentation is a recurring theme—if it is not in scope, it cannot drag you into assessment.</li><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li><li>KMS key policies can deny even root in AWS when configured—explicit deny wins.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L4-10: Purple teaming and tabletop exercises</em>:</strong> Cloud items assume you can articulate <strong>shared responsibility</strong>: what the provider patches vs what the customer must configure (IAM, encryption, network exposure). Misconfiguration beats novel cloud exploits in real incidents and on the exam.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L4-10: Purple teaming and tabletop exercises</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L4-10: Purple teaming and tabletop exercises</em>:</strong> LDAP vs Active Directory questions test directory concepts at a high level—binding, searches, and secure transport (LDAPS) appear often.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L4-10: Purple teaming and tabletop exercises</em>:</strong> Cryptography questions reward vocabulary precision: hashing vs encryption vs encoding; symmetric vs asymmetric roles in TLS; what signatures prove; and why key management is usually harder than picking an algorithm. If an answer sounds magical, it is probably wrong.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L4-10: Purple teaming and tabletop exercises</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L4-10: Purple teaming and tabletop exercises</em>:</strong> GraphQL introspection risk is about <strong>schema discovery</strong> aiding attackers—rate limits, authz on fields, and disabling introspection in prod are common answers.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L4-10: Purple teaming and tabletop exercises</em>:</strong> Defense in depth is not “more products,” it is <strong>independent mechanisms</strong>—if one layer is bypassed, another still limits movement, slows the adversary, or preserves evidence. Be ready to explain why network controls alone cannot compensate for missing app-layer authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L4-10: Purple teaming and tabletop exercises</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L4-10: Purple teaming and tabletop exercises</em>:</strong> Tabletop exercises test <strong>comms trees</strong>, legal escalation, and customer notification templates—not only technical runbooks.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L4-10: Purple teaming and tabletop exercises</em>:</strong> Clean desk pairs with <strong>screen privacy</strong> and <strong>clear desk checks</strong> for regulated spaces—physical + procedural controls together.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> During a tabletop, the CFO asks how “L4-10: Purple teaming and tabletop exercises” could become a material incident. Answer with <strong>one plausible attack path</strong>, <strong>one detective control</strong> you already have, and <strong>one preventive gap</strong> you would fund next quarter.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l4-11":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L4-11: Forensics chain of custody (hashing, write blockers, time)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-11</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Admissibility concepts; work order discipline.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>dd if=/dev/zero of=~/dummy.img bs=1M count=5</code> then <code>sha256sum ~/dummy.img</code>; document who/when/where.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-11</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Purple team references test <strong>authorization to simulate</strong> and <strong>logging of exercises</strong>—safety and auditability matter.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 4 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>DDoS</strong></dt><dd>Distributed denial of service—volumetric, protocol, or application-layer floods; mitigations include scrubbing, anycast, rate limits, and architecture elasticity.</dd><dt><strong>Encryption at rest / in transit</strong></dt><dd>KMS/HSM-backed keys, envelope encryption, and TLS everywhere for administrative and user paths.</dd><dt><strong>MAC</strong></dt><dd>Message authentication code—integrity with a secret key; differs from digital signature which uses asymmetric keys.</dd><dt><strong>Authenticity</strong></dt><dd>Verifies that users, devices, or data are genuine—cryptographic identity, attestation, and strong issuance processes matter.</dd><dt><strong>Secure SDLC</strong></dt><dd>Requirements, threat modeling, secure design, code review, SAST/DAST, dependency scanning, and hardened deployment pipelines.</dd><dt><strong>Data loss prevention (DLP)</strong></dt><dd>Content-aware controls to block or alert on sensitive data movement—policy + tech, tuned to avoid blocking work.</dd><dt><strong>Quantitative vs qualitative risk</strong></dt><dd>Qualitative uses scales (high/medium/low); quantitative uses dollar or probability estimates—both need consistent assumptions and reviewer judgment.</dd><dt><strong>Hashing</strong></dt><dd>One-way fingerprint for integrity verification—SHA-256 family; not secrecy; used with HMAC for keyed integrity.</dd><dt><strong>Attack surface</strong></dt><dd>The sum of exposure—every service, API, integration, and human workflow that can be reached by a threat; reduction beats perfect monitoring alone.</dd><dt><strong>RPO / RTO recap</strong></dt><dd>RPO = max acceptable data loss time; RTO = max acceptable outage—drive backup frequency and HA design.</dd><dt><strong>NAT (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Rewrites addresses/ports for traversal—security relevance includes logging visibility, port forwarding risks, and split tunnel implications for inspection.</dd><dt><strong>Misconfiguration</strong></dt><dd>Top cloud incident driver—public buckets, open security groups, permissive trust policies; IaC scanning catches drift early.</dd><dt><strong>IV / nonce</strong></dt><dd>Initialization vector or number-used-once—must be unique per encryption under a key for many modes.</dd><dt><strong>Availability</strong></dt><dd>Assures timely and reliable access—redundancy, patching, DDoS defenses, and DR planning keep services usable for authorized users.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Typical exam angle</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Confidentiality</strong></td><td>Who may read? Encryption, ACLs, DLP, classification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Integrity</strong></td><td>Was it modified? Hashing, signatures, change control, backups.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Availability</strong></td><td>Can authorized users work? HA, patching windows, DDoS defense, DR.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authenticity / non-repudiation</strong></td><td>Prove source and intent—signatures, strong issuance, tamper-evident logs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li><li>Race conditions in web apps can undermine authorization—sequential logic tests in secure design reviews.</li><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li><li>Split tunnel VPN can exfil corporate data outside inspection if misconfigured—policy and routing matter.</li><li>SBOM formats (CycloneDX/SPDX) help inventory components for incident response and licensing—not only security.</li><li>ATT&CK technique IDs are stable references for detection content—good for purple team reporting.</li><li>Admission controllers can block privileged pods—policy-as-code integrates with GitOps reviews.</li><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L4-11: Forensics chain of custody (hashing, write blockers, time)</em>:</strong> Sanitization vs wiping vs destruction: exams like knowing which media needs <strong>degaussing, shredding, or crypto erase</strong> per policy.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L4-11: Forensics chain of custody (hashing, write blockers, time)</em>:</strong> Email security stems often combine SPF alignment failures with <strong>look-alike domains</strong>. The best answer addresses user training plus technical authenticity controls, not only one or the other.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L4-11: Forensics chain of custody (hashing, write blockers, time)</em>:</strong> Social engineering callbacks to <strong>pretexting</strong>, <strong>baiting</strong>, and <strong>vishing</strong>—name the subtype when the stem describes the tactic.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L4-11: Forensics chain of custody (hashing, write blockers, time)</em>:</strong> When logs “mysteriously stop,” think <strong>time sync failure</strong>, collector saturation, retention misconfiguration, or attacker tampering—in that diagnostic order for a fair exam narrative.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L4-11: Forensics chain of custody (hashing, write blockers, time)</em>:</strong> Clean desk pairs with <strong>screen privacy</strong> and <strong>clear desk checks</strong> for regulated spaces—physical + procedural controls together.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L4-11: Forensics chain of custody (hashing, write blockers, time)</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L4-11: Forensics chain of custody (hashing, write blockers, time)</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L4-11: Forensics chain of custody (hashing, write blockers, time)</em>:</strong> Container escape questions hinge on <strong>kernel boundary</strong> and misconfigured capabilities—namespaces are helpful but not a complete trust boundary without seccomp, AppArmor, and least-privileged service accounts.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L4-11: Forensics chain of custody (hashing, write blockers, time)</em>:</strong> For the Security+ mindset, translate every control into <strong>who</strong> it protects, <strong>what</strong> asset is at risk, and <strong>how</strong> you would detect failure. Interview and exam items often reward practical prioritization over buzzwords—choose the mitigation that reduces realistic loss first.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L4-11: Forensics chain of custody (hashing, write blockers, time)</em>:</strong> Serverless cold start is not a security control; <strong>per-function IAM</strong> and least-privilege API scopes are. Watch for attractive nonsense distractors tied to performance tuning.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Marketing launches a campaign referencing “L4-11: Forensics chain of custody (hashing, write blockers, time)” with a new subdomain. Security review finds DNS delegated to an unknown party. Explain <strong>trust chain</strong> risks and the <strong>minimum fixes</strong> before go-live.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l4-12":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L4-12: Memory and disk artifacts at high level (Volatility idea)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-12</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> What RAM captures vs disk; volatility of evidence.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Read Volatility3 docs intro; list 3 plugins and what analyst question they answer.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-12</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>SaaS governance (CASB-style thinking) pairs technical visibility with <strong>OAuth consent</strong> and <strong>guest sharing</strong> policy.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 4 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Vulnerability management</strong></dt><dd>Discover, prioritize, remediate, verify, and report—SLAs differ by exposure, exploitability, and asset criticality.</dd><dt><strong>SOC triage order</strong></dt><dd>Scope → impact → evidence → containment hypothesis; avoid fixing symptoms before you know blast radius.</dd><dt><strong>BGP prefix hijack</strong></dt><dd>Unauthorized route advertisement—RPKI ROV reduces impact but does not replace monitoring.</dd><dt><strong>Due care</strong></dt><dd>The effort a prudent person would take to meet a duty; in security, reasonable steps to protect assets and stakeholders.</dd><dt><strong>Symmetric encryption</strong></dt><dd>Same key encrypts and decrypts—fast for bulk data (AES-GCM); key distribution is the hard problem.</dd><dt><strong>Container security</strong></dt><dd>Image provenance, non-root users, read-only roots, seccomp/AppArmor, and admission control for risky capabilities.</dd><dt><strong>OCSP stapling (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Server sends fresh revocation info with handshake—reduces client privacy leaks and lookup failures.</dd><dt><strong>UEBA</strong></dt><dd>User and entity behavior analytics—baseline deviations; tune to avoid HR/privacy backlash.</dd><dt><strong>Data classification</strong></dt><dd>Labels (public, internal, confidential, restricted) drive storage, encryption, sharing, and disposal requirements.</dd><dt><strong>OWASP Top 10</strong></dt><dd>High-prevalence web risks—broken access control and crypto failures often dominate; study each category with one workplace example.</dd><dt><strong>Metrics that matter</strong></dt><dd>Mean time to detect/remediate with quality, coverage of critical assets, and control effectiveness—not vanity ticket counts.</dd><dt><strong>HMAC</strong></dt><dd>Keyed hash construction—common for API authenticity when symmetric secret is shared out-of-band.</dd><dt><strong>CASB / SaaS governance</strong></dt><dd>Visibility and policy for sanctioned vs shadow SaaS—OAuth consent attacks and guest sharing are common gaps.</dd><dt><strong>DDoS</strong></dt><dd>Distributed denial of service—volumetric, protocol, or application-layer floods; mitigations include scrubbing, anycast, rate limits, and architecture elasticity.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>SLSA levels describe increasing supply-chain assurance—useful vocabulary in modern governance questions.</li><li>Sigma rules are vendor-agnostic detection snippets—tuning required per log source fields.</li><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li><li>OAuth access tokens are not a replacement for server-side authorization checks on every sensitive action.</li><li>JWT alg:none historical vulnerability class—always validate algorithm and signature keys explicitly.</li><li>AES-128 is not “half as strong” as AES-256 in practical threat models for many cases—key management quality dominates.</li><li>Immutable backups mitigate ransomware that tries to delete online copies—air-gapped or WORM patterns.</li><li>Azure AD / Entra conditional access is analogous to risk-based policies—device compliance signals matter.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L4-12: Memory and disk artifacts at high level (Volatility idea)</em>:</strong> Wireless assessments should mention <strong>rogue AP</strong> discovery, client isolation, and guest segmentation—not just “use WPA2” as a slogan. Exam writers like the distinction between personal and enterprise authentication modes at a conceptual level.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L4-12: Memory and disk artifacts at high level (Volatility idea)</em>:</strong> Cryptography questions reward vocabulary precision: hashing vs encryption vs encoding; symmetric vs asymmetric roles in TLS; what signatures prove; and why key management is usually harder than picking an algorithm. If an answer sounds magical, it is probably wrong.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L4-12: Memory and disk artifacts at high level (Volatility idea)</em>:</strong> RADIUS is still referenced for <strong>network access control</strong> integrations; know it as a AAA component in enterprise Wi-Fi contexts.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L4-12: Memory and disk artifacts at high level (Volatility idea)</em>:</strong> Serverless cold start is not a security control; <strong>per-function IAM</strong> and least-privilege API scopes are. Watch for attractive nonsense distractors tied to performance tuning.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L4-12: Memory and disk artifacts at high level (Volatility idea)</em>:</strong> Logging questions often test whether you understand <strong>what to log</strong> (who, what, when, where, outcome), <strong>time sync</strong> for correlation, and <strong>tamper resistance</strong> for evidentiary value—not whether you can collect infinite bytes.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L4-12: Memory and disk artifacts at high level (Volatility idea)</em>:</strong> TPM-backed BitLocker keys illustrate <strong>key protection</strong> binding to platform state—recovery keys must be guarded like crown jewels.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L4-12: Memory and disk artifacts at high level (Volatility idea)</em>:</strong> DAST exercises running apps but misses authz logic without credentials; combine with <strong>manual review</strong> for business-rule flaws.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L4-12: Memory and disk artifacts at high level (Volatility idea)</em>:</strong> Data handling questions often hinge on <strong>classification</strong>, <strong>least data</strong>, and <strong>retention</strong>: collect only what you need, keep it only as long as allowed, and destroy securely when done.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L4-12: Memory and disk artifacts at high level (Volatility idea)</em>:</strong> Defense in depth is not “more products,” it is <strong>independent mechanisms</strong>—if one layer is bypassed, another still limits movement, slows the adversary, or preserves evidence. Be ready to explain why network controls alone cannot compensate for missing app-layer authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L4-12: Memory and disk artifacts at high level (Volatility idea)</em>:</strong> CSP reporting helps tune policy but can leak URLs—<strong>privacy review</strong> of report endpoints matters in regulated environments.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> You are the on-call analyst reviewing an alert tied to “L4-12: Memory and disk artifacts at high level (Volatility idea)”. Leadership wants a <strong>60-second</strong> brief: business impact, evidence gaps, and the <strong>first</strong> containment step that preserves logs. No tool-specific jargon—prioritize scope, evidence, blast radius, then root-cause remediation under change control.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l4-13":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L4-13: EDR behavior: telemetry, response actions, rollback limits</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-13</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Kernel callbacks vs userland hooks (conceptual).<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Vendor datasheet comparison table (your org’s EDR if allowed): 5 rows.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-13</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Cloud answers should articulate <strong>shared responsibility</strong> boundaries without blaming the provider for customer IAM mistakes.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 4 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Zero Trust architecture</strong></dt><dd>Identity-centric access with continuous verification—policy enforcement points for users, devices, and workloads.</dd><dt><strong>Collision (hash)</strong></dt><dd>Two inputs produce same hash—breaks integrity assumptions; choose strong hash families for security use.</dd><dt><strong>IOC</strong></dt><dd>Indicator of compromise—often ephemeral (IPs, domains); pair with TTP-based detections for durability.</dd><dt><strong>Residual risk</strong></dt><dd>Risk remaining after controls are applied; organizations accept, transfer, mitigate, or avoid it explicitly.</dd><dt><strong>Firewall</strong></dt><dd>Enforces allow/deny rules on traffic—stateful inspection tracks sessions; default-deny with explicit permits is the secure baseline.</dd><dt><strong>IDOR</strong></dt><dd>Insecure direct object reference—missing object-level authorization; test horizontal/vertical access with different accounts.</dd><dt><strong>Security awareness</strong></dt><dd>Training plus culture—measure reporting rates, not shame metrics; phishing simulations should reinforce reporting.</dd><dt><strong>Downgrade attack</strong></dt><dd>Forcing weaker crypto or protocols—HSTS and modern TLS config reduce browser downgrade paths.</dd><dt><strong>BGP prefix hijack</strong></dt><dd>Unauthorized route advertisement—RPKI ROV reduces impact but does not replace monitoring.</dd><dt><strong>Quantitative vs qualitative risk</strong></dt><dd>Qualitative uses scales (high/medium/low); quantitative uses dollar or probability estimates—both need consistent assumptions and reviewer judgment.</dd><dt><strong>Password policy</strong></dt><dd>Modern guidance favors long passphrases, breach-banned lists, and vaults over rotation-for-its-own-sake complexity theater.</dd><dt><strong>AEAD</strong></dt><dd>Authenticated encryption with associated data—confidentiality plus integrity in one primitive (e.g., AES-GCM) when used correctly.</dd><dt><strong>Encryption at rest / in transit</strong></dt><dd>KMS/HSM-backed keys, envelope encryption, and TLS everywhere for administrative and user paths.</dd><dt><strong>Separation of duties (SoD)</strong></dt><dd>No single person can complete a sensitive transaction alone—classic finance control that also limits insider abuse.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Cloud responsibility</th><th>Who typically owns it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Patching the hypervisor</strong></td><td>Provider responsibility in major IaaS models—customer still patches guests.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>IAM policy and keys</strong></td><td>Customer-owned configuration—misconfigurations dominate incidents.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Data encryption at rest</strong></td><td>Often customer-controlled keys/KMS policies with provider primitives.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Network exposure (SGs/NACLs)</strong></td><td>Customer configures; default-deny patterns are exam favorites.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Application vulnerabilities</strong></td><td>Customer code and dependencies—shared model does not absolve secure SDLC.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Linux auth.log style entries pair with SSH brute-force detection patterns—velocity and geo anomalies.</li><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>SBOM formats (CycloneDX/SPDX) help inventory components for incident response and licensing—not only security.</li><li>Race conditions in web apps can undermine authorization—sequential logic tests in secure design reviews.</li><li>Immutable backups mitigate ransomware that tries to delete online copies—air-gapped or WORM patterns.</li><li>OAuth access tokens are not a replacement for server-side authorization checks on every sensitive action.</li><li>SLSA levels describe increasing supply-chain assurance—useful vocabulary in modern governance questions.</li><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L4-13: EDR behavior: telemetry, response actions, rollback limits</em>:</strong> Engineers often optimize for speed; attackers optimize for <strong>cheap reuse</strong> of stolen creds and known exploits. The winning answer bridges both: ship fast with guardrails—feature flags, staged rollouts, and automated security checks in CI.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L4-13: EDR behavior: telemetry, response actions, rollback limits</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L4-13: EDR behavior: telemetry, response actions, rollback limits</em>:</strong> GraphQL introspection risk is about <strong>schema discovery</strong> aiding attackers—rate limits, authz on fields, and disabling introspection in prod are common answers.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L4-13: EDR behavior: telemetry, response actions, rollback limits</em>:</strong> BIOS/UEFI passwords and secure boot reduce some pre-boot attacks but do not stop <strong>evil maid</strong> classes without additional controls.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L4-13: EDR behavior: telemetry, response actions, rollback limits</em>:</strong> Identity is the new perimeter: credentials, tokens, and sessions are stolen more often than novel zero-days are burned. Expect Security+ items on MFA bypass awareness, phishing-resistant factors, and why <strong>authorization</strong> must be enforced server-side.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L4-13: EDR behavior: telemetry, response actions, rollback limits</em>:</strong> Physical security is still on the exam: tailgating, visitor escorts, locks, destruction of media, and environmental controls (fire, HVAC) as availability/confidentiality supports.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L4-13: EDR behavior: telemetry, response actions, rollback limits</em>:</strong> Email security stems often combine SPF alignment failures with <strong>look-alike domains</strong>. The best answer addresses user training plus technical authenticity controls, not only one or the other.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L4-13: EDR behavior: telemetry, response actions, rollback limits</em>:</strong> DAST exercises running apps but misses authz logic without credentials; combine with <strong>manual review</strong> for business-rule flaws.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L4-13: EDR behavior: telemetry, response actions, rollback limits</em>:</strong> RADIUS is still referenced for <strong>network access control</strong> integrations; know it as a AAA component in enterprise Wi-Fi contexts.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L4-13: EDR behavior: telemetry, response actions, rollback limits</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Junior staff proposes a quick fix for “L4-13: EDR behavior: telemetry, response actions, rollback limits” that disables logging on a noisy host. Walk through why that is unacceptable and propose a <strong>tuning</strong> path that preserves <strong>integrity and retention</strong> commitments.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l4-14":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L4-14: Data loss prevention (DLP) and insider risk programs</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-14</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Technical + HR + legal balance; proportionality.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Policy red-team: find 3 ways DLP can misfire on developer workflows.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-14</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>SaaS governance (CASB-style thinking) pairs technical visibility with <strong>OAuth consent</strong> and <strong>guest sharing</strong> policy.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 4 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Injection</strong></dt><dd>Untrusted input becomes part of a command or query—parameterized queries, input validation, and context escaping are core defenses.</dd><dt><strong>SIEM</strong></dt><dd>Security information and event management—centralize logs, parse fields, correlate alerts; tuning reduces false positives and fatigue.</dd><dt><strong>CASB / SaaS governance</strong></dt><dd>Visibility and policy for sanctioned vs shadow SaaS—OAuth consent attacks and guest sharing are common gaps.</dd><dt><strong>Zero Trust architecture</strong></dt><dd>Identity-centric access with continuous verification—policy enforcement points for users, devices, and workloads.</dd><dt><strong>Mandatory vacation</strong></dt><dd>Forces handover and review of another employee’s work—can uncover fraud or backdoors.</dd><dt><strong>Rainbow table</strong></dt><dd>Precomputed hash chains for fast password cracking—salting and modern KDFs are the defense.</dd><dt><strong>Proxy vs reverse proxy</strong></dt><dd>Forward proxy represents clients outbound; reverse proxy fronts servers—different trust and logging points.</dd><dt><strong>Diamond model</strong></dt><dd>Adversary, infrastructure, capability, victim—useful for pivoting investigations and intel fusion.</dd><dt><strong>Firewall</strong></dt><dd>Enforces allow/deny rules on traffic—stateful inspection tracks sessions; default-deny with explicit permits is the secure baseline.</dd><dt><strong>Threat</strong></dt><dd>Any circumstance or actor with the potential to cause harm by exploiting a vulnerability (malware, insider, natural disaster).</dd><dt><strong>Availability</strong></dt><dd>Assures timely and reliable access—redundancy, patching, DDoS defenses, and DR planning keep services usable for authorized users.</dd><dt><strong>Session management</strong></dt><dd>Server-side session IDs or tokens must rotate on privilege change, bind to channel, and expire predictably.</dd><dt><strong>Zero Trust (headline)</strong></dt><dd>Assume breach; verify explicitly per request using identity, device posture, and least privilege—not “trust the LAN.”</dd><dt><strong>AEAD</strong></dt><dd>Authenticated encryption with associated data—confidentiality plus integrity in one primitive (e.g., AES-GCM) when used correctly.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Cloud responsibility</th><th>Who typically owns it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Patching the hypervisor</strong></td><td>Provider responsibility in major IaaS models—customer still patches guests.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>IAM policy and keys</strong></td><td>Customer-owned configuration—misconfigurations dominate incidents.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Data encryption at rest</strong></td><td>Often customer-controlled keys/KMS policies with provider primitives.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Network exposure (SGs/NACLs)</strong></td><td>Customer configures; default-deny patterns are exam favorites.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Application vulnerabilities</strong></td><td>Customer code and dependencies—shared model does not absolve secure SDLC.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li><li>Server-side template injection is distinct from XSS—context and sinks differ.</li><li>SBOM formats (CycloneDX/SPDX) help inventory components for incident response and licensing—not only security.</li><li>OAuth access tokens are not a replacement for server-side authorization checks on every sensitive action.</li><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li><li>Responsible disclosure timelines balance vendor patch readiness with public safety—coordinate, don’t surprise.</li><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L4-14: Data loss prevention (DLP) and insider risk programs</em>:</strong> Third-party and supply chain answers should emphasize <strong>contracts</strong>, <strong>evidence</strong>, and <strong>continuous monitoring</strong>—not “trust the SOC 2 logo” without scope review.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L4-14: Data loss prevention (DLP) and insider risk programs</em>:</strong> Cryptojacking still appears: high CPU, unexpected mining pools, and cloud billing spikes—detection plus credential hygiene beats chasing miner signatures alone.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L4-14: Data loss prevention (DLP) and insider risk programs</em>:</strong> Deception tech is not a replacement for <strong>baselines and patching</strong>; it augments detection when mature processes exist.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L4-14: Data loss prevention (DLP) and insider risk programs</em>:</strong> Vulnerability management is a lifecycle: scanners find candidates, analysts prioritize with exploitability and business context, owners remediate, and verification closes the loop. “Patch everything immediately” is rarely operational; <strong>risk-based SLAs</strong> are the adult answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L4-14: Data loss prevention (DLP) and insider risk programs</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L4-14: Data loss prevention (DLP) and insider risk programs</em>:</strong> Multicloud complexity increases <strong>identity sprawl</strong>; centralized IdP and consistent conditional access policies reduce human error.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L4-14: Data loss prevention (DLP) and insider risk programs</em>:</strong> Clean desk pairs with <strong>screen privacy</strong> and <strong>clear desk checks</strong> for regulated spaces—physical + procedural controls together.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L4-14: Data loss prevention (DLP) and insider risk programs</em>:</strong> Wireless and mobility items reward knowing basics: WPA3 improvements conceptually, evil twin risks, captive portals, and why client isolation matters on guest networks—without memorizing obsolete WEP details unless explicitly historical.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L4-14: Data loss prevention (DLP) and insider risk programs</em>:</strong> KMS keys are not “magic secrecy dust”—<strong>who can invoke decrypt</strong> and from which contexts (VPC endpoint policies, IAM conditions) is what exams probe.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L4-14: Data loss prevention (DLP) and insider risk programs</em>:</strong> RADIUS is still referenced for <strong>network access control</strong> integrations; know it as a AAA component in enterprise Wi-Fi contexts.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Junior staff proposes a quick fix for “L4-14: Data loss prevention (DLP) and insider risk programs” that disables logging on a noisy host. Walk through why that is unacceptable and propose a <strong>tuning</strong> path that preserves <strong>integrity and retention</strong> commitments.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l4-15":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L4-15: Business continuity, IR retainers, cyber insurance caveats</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-15</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> “Not all incidents are claims”; sublimits for BEC.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Read one insurer security questionnaire outline; map controls to NIST CSF functions.</p>\n<h2>Lab pack — Level 4</h2>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Cloud IAM review:</strong> Draw trust boundaries for SaaS + IdP + IaaS; mark secret flows.  </li>\n<li><strong>Detection gap analysis:</strong> Pick 10 ATT&amp;CK techniques; mark “logged / alerted / tuned / gap.”  </li>\n<li><strong>Forensics dry run:</strong> Image USB with dummy data; maintain custody form.  </li>\n<li><strong>Purple mini:</strong> Developer runs benign PowerShell obfuscation in <strong>sandbox</strong>; analyst writes detection tweak.  </li>\n<li><strong>BCP table top:</strong> 90-minute agenda doc with injects (comms failure, key person unavailable).</li>\n</ol>\n<h2>Question bank — Level 4</h2>\n<p><strong>Q1.</strong> Kerberos TGT is roughly: (a) DHCP lease (b) proof of auth to request service tickets (c) BIOS password.<br><strong>Q2.</strong> LAPS primarily: (a) rotates local admin passwords (b) encrypts Wi-Fi (c) replaces TLS.<br><strong>Q3.</strong> Conditional Access uses signals like: (a) device compliance, location, risk (b) only password length (c) printer DPI.<br><strong>Q4.</strong> SCP in AWS Organizations can: (a) restrict max permissions for accounts (b) replace IAM entirely (c) fix SQLi.<br><strong>Q5.</strong> CloudTrail captures mainly: (a) API control-plane activity (b) every disk block write always (c) GPU fan speed.<br><strong>Q6.</strong> SBOM helps: (a) track software components for incident response (b) replace pentesting (c) remove MFA.<br><strong>Q7.</strong> Chain of custody ensures: (a) faster CPUs (b) evidence integrity and auditability (c) anonymous browsing.<br><strong>Q8.</strong> EDR differs from traditional AV partly by: (a) richer behavioral telemetry (b) no logs (c) only email.<br><strong>Q9.</strong> Purple team goal: (a) hide incidents (b) validate detections with controlled adversary behavior (c) delete backups.<br><strong>Q10.</strong> Insider risk programs should be: (a) covert only always (b) lawful, transparent, proportionate (c) solely technical.<br><strong>Q11.</strong> Write blockers protect: (a) integrity of acquired media (b) Wi-Fi speed (c) TLS handshakes.<br><strong>Q12.</strong> PIM / JIT admin reduces: (a) standing privileged access (b) MFA need (c) patch needs.<br><strong>Q13.</strong> <code>aws:MultiFactorAuthPresent</code> in Deny policies encourages: (a) MFA for sensitive APIs (b) weaker keys (c) BGP safety.<br><strong>Q14.</strong> Volatility-style analysis targets: (a) RAM artifacts (b) printer ink (c) DNS only.<br><strong>Q15.</strong> Cyber insurance does not remove: (a) need for security controls (b) accountants (c) CPUs.<br><strong>Q16.</strong> Kubernetes NetworkPolicy conceptually: (a) layer-3/4 segmentation for pods (b) TLS cipher suite (c) BIOS.<br><strong>Q17.</strong> SLSA focuses on: (a) supply chain integrity levels (b) Wi-Fi bands (c) SQL indexes.<br><strong>Q18.</strong> Detection engineering includes: (a) testing rules against representative data (b) ignoring false positives (c) deleting logs.<br><strong>Q19.</strong> GPO can enforce: (a) Windows security baselines (b) BGP attributes (c) GPU overclock only.<br><strong>Q20.</strong> BEC (business email compromise) primarily abuses: (a) trust in email + finance processes (b) RAID 5 (c) HDMI.</p>\n<h3>Answer key — Level 4</h3>\n<p>1–5: B/A/A/A/A<br>6–10: A/B/B/B/B<br>11–15: A/A/A/A/A<br>16–20: A/A/A/A/A  </p>\n<hr>\n<h1>Level 5 — Heavy advanced (architecture, crypto attacks, hardware trust, formal assurance)</h1>\n<p><strong>Workplace outcomes:</strong> You can participate in zero-trust design reviews, red-team scoping, crypto uplift projects, and high-assurance discussions without hand-waving.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-15</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Evidence handling in regulated orgs may invoke <strong>legal hold</strong>—do not pick answers that “clean up” data prematurely.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 4 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>CWE</strong></dt><dd>Common Weakness Enumeration—taxonomy of software weakness types that help root-cause fixes beyond one CVE instance.</dd><dt><strong>Security awareness</strong></dt><dd>Training plus culture—measure reporting rates, not shame metrics; phishing simulations should reinforce reporting.</dd><dt><strong>Job rotation</strong></dt><dd>Reduces collusion and fraud risk; also surfaces “tribal knowledge” silos before an employee leaves.</dd><dt><strong>MAC</strong></dt><dd>Message authentication code—integrity with a secret key; differs from digital signature which uses asymmetric keys.</dd><dt><strong>Diamond model</strong></dt><dd>Adversary, infrastructure, capability, victim—useful for pivoting investigations and intel fusion.</dd><dt><strong>DevSecOps</strong></dt><dd>Embed security gates in CI/CD with fast feedback—policy-as-code, secret scanning, and SBOMs support supply-chain resilience.</dd><dt><strong>Authenticity</strong></dt><dd>Verifies that users, devices, or data are genuine—cryptographic identity, attestation, and strong issuance processes matter.</dd><dt><strong>TLS</strong></dt><dd>Encrypts data in motion and authenticates endpoints when certificates and hostnames are validated; termination points affect trust boundaries.</dd><dt><strong>Security misconfiguration</strong></dt><dd>Default creds, debug features on in prod, verbose errors, open directory listings—hardening baselines and drift detection reduce this class.</dd><dt><strong>Shared responsibility model</strong></dt><dd>Cloud provider secures the platform; customer secures configuration, identities, data, and app code in their scope.</dd><dt><strong>Attack surface</strong></dt><dd>The sum of exposure—every service, API, integration, and human workflow that can be reached by a threat; reduction beats perfect monitoring alone.</dd><dt><strong>Downgrade attack</strong></dt><dd>Forcing weaker crypto or protocols—HSTS and modern TLS config reduce browser downgrade paths.</dd><dt><strong>Proxy vs reverse proxy</strong></dt><dd>Forward proxy represents clients outbound; reverse proxy fronts servers—different trust and logging points.</dd><dt><strong>Data residency</strong></dt><dd>Legal requirement for where data lives—impacts cloud region selection and key custody.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Cloud responsibility</th><th>Who typically owns it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Patching the hypervisor</strong></td><td>Provider responsibility in major IaaS models—customer still patches guests.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>IAM policy and keys</strong></td><td>Customer-owned configuration—misconfigurations dominate incidents.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Data encryption at rest</strong></td><td>Often customer-controlled keys/KMS policies with provider primitives.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Network exposure (SGs/NACLs)</strong></td><td>Customer configures; default-deny patterns are exam favorites.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Application vulnerabilities</strong></td><td>Customer code and dependencies—shared model does not absolve secure SDLC.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authorization</strong></td><td>Server-side object checks—headers and TLS do not replace this.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li><li>AES-128 is not “half as strong” as AES-256 in practical threat models for many cases—key management quality dominates.</li><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li><li>DNS over HTTPS changes visibility for some networks—understand resolver policy and logging tradeoffs.</li><li>CVSS base does not include your asset criticality—environmental metrics exist for a reason.</li><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li><li>S3 bucket policies and ACLs layer with IAM—effective permissions require understanding intersection.</li><li>Certificate pinning misconfigurations can brick apps—plan rotation and emergency releases.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L4-15: Business continuity, IR retainers, cyber insurance caveats</em>:</strong> Evidence bags and write blockers signal <strong>forensics awareness</strong>; touching disks before imaging is a classic wrong answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L4-15: Business continuity, IR retainers, cyber insurance caveats</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L4-15: Business continuity, IR retainers, cyber insurance caveats</em>:</strong> Third-party and supply chain answers should emphasize <strong>contracts</strong>, <strong>evidence</strong>, and <strong>continuous monitoring</strong>—not “trust the SOC 2 logo” without scope review.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L4-15: Business continuity, IR retainers, cyber insurance caveats</em>:</strong> SAST finds issues early but produces false positives; <strong>triage workflows</strong> and developer feedback loops are part of a mature program, not “run tool once.”</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L4-15: Business continuity, IR retainers, cyber insurance caveats</em>:</strong> TPM-backed BitLocker keys illustrate <strong>key protection</strong> binding to platform state—recovery keys must be guarded like crown jewels.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L4-15: Business continuity, IR retainers, cyber insurance caveats</em>:</strong> Access control stems frequently mix <strong>role</strong> vs <strong>attribute</strong> vs <strong>rule</strong> models; pick the answer that matches the scenario’s constraints (temporary contractor, cross-department data, dynamic tags on resources).</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L4-15: Business continuity, IR retainers, cyber insurance caveats</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L4-15: Business continuity, IR retainers, cyber insurance caveats</em>:</strong> Deception tech is not a replacement for <strong>baselines and patching</strong>; it augments detection when mature processes exist.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L4-15: Business continuity, IR retainers, cyber insurance caveats</em>:</strong> Cloud items assume you can articulate <strong>shared responsibility</strong>: what the provider patches vs what the customer must configure (IAM, encryption, network exposure). Misconfiguration beats novel cloud exploits in real incidents and on the exam.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L4-15: Business continuity, IR retainers, cyber insurance caveats</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> A cloud bill spike correlates with traffic about “L4-15: Business continuity, IR retainers, cyber insurance caveats”. Differentiate <strong>misconfiguration</strong> vs <strong>abuse</strong> in your first triage questions and what logs prove each hypothesis.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l5-01":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L5-01: Zero Trust Architecture (NIST SP 800-207 themes)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-01</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> PDP/PEP, continuous verification, assume breach.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> ZT logical diagram for “admin access to production” with 6 controls labeled PDP/PEP.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-01</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Advanced IR/intel questions still punish <strong>evidence destruction</strong> and <strong>unscoped testing</strong>—professional ethics are in scope.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 5 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Confidentiality</strong></dt><dd>Assures that information is not disclosed to unauthorized subjects—encryption, access control, and data minimization support it.</dd><dt><strong>DDoS</strong></dt><dd>Distributed denial of service—volumetric, protocol, or application-layer floods; mitigations include scrubbing, anycast, rate limits, and architecture elasticity.</dd><dt><strong>Key management</strong></dt><dd>Generation, storage, rotation, and destruction—HSM/KMS patterns reduce exposure compared to software-only secrets.</dd><dt><strong>MITRE ATT&amp;CK</strong></dt><dd>Tactics (why) and techniques (how) adversaries operate—use for detection engineering, gap analysis, and purple team scenarios.</dd><dt><strong>Supply chain security</strong></dt><dd>SBOM, provenance signing (SLSA-style thinking), and dependency pinning reduce “update from upstream” surprises.</dd><dt><strong>Data loss prevention (DLP)</strong></dt><dd>Content-aware controls to block or alert on sensitive data movement—policy + tech, tuned to avoid blocking work.</dd><dt><strong>MITM</strong></dt><dd>Man-in-the-middle intercepts or alters traffic—TLS with proper validation mitigates; corporate SSL inspection is its own trust zone.</dd><dt><strong>TTP</strong></dt><dd>Tactics, techniques, and procedures—behavioral patterns; harder to change than IOCs, better for resilient detection.</dd><dt><strong>Threat</strong></dt><dd>Any circumstance or actor with the potential to cause harm by exploiting a vulnerability (malware, insider, natural disaster).</dd><dt><strong>Authentication</strong></dt><dd>Proving identity—something you know, have, or are; combine factors for MFA; never equate login with authorization alone.</dd><dt><strong>Network segmentation</strong></dt><dd>VLANs, micro-segmentation, and east-west controls limit lateral movement after an initial foothold.</dd><dt><strong>IDOR</strong></dt><dd>Insecure direct object reference—missing object-level authorization; test horizontal/vertical access with different accounts.</dd><dt><strong>Container security</strong></dt><dd>Image provenance, non-root users, read-only roots, seccomp/AppArmor, and admission control for risky capabilities.</dd><dt><strong>Purple teaming</strong></dt><dd>Collaborative attack/defense exercises to validate detections without surprise production harm—scope and safety first.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Cloud responsibility</th><th>Who typically owns it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Patching the hypervisor</strong></td><td>Provider responsibility in major IaaS models—customer still patches guests.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>IAM policy and keys</strong></td><td>Customer-owned configuration—misconfigurations dominate incidents.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Data encryption at rest</strong></td><td>Often customer-controlled keys/KMS policies with provider primitives.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Network exposure (SGs/NACLs)</strong></td><td>Customer configures; default-deny patterns are exam favorites.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Application vulnerabilities</strong></td><td>Customer code and dependencies—shared model does not absolve secure SDLC.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>AES-128 is not “half as strong” as AES-256 in practical threat models for many cases—key management quality dominates.</li><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li><li>SLSA levels describe increasing supply-chain assurance—useful vocabulary in modern governance questions.</li><li>Linux auth.log style entries pair with SSH brute-force detection patterns—velocity and geo anomalies.</li><li>GCP service account keys are long-lived secrets—prefer workload identity federation from CI where possible.</li><li>ATT&CK technique IDs are stable references for detection content—good for purple team reporting.</li><li>S3 bucket policies and ACLs layer with IAM—effective permissions require understanding intersection.</li><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L5-01: Zero Trust Architecture (NIST SP 800-207 themes)</em>:</strong> Industrial and OT adjacent questions reward knowing <strong>safety vs security</strong> tension: availability may trump confidentiality; testing must avoid breaking physical processes.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L5-01: Zero Trust Architecture (NIST SP 800-207 themes)</em>:</strong> Penetration tests require <strong>written authorization</strong>, defined scope, and rules of engagement—even in internal labs for professional conduct.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L5-01: Zero Trust Architecture (NIST SP 800-207 themes)</em>:</strong> Deception tech is not a replacement for <strong>baselines and patching</strong>; it augments detection when mature processes exist.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L5-01: Zero Trust Architecture (NIST SP 800-207 themes)</em>:</strong> Risk decisions are economic: organizations <strong>accept</strong>, <strong>mitigate</strong>, <strong>transfer</strong> (insurance, outsourcing with contracts), or <strong>avoid</strong> (stop the activity). Controls change likelihood or impact; residual risk should be explicit, not invisible.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L5-01: Zero Trust Architecture (NIST SP 800-207 themes)</em>:</strong> Patching and change management appear as <strong>risk tradeoffs</strong>: emergency patches vs testing rings; compensating monitoring when patching lags; and documenting exceptions for auditors.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L5-01: Zero Trust Architecture (NIST SP 800-207 themes)</em>:</strong> Container escape questions hinge on <strong>kernel boundary</strong> and misconfigured capabilities—namespaces are helpful but not a complete trust boundary without seccomp, AppArmor, and least-privileged service accounts.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L5-01: Zero Trust Architecture (NIST SP 800-207 themes)</em>:</strong> API keys in mobile apps are often extractable—prefer <strong>short-lived tokens</strong> and server-mediated access to backends.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L5-01: Zero Trust Architecture (NIST SP 800-207 themes)</em>:</strong> TPM-backed BitLocker keys illustrate <strong>key protection</strong> binding to platform state—recovery keys must be guarded like crown jewels.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L5-01: Zero Trust Architecture (NIST SP 800-207 themes)</em>:</strong> Vulnerability management is a lifecycle: scanners find candidates, analysts prioritize with exploitability and business context, owners remediate, and verification closes the loop. “Patch everything immediately” is rarely operational; <strong>risk-based SLAs</strong> are the adult answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L5-01: Zero Trust Architecture (NIST SP 800-207 themes)</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> An engineer wants emergency access to production to debug “L5-01: Zero Trust Architecture (NIST SP 800-207 themes)” during change freeze. Outline <strong>break-glass</strong> steps: who approves, how sessions are recorded, and how credentials are rotated after.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l5-02":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L5-02: Microsegmentation vs macro firewalling</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-02</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Identity-based L4/L7 policy; east-west visibility.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Compare two vendor reference architectures in bullets (no endorsement).</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-02</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Architecture tradeoff prompts want <strong>explicit assumptions</strong>—availability vs cost vs complexity, stated cleanly.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 5 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Defense in depth</strong></dt><dd>Layered controls so one failure does not equal total failure—network, host, app, identity, and monitoring each contribute.</dd><dt><strong>Asymmetric encryption</strong></dt><dd>Key pairs for key agreement/signing—RSA/ECC; hybrid TLS uses asymmetric to establish symmetric session keys.</dd><dt><strong>XSS</strong></dt><dd>Cross-site scripting injects script in a victim context—CSP, output encoding, HttpOnly cookies, and DOM hygiene reduce blast radius.</dd><dt><strong>MITRE ATT&amp;CK</strong></dt><dd>Tactics (why) and techniques (how) adversaries operate—use for detection engineering, gap analysis, and purple team scenarios.</dd><dt><strong>GRC</strong></dt><dd>Governance, risk, and compliance—align security decisions with law, policy, and business appetite; audits test design and operation.</dd><dt><strong>PQC</strong></dt><dd>Post-quantum cryptography migration—hybrid schemes and crypto-agility for long-lived secrets exposed to harvest-now/decrypt-later risk.</dd><dt><strong>Need to know</strong></dt><dd>Finer than least privilege for data—access only to the minimum subset required for the current task.</dd><dt><strong>Collision (hash)</strong></dt><dd>Two inputs produce same hash—breaks integrity assumptions; choose strong hash families for security use.</dd><dt><strong>WAF vs IPS</strong></dt><dd>WAF focuses on application-layer attacks; IPS often line-rate network signatures—overlap exists but priorities differ.</dd><dt><strong>Kill chain / cyber kill chain</strong></dt><dd>Stages of intrusion—mapping controls and detections to stages clarifies coverage gaps.</dd><dt><strong>Threat</strong></dt><dd>Any circumstance or actor with the potential to cause harm by exploiting a vulnerability (malware, insider, natural disaster).</dd><dt><strong>Availability</strong></dt><dd>Assures timely and reliable access—redundancy, patching, DDoS defenses, and DR planning keep services usable for authorized users.</dd><dt><strong>Session management</strong></dt><dd>Server-side session IDs or tokens must rotate on privilege change, bind to channel, and expire predictably.</dd><dt><strong>Zero Trust (headline)</strong></dt><dd>Assume breach; verify explicitly per request using identity, device posture, and least privilege—not “trust the LAN.”</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>IR phase</th><th>What you do there (exam shorthand)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Prepare</strong></td><td>Playbooks, contacts, tooling, baseline logging—before the pager fires.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detect &amp; analyze</strong></td><td>Scope, timelines, hypotheses—preserve volatile evidence early.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Contain</strong></td><td>Stop spread with minimal evidence damage—network isolation variants matter.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Eradicate &amp; recover</strong></td><td>Remove persistence, patch root cause, restore with verification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Lessons learned</strong></td><td>Metrics, control changes, and communication improvements—close the loop.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>Split tunnel VPN can exfil corporate data outside inspection if misconfigured—policy and routing matter.</li><li>Azure AD / Entra conditional access is analogous to risk-based policies—device compliance signals matter.</li><li>OAuth access tokens are not a replacement for server-side authorization checks on every sensitive action.</li><li>DNS over HTTPS changes visibility for some networks—understand resolver policy and logging tradeoffs.</li><li>GCP service account keys are long-lived secrets—prefer workload identity federation from CI where possible.</li><li>SameSite=Lax blocks many CSRF POSTs from cross-site contexts in modern browsers—know the nuance vs Strict.</li><li>Certificate pinning misconfigurations can brick apps—plan rotation and emergency releases.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L5-02: Microsegmentation vs macro firewalling</em>:</strong> Patching and change management appear as <strong>risk tradeoffs</strong>: emergency patches vs testing rings; compensating monitoring when patching lags; and documenting exceptions for auditors.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L5-02: Microsegmentation vs macro firewalling</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L5-02: Microsegmentation vs macro firewalling</em>:</strong> Multicloud complexity increases <strong>identity sprawl</strong>; centralized IdP and consistent conditional access policies reduce human error.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L5-02: Microsegmentation vs macro firewalling</em>:</strong> Wireless assessments should mention <strong>rogue AP</strong> discovery, client isolation, and guest segmentation—not just “use WPA2” as a slogan. Exam writers like the distinction between personal and enterprise authentication modes at a conceptual level.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L5-02: Microsegmentation vs macro firewalling</em>:</strong> Cryptography questions reward vocabulary precision: hashing vs encryption vs encoding; symmetric vs asymmetric roles in TLS; what signatures prove; and why key management is usually harder than picking an algorithm. If an answer sounds magical, it is probably wrong.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L5-02: Microsegmentation vs macro firewalling</em>:</strong> RADIUS is still referenced for <strong>network access control</strong> integrations; know it as a AAA component in enterprise Wi-Fi contexts.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L5-02: Microsegmentation vs macro firewalling</em>:</strong> Serverless cold start is not a security control; <strong>per-function IAM</strong> and least-privilege API scopes are. Watch for attractive nonsense distractors tied to performance tuning.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L5-02: Microsegmentation vs macro firewalling</em>:</strong> Logging questions often test whether you understand <strong>what to log</strong> (who, what, when, where, outcome), <strong>time sync</strong> for correlation, and <strong>tamper resistance</strong> for evidentiary value—not whether you can collect infinite bytes.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L5-02: Microsegmentation vs macro firewalling</em>:</strong> TPM-backed BitLocker keys illustrate <strong>key protection</strong> binding to platform state—recovery keys must be guarded like crown jewels.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L5-02: Microsegmentation vs macro firewalling</em>:</strong> DAST exercises running apps but misses authz logic without credentials; combine with <strong>manual review</strong> for business-rule flaws.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> An engineer wants emergency access to production to debug “L5-02: Microsegmentation vs macro firewalling” during change freeze. Outline <strong>break-glass</strong> steps: who approves, how sessions are recorded, and how credentials are rotated after.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l5-03":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L5-03: mTLS everywhere — operational costs</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-03</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Cert rotation, SPIFFE/SPIRE idea.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>openssl req -x509 -newkey rsa:2048 -keyout key.pem -out cert.pem -days 30 -nodes -subj &quot;/CN=lab&quot;</code> — <strong>lab only</strong>; describe rotation calendar.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-03</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Zero Trust answers should emphasize <strong>continuous verification</strong> and <strong>policy enforcement points</strong>, not removing all network security.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 5 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Shared responsibility model</strong></dt><dd>Cloud provider secures the platform; customer secures configuration, identities, data, and app code in their scope.</dd><dt><strong>Mandatory vacation</strong></dt><dd>Forces handover and review of another employee’s work—can uncover fraud or backdoors.</dd><dt><strong>RPO / RTO recap</strong></dt><dd>RPO = max acceptable data loss time; RTO = max acceptable outage—drive backup frequency and HA design.</dd><dt><strong>Control</strong></dt><dd>Administrative, technical, or physical safeguards that reduce likelihood or impact of a security event (prevent, detect, correct).</dd><dt><strong>SPF / DKIM / DMARC</strong></dt><dd>Email authenticity stack—SPF authorizes senders, DKIM signs messages, DMARC aligns policies and reporting for abuse handling.</dd><dt><strong>IR phases</strong></dt><dd>Prepare, detect, analyze, contain, eradicate, recover, and lessons learned—legal hold and evidence integrity matter throughout.</dd><dt><strong>Separation of duties (SoD)</strong></dt><dd>No single person can complete a sensitive transaction alone—classic finance control that also limits insider abuse.</dd><dt><strong>Sinkhole (routing)</strong></dt><dd>Different meaning in BGP—be careful with homonyms on exams; read the stem’s context.</dd><dt><strong>Vulnerability</strong></dt><dd>A weakness in design, implementation, configuration, or process that could be exploited to violate a security policy.</dd><dt><strong>DNS</strong></dt><dd>Name resolution is a trust anchor—DNSSEC, cache poisoning, and malicious resolutions are classic abuse paths; log resolver anomalies.</dd><dt><strong>SIEM</strong></dt><dd>Security information and event management—centralize logs, parse fields, correlate alerts; tuning reduces false positives and fatigue.</dd><dt><strong>Business continuity testing</strong></dt><dd>Tabletops and technical failover drills reveal gaps in comms, dependencies, and vendor SLAs.</dd><dt><strong>NetFlow / IPFIX</strong></dt><dd>Flow metadata for volume and anomaly detection—lighter than PCAP but less payload visibility.</dd><dt><strong>Asset</strong></dt><dd>Anything of value to the organization—data, systems, people, reputation, or services—that security controls protect.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li><li>OAuth access tokens are not a replacement for server-side authorization checks on every sensitive action.</li><li>Terraform state can hold secrets—remote secure backend and scanning are baseline hygiene.</li><li>JWT alg:none historical vulnerability class—always validate algorithm and signature keys explicitly.</li><li>EPSS (concept) scores exploitation probability—useful alongside CVSS for prioritization in mature programs.</li><li>AES-128 is not “half as strong” as AES-256 in practical threat models for many cases—key management quality dominates.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li><li>Immutable backups mitigate ransomware that tries to delete online copies—air-gapped or WORM patterns.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L5-03: mTLS everywhere — operational costs</em>:</strong> API keys in mobile apps are often extractable—prefer <strong>short-lived tokens</strong> and server-mediated access to backends.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L5-03: mTLS everywhere — operational costs</em>:</strong> Virtualization risks include <strong>snapshot sprawl</strong> containing secrets and stale VM images drifting from hardened baselines.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L5-03: mTLS everywhere — operational costs</em>:</strong> Risk decisions are economic: organizations <strong>accept</strong>, <strong>mitigate</strong>, <strong>transfer</strong> (insurance, outsourcing with contracts), or <strong>avoid</strong> (stop the activity). Controls change likelihood or impact; residual risk should be explicit, not invisible.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L5-03: mTLS everywhere — operational costs</em>:</strong> Wireless and mobility items reward knowing basics: WPA3 improvements conceptually, evil twin risks, captive portals, and why client isolation matters on guest networks—without memorizing obsolete WEP details unless explicitly historical.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L5-03: mTLS everywhere — operational costs</em>:</strong> Industrial and OT adjacent questions reward knowing <strong>safety vs security</strong> tension: availability may trump confidentiality; testing must avoid breaking physical processes.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L5-03: mTLS everywhere — operational costs</em>:</strong> SAST finds issues early but produces false positives; <strong>triage workflows</strong> and developer feedback loops are part of a mature program, not “run tool once.”</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L5-03: mTLS everywhere — operational costs</em>:</strong> LDAP vs Active Directory questions test directory concepts at a high level—binding, searches, and secure transport (LDAPS) appear often.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L5-03: mTLS everywhere — operational costs</em>:</strong> Clean desk pairs with <strong>screen privacy</strong> and <strong>clear desk checks</strong> for regulated spaces—physical + procedural controls together.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L5-03: mTLS everywhere — operational costs</em>:</strong> Incident response questions probe containment vs evidence preservation tension, legal escalation, and communication discipline. The exam rewards knowing when to isolate systems, when to involve counsel, and why mass log deletion is catastrophic.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L5-03: mTLS everywhere — operational costs</em>:</strong> Data handling questions often hinge on <strong>classification</strong>, <strong>least data</strong>, and <strong>retention</strong>: collect only what you need, keep it only as long as allowed, and destroy securely when done.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> You are the on-call analyst reviewing an alert tied to “L5-03: mTLS everywhere — operational costs”. Leadership wants a <strong>60-second</strong> brief: business impact, evidence gaps, and the <strong>first</strong> containment step that preserves logs. No tool-specific jargon—prioritize scope, evidence, blast radius, then root-cause remediation under change control.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l5-04":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L5-04: Post-quantum cryptography (PQC) migration planning</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-04</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Harvest-now-decrypt-later; hybrid schemes.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Read NIST PQC round summary; list 3 inventory fields apps must capture (cipher suite, protocol version, cert chain).</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-04</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Level 5 is Security+ <strong>advanced integration</strong>: Zero Trust themes, crypto agility, architecture tradeoffs, and ethical offensive work. Even advanced stems still reduce to least privilege, segmentation, logging, and tested recovery.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 5 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Sinkhole (DNS)</strong></dt><dd>Controlled resolution for malicious domains—intel and disruption technique with legal process considerations.</dd><dt><strong>Privacy</strong></dt><dd>Protection of personal information and individual rights—overlaps with security but adds legal/regulatory obligations (GDPR-style).</dd><dt><strong>CWE</strong></dt><dd>Common Weakness Enumeration—taxonomy of software weakness types that help root-cause fixes beyond one CVE instance.</dd><dt><strong>CRL</strong></dt><dd>Certificate Revocation List—signed list of revoked serials; size/latency issues drove OCSP adoption.</dd><dt><strong>Security control categories</strong></dt><dd>Technical (firewalls, encryption), administrative (policies, training), and physical (badges, locks)—exam items often ask which category fits a scenario.</dd><dt><strong>Hashing</strong></dt><dd>One-way fingerprint for integrity verification—SHA-256 family; not secrecy; used with HMAC for keyed integrity.</dd><dt><strong>PQC</strong></dt><dd>Post-quantum cryptography migration—hybrid schemes and crypto-agility for long-lived secrets exposed to harvest-now/decrypt-later risk.</dd><dt><strong>Diamond model</strong></dt><dd>Adversary, infrastructure, capability, victim—useful for pivoting investigations and intel fusion.</dd><dt><strong>Password policy</strong></dt><dd>Modern guidance favors long passphrases, breach-banned lists, and vaults over rotation-for-its-own-sake complexity theater.</dd><dt><strong>IAM least privilege</strong></dt><dd>Grant minimum API/console rights; prefer roles over long-lived keys; audit risky admin-equivalent paths regularly.</dd><dt><strong>IV / nonce</strong></dt><dd>Initialization vector or number-used-once—must be unique per encryption under a key for many modes.</dd><dt><strong>Control</strong></dt><dd>Administrative, technical, or physical safeguards that reduce likelihood or impact of a security event (prevent, detect, correct).</dd><dt><strong>Security misconfiguration</strong></dt><dd>Default creds, debug features on in prod, verbose errors, open directory listings—hardening baselines and drift detection reduce this class.</dd><dt><strong>SOC triage order</strong></dt><dd>Scope → impact → evidence → containment hypothesis; avoid fixing symptoms before you know blast radius.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>GCP service account keys are long-lived secrets—prefer workload identity federation from CI where possible.</li><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li><li>SameSite=Lax blocks many CSRF POSTs from cross-site contexts in modern browsers—know the nuance vs Strict.</li><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li><li>Certificate pinning misconfigurations can brick apps—plan rotation and emergency releases.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li><li>Terraform state can hold secrets—remote secure backend and scanning are baseline hygiene.</li><li>UDP-based protocols can be abused for amplification DDoS—patch open resolvers and monitor volumetric baselines.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L5-04: Post-quantum cryptography (PQC) migration planning</em>:</strong> Governance and awareness questions tie policy to behavior: acceptable use, clean desk, travel security, and vendor due diligence. Pick answers that reduce <strong>realistic</strong> human failure modes, not answers that maximize surveillance without process support.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L5-04: Post-quantum cryptography (PQC) migration planning</em>:</strong> Deception tech is not a replacement for <strong>baselines and patching</strong>; it augments detection when mature processes exist.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L5-04: Post-quantum cryptography (PQC) migration planning</em>:</strong> KMS keys are not “magic secrecy dust”—<strong>who can invoke decrypt</strong> and from which contexts (VPC endpoint policies, IAM conditions) is what exams probe.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L5-04: Post-quantum cryptography (PQC) migration planning</em>:</strong> Advanced topics still return to fundamentals: least privilege, segmentation, logging, and tested recovery. When you see Zero Trust or PQC buzzwords, map them back to concrete controls and threat models rather than treating them as magic shields.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L5-04: Post-quantum cryptography (PQC) migration planning</em>:</strong> Air gapped networks still need <strong>patching via sneaker-net</strong> and insider controls—physical isolation is not logical isolation.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L5-04: Post-quantum cryptography (PQC) migration planning</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L5-04: Post-quantum cryptography (PQC) migration planning</em>:</strong> Logging questions often test whether you understand <strong>what to log</strong> (who, what, when, where, outcome), <strong>time sync</strong> for correlation, and <strong>tamper resistance</strong> for evidentiary value—not whether you can collect infinite bytes.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L5-04: Post-quantum cryptography (PQC) migration planning</em>:</strong> Virtualization risks include <strong>snapshot sprawl</strong> containing secrets and stale VM images drifting from hardened baselines.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L5-04: Post-quantum cryptography (PQC) migration planning</em>:</strong> Ransomware stems often pair encryption with <strong>exfiltration</strong>—the correct answer may include legal/notification obligations, not only restoring from backup.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L5-04: Post-quantum cryptography (PQC) migration planning</em>:</strong> Access control stems frequently mix <strong>role</strong> vs <strong>attribute</strong> vs <strong>rule</strong> models; pick the answer that matches the scenario’s constraints (temporary contractor, cross-department data, dynamic tags on resources).</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> An engineer wants emergency access to production to debug “L5-04: Post-quantum cryptography (PQC) migration planning” during change freeze. Outline <strong>break-glass</strong> steps: who approves, how sessions are recorded, and how credentials are rotated after.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l5-05":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L5-05: Advanced TLS attacks (downgrade, Renegotiation, ROBOT — concept)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-05</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Why modern TLS configs ban old protocols.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>nmap --script ssl-enum-ciphers -p 443 example.com</code> only if <strong>permitted</strong>; else annotate sample output explaining risk ranking.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-05</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>When buzzwords appear (PQC, confidential computing), translate them into <strong>concrete threats and controls</strong> before selecting an answer.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 5 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Firewall</strong></dt><dd>Enforces allow/deny rules on traffic—stateful inspection tracks sessions; default-deny with explicit permits is the secure baseline.</dd><dt><strong>Serverless blast radius</strong></dt><dd>One broad execution role affects every invocation—scope IAM per function and watch environment variable leaks.</dd><dt><strong>Diffie-Hellman (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Key agreement over insecure channel—combine with authentication to prevent MITM.</dd><dt><strong>Privacy</strong></dt><dd>Protection of personal information and individual rights—overlaps with security but adds legal/regulatory obligations (GDPR-style).</dd><dt><strong>CVE</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures identifier for a specific flaw—pairs with CVSS severity and vendor advisories for prioritization.</dd><dt><strong>Replay attack</strong></dt><dd>Valid data maliciously re-sent—nonces, timestamps, and session freshness mitigate.</dd><dt><strong>Threat</strong></dt><dd>Any circumstance or actor with the potential to cause harm by exploiting a vulnerability (malware, insider, natural disaster).</dd><dt><strong>PKI</strong></dt><dd>Public Key Infrastructure—CAs, RAs, CRL/OCSP, and certificate lifecycle; mis-issuance or weak validation breaks trust chains.</dd><dt><strong>PQC</strong></dt><dd>Post-quantum cryptography migration—hybrid schemes and crypto-agility for long-lived secrets exposed to harvest-now/decrypt-later risk.</dd><dt><strong>MTTD / MTTR</strong></dt><dd>Mean time to detect / remediate—quality matters; gaming metrics by closing tickets inflates false success.</dd><dt><strong>Defense in depth</strong></dt><dd>Layered controls so one failure does not equal total failure—network, host, app, identity, and monitoring each contribute.</dd><dt><strong>Container security</strong></dt><dd>Image provenance, non-root users, read-only roots, seccomp/AppArmor, and admission control for risky capabilities.</dd><dt><strong>HMAC</strong></dt><dd>Keyed hash construction—common for API authenticity when symmetric secret is shared out-of-band.</dd><dt><strong>Non-repudiation</strong></dt><dd>Prevents a party from credibly denying an action—digital signatures, tamper-evident logs, and time-stamping support it.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Typical exam angle</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Confidentiality</strong></td><td>Who may read? Encryption, ACLs, DLP, classification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Integrity</strong></td><td>Was it modified? Hashing, signatures, change control, backups.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Availability</strong></td><td>Can authorized users work? HA, patching windows, DDoS defense, DR.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authenticity / non-repudiation</strong></td><td>Prove source and intent—signatures, strong issuance, tamper-evident logs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>AES-128 is not “half as strong” as AES-256 in practical threat models for many cases—key management quality dominates.</li><li>SBOM formats (CycloneDX/SPDX) help inventory components for incident response and licensing—not only security.</li><li>KMS key policies can deny even root in AWS when configured—explicit deny wins.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li><li>GraphQL batching can amplify complexity attacks—depth and cost limits are first-class controls.</li><li>DNS over HTTPS changes visibility for some networks—understand resolver policy and logging tradeoffs.</li><li>Immutable backups mitigate ransomware that tries to delete online copies—air-gapped or WORM patterns.</li><li>ATT&CK technique IDs are stable references for detection content—good for purple team reporting.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L5-05: Advanced TLS attacks (downgrade, Renegotiation, ROBOT — concept)</em>:</strong> Third-party and supply chain answers should emphasize <strong>contracts</strong>, <strong>evidence</strong>, and <strong>continuous monitoring</strong>—not “trust the SOC 2 logo” without scope review.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L5-05: Advanced TLS attacks (downgrade, Renegotiation, ROBOT — concept)</em>:</strong> For the Security+ mindset, translate every control into <strong>who</strong> it protects, <strong>what</strong> asset is at risk, and <strong>how</strong> you would detect failure. Interview and exam items often reward practical prioritization over buzzwords—choose the mitigation that reduces realistic loss first.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L5-05: Advanced TLS attacks (downgrade, Renegotiation, ROBOT — concept)</em>:</strong> API keys in mobile apps are often extractable—prefer <strong>short-lived tokens</strong> and server-mediated access to backends.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L5-05: Advanced TLS attacks (downgrade, Renegotiation, ROBOT — concept)</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L5-05: Advanced TLS attacks (downgrade, Renegotiation, ROBOT — concept)</em>:</strong> Application security scenarios often test whether you know <strong>where</strong> enforcement belongs—browser controls supplement but do not replace server-side checks. SameSite cookies, CSP, and HttpOnly mitigate classes of issues; they do not fix broken object-level authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L5-05: Advanced TLS attacks (downgrade, Renegotiation, ROBOT — concept)</em>:</strong> TACACS+ vs RADIUS separation of duties in device admin access—exams may contrast accounting granularity.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L5-05: Advanced TLS attacks (downgrade, Renegotiation, ROBOT — concept)</em>:</strong> KMS keys are not “magic secrecy dust”—<strong>who can invoke decrypt</strong> and from which contexts (VPC endpoint policies, IAM conditions) is what exams probe.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L5-05: Advanced TLS attacks (downgrade, Renegotiation, ROBOT — concept)</em>:</strong> Access control stems frequently mix <strong>role</strong> vs <strong>attribute</strong> vs <strong>rule</strong> models; pick the answer that matches the scenario’s constraints (temporary contractor, cross-department data, dynamic tags on resources).</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L5-05: Advanced TLS attacks (downgrade, Renegotiation, ROBOT — concept)</em>:</strong> Sanitization vs wiping vs destruction: exams like knowing which media needs <strong>degaussing, shredding, or crypto erase</strong> per policy.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L5-05: Advanced TLS attacks (downgrade, Renegotiation, ROBOT — concept)</em>:</strong> Penetration tests require <strong>written authorization</strong>, defined scope, and rules of engagement—even in internal labs for professional conduct.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> A vendor integration project mentions “L5-05: Advanced TLS attacks (downgrade, Renegotiation, ROBOT — concept)” as out-of-scope for pen testing. Explain what <strong>residual risk</strong> remains, what <strong>compensating monitoring</strong> you would demand, and how you would <strong>document acceptance</strong>.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l5-06":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L5-06: Padding oracle / CBC misuse (developer-facing)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-06</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Authenticated encryption (AES-GCM, ChaCha20-Poly1305).<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Pseudocode showing encrypt-then-MAC vs AEAD; one paragraph on why MAC-then-encrypt is fragile.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-06</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Modern crypto stems may reference <strong>harvest-now/decrypt-later</strong>—think inventory of secret longevity and hybrid transitions.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 5 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Authorization</strong></dt><dd>What an authenticated subject is allowed to do—RBAC/ABAC, scopes, and server-side checks enforce least privilege.</dd><dt><strong>NAT (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Rewrites addresses/ports for traversal—security relevance includes logging visibility, port forwarding risks, and split tunnel implications for inspection.</dd><dt><strong>SPF / DKIM / DMARC</strong></dt><dd>Email authenticity stack—SPF authorizes senders, DKIM signs messages, DMARC aligns policies and reporting for abuse handling.</dd><dt><strong>Hashing</strong></dt><dd>One-way fingerprint for integrity verification—SHA-256 family; not secrecy; used with HMAC for keyed integrity.</dd><dt><strong>Security misconfiguration</strong></dt><dd>Default creds, debug features on in prod, verbose errors, open directory listings—hardening baselines and drift detection reduce this class.</dd><dt><strong>Secure SDLC</strong></dt><dd>Requirements, threat modeling, secure design, code review, SAST/DAST, dependency scanning, and hardened deployment pipelines.</dd><dt><strong>MITRE ATT&amp;CK</strong></dt><dd>Tactics (why) and techniques (how) adversaries operate—use for detection engineering, gap analysis, and purple team scenarios.</dd><dt><strong>Encryption at rest / in transit</strong></dt><dd>KMS/HSM-backed keys, envelope encryption, and TLS everywhere for administrative and user paths.</dd><dt><strong>Security awareness</strong></dt><dd>Training plus culture—measure reporting rates, not shame metrics; phishing simulations should reinforce reporting.</dd><dt><strong>Zero Trust architecture</strong></dt><dd>Identity-centric access with continuous verification—policy enforcement points for users, devices, and workloads.</dd><dt><strong>Business continuity testing</strong></dt><dd>Tabletops and technical failover drills reveal gaps in comms, dependencies, and vendor SLAs.</dd><dt><strong>Token replay</strong></dt><dd>Reusing a stolen token/session artifact—rotation, binding, and short TTLs reduce window.</dd><dt><strong>PBKDF2 / Argon2 (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Key derivation functions that slow brute force—work factors must track attacker economics.</dd><dt><strong>HMAC</strong></dt><dd>Keyed hash construction—common for API authenticity when symmetric secret is shared out-of-band.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>AEAD</strong></td><td>Confidentiality + integrity together—misuse of IV/nonce still breaks security.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>ISO 27001 is an ISMS standard; it emphasizes risk treatment and continual improvement, not a product checklist.</li><li>Immutable backups mitigate ransomware that tries to delete online copies—air-gapped or WORM patterns.</li><li>Admission controllers can block privileged pods—policy-as-code integrates with GitOps reviews.</li><li>UDP-based protocols can be abused for amplification DDoS—patch open resolvers and monitor volumetric baselines.</li><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li><li>AES-128 is not “half as strong” as AES-256 in practical threat models for many cases—key management quality dominates.</li><li>ATT&CK technique IDs are stable references for detection content—good for purple team reporting.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L5-06: Padding oracle / CBC misuse (developer-facing)</em>:</strong> CSP reporting helps tune policy but can leak URLs—<strong>privacy review</strong> of report endpoints matters in regulated environments.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L5-06: Padding oracle / CBC misuse (developer-facing)</em>:</strong> Social engineering callbacks to <strong>pretexting</strong>, <strong>baiting</strong>, and <strong>vishing</strong>—name the subtype when the stem describes the tactic.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L5-06: Padding oracle / CBC misuse (developer-facing)</em>:</strong> Cloud items assume you can articulate <strong>shared responsibility</strong>: what the provider patches vs what the customer must configure (IAM, encryption, network exposure). Misconfiguration beats novel cloud exploits in real incidents and on the exam.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L5-06: Padding oracle / CBC misuse (developer-facing)</em>:</strong> Help desk scenarios test whether you know <strong>identity proofing</strong> vs <strong>account recovery</strong> abuse. The secure path verifies the human through out-of-band channels without teaching attackers how to bypass your process in the stem text.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L5-06: Padding oracle / CBC misuse (developer-facing)</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L5-06: Padding oracle / CBC misuse (developer-facing)</em>:</strong> RADIUS is still referenced for <strong>network access control</strong> integrations; know it as a AAA component in enterprise Wi-Fi contexts.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L5-06: Padding oracle / CBC misuse (developer-facing)</em>:</strong> Controls fail in three predictable ways: <strong>misconfiguration</strong>, <strong>missing coverage</strong> (gaps between tools), and <strong>human process</strong> breakdown (exceptions, shared accounts, emergency access). When you read a scenario, ask which failure mode is most plausible before picking an answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L5-06: Padding oracle / CBC misuse (developer-facing)</em>:</strong> Access control stems frequently mix <strong>role</strong> vs <strong>attribute</strong> vs <strong>rule</strong> models; pick the answer that matches the scenario’s constraints (temporary contractor, cross-department data, dynamic tags on resources).</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L5-06: Padding oracle / CBC misuse (developer-facing)</em>:</strong> Email security stems often combine SPF alignment failures with <strong>look-alike domains</strong>. The best answer addresses user training plus technical authenticity controls, not only one or the other.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L5-06: Padding oracle / CBC misuse (developer-facing)</em>:</strong> Tabletop exercises test <strong>comms trees</strong>, legal escalation, and customer notification templates—not only technical runbooks.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Marketing launches a campaign referencing “L5-06: Padding oracle / CBC misuse (developer-facing)” with a new subdomain. Security review finds DNS delegated to an unknown party. Explain <strong>trust chain</strong> risks and the <strong>minimum fixes</strong> before go-live.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l5-07":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L5-07: Side channels (timing, cache) — awareness</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-07</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Constant-time crypto need; Spectre/Meltdown class lessons.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Read a CVE summary; explain attacker model (local vs remote) in 5 sentences.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-07</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Advanced IR/intel questions still punish <strong>evidence destruction</strong> and <strong>unscoped testing</strong>—professional ethics are in scope.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 5 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Due diligence</strong></dt><dd>Investigation and verification before decisions (vendor risk, M&amp;A) to ensure claims about controls are credible.</dd><dt><strong>Kerberos (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Ticket-based enterprise auth—TGT vs service tickets; golden/silver ticket classes of abuse appear in advanced IR.</dd><dt><strong>PKI</strong></dt><dd>Public Key Infrastructure—CAs, RAs, CRL/OCSP, and certificate lifecycle; mis-issuance or weak validation breaks trust chains.</dd><dt><strong>Vulnerability management</strong></dt><dd>Discover, prioritize, remediate, verify, and report—SLAs differ by exposure, exploitability, and asset criticality.</dd><dt><strong>Insider threat</strong></dt><dd>Malicious or negligent insiders—monitor with proportionality, separation of duties, and HR/legal partnership.</dd><dt><strong>Mandatory vacation</strong></dt><dd>Forces handover and review of another employee’s work—can uncover fraud or backdoors.</dd><dt><strong>HMAC</strong></dt><dd>Keyed hash construction—common for API authenticity when symmetric secret is shared out-of-band.</dd><dt><strong>Kill chain / cyber kill chain</strong></dt><dd>Stages of intrusion—mapping controls and detections to stages clarifies coverage gaps.</dd><dt><strong>Security control categories</strong></dt><dd>Technical (firewalls, encryption), administrative (policies, training), and physical (badges, locks)—exam items often ask which category fits a scenario.</dd><dt><strong>Non-repudiation</strong></dt><dd>Prevents a party from credibly denying an action—digital signatures, tamper-evident logs, and time-stamping support it.</dd><dt><strong>DNS</strong></dt><dd>Name resolution is a trust anchor—DNSSEC, cache poisoning, and malicious resolutions are classic abuse paths; log resolver anomalies.</dd><dt><strong>OWASP Top 10</strong></dt><dd>High-prevalence web risks—broken access control and crypto failures often dominate; study each category with one workplace example.</dd><dt><strong>IAM least privilege</strong></dt><dd>Grant minimum API/console rights; prefer roles over long-lived keys; audit risky admin-equivalent paths regularly.</dd><dt><strong>Zero Trust architecture</strong></dt><dd>Identity-centric access with continuous verification—policy enforcement points for users, devices, and workloads.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>AEAD</strong></td><td>Confidentiality + integrity together—misuse of IV/nonce still breaks security.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li><li>Admission controllers can block privileged pods—policy-as-code integrates with GitOps reviews.</li><li>S3 bucket policies and ACLs layer with IAM—effective permissions require understanding intersection.</li><li>Azure AD / Entra conditional access is analogous to risk-based policies—device compliance signals matter.</li><li>Terraform state can hold secrets—remote secure backend and scanning are baseline hygiene.</li><li>SLSA levels describe increasing supply-chain assurance—useful vocabulary in modern governance questions.</li><li>Responsible disclosure timelines balance vendor patch readiness with public safety—coordinate, don’t surprise.</li><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L5-07: Side channels (timing, cache) — awareness</em>:</strong> Application security scenarios often test whether you know <strong>where</strong> enforcement belongs—browser controls supplement but do not replace server-side checks. SameSite cookies, CSP, and HttpOnly mitigate classes of issues; they do not fix broken object-level authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L5-07: Side channels (timing, cache) — awareness</em>:</strong> DAST exercises running apps but misses authz logic without credentials; combine with <strong>manual review</strong> for business-rule flaws.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L5-07: Side channels (timing, cache) — awareness</em>:</strong> Vulnerability management is a lifecycle: scanners find candidates, analysts prioritize with exploitability and business context, owners remediate, and verification closes the loop. “Patch everything immediately” is rarely operational; <strong>risk-based SLAs</strong> are the adult answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L5-07: Side channels (timing, cache) — awareness</em>:</strong> Penetration tests require <strong>written authorization</strong>, defined scope, and rules of engagement—even in internal labs for professional conduct.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L5-07: Side channels (timing, cache) — awareness</em>:</strong> Incident response questions probe containment vs evidence preservation tension, legal escalation, and communication discipline. The exam rewards knowing when to isolate systems, when to involve counsel, and why mass log deletion is catastrophic.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L5-07: Side channels (timing, cache) — awareness</em>:</strong> Tabletop exercises test <strong>comms trees</strong>, legal escalation, and customer notification templates—not only technical runbooks.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L5-07: Side channels (timing, cache) — awareness</em>:</strong> Cloud items assume you can articulate <strong>shared responsibility</strong>: what the provider patches vs what the customer must configure (IAM, encryption, network exposure). Misconfiguration beats novel cloud exploits in real incidents and on the exam.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L5-07: Side channels (timing, cache) — awareness</em>:</strong> Evidence bags and write blockers signal <strong>forensics awareness</strong>; touching disks before imaging is a classic wrong answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L5-07: Side channels (timing, cache) — awareness</em>:</strong> Governance and awareness questions tie policy to behavior: acceptable use, clean desk, travel security, and vendor due diligence. Pick answers that reduce <strong>realistic</strong> human failure modes, not answers that maximize surveillance without process support.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L5-07: Side channels (timing, cache) — awareness</em>:</strong> Multicloud complexity increases <strong>identity sprawl</strong>; centralized IdP and consistent conditional access policies reduce human error.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Purple team wants to simulate abuse of “L5-07: Side channels (timing, cache) — awareness” next Friday. List <strong>safety gates</strong> (scope, rollback, monitoring) you require before authorizing the exercise.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l5-08":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L5-08: TPM 2.0, measured boot, BitLocker/ LUKS interaction</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-08</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Sealing keys to PCRs; anti-tamper chain.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>systemd-cryptenroll --help 2&gt;/dev/null | head</code> or read docs; note TPM token enrollment.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-08</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Level 5 is Security+ <strong>advanced integration</strong>: Zero Trust themes, crypto agility, architecture tradeoffs, and ethical offensive work. Even advanced stems still reduce to least privilege, segmentation, logging, and tested recovery.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 5 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Supply chain security</strong></dt><dd>SBOM, provenance signing (SLSA-style thinking), and dependency pinning reduce “update from upstream” surprises.</dd><dt><strong>BGP prefix hijack</strong></dt><dd>Unauthorized route advertisement—RPKI ROV reduces impact but does not replace monitoring.</dd><dt><strong>Data classification</strong></dt><dd>Labels (public, internal, confidential, restricted) drive storage, encryption, sharing, and disposal requirements.</dd><dt><strong>SIEM</strong></dt><dd>Security information and event management—centralize logs, parse fields, correlate alerts; tuning reduces false positives and fatigue.</dd><dt><strong>PBKDF2 / Argon2 (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Key derivation functions that slow brute force—work factors must track attacker economics.</dd><dt><strong>Quantitative vs qualitative risk</strong></dt><dd>Qualitative uses scales (high/medium/low); quantitative uses dollar or probability estimates—both need consistent assumptions and reviewer judgment.</dd><dt><strong>PKI</strong></dt><dd>Public Key Infrastructure—CAs, RAs, CRL/OCSP, and certificate lifecycle; mis-issuance or weak validation breaks trust chains.</dd><dt><strong>Threat modeling (STRIDE)</strong></dt><dd>Spoofing, tampering, repudiation, information disclosure, denial of service, elevation of privilege—drive controls early.</dd><dt><strong>IOC</strong></dt><dd>Indicator of compromise—often ephemeral (IPs, domains); pair with TTP-based detections for durability.</dd><dt><strong>SSO</strong></dt><dd>Single sign-on federates trust to an IdP—misconfigured SAML/OIDC trusts are high-impact; validate metadata and signing keys.</dd><dt><strong>Misconfiguration</strong></dt><dd>Top cloud incident driver—public buckets, open security groups, permissive trust policies; IaC scanning catches drift early.</dd><dt><strong>HMAC</strong></dt><dd>Keyed hash construction—common for API authenticity when symmetric secret is shared out-of-band.</dd><dt><strong>Residual risk</strong></dt><dd>Risk remaining after controls are applied; organizations accept, transfer, mitigate, or avoid it explicitly.</dd><dt><strong>Injection</strong></dt><dd>Untrusted input becomes part of a command or query—parameterized queries, input validation, and context escaping are core defenses.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>S3 bucket policies and ACLs layer with IAM—effective permissions require understanding intersection.</li><li>Certificate pinning misconfigurations can brick apps—plan rotation and emergency releases.</li><li>EPSS (concept) scores exploitation probability—useful alongside CVSS for prioritization in mature programs.</li><li>UDP-based protocols can be abused for amplification DDoS—patch open resolvers and monitor volumetric baselines.</li><li>KMS key policies can deny even root in AWS when configured—explicit deny wins.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>ATT&CK technique IDs are stable references for detection content—good for purple team reporting.</li><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L5-08: TPM 2.0, measured boot, BitLocker/ LUKS interaction</em>:</strong> BIOS/UEFI passwords and secure boot reduce some pre-boot attacks but do not stop <strong>evil maid</strong> classes without additional controls.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L5-08: TPM 2.0, measured boot, BitLocker/ LUKS interaction</em>:</strong> Serverless cold start is not a security control; <strong>per-function IAM</strong> and least-privilege API scopes are. Watch for attractive nonsense distractors tied to performance tuning.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L5-08: TPM 2.0, measured boot, BitLocker/ LUKS interaction</em>:</strong> Application security scenarios often test whether you know <strong>where</strong> enforcement belongs—browser controls supplement but do not replace server-side checks. SameSite cookies, CSP, and HttpOnly mitigate classes of issues; they do not fix broken object-level authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L5-08: TPM 2.0, measured boot, BitLocker/ LUKS interaction</em>:</strong> GraphQL introspection risk is about <strong>schema discovery</strong> aiding attackers—rate limits, authz on fields, and disabling introspection in prod are common answers.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L5-08: TPM 2.0, measured boot, BitLocker/ LUKS interaction</em>:</strong> Data handling questions often hinge on <strong>classification</strong>, <strong>least data</strong>, and <strong>retention</strong>: collect only what you need, keep it only as long as allowed, and destroy securely when done.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L5-08: TPM 2.0, measured boot, BitLocker/ LUKS interaction</em>:</strong> Sanitization vs wiping vs destruction: exams like knowing which media needs <strong>degaussing, shredding, or crypto erase</strong> per policy.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L5-08: TPM 2.0, measured boot, BitLocker/ LUKS interaction</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L5-08: TPM 2.0, measured boot, BitLocker/ LUKS interaction</em>:</strong> Incident response questions probe containment vs evidence preservation tension, legal escalation, and communication discipline. The exam rewards knowing when to isolate systems, when to involve counsel, and why mass log deletion is catastrophic.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L5-08: TPM 2.0, measured boot, BitLocker/ LUKS interaction</em>:</strong> Subresource integrity protects against <strong>CDN compromise</strong> but requires operational discipline when vendors rotate files.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L5-08: TPM 2.0, measured boot, BitLocker/ LUKS interaction</em>:</strong> Engineers often optimize for speed; attackers optimize for <strong>cheap reuse</strong> of stolen creds and known exploits. The winning answer bridges both: ship fast with guardrails—feature flags, staged rollouts, and automated security checks in CI.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Purple team wants to simulate abuse of “L5-08: TPM 2.0, measured boot, BitLocker/ LUKS interaction” next Friday. List <strong>safety gates</strong> (scope, rollback, monitoring) you require before authorizing the exercise.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l5-09":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L5-09: Confidential computing (TEEs, attestation)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-09</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Threat model: cloud provider admin vs workload.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> 10-line comparison: SGX-style vs SEV-style trust boundaries (high level).</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-09</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>When buzzwords appear (PQC, confidential computing), translate them into <strong>concrete threats and controls</strong> before selecting an answer.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 5 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>CSRF</strong></dt><dd>Cross-site request forgery rides ambient auth—anti-CSRF tokens, SameSite cookies, and re-auth for sensitive actions help.</dd><dt><strong>Zero Trust architecture</strong></dt><dd>Identity-centric access with continuous verification—policy enforcement points for users, devices, and workloads.</dd><dt><strong>Port knocking (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Obscurity-based pre-auth to open firewall—weak alone; exam may present as non-primary control.</dd><dt><strong>Quantitative vs qualitative risk</strong></dt><dd>Qualitative uses scales (high/medium/low); quantitative uses dollar or probability estimates—both need consistent assumptions and reviewer judgment.</dd><dt><strong>TLS</strong></dt><dd>Encrypts data in motion and authenticates endpoints when certificates and hostnames are validated; termination points affect trust boundaries.</dd><dt><strong>MITRE ATT&amp;CK</strong></dt><dd>Tactics (why) and techniques (how) adversaries operate—use for detection engineering, gap analysis, and purple team scenarios.</dd><dt><strong>Job rotation</strong></dt><dd>Reduces collusion and fraud risk; also surfaces “tribal knowledge” silos before an employee leaves.</dd><dt><strong>Warm site / cold site</strong></dt><dd>Warm has partial hardware ready; cold is space only—cost vs recovery speed tradeoff.</dd><dt><strong>Policy vs standard vs procedure</strong></dt><dd>Policy states intent; standards define mandatory requirements; procedures are step-by-step how-to for operators.</dd><dt><strong>Hashing</strong></dt><dd>One-way fingerprint for integrity verification—SHA-256 family; not secrecy; used with HMAC for keyed integrity.</dd><dt><strong>CASB / SaaS governance</strong></dt><dd>Visibility and policy for sanctioned vs shadow SaaS—OAuth consent attacks and guest sharing are common gaps.</dd><dt><strong>Salt (crypto)</strong></dt><dd>Random input to a password hash to defeat rainbow tables—must be unique per password.</dd><dt><strong>Right to be forgotten (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Privacy request to delete data—may conflict with legal hold; counsel resolves precedence.</dd><dt><strong>Authorization</strong></dt><dd>What an authenticated subject is allowed to do—RBAC/ABAC, scopes, and server-side checks enforce least privilege.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li><li>DNS over HTTPS changes visibility for some networks—understand resolver policy and logging tradeoffs.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>GraphQL batching can amplify complexity attacks—depth and cost limits are first-class controls.</li><li>Race conditions in web apps can undermine authorization—sequential logic tests in secure design reviews.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li><li>KMS key policies can deny even root in AWS when configured—explicit deny wins.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L5-09: Confidential computing (TEEs, attestation)</em>:</strong> Help desk scenarios test whether you know <strong>identity proofing</strong> vs <strong>account recovery</strong> abuse. The secure path verifies the human through out-of-band channels without teaching attackers how to bypass your process in the stem text.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L5-09: Confidential computing (TEEs, attestation)</em>:</strong> Security operations value <strong>repeatable evidence</strong>: timestamps, authoritative configuration sources, and tamper-aware logs beat heroic memory after an incident. Many exam questions hinge on whether an action preserves integrity and accountability rather than whether it feels fast.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L5-09: Confidential computing (TEEs, attestation)</em>:</strong> GraphQL introspection risk is about <strong>schema discovery</strong> aiding attackers—rate limits, authz on fields, and disabling introspection in prod are common answers.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L5-09: Confidential computing (TEEs, attestation)</em>:</strong> Wireless assessments should mention <strong>rogue AP</strong> discovery, client isolation, and guest segmentation—not just “use WPA2” as a slogan. Exam writers like the distinction between personal and enterprise authentication modes at a conceptual level.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L5-09: Confidential computing (TEEs, attestation)</em>:</strong> Risk decisions are economic: organizations <strong>accept</strong>, <strong>mitigate</strong>, <strong>transfer</strong> (insurance, outsourcing with contracts), or <strong>avoid</strong> (stop the activity). Controls change likelihood or impact; residual risk should be explicit, not invisible.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L5-09: Confidential computing (TEEs, attestation)</em>:</strong> CSP reporting helps tune policy but can leak URLs—<strong>privacy review</strong> of report endpoints matters in regulated environments.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L5-09: Confidential computing (TEEs, attestation)</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L5-09: Confidential computing (TEEs, attestation)</em>:</strong> Identity is the new perimeter: credentials, tokens, and sessions are stolen more often than novel zero-days are burned. Expect Security+ items on MFA bypass awareness, phishing-resistant factors, and why <strong>authorization</strong> must be enforced server-side.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L5-09: Confidential computing (TEEs, attestation)</em>:</strong> Subresource integrity protects against <strong>CDN compromise</strong> but requires operational discipline when vendors rotate files.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L5-09: Confidential computing (TEEs, attestation)</em>:</strong> Industrial and OT adjacent questions reward knowing <strong>safety vs security</strong> tension: availability may trump confidentiality; testing must avoid breaking physical processes.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> An engineer wants emergency access to production to debug “L5-09: Confidential computing (TEEs, attestation)” during change freeze. Outline <strong>break-glass</strong> steps: who approves, how sessions are recorded, and how credentials are rotated after.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l5-10":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L5-10: Formal methods / specification — where they help</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-10</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Protocol verification; limited scope wins.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Find one published protocol verification (TLS 1.3 papers) — write 5-sentence abstract in your words.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-10</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Advanced IR/intel questions still punish <strong>evidence destruction</strong> and <strong>unscoped testing</strong>—professional ethics are in scope.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 5 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Due care</strong></dt><dd>The effort a prudent person would take to meet a duty; in security, reasonable steps to protect assets and stakeholders.</dd><dt><strong>Authentication</strong></dt><dd>Proving identity—something you know, have, or are; combine factors for MFA; never equate login with authorization alone.</dd><dt><strong>Firewall</strong></dt><dd>Enforces allow/deny rules on traffic—stateful inspection tracks sessions; default-deny with explicit permits is the secure baseline.</dd><dt><strong>Hashing</strong></dt><dd>One-way fingerprint for integrity verification—SHA-256 family; not secrecy; used with HMAC for keyed integrity.</dd><dt><strong>CSRF</strong></dt><dd>Cross-site request forgery rides ambient auth—anti-CSRF tokens, SameSite cookies, and re-auth for sensitive actions help.</dd><dt><strong>IR phases</strong></dt><dd>Prepare, detect, analyze, contain, eradicate, recover, and lessons learned—legal hold and evidence integrity matter throughout.</dd><dt><strong>BCP / DR</strong></dt><dd>Business continuity and disaster recovery—RTO/RPO drive architecture; test restores, not just backups on paper.</dd><dt><strong>Confidential computing</strong></dt><dd>Use of hardware enclaves/TEEs to reduce exposure to privileged operators—threat model still required.</dd><dt><strong>Data loss prevention (DLP)</strong></dt><dd>Content-aware controls to block or alert on sensitive data movement—policy + tech, tuned to avoid blocking work.</dd><dt><strong>Block cipher vs stream</strong></dt><dd>Block operates on fixed-size chunks; stream on bits/bytes—misuse modes (e.g., ECB) create patterns.</dd><dt><strong>Full packet capture</strong></dt><dd>High fidelity evidence for investigations—storage, privacy, and legal review constraints apply.</dd><dt><strong>IOC</strong></dt><dd>Indicator of compromise—often ephemeral (IPs, domains); pair with TTP-based detections for durability.</dd><dt><strong>DNS</strong></dt><dd>Name resolution is a trust anchor—DNSSEC, cache poisoning, and malicious resolutions are classic abuse paths; log resolver anomalies.</dd><dt><strong>Exploit</strong></dt><dd>A technique or code that takes advantage of a vulnerability to achieve an attacker goal (exfiltration, persistence, disruption).</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Cloud responsibility</th><th>Who typically owns it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Patching the hypervisor</strong></td><td>Provider responsibility in major IaaS models—customer still patches guests.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>IAM policy and keys</strong></td><td>Customer-owned configuration—misconfigurations dominate incidents.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Data encryption at rest</strong></td><td>Often customer-controlled keys/KMS policies with provider primitives.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Network exposure (SGs/NACLs)</strong></td><td>Customer configures; default-deny patterns are exam favorites.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Application vulnerabilities</strong></td><td>Customer code and dependencies—shared model does not absolve secure SDLC.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li><li>Terraform state can hold secrets—remote secure backend and scanning are baseline hygiene.</li><li>EPSS (concept) scores exploitation probability—useful alongside CVSS for prioritization in mature programs.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li><li>PCI DSS scope reduction via segmentation is a recurring theme—if it is not in scope, it cannot drag you into assessment.</li><li>Certificate pinning misconfigurations can brick apps—plan rotation and emergency releases.</li><li>Bug bounty scope must exclude destructive testing—safe harbor language still needs legal review.</li><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L5-10: Formal methods / specification — where they help</em>:</strong> Container escape questions hinge on <strong>kernel boundary</strong> and misconfigured capabilities—namespaces are helpful but not a complete trust boundary without seccomp, AppArmor, and least-privileged service accounts.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L5-10: Formal methods / specification — where they help</em>:</strong> Air gapped networks still need <strong>patching via sneaker-net</strong> and insider controls—physical isolation is not logical isolation.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L5-10: Formal methods / specification — where they help</em>:</strong> Wireless and mobility items reward knowing basics: WPA3 improvements conceptually, evil twin risks, captive portals, and why client isolation matters on guest networks—without memorizing obsolete WEP details unless explicitly historical.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L5-10: Formal methods / specification — where they help</em>:</strong> DAST exercises running apps but misses authz logic without credentials; combine with <strong>manual review</strong> for business-rule flaws.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L5-10: Formal methods / specification — where they help</em>:</strong> For the Security+ mindset, translate every control into <strong>who</strong> it protects, <strong>what</strong> asset is at risk, and <strong>how</strong> you would detect failure. Interview and exam items often reward practical prioritization over buzzwords—choose the mitigation that reduces realistic loss first.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L5-10: Formal methods / specification — where they help</em>:</strong> Help desk scenarios test whether you know <strong>identity proofing</strong> vs <strong>account recovery</strong> abuse. The secure path verifies the human through out-of-band channels without teaching attackers how to bypass your process in the stem text.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L5-10: Formal methods / specification — where they help</em>:</strong> Subresource integrity protects against <strong>CDN compromise</strong> but requires operational discipline when vendors rotate files.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L5-10: Formal methods / specification — where they help</em>:</strong> Vulnerability management is a lifecycle: scanners find candidates, analysts prioritize with exploitability and business context, owners remediate, and verification closes the loop. “Patch everything immediately” is rarely operational; <strong>risk-based SLAs</strong> are the adult answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L5-10: Formal methods / specification — where they help</em>:</strong> Serverless cold start is not a security control; <strong>per-function IAM</strong> and least-privilege API scopes are. Watch for attractive nonsense distractors tied to performance tuning.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L5-10: Formal methods / specification — where they help</em>:</strong> Virtualization risks include <strong>snapshot sprawl</strong> containing secrets and stale VM images drifting from hardened baselines.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> A cloud bill spike correlates with traffic about “L5-10: Formal methods / specification — where they help”. Differentiate <strong>misconfiguration</strong> vs <strong>abuse</strong> in your first triage questions and what logs prove each hypothesis.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l5-11":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L5-11: Smart contract / Web3 security pitfalls (reentrancy, oracle manipulation)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-11</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Composability increases attack surface.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Read OpenZeppelin reentrancy article; diagram call flow that is unsafe.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-11</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Architecture tradeoff prompts want <strong>explicit assumptions</strong>—availability vs cost vs complexity, stated cleanly.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 5 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>SIEM</strong></dt><dd>Security information and event management—centralize logs, parse fields, correlate alerts; tuning reduces false positives and fatigue.</dd><dt><strong>Misconfiguration</strong></dt><dd>Top cloud incident driver—public buckets, open security groups, permissive trust policies; IaC scanning catches drift early.</dd><dt><strong>Third-party risk</strong></dt><dd>Vendor access expands attack surface—DPAs, SOC reports, and continuous monitoring for critical suppliers.</dd><dt><strong>Attack surface</strong></dt><dd>The sum of exposure—every service, API, integration, and human workflow that can be reached by a threat; reduction beats perfect monitoring alone.</dd><dt><strong>Forensics basics</strong></dt><dd>Volatile vs non-volatile collection, order of volatility, hashing, and legal escalation paths before deep technical work.</dd><dt><strong>Data loss prevention (DLP)</strong></dt><dd>Content-aware controls to block or alert on sensitive data movement—policy + tech, tuned to avoid blocking work.</dd><dt><strong>Salt (crypto)</strong></dt><dd>Random input to a password hash to defeat rainbow tables—must be unique per password.</dd><dt><strong>MAC</strong></dt><dd>Message authentication code—integrity with a secret key; differs from digital signature which uses asymmetric keys.</dd><dt><strong>WAF vs IPS</strong></dt><dd>WAF focuses on application-layer attacks; IPS often line-rate network signatures—overlap exists but priorities differ.</dd><dt><strong>Warm site / cold site</strong></dt><dd>Warm has partial hardware ready; cold is space only—cost vs recovery speed tradeoff.</dd><dt><strong>SOAR</strong></dt><dd>Security orchestration, automation, response—playbooks must have human gates for destructive actions.</dd><dt><strong>Firewall</strong></dt><dd>Enforces allow/deny rules on traffic—stateful inspection tracks sessions; default-deny with explicit permits is the secure baseline.</dd><dt><strong>Security control categories</strong></dt><dd>Technical (firewalls, encryption), administrative (policies, training), and physical (badges, locks)—exam items often ask which category fits a scenario.</dd><dt><strong>Control</strong></dt><dd>Administrative, technical, or physical safeguards that reduce likelihood or impact of a security event (prevent, detect, correct).</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Typical exam angle</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Confidentiality</strong></td><td>Who may read? Encryption, ACLs, DLP, classification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Integrity</strong></td><td>Was it modified? Hashing, signatures, change control, backups.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Availability</strong></td><td>Can authorized users work? HA, patching windows, DDoS defense, DR.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authenticity / non-repudiation</strong></td><td>Prove source and intent—signatures, strong issuance, tamper-evident logs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li><li>OAuth access tokens are not a replacement for server-side authorization checks on every sensitive action.</li><li>Server-side template injection is distinct from XSS—context and sinks differ.</li><li>ISO 27001 is an ISMS standard; it emphasizes risk treatment and continual improvement, not a product checklist.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li><li>Split tunnel VPN can exfil corporate data outside inspection if misconfigured—policy and routing matter.</li><li>Bug bounty scope must exclude destructive testing—safe harbor language still needs legal review.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L5-11: Smart contract / Web3 security pitfalls (reentrancy, oracle manipulation)</em>:</strong> Industrial and OT adjacent questions reward knowing <strong>safety vs security</strong> tension: availability may trump confidentiality; testing must avoid breaking physical processes.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L5-11: Smart contract / Web3 security pitfalls (reentrancy, oracle manipulation)</em>:</strong> Vulnerability management is a lifecycle: scanners find candidates, analysts prioritize with exploitability and business context, owners remediate, and verification closes the loop. “Patch everything immediately” is rarely operational; <strong>risk-based SLAs</strong> are the adult answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L5-11: Smart contract / Web3 security pitfalls (reentrancy, oracle manipulation)</em>:</strong> Honeypots can generate high-signal alerts but carry <strong>legal and operational</strong> risk if touched by real users; scope carefully.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L5-11: Smart contract / Web3 security pitfalls (reentrancy, oracle manipulation)</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L5-11: Smart contract / Web3 security pitfalls (reentrancy, oracle manipulation)</em>:</strong> Wireless and mobility items reward knowing basics: WPA3 improvements conceptually, evil twin risks, captive portals, and why client isolation matters on guest networks—without memorizing obsolete WEP details unless explicitly historical.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L5-11: Smart contract / Web3 security pitfalls (reentrancy, oracle manipulation)</em>:</strong> Social engineering callbacks to <strong>pretexting</strong>, <strong>baiting</strong>, and <strong>vishing</strong>—name the subtype when the stem describes the tactic.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L5-11: Smart contract / Web3 security pitfalls (reentrancy, oracle manipulation)</em>:</strong> Tabletop exercises test <strong>comms trees</strong>, legal escalation, and customer notification templates—not only technical runbooks.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L5-11: Smart contract / Web3 security pitfalls (reentrancy, oracle manipulation)</em>:</strong> Engineers often optimize for speed; attackers optimize for <strong>cheap reuse</strong> of stolen creds and known exploits. The winning answer bridges both: ship fast with guardrails—feature flags, staged rollouts, and automated security checks in CI.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L5-11: Smart contract / Web3 security pitfalls (reentrancy, oracle manipulation)</em>:</strong> Risk decisions are economic: organizations <strong>accept</strong>, <strong>mitigate</strong>, <strong>transfer</strong> (insurance, outsourcing with contracts), or <strong>avoid</strong> (stop the activity). Controls change likelihood or impact; residual risk should be explicit, not invisible.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L5-11: Smart contract / Web3 security pitfalls (reentrancy, oracle manipulation)</em>:</strong> Certificate pinning failures during rotation teach why <strong>key continuity strategy</strong> must be planned before mobile releases.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Purple team wants to simulate abuse of “L5-11: Smart contract / Web3 security pitfalls (reentrancy, oracle manipulation)” next Friday. List <strong>safety gates</strong> (scope, rollback, monitoring) you require before authorizing the exercise.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l5-12":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L5-12: Kernel exploit mitigations (ASLR, KASLR, CET, CFI)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-12</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Depth vs performance; bypass economics.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>cat /proc/sys/kernel/randomize_va_space</code> — interpret value.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-12</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Zero Trust answers should emphasize <strong>continuous verification</strong> and <strong>policy enforcement points</strong>, not removing all network security.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 5 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Need to know</strong></dt><dd>Finer than least privilege for data—access only to the minimum subset required for the current task.</dd><dt><strong>Full packet capture</strong></dt><dd>High fidelity evidence for investigations—storage, privacy, and legal review constraints apply.</dd><dt><strong>Exploit</strong></dt><dd>A technique or code that takes advantage of a vulnerability to achieve an attacker goal (exfiltration, persistence, disruption).</dd><dt><strong>NAT (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Rewrites addresses/ports for traversal—security relevance includes logging visibility, port forwarding risks, and split tunnel implications for inspection.</dd><dt><strong>Injection</strong></dt><dd>Untrusted input becomes part of a command or query—parameterized queries, input validation, and context escaping are core defenses.</dd><dt><strong>GRC</strong></dt><dd>Governance, risk, and compliance—align security decisions with law, policy, and business appetite; audits test design and operation.</dd><dt><strong>Data loss prevention (DLP)</strong></dt><dd>Content-aware controls to block or alert on sensitive data movement—policy + tech, tuned to avoid blocking work.</dd><dt><strong>NetFlow / IPFIX</strong></dt><dd>Flow metadata for volume and anomaly detection—lighter than PCAP but less payload visibility.</dd><dt><strong>Control</strong></dt><dd>Administrative, technical, or physical safeguards that reduce likelihood or impact of a security event (prevent, detect, correct).</dd><dt><strong>DDoS</strong></dt><dd>Distributed denial of service—volumetric, protocol, or application-layer floods; mitigations include scrubbing, anycast, rate limits, and architecture elasticity.</dd><dt><strong>XSS</strong></dt><dd>Cross-site scripting injects script in a victim context—CSP, output encoding, HttpOnly cookies, and DOM hygiene reduce blast radius.</dd><dt><strong>BCP / DR</strong></dt><dd>Business continuity and disaster recovery—RTO/RPO drive architecture; test restores, not just backups on paper.</dd><dt><strong>Token replay</strong></dt><dd>Reusing a stolen token/session artifact—rotation, binding, and short TTLs reduce window.</dd><dt><strong>Sinkhole (DNS)</strong></dt><dd>Controlled resolution for malicious domains—intel and disruption technique with legal process considerations.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>IR phase</th><th>What you do there (exam shorthand)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Prepare</strong></td><td>Playbooks, contacts, tooling, baseline logging—before the pager fires.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detect &amp; analyze</strong></td><td>Scope, timelines, hypotheses—preserve volatile evidence early.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Contain</strong></td><td>Stop spread with minimal evidence damage—network isolation variants matter.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Eradicate &amp; recover</strong></td><td>Remove persistence, patch root cause, restore with verification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Lessons learned</strong></td><td>Metrics, control changes, and communication improvements—close the loop.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>Terraform state can hold secrets—remote secure backend and scanning are baseline hygiene.</li><li>SameSite=Lax blocks many CSRF POSTs from cross-site contexts in modern browsers—know the nuance vs Strict.</li><li>DNS over HTTPS changes visibility for some networks—understand resolver policy and logging tradeoffs.</li><li>Azure AD / Entra conditional access is analogous to risk-based policies—device compliance signals matter.</li><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L5-12: Kernel exploit mitigations (ASLR, KASLR, CET, CFI)</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L5-12: Kernel exploit mitigations (ASLR, KASLR, CET, CFI)</em>:</strong> Application security scenarios often test whether you know <strong>where</strong> enforcement belongs—browser controls supplement but do not replace server-side checks. SameSite cookies, CSP, and HttpOnly mitigate classes of issues; they do not fix broken object-level authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L5-12: Kernel exploit mitigations (ASLR, KASLR, CET, CFI)</em>:</strong> TACACS+ vs RADIUS separation of duties in device admin access—exams may contrast accounting granularity.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L5-12: Kernel exploit mitigations (ASLR, KASLR, CET, CFI)</em>:</strong> KMS keys are not “magic secrecy dust”—<strong>who can invoke decrypt</strong> and from which contexts (VPC endpoint policies, IAM conditions) is what exams probe.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L5-12: Kernel exploit mitigations (ASLR, KASLR, CET, CFI)</em>:</strong> Access control stems frequently mix <strong>role</strong> vs <strong>attribute</strong> vs <strong>rule</strong> models; pick the answer that matches the scenario’s constraints (temporary contractor, cross-department data, dynamic tags on resources).</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L5-12: Kernel exploit mitigations (ASLR, KASLR, CET, CFI)</em>:</strong> Sanitization vs wiping vs destruction: exams like knowing which media needs <strong>degaussing, shredding, or crypto erase</strong> per policy.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L5-12: Kernel exploit mitigations (ASLR, KASLR, CET, CFI)</em>:</strong> Penetration tests require <strong>written authorization</strong>, defined scope, and rules of engagement—even in internal labs for professional conduct.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L5-12: Kernel exploit mitigations (ASLR, KASLR, CET, CFI)</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L5-12: Kernel exploit mitigations (ASLR, KASLR, CET, CFI)</em>:</strong> Security operations value <strong>repeatable evidence</strong>: timestamps, authoritative configuration sources, and tamper-aware logs beat heroic memory after an incident. Many exam questions hinge on whether an action preserves integrity and accountability rather than whether it feels fast.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L5-12: Kernel exploit mitigations (ASLR, KASLR, CET, CFI)</em>:</strong> Subresource integrity protects against <strong>CDN compromise</strong> but requires operational discipline when vendors rotate files.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Legal asks whether “L5-12: Kernel exploit mitigations (ASLR, KASLR, CET, CFI)” artifacts require <strong>hold</strong> before deletion. Describe how you would <strong>tag systems</strong>, <strong>freeze backups</strong> appropriately, and <strong>escalate</strong> without tipping external actors.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l5-13":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L5-13: Advanced persistent threat (APT) lifecycle and cyber kill chain</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-13</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Merge kill chain with ATT&amp;CK for reporting.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Map one public <strong>sanitized</strong> IR report stages to ATT&amp;CK tactics (citation).</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-13</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Modern crypto stems may reference <strong>harvest-now/decrypt-later</strong>—think inventory of secret longevity and hybrid transitions.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 5 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Authentication</strong></dt><dd>Proving identity—something you know, have, or are; combine factors for MFA; never equate login with authorization alone.</dd><dt><strong>DevSecOps</strong></dt><dd>Embed security gates in CI/CD with fast feedback—policy-as-code, secret scanning, and SBOMs support supply-chain resilience.</dd><dt><strong>Job rotation</strong></dt><dd>Reduces collusion and fraud risk; also surfaces “tribal knowledge” silos before an employee leaves.</dd><dt><strong>TTP</strong></dt><dd>Tactics, techniques, and procedures—behavioral patterns; harder to change than IOCs, better for resilient detection.</dd><dt><strong>Authorization</strong></dt><dd>What an authenticated subject is allowed to do—RBAC/ABAC, scopes, and server-side checks enforce least privilege.</dd><dt><strong>CVE</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures identifier for a specific flaw—pairs with CVSS severity and vendor advisories for prioritization.</dd><dt><strong>Mandatory vacation</strong></dt><dd>Forces handover and review of another employee’s work—can uncover fraud or backdoors.</dd><dt><strong>SOAR</strong></dt><dd>Security orchestration, automation, response—playbooks must have human gates for destructive actions.</dd><dt><strong>MFA</strong></dt><dd>Multi-factor authentication—requires two or more independent factors; push fatigue and MFA phishing are real bypass paths.</dd><dt><strong>CVSS</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerability Scoring System—base metrics describe technical severity; environmental and temporal modifiers refine priority.</dd><dt><strong>Need to know</strong></dt><dd>Finer than least privilege for data—access only to the minimum subset required for the current task.</dd><dt><strong>UEBA</strong></dt><dd>User and entity behavior analytics—baseline deviations; tune to avoid HR/privacy backlash.</dd><dt><strong>FIDO2 / WebAuthn</strong></dt><dd>Phishing-resistant possession factors using asymmetric crypto and origin binding; preferred where supported.</dd><dt><strong>CWE</strong></dt><dd>Common Weakness Enumeration—taxonomy of software weakness types that help root-cause fixes beyond one CVE instance.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>ATT&CK technique IDs are stable references for detection content—good for purple team reporting.</li><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li><li>Immutable backups mitigate ransomware that tries to delete online copies—air-gapped or WORM patterns.</li><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li><li>DNS over HTTPS changes visibility for some networks—understand resolver policy and logging tradeoffs.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>GraphQL batching can amplify complexity attacks—depth and cost limits are first-class controls.</li><li>Race conditions in web apps can undermine authorization—sequential logic tests in secure design reviews.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L5-13: Advanced persistent threat (APT) lifecycle and cyber kill chain</em>:</strong> Controls fail in three predictable ways: <strong>misconfiguration</strong>, <strong>missing coverage</strong> (gaps between tools), and <strong>human process</strong> breakdown (exceptions, shared accounts, emergency access). When you read a scenario, ask which failure mode is most plausible before picking an answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L5-13: Advanced persistent threat (APT) lifecycle and cyber kill chain</em>:</strong> Access control stems frequently mix <strong>role</strong> vs <strong>attribute</strong> vs <strong>rule</strong> models; pick the answer that matches the scenario’s constraints (temporary contractor, cross-department data, dynamic tags on resources).</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L5-13: Advanced persistent threat (APT) lifecycle and cyber kill chain</em>:</strong> Email security stems often combine SPF alignment failures with <strong>look-alike domains</strong>. The best answer addresses user training plus technical authenticity controls, not only one or the other.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L5-13: Advanced persistent threat (APT) lifecycle and cyber kill chain</em>:</strong> Tabletop exercises test <strong>comms trees</strong>, legal escalation, and customer notification templates—not only technical runbooks.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L5-13: Advanced persistent threat (APT) lifecycle and cyber kill chain</em>:</strong> Air gapped networks still need <strong>patching via sneaker-net</strong> and insider controls—physical isolation is not logical isolation.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L5-13: Advanced persistent threat (APT) lifecycle and cyber kill chain</em>:</strong> Identity is the new perimeter: credentials, tokens, and sessions are stolen more often than novel zero-days are burned. Expect Security+ items on MFA bypass awareness, phishing-resistant factors, and why <strong>authorization</strong> must be enforced server-side.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L5-13: Advanced persistent threat (APT) lifecycle and cyber kill chain</em>:</strong> Third-party and supply chain answers should emphasize <strong>contracts</strong>, <strong>evidence</strong>, and <strong>continuous monitoring</strong>—not “trust the SOC 2 logo” without scope review.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L5-13: Advanced persistent threat (APT) lifecycle and cyber kill chain</em>:</strong> Serverless cold start is not a security control; <strong>per-function IAM</strong> and least-privilege API scopes are. Watch for attractive nonsense distractors tied to performance tuning.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L5-13: Advanced persistent threat (APT) lifecycle and cyber kill chain</em>:</strong> GraphQL introspection risk is about <strong>schema discovery</strong> aiding attackers—rate limits, authz on fields, and disabling introspection in prod are common answers.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L5-13: Advanced persistent threat (APT) lifecycle and cyber kill chain</em>:</strong> Sanitization vs wiping vs destruction: exams like knowing which media needs <strong>degaussing, shredding, or crypto erase</strong> per policy.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Internal audit samples “L5-13: Advanced persistent threat (APT) lifecycle and cyber kill chain” controls and finds screenshots instead of config exports. Explain why <strong>authoritative evidence</strong> matters and what you would collect instead.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l5-14":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L5-14: Red team legal scope, RoE, safety checks (“stop triggers”)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-14</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Authorization boundaries; production safety.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Write RoE appendix: prohibited techniques, evidence handling, comms tree.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-14</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Zero Trust answers should emphasize <strong>continuous verification</strong> and <strong>policy enforcement points</strong>, not removing all network security.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 5 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Attack surface</strong></dt><dd>The sum of exposure—every service, API, integration, and human workflow that can be reached by a threat; reduction beats perfect monitoring alone.</dd><dt><strong>Need to know</strong></dt><dd>Finer than least privilege for data—access only to the minimum subset required for the current task.</dd><dt><strong>ECB mode weakness</strong></dt><dd>Identical plaintext blocks yield identical ciphertext—leaks structure; prefer modes with IVs and authentication.</dd><dt><strong>Sinkhole (routing)</strong></dt><dd>Different meaning in BGP—be careful with homonyms on exams; read the stem’s context.</dd><dt><strong>Right to be forgotten (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Privacy request to delete data—may conflict with legal hold; counsel resolves precedence.</dd><dt><strong>Threat</strong></dt><dd>Any circumstance or actor with the potential to cause harm by exploiting a vulnerability (malware, insider, natural disaster).</dd><dt><strong>Non-repudiation</strong></dt><dd>Prevents a party from credibly denying an action—digital signatures, tamper-evident logs, and time-stamping support it.</dd><dt><strong>DDoS</strong></dt><dd>Distributed denial of service—volumetric, protocol, or application-layer floods; mitigations include scrubbing, anycast, rate limits, and architecture elasticity.</dd><dt><strong>Hashing</strong></dt><dd>One-way fingerprint for integrity verification—SHA-256 family; not secrecy; used with HMAC for keyed integrity.</dd><dt><strong>Security headers</strong></dt><dd>HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options/Frame-ancestors, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy—reduce browser-driven attack surface.</dd><dt><strong>Logging &amp; monitoring</strong></dt><dd>CloudTrail-style management events differ from data-plane logs—enable central export, immutability, and alerting.</dd><dt><strong>Metrics that matter</strong></dt><dd>Mean time to detect/remediate with quality, coverage of critical assets, and control effectiveness—not vanity ticket counts.</dd><dt><strong>Job rotation</strong></dt><dd>Reduces collusion and fraud risk; also surfaces “tribal knowledge” silos before an employee leaves.</dd><dt><strong>Collision (hash)</strong></dt><dd>Two inputs produce same hash—breaks integrity assumptions; choose strong hash families for security use.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Cloud responsibility</th><th>Who typically owns it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Patching the hypervisor</strong></td><td>Provider responsibility in major IaaS models—customer still patches guests.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>IAM policy and keys</strong></td><td>Customer-owned configuration—misconfigurations dominate incidents.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Data encryption at rest</strong></td><td>Often customer-controlled keys/KMS policies with provider primitives.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Network exposure (SGs/NACLs)</strong></td><td>Customer configures; default-deny patterns are exam favorites.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Application vulnerabilities</strong></td><td>Customer code and dependencies—shared model does not absolve secure SDLC.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Sigma rules are vendor-agnostic detection snippets—tuning required per log source fields.</li><li>GraphQL batching can amplify complexity attacks—depth and cost limits are first-class controls.</li><li>Terraform state can hold secrets—remote secure backend and scanning are baseline hygiene.</li><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>Immutable backups mitigate ransomware that tries to delete online copies—air-gapped or WORM patterns.</li><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li><li>Bug bounty scope must exclude destructive testing—safe harbor language still needs legal review.</li><li>HttpOnly does not stop CSRF; it reduces token theft from XSS reading document.cookie in many setups.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L5-14: Red team legal scope, RoE, safety checks (“stop triggers”)</em>:</strong> Honeypots can generate high-signal alerts but carry <strong>legal and operational</strong> risk if touched by real users; scope carefully.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L5-14: Red team legal scope, RoE, safety checks (“stop triggers”)</em>:</strong> Incident response questions probe containment vs evidence preservation tension, legal escalation, and communication discipline. The exam rewards knowing when to isolate systems, when to involve counsel, and why mass log deletion is catastrophic.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L5-14: Red team legal scope, RoE, safety checks (“stop triggers”)</em>:</strong> When logs “mysteriously stop,” think <strong>time sync failure</strong>, collector saturation, retention misconfiguration, or attacker tampering—in that diagnostic order for a fair exam narrative.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L5-14: Red team legal scope, RoE, safety checks (“stop triggers”)</em>:</strong> Certificate pinning failures during rotation teach why <strong>key continuity strategy</strong> must be planned before mobile releases.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L5-14: Red team legal scope, RoE, safety checks (“stop triggers”)</em>:</strong> Identity is the new perimeter: credentials, tokens, and sessions are stolen more often than novel zero-days are burned. Expect Security+ items on MFA bypass awareness, phishing-resistant factors, and why <strong>authorization</strong> must be enforced server-side.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L5-14: Red team legal scope, RoE, safety checks (“stop triggers”)</em>:</strong> Wireless assessments should mention <strong>rogue AP</strong> discovery, client isolation, and guest segmentation—not just “use WPA2” as a slogan. Exam writers like the distinction between personal and enterprise authentication modes at a conceptual level.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L5-14: Red team legal scope, RoE, safety checks (“stop triggers”)</em>:</strong> API keys in mobile apps are often extractable—prefer <strong>short-lived tokens</strong> and server-mediated access to backends.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L5-14: Red team legal scope, RoE, safety checks (“stop triggers”)</em>:</strong> Controls fail in three predictable ways: <strong>misconfiguration</strong>, <strong>missing coverage</strong> (gaps between tools), and <strong>human process</strong> breakdown (exceptions, shared accounts, emergency access). When you read a scenario, ask which failure mode is most plausible before picking an answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L5-14: Red team legal scope, RoE, safety checks (“stop triggers”)</em>:</strong> Data handling questions often hinge on <strong>classification</strong>, <strong>least data</strong>, and <strong>retention</strong>: collect only what you need, keep it only as long as allowed, and destroy securely when done.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L5-14: Red team legal scope, RoE, safety checks (“stop triggers”)</em>:</strong> Penetration tests require <strong>written authorization</strong>, defined scope, and rules of engagement—even in internal labs for professional conduct.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Legal asks whether “L5-14: Red team legal scope, RoE, safety checks (“stop triggers”)” artifacts require <strong>hold</strong> before deletion. Describe how you would <strong>tag systems</strong>, <strong>freeze backups</strong> appropriately, and <strong>escalate</strong> without tipping external actors.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l5-15":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L5-15: Security metrics that are not vanity</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-15</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> MTTD/MTTR, coverage % of ATT&amp;CK, vuln age SLAs, phishing sim click rate trends.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Dashboard wireframe (ASCII) with 6 KPIs and data sources.</p>\n<h2>Lab pack — Level 5</h2>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Zero-trust design review:</strong> Pick internal app; list 15 control gaps vs ZT principles; propose phased roadmap (people/process/tech).  </li>\n<li><strong>Crypto inventory:</strong> Spreadsheet of all TLS endpoints with cipher suite allowlist proposal.  </li>\n<li><strong>PQC readiness workshop:</strong> Agenda + stakeholder list (app owners, PKI team, network).  </li>\n<li><strong>Attestation deep dive:</strong> Read confidential computing vendor whitepaper; 2-page threat model “honest but curious provider.”  </li>\n<li><strong>Red team dry run:</strong> Tabletop legal + out-of-band comms + “customer impact” stop trigger.</li>\n</ol>\n<h2>Question bank — Level 5</h2>\n<p><strong>Q1.</strong> Zero Trust replaces perimeter-only trust with: (a) no encryption (b) continuous explicit verification (c) single password.<br><strong>Q2.</strong> mTLS primarily adds: (a) client authentication via certificates (b) GPU acceleration (c) RAID 6.<br><strong>Q3.</strong> PQC addresses: (a) quantum threat to asymmetric schemes (b) slow HDD (c) SMTP banners.<br><strong>Q4.</strong> AEAD modes aim to provide: (a) confidentiality+integrity together (b) only compression (c) only key escrow.<br><strong>Q5.</strong> TPM sealing ties keys to: (a) PCR measurements / platform state (b) Wi-Fi SSID only (c) DHCP pool.<br><strong>Q6.</strong> Confidential computing mitigates: (a) malicious cloud admin reading memory of enclave (model-dependent) (b) all phishing (c) BGP only.<br><strong>Q7.</strong> ASLR mainly mitigates: (a) memory corruption exploitation reliability (b) SQLi (c) weak DNS TTL.<br><strong>Q8.</strong> Padding oracle class attacks target: (a) bad MAC/unauthenticated decryption (b) RAID (c) MFA apps.<br><strong>Q9.</strong> Red team engagement requires: (a) written authorization + scope (b) dark web account (c) domain purchase only.<br><strong>Q10.</strong> SPIFFE helps: (a) cryptographic identity for workloads (b) printer sharing (c) BIOS passwords.<br><strong>Q11.</strong> Microsegmentation often leverages: (a) identity-aware L4/L7 policy (b) only physical keys (c) VGA only.<br><strong>Q12.</strong> “Harvest now, decrypt later” motivates: (a) early PQC migration for long-lived secrets (b) deleting TLS (c) disabling logs.<br><strong>Q13.</strong> Smart contract reentrancy is fundamentally: (a) unsafe external call ordering/state updates (b) SQL join (c) RAID stripe.<br><strong>Q14.</strong> Formal verification is strongest when: (a) scope is well-defined protocol/properties (b) applied to “all possible apps” loosely (c) replacing pentests entirely always.<br><strong>Q15.</strong> Measured boot helps detect: (a) firmware/bootloader tampering (b) weak Wi-Fi password only (c) printer jams.<br><strong>Q16.</strong> ZT PDP/PEP means: (a) policy decision/enforcement points (b) disk partitions (c) DNS TTL fields.<br><strong>Q17.</strong> KASLR extends ASLR to: (a) kernel memory layout randomization (b) cookies (c) SMTP.<br><strong>Q18.</strong> Oracle manipulation in DeFi refers to: (a) untrusted price/input feeds (b) TLS OCSP (c) TPM counters.<br><strong>Q19.</strong> MTTR is: (a) mean time to remediate/recover from incident (b) mean time to rotate wallpaper (c) MAC time to live.<br><strong>Q20.</strong> “Safety checks” in red teaming include: (a) stop triggers for customer harm (b) deleting evidence (c) disabling EDR always.</p>\n<h3>Answer key — Level 5</h3>\n<p>1–5: B/A/A/A/A<br>6–10: A/A/A/A/A<br>11–15: A/A/A/A/A<br>16–20: A/A/A/A/A  </p>\n<hr>\n<h1>Capstone — End examination (all levels)</h1>\n<p><strong>Instructions:</strong> Closed book unless your instructor allows NVD/MITRE docs. 60 questions, ~120 minutes. Select the best single answer unless noted.</p>\n<p><strong>Section A — Foundations (L1) — Q1–12</strong>  </p>\n<ol>\n<li>Which is the clearest <strong>availability</strong> impact? (a) ransomware denies access to files until recovery (b) wrong file owner on <code>chmod</code> (c) expired TLS on an internal-only tool with no outage.  </li>\n<li>Integrity example: (a) DDoS (b) altered database row (c) stolen laptop powered off.  </li>\n<li>Accounting in AAA refers to: (a) finance department (b) logging/auditing of actions (c) antivirus scans.  </li>\n<li>MFA bypass awareness: (a) impossible (b) push fatigue/MFA phishing exists (c) only nation-states.  </li>\n<li>Least privilege: (a) grant admin to devs for speed (b) minimal rights (c) shared root passwords.  </li>\n<li>RTO is: (a) max acceptable downtime (b) max data loss (c) password age.  </li>\n<li>Patch ring strategy: (a) prod first always (b) progressive rollout with validation (c) never patch.  </li>\n<li>Clean desk: (a) irrelevant (b) reduces sensitive data exposure (c) replaces encryption.  </li>\n<li>Social engineering: (a) only email (b) any human manipulation tactic (c) only SQLi.  </li>\n<li>Risk “mitigate”: (a) add controls (b) ignore (c) delete customers.  </li>\n<li>PII: (a) aggregate weather trends (b) passport number (c) anonymous telemetry with no link.  </li>\n<li>Incident escalation: (a) post publicly first (b) follow playbooks and legal guidance (c) pay silently always.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Section B — Intermediate (L2) — Q13–24</strong><br>13. TLS provides: (a) magic anonymity (b) channel security between endpoints if verified (c) disk encryption always.<br>14. HSTS fights: (a) SSL stripping (b) SQLi (c) weak Wi-Fi.<br>15. <code>SameSite</code> reduces: (a) some CSRF scenarios (b) TLS need (c) RAID overhead.<br>16. Parameterized queries mitigate: (a) SQLi (b) BGP hijack (c) BIOS password loss.<br>17. CSP reduces impact of: (a) XSS (b) RAID 0 failures (c) DHCP.<br>18. DKIM proves: (a) signing integrity (b) SPF alignment only (c) GPU brand.<br>19. DMARC policy <code>p=reject</code> means: (a) accept all (b) instruct receivers to reject fails (c) encrypt mail at rest only.<br>20. Encoding Base64: (a) secrecy (b) not secrecy (c) integrity.<br>21. Default-deny firewall: (a) allow all (b) deny unless allowed (c) log only never block.<br>22. Session fixation fix: (a) reuse IDs (b) rotate session on login (c) disable cookies.<br>23. VPN split tunnel risk: (a) corporate traffic bypasses security controls (b) always safer (c) removes MFA.<br>24. Symmetric crypto in TLS bulk data: (a) true (b) false (c) only for DNS.</p>\n<p><strong>Section C — Advanced (L3) — Q25–36</strong><br>25. CVSS is: (a) legal severity (b) technical scoring framework (c) patch file format.<br>26. CVE is: (a) weakness taxonomy (b) vuln ID (c) firewall log code.<br>27. MITRE ATT&amp;CK tactic describes: (a) why adversary goal category (b) CVE number (c) patch CAB.<br>28. STRIDE repudiation mitigation examples: (a) signatures/audit trails (b) longer Wi-Fi range (c) RAID 1.<br>29. <code>sudo</code> logging important for: (a) accountability (b) GPU FPS (c) DHCP speed.<br>30. SIEM value: (a) correlate events (b) replace IdP (c) encrypt laptops automatically.<br>31. IDS sensor placement on encrypted east-west without decryption: (a) full content always visible (b) limited visibility; design matters (c) impossible to place.<br>32. IR containment: (a) announce on social first (b) isolate affected systems (c) delete logs to save disk.<br>33. IAM SCP: (a) AWS org guardrail (b) Linux file ACL (c) SMTP header.<br>34. Remote syslog helps: (a) attacker-only logs (b) central tamper resistance (c) remove MFA.<br>35. Threat modeling best timing: (a) design (b) never (c) only post-breach PR.<br>36. OAuth PKCE protects: (a) public clients in auth code flow (b) printers (c) RAID.</p>\n<p><strong>Section D — Expert (L4) — Q37–48</strong><br>37. Kerberos service tickets relate to: (a) individual services/resources (b) DHCP (c) HDMI-CEC.<br>38. LAPS addresses: (a) predictable local admin passwords (b) SQL indexes (c) SMTP TLS.<br>39. Conditional Access may block login if: (a) risky sign-in + non-compliant device (b) username has vowels (c) always never blocks.<br>40. CloudTrail-like logs capture: (a) management events (b) every S3 object read always in all cases (c) GPU temperature.<br>41. Chain of custody supports: (a) evidence credibility (b) faster Wi-Fi (c) SQL performance.<br>42. EDR value: (a) behavioral telemetry + response (b) replaces policy (c) removes logging need.<br>43. Purple teaming: (a) validate detections with controlled tests (b) hide malware (c) delete backups.<br>44. Insider risk must consider: (a) law and proportionality (b) only tech blocks (c) ignore HR.<br>45. SBOM helps during: (a) supply chain incident triage (b) monitor refresh rate (c) BGP only.<br>46. PIM reduces: (a) standing admin (b) need for audits (c) encryption need totally.<br>47. BEC relies on: (a) process trust in email payments (b) RAID 6 (c) GPU driver signing only.<br>48. Write blocker used in: (a) disk acquisition (b) Wi-Fi pairing (c) TLS session resumption.</p>\n<p><strong>Section E — Heavy advanced (L5) — Q49–60</strong><br>49. Zero Trust core: (a) continuous verification (b) trust LAN always (c) single factor everywhere.<br>50. mTLS adds: (a) mutual authentication (b) RAID (c) DHCP options only.<br>51. PQC migration driver: (a) quantum threat timeline uncertainty (b) slower RAM (c) SMTP banners.<br>52. AEAD provides: (a) confidentiality and integrity (b) compression only (c) key escrow by default.<br>53. TPM sealing ties secrets to: (a) platform measurements (b) monitor Hz (c) DNS TTL.<br>54. Confidential computing addresses threats from: (a) privileged infrastructure operators (model-dependent) (b) all phishing always (c) paper shredders.<br>55. ASLR makes: (a) exploits less reliable (b) SQL faster (c) TLS unnecessary.<br>56. Red team requires: (a) explicit authorization (b) any GitHub tool free use anywhere (c) dark web membership.<br>57. SPIFFE relates to: (a) workload identity (b) printer drivers (c) FAT32.<br>58. Microsegmentation helps: (a) east-west blast radius control (b) monitor brightness (c) HDMI-CEC.<br>59. Formal methods excel with: (a) precise specifications (b) vague “secure the app” (c) marketing slogans only.<br>60. Good security KPI: (a) MTTR trend down with quality preserved (b) ticket count up only (c) alerts disabled for noise.</p>\n<h3>Capstone answer key (quick)</h3>\n<p>1–12: A,B,B,B,B,A,B,B,B,A,B,B<br>13–24: B,A,A,A,A,A,B,B,B,B,A,A<br>25–36: B,B,A,A,A,A,B,B,A,B,A,A<br>37–48: A,A,A,A,A,A,A,B,A,A,A,A<br>49–60: A,A,A,A,A,A,A,A,A,A,A,A  </p>\n<hr>\n<h2>Instructor notes (workplace alignment)</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>SOC analyst:</strong> Levels 1–3 heavy; drill SIEM queries and triage narratives.  </li>\n<li><strong>IT security / infrastructure:</strong> Levels 1–4; labs on SSH, patching, IAM, logging.  </li>\n<li><strong>AppSec / developer:</strong> Levels 2–3 + parts of 5; STRIDE, OWASP, OAuth, crypto.  </li>\n<li><strong>GRC / risk:</strong> Levels 1, 3, 4, 5 architecture + policy mapping to frameworks (NIST CSF, ISO 27001 awareness).  </li>\n<li><strong>Cloud security associate:</strong> Levels 2–4; emphasize logging, IAM guardrails, incident paths.  </li>\n<li><strong>Part 2 extensions (lessons 16–20):</strong> Assign as “week 2” depth, homework reading, or honors track.  </li>\n<li><strong>Part 3 extensions (lessons 21–25):</strong> Specialization (JWT/GraphQL/CSP, intel/STIX, CI/CD, privacy tech); pair with <strong>Appendix G</strong> syllabus and <strong>Appendix I</strong> scenarios.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Assessment integrity:</strong> Rotate capstone numbers/narratives each cohort; allow open-notes only for NIST/MITRE references if desired.</p>\n<hr>\n<h1>Part 2 — Extended lessons (16–20 per level)</h1>\n<p>Use the same Learn-Hub mapping as Part 1. IDs continue <code>lh-sec-l*-16</code> … <code>lh-sec-l*-20</code>.</p>\n<h2>Level 1 extensions</h2>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-15</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Modern crypto stems may reference <strong>harvest-now/decrypt-later</strong>—think inventory of secret longevity and hybrid transitions.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 5 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Security awareness</strong></dt><dd>Training plus culture—measure reporting rates, not shame metrics; phishing simulations should reinforce reporting.</dd><dt><strong>Purple teaming</strong></dt><dd>Collaborative attack/defense exercises to validate detections without surprise production harm—scope and safety first.</dd><dt><strong>Replay attack</strong></dt><dd>Valid data maliciously re-sent—nonces, timestamps, and session freshness mitigate.</dd><dt><strong>IV / nonce</strong></dt><dd>Initialization vector or number-used-once—must be unique per encryption under a key for many modes.</dd><dt><strong>Sinkhole (DNS)</strong></dt><dd>Controlled resolution for malicious domains—intel and disruption technique with legal process considerations.</dd><dt><strong>SOAR</strong></dt><dd>Security orchestration, automation, response—playbooks must have human gates for destructive actions.</dd><dt><strong>Security headers</strong></dt><dd>HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options/Frame-ancestors, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy—reduce browser-driven attack surface.</dd><dt><strong>Risk</strong></dt><dd>The intersection of threat, vulnerability, and impact—often assessed qualitatively (high/medium/low) or with scoring frameworks.</dd><dt><strong>PII</strong></dt><dd>Personally identifiable information—names, government IDs, biometrics, account numbers; triggers handling, retention, and breach rules.</dd><dt><strong>DDoS</strong></dt><dd>Distributed denial of service—volumetric, protocol, or application-layer floods; mitigations include scrubbing, anycast, rate limits, and architecture elasticity.</dd><dt><strong>Symmetric encryption</strong></dt><dd>Same key encrypts and decrypts—fast for bulk data (AES-GCM); key distribution is the hard problem.</dd><dt><strong>Injection</strong></dt><dd>Untrusted input becomes part of a command or query—parameterized queries, input validation, and context escaping are core defenses.</dd><dt><strong>SIEM</strong></dt><dd>Security information and event management—centralize logs, parse fields, correlate alerts; tuning reduces false positives and fatigue.</dd><dt><strong>CASB / SaaS governance</strong></dt><dd>Visibility and policy for sanctioned vs shadow SaaS—OAuth consent attacks and guest sharing are common gaps.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authorization</strong></td><td>Server-side object checks—headers and TLS do not replace this.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>UDP-based protocols can be abused for amplification DDoS—patch open resolvers and monitor volumetric baselines.</li><li>Bug bounty scope must exclude destructive testing—safe harbor language still needs legal review.</li><li>GCP service account keys are long-lived secrets—prefer workload identity federation from CI where possible.</li><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li><li>Race conditions in web apps can undermine authorization—sequential logic tests in secure design reviews.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L5-15: Security metrics that are not vanity</em>:</strong> GraphQL introspection risk is about <strong>schema discovery</strong> aiding attackers—rate limits, authz on fields, and disabling introspection in prod are common answers.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L5-15: Security metrics that are not vanity</em>:</strong> Cryptography questions reward vocabulary precision: hashing vs encryption vs encoding; symmetric vs asymmetric roles in TLS; what signatures prove; and why key management is usually harder than picking an algorithm. If an answer sounds magical, it is probably wrong.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L5-15: Security metrics that are not vanity</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L5-15: Security metrics that are not vanity</em>:</strong> Deception tech is not a replacement for <strong>baselines and patching</strong>; it augments detection when mature processes exist.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L5-15: Security metrics that are not vanity</em>:</strong> Access control stems frequently mix <strong>role</strong> vs <strong>attribute</strong> vs <strong>rule</strong> models; pick the answer that matches the scenario’s constraints (temporary contractor, cross-department data, dynamic tags on resources).</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L5-15: Security metrics that are not vanity</em>:</strong> SAST finds issues early but produces false positives; <strong>triage workflows</strong> and developer feedback loops are part of a mature program, not “run tool once.”</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L5-15: Security metrics that are not vanity</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L5-15: Security metrics that are not vanity</em>:</strong> Engineers often optimize for speed; attackers optimize for <strong>cheap reuse</strong> of stolen creds and known exploits. The winning answer bridges both: ship fast with guardrails—feature flags, staged rollouts, and automated security checks in CI.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L5-15: Security metrics that are not vanity</em>:</strong> CSP reporting helps tune policy but can leak URLs—<strong>privacy review</strong> of report endpoints matters in regulated environments.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L5-15: Security metrics that are not vanity</em>:</strong> Application security scenarios often test whether you know <strong>where</strong> enforcement belongs—browser controls supplement but do not replace server-side checks. SameSite cookies, CSP, and HttpOnly mitigate classes of issues; they do not fix broken object-level authorization.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> An engineer wants emergency access to production to debug “L5-15: Security metrics that are not vanity” during change freeze. Outline <strong>break-glass</strong> steps: who approves, how sessions are recorded, and how credentials are rotated after.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l1-16":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L1-16: Security awareness metrics that are not vanity</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-16</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Distinguish click rate vs reporting rate vs time-to-report; avoid punishing reporters.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Program owners report to risk committee; tie to control testing.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Design a 4-metric dashboard in <code>~/awareness-kpi.md</code> with formulas and data sources.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-16</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>At Level 1, think like an analyst who must <strong>classify</strong> an event: asset, threat, vulnerability, control, residual risk. If you can narrate those five words for any headline topic, you are aligned with how writers build scenario questions.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 1 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Port knocking (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Obscurity-based pre-auth to open firewall—weak alone; exam may present as non-primary control.</dd><dt><strong>Due care</strong></dt><dd>The effort a prudent person would take to meet a duty; in security, reasonable steps to protect assets and stakeholders.</dd><dt><strong>OWASP Top 10</strong></dt><dd>High-prevalence web risks—broken access control and crypto failures often dominate; study each category with one workplace example.</dd><dt><strong>Business continuity testing</strong></dt><dd>Tabletops and technical failover drills reveal gaps in comms, dependencies, and vendor SLAs.</dd><dt><strong>SOAR</strong></dt><dd>Security orchestration, automation, response—playbooks must have human gates for destructive actions.</dd><dt><strong>SSO</strong></dt><dd>Single sign-on federates trust to an IdP—misconfigured SAML/OIDC trusts are high-impact; validate metadata and signing keys.</dd><dt><strong>IAM least privilege</strong></dt><dd>Grant minimum API/console rights; prefer roles over long-lived keys; audit risky admin-equivalent paths regularly.</dd><dt><strong>Block cipher vs stream</strong></dt><dd>Block operates on fixed-size chunks; stream on bits/bytes—misuse modes (e.g., ECB) create patterns.</dd><dt><strong>Asset</strong></dt><dd>Anything of value to the organization—data, systems, people, reputation, or services—that security controls protect.</dd><dt><strong>Digital signature</strong></dt><dd>Proves origin and integrity using private key to sign and public key to verify—non-repudiation when keys are well governed.</dd><dt><strong>Zero Trust architecture</strong></dt><dd>Identity-centric access with continuous verification—policy enforcement points for users, devices, and workloads.</dd><dt><strong>Warm site / cold site</strong></dt><dd>Warm has partial hardware ready; cold is space only—cost vs recovery speed tradeoff.</dd><dt><strong>Data classification</strong></dt><dd>Labels (public, internal, confidential, restricted) drive storage, encryption, sharing, and disposal requirements.</dd><dt><strong>CWE</strong></dt><dd>Common Weakness Enumeration—taxonomy of software weakness types that help root-cause fixes beyond one CVE instance.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Cloud responsibility</th><th>Who typically owns it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Patching the hypervisor</strong></td><td>Provider responsibility in major IaaS models—customer still patches guests.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>IAM policy and keys</strong></td><td>Customer-owned configuration—misconfigurations dominate incidents.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Data encryption at rest</strong></td><td>Often customer-controlled keys/KMS policies with provider primitives.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Network exposure (SGs/NACLs)</strong></td><td>Customer configures; default-deny patterns are exam favorites.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Application vulnerabilities</strong></td><td>Customer code and dependencies—shared model does not absolve secure SDLC.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li><li>Responsible disclosure timelines balance vendor patch readiness with public safety—coordinate, don’t surprise.</li><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li><li>DNS over HTTPS changes visibility for some networks—understand resolver policy and logging tradeoffs.</li><li>S3 bucket policies and ACLs layer with IAM—effective permissions require understanding intersection.</li><li>UDP-based protocols can be abused for amplification DDoS—patch open resolvers and monitor volumetric baselines.</li><li>ATT&CK technique IDs are stable references for detection content—good for purple team reporting.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L1-16: Security awareness metrics that are not vanity</em>:</strong> Certificate pinning failures during rotation teach why <strong>key continuity strategy</strong> must be planned before mobile releases.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L1-16: Security awareness metrics that are not vanity</em>:</strong> Identity is the new perimeter: credentials, tokens, and sessions are stolen more often than novel zero-days are burned. Expect Security+ items on MFA bypass awareness, phishing-resistant factors, and why <strong>authorization</strong> must be enforced server-side.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L1-16: Security awareness metrics that are not vanity</em>:</strong> Wireless assessments should mention <strong>rogue AP</strong> discovery, client isolation, and guest segmentation—not just “use WPA2” as a slogan. Exam writers like the distinction between personal and enterprise authentication modes at a conceptual level.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L1-16: Security awareness metrics that are not vanity</em>:</strong> API keys in mobile apps are often extractable—prefer <strong>short-lived tokens</strong> and server-mediated access to backends.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L1-16: Security awareness metrics that are not vanity</em>:</strong> Controls fail in three predictable ways: <strong>misconfiguration</strong>, <strong>missing coverage</strong> (gaps between tools), and <strong>human process</strong> breakdown (exceptions, shared accounts, emergency access). When you read a scenario, ask which failure mode is most plausible before picking an answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L1-16: Security awareness metrics that are not vanity</em>:</strong> Data handling questions often hinge on <strong>classification</strong>, <strong>least data</strong>, and <strong>retention</strong>: collect only what you need, keep it only as long as allowed, and destroy securely when done.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L1-16: Security awareness metrics that are not vanity</em>:</strong> Penetration tests require <strong>written authorization</strong>, defined scope, and rules of engagement—even in internal labs for professional conduct.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L1-16: Security awareness metrics that are not vanity</em>:</strong> Social engineering callbacks to <strong>pretexting</strong>, <strong>baiting</strong>, and <strong>vishing</strong>—name the subtype when the stem describes the tactic.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L1-16: Security awareness metrics that are not vanity</em>:</strong> Physical security is still on the exam: tailgating, visitor escorts, locks, destruction of media, and environmental controls (fire, HVAC) as availability/confidentiality supports.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L1-16: Security awareness metrics that are not vanity</em>:</strong> Cryptojacking still appears: high CPU, unexpected mining pools, and cloud billing spikes—detection plus credential hygiene beats chasing miner signatures alone.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> A cloud bill spike correlates with traffic about “L1-16: Security awareness metrics that are not vanity”. Differentiate <strong>misconfiguration</strong> vs <strong>abuse</strong> in your first triage questions and what logs prove each hypothesis.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l1-17":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L1-17: BYOD, MDM, and mobile threat model</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-17</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Containerized work profile vs full device control; lost-device wipe policy.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Regulatory constraints on personal device inspection.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> List mobile risks (jailbreak, sideload, outdated OS) — 10 bullets, no device compromise.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-17</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Expect “which control type?” questions—administrative vs technical vs physical—tied to realistic workplace moments like contractor onboarding.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 1 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>XSS</strong></dt><dd>Cross-site scripting injects script in a victim context—CSP, output encoding, HttpOnly cookies, and DOM hygiene reduce blast radius.</dd><dt><strong>CVSS</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerability Scoring System—base metrics describe technical severity; environmental and temporal modifiers refine priority.</dd><dt><strong>Shared responsibility model</strong></dt><dd>Cloud provider secures the platform; customer secures configuration, identities, data, and app code in their scope.</dd><dt><strong>CASB / SaaS governance</strong></dt><dd>Visibility and policy for sanctioned vs shadow SaaS—OAuth consent attacks and guest sharing are common gaps.</dd><dt><strong>Supply chain security</strong></dt><dd>SBOM, provenance signing (SLSA-style thinking), and dependency pinning reduce “update from upstream” surprises.</dd><dt><strong>Threat modeling (STRIDE)</strong></dt><dd>Spoofing, tampering, repudiation, information disclosure, denial of service, elevation of privilege—drive controls early.</dd><dt><strong>Job rotation</strong></dt><dd>Reduces collusion and fraud risk; also surfaces “tribal knowledge” silos before an employee leaves.</dd><dt><strong>Certificate transparency (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Public logs of issued certs help detect mis-issued certificates for your domains.</dd><dt><strong>Block cipher vs stream</strong></dt><dd>Block operates on fixed-size chunks; stream on bits/bytes—misuse modes (e.g., ECB) create patterns.</dd><dt><strong>Port knocking (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Obscurity-based pre-auth to open firewall—weak alone; exam may present as non-primary control.</dd><dt><strong>Sinkhole (routing)</strong></dt><dd>Different meaning in BGP—be careful with homonyms on exams; read the stem’s context.</dd><dt><strong>Kill chain / cyber kill chain</strong></dt><dd>Stages of intrusion—mapping controls and detections to stages clarifies coverage gaps.</dd><dt><strong>Security control categories</strong></dt><dd>Technical (firewalls, encryption), administrative (policies, training), and physical (badges, locks)—exam items often ask which category fits a scenario.</dd><dt><strong>Control</strong></dt><dd>Administrative, technical, or physical safeguards that reduce likelihood or impact of a security event (prevent, detect, correct).</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>GraphQL batching can amplify complexity attacks—depth and cost limits are first-class controls.</li><li>ATT&CK technique IDs are stable references for detection content—good for purple team reporting.</li><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li><li>Admission controllers can block privileged pods—policy-as-code integrates with GitOps reviews.</li><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>GCP service account keys are long-lived secrets—prefer workload identity federation from CI where possible.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L1-17: BYOD, MDM, and mobile threat model</em>:</strong> Serverless cold start is not a security control; <strong>per-function IAM</strong> and least-privilege API scopes are. Watch for attractive nonsense distractors tied to performance tuning.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L1-17: BYOD, MDM, and mobile threat model</em>:</strong> Multicloud complexity increases <strong>identity sprawl</strong>; centralized IdP and consistent conditional access policies reduce human error.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L1-17: BYOD, MDM, and mobile threat model</em>:</strong> Air gapped networks still need <strong>patching via sneaker-net</strong> and insider controls—physical isolation is not logical isolation.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L1-17: BYOD, MDM, and mobile threat model</em>:</strong> Security operations value <strong>repeatable evidence</strong>: timestamps, authoritative configuration sources, and tamper-aware logs beat heroic memory after an incident. Many exam questions hinge on whether an action preserves integrity and accountability rather than whether it feels fast.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L1-17: BYOD, MDM, and mobile threat model</em>:</strong> Access control stems frequently mix <strong>role</strong> vs <strong>attribute</strong> vs <strong>rule</strong> models; pick the answer that matches the scenario’s constraints (temporary contractor, cross-department data, dynamic tags on resources).</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L1-17: BYOD, MDM, and mobile threat model</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L1-17: BYOD, MDM, and mobile threat model</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L1-17: BYOD, MDM, and mobile threat model</em>:</strong> Certificate pinning failures during rotation teach why <strong>key continuity strategy</strong> must be planned before mobile releases.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L1-17: BYOD, MDM, and mobile threat model</em>:</strong> Social engineering callbacks to <strong>pretexting</strong>, <strong>baiting</strong>, and <strong>vishing</strong>—name the subtype when the stem describes the tactic.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L1-17: BYOD, MDM, and mobile threat model</em>:</strong> Vulnerability management is a lifecycle: scanners find candidates, analysts prioritize with exploitability and business context, owners remediate, and verification closes the loop. “Patch everything immediately” is rarely operational; <strong>risk-based SLAs</strong> are the adult answer.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> During a tabletop, the CFO asks how “L1-17: BYOD, MDM, and mobile threat model” could become a material incident. Answer with <strong>one plausible attack path</strong>, <strong>one detective control</strong> you already have, and <strong>one preventive gap</strong> you would fund next quarter.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l1-18":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L1-18: Media destruction and secure disposal</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-18</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Clear vs purge vs destroy (NIST SP 800-88 concepts); chain of custody for drives.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> RMA drives with sensitive data; SSD trim implications.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>lsblk -o NAME,SIZE,TYPE,MOUNTPOINT</code>; document how you would <strong>record</strong> serials before decommission.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-18</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>At Level 1, think like an analyst who must <strong>classify</strong> an event: asset, threat, vulnerability, control, residual risk. If you can narrate those five words for any headline topic, you are aligned with how writers build scenario questions.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 1 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>IOC</strong></dt><dd>Indicator of compromise—often ephemeral (IPs, domains); pair with TTP-based detections for durability.</dd><dt><strong>FIDO2 / WebAuthn</strong></dt><dd>Phishing-resistant possession factors using asymmetric crypto and origin binding; preferred where supported.</dd><dt><strong>Shared responsibility model</strong></dt><dd>Cloud provider secures the platform; customer secures configuration, identities, data, and app code in their scope.</dd><dt><strong>ECB mode weakness</strong></dt><dd>Identical plaintext blocks yield identical ciphertext—leaks structure; prefer modes with IVs and authentication.</dd><dt><strong>Asset</strong></dt><dd>Anything of value to the organization—data, systems, people, reputation, or services—that security controls protect.</dd><dt><strong>Encoding (e.g., Base64)</strong></dt><dd>Transforms representation without cryptographic protection—do not confuse with encryption or integrity.</dd><dt><strong>Purple teaming</strong></dt><dd>Collaborative attack/defense exercises to validate detections without surprise production harm—scope and safety first.</dd><dt><strong>TTP</strong></dt><dd>Tactics, techniques, and procedures—behavioral patterns; harder to change than IOCs, better for resilient detection.</dd><dt><strong>Password policy</strong></dt><dd>Modern guidance favors long passphrases, breach-banned lists, and vaults over rotation-for-its-own-sake complexity theater.</dd><dt><strong>IAM least privilege</strong></dt><dd>Grant minimum API/console rights; prefer roles over long-lived keys; audit risky admin-equivalent paths regularly.</dd><dt><strong>IV / nonce</strong></dt><dd>Initialization vector or number-used-once—must be unique per encryption under a key for many modes.</dd><dt><strong>Threat</strong></dt><dd>Any circumstance or actor with the potential to cause harm by exploiting a vulnerability (malware, insider, natural disaster).</dd><dt><strong>Key management</strong></dt><dd>Generation, storage, rotation, and destruction—HSM/KMS patterns reduce exposure compared to software-only secrets.</dd><dt><strong>Purple / red / blue</strong></dt><dd>Red emulates adversaries, blue defends, purple bridges—authorization and logging are mandatory for any simulation.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>PCI DSS scope reduction via segmentation is a recurring theme—if it is not in scope, it cannot drag you into assessment.</li><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li><li>Linux auth.log style entries pair with SSH brute-force detection patterns—velocity and geo anomalies.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li><li>Sigma rules are vendor-agnostic detection snippets—tuning required per log source fields.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L1-18: Media destruction and secure disposal</em>:</strong> Air gapped networks still need <strong>patching via sneaker-net</strong> and insider controls—physical isolation is not logical isolation.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L1-18: Media destruction and secure disposal</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L1-18: Media destruction and secure disposal</em>:</strong> Identity is the new perimeter: credentials, tokens, and sessions are stolen more often than novel zero-days are burned. Expect Security+ items on MFA bypass awareness, phishing-resistant factors, and why <strong>authorization</strong> must be enforced server-side.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L1-18: Media destruction and secure disposal</em>:</strong> Multicloud complexity increases <strong>identity sprawl</strong>; centralized IdP and consistent conditional access policies reduce human error.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L1-18: Media destruction and secure disposal</em>:</strong> Third-party and supply chain answers should emphasize <strong>contracts</strong>, <strong>evidence</strong>, and <strong>continuous monitoring</strong>—not “trust the SOC 2 logo” without scope review.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L1-18: Media destruction and secure disposal</em>:</strong> BIOS/UEFI passwords and secure boot reduce some pre-boot attacks but do not stop <strong>evil maid</strong> classes without additional controls.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L1-18: Media destruction and secure disposal</em>:</strong> Serverless cold start is not a security control; <strong>per-function IAM</strong> and least-privilege API scopes are. Watch for attractive nonsense distractors tied to performance tuning.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L1-18: Media destruction and secure disposal</em>:</strong> Application security scenarios often test whether you know <strong>where</strong> enforcement belongs—browser controls supplement but do not replace server-side checks. SameSite cookies, CSP, and HttpOnly mitigate classes of issues; they do not fix broken object-level authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L1-18: Media destruction and secure disposal</em>:</strong> GraphQL introspection risk is about <strong>schema discovery</strong> aiding attackers—rate limits, authz on fields, and disabling introspection in prod are common answers.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L1-18: Media destruction and secure disposal</em>:</strong> Data handling questions often hinge on <strong>classification</strong>, <strong>least data</strong>, and <strong>retention</strong>: collect only what you need, keep it only as long as allowed, and destroy securely when done.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> You are the on-call analyst reviewing an alert tied to “L1-18: Media destruction and secure disposal”. Leadership wants a <strong>60-second</strong> brief: business impact, evidence gaps, and the <strong>first</strong> containment step that preserves logs. No tool-specific jargon—prioritize scope, evidence, blast radius, then root-cause remediation under change control.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l1-19":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L1-19: Travel security for laptops and MFA devices</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-19</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Border search risks; full-disk encryption; tamper seals (awareness).<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> “Clean travel laptop” programs for high-risk countries.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Check FDE status hints: <code>lsblk -f | head</code>; summarize encryption column meaning.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-19</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Foundations on the exam often pair <strong>policy intent</strong> with <strong>technical examples</strong>—pick answers that show both, not policy theater without enforcement.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 1 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Compensating control</strong></dt><dd>Alternative control that meets intent when primary control cannot be implemented—must provide equivalent or greater assurance with documentation.</dd><dt><strong>Privacy</strong></dt><dd>Protection of personal information and individual rights—overlaps with security but adds legal/regulatory obligations (GDPR-style).</dd><dt><strong>VPN</strong></dt><dd>Creates an encrypted tunnel; split tunneling can bypass corporate inspection; VPN is not anonymity or a substitute for app-layer auth.</dd><dt><strong>Injection</strong></dt><dd>Untrusted input becomes part of a command or query—parameterized queries, input validation, and context escaping are core defenses.</dd><dt><strong>Logging &amp; monitoring</strong></dt><dd>CloudTrail-style management events differ from data-plane logs—enable central export, immutability, and alerting.</dd><dt><strong>PQC</strong></dt><dd>Post-quantum cryptography migration—hybrid schemes and crypto-agility for long-lived secrets exposed to harvest-now/decrypt-later risk.</dd><dt><strong>OCSP stapling (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Server sends fresh revocation info with handshake—reduces client privacy leaks and lookup failures.</dd><dt><strong>Full packet capture</strong></dt><dd>High fidelity evidence for investigations—storage, privacy, and legal review constraints apply.</dd><dt><strong>Perfect forward secrecy (PFS)</strong></dt><dd>Ephemeral key exchange means past session keys are not compromised if long-term keys leak later—TLS cipher suites can offer this property.</dd><dt><strong>Control</strong></dt><dd>Administrative, technical, or physical safeguards that reduce likelihood or impact of a security event (prevent, detect, correct).</dd><dt><strong>FIDO2 / WebAuthn</strong></dt><dd>Phishing-resistant possession factors using asymmetric crypto and origin binding; preferred where supported.</dd><dt><strong>Symmetric encryption</strong></dt><dd>Same key encrypts and decrypts—fast for bulk data (AES-GCM); key distribution is the hard problem.</dd><dt><strong>DevSecOps</strong></dt><dd>Embed security gates in CI/CD with fast feedback—policy-as-code, secret scanning, and SBOMs support supply-chain resilience.</dd><dt><strong>GRC</strong></dt><dd>Governance, risk, and compliance—align security decisions with law, policy, and business appetite; audits test design and operation.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Cloud responsibility</th><th>Who typically owns it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Patching the hypervisor</strong></td><td>Provider responsibility in major IaaS models—customer still patches guests.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>IAM policy and keys</strong></td><td>Customer-owned configuration—misconfigurations dominate incidents.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Data encryption at rest</strong></td><td>Often customer-controlled keys/KMS policies with provider primitives.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Network exposure (SGs/NACLs)</strong></td><td>Customer configures; default-deny patterns are exam favorites.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Application vulnerabilities</strong></td><td>Customer code and dependencies—shared model does not absolve secure SDLC.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>AEAD</strong></td><td>Confidentiality + integrity together—misuse of IV/nonce still breaks security.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>EPSS (concept) scores exploitation probability—useful alongside CVSS for prioritization in mature programs.</li><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li><li>HttpOnly does not stop CSRF; it reduces token theft from XSS reading document.cookie in many setups.</li><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>GraphQL batching can amplify complexity attacks—depth and cost limits are first-class controls.</li><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li><li>Certificate pinning misconfigurations can brick apps—plan rotation and emergency releases.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L1-19: Travel security for laptops and MFA devices</em>:</strong> Wireless assessments should mention <strong>rogue AP</strong> discovery, client isolation, and guest segmentation—not just “use WPA2” as a slogan. Exam writers like the distinction between personal and enterprise authentication modes at a conceptual level.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L1-19: Travel security for laptops and MFA devices</em>:</strong> Air gapped networks still need <strong>patching via sneaker-net</strong> and insider controls—physical isolation is not logical isolation.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L1-19: Travel security for laptops and MFA devices</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L1-19: Travel security for laptops and MFA devices</em>:</strong> TACACS+ vs RADIUS separation of duties in device admin access—exams may contrast accounting granularity.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L1-19: Travel security for laptops and MFA devices</em>:</strong> Third-party and supply chain answers should emphasize <strong>contracts</strong>, <strong>evidence</strong>, and <strong>continuous monitoring</strong>—not “trust the SOC 2 logo” without scope review.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L1-19: Travel security for laptops and MFA devices</em>:</strong> Certificate pinning failures during rotation teach why <strong>key continuity strategy</strong> must be planned before mobile releases.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L1-19: Travel security for laptops and MFA devices</em>:</strong> Wireless and mobility items reward knowing basics: WPA3 improvements conceptually, evil twin risks, captive portals, and why client isolation matters on guest networks—without memorizing obsolete WEP details unless explicitly historical.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L1-19: Travel security for laptops and MFA devices</em>:</strong> GraphQL introspection risk is about <strong>schema discovery</strong> aiding attackers—rate limits, authz on fields, and disabling introspection in prod are common answers.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L1-19: Travel security for laptops and MFA devices</em>:</strong> Advanced topics still return to fundamentals: least privilege, segmentation, logging, and tested recovery. When you see Zero Trust or PQC buzzwords, map them back to concrete controls and threat models rather than treating them as magic shields.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L1-19: Travel security for laptops and MFA devices</em>:</strong> Evidence bags and write blockers signal <strong>forensics awareness</strong>; touching disks before imaging is a classic wrong answer.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Legal asks whether “L1-19: Travel security for laptops and MFA devices” artifacts require <strong>hold</strong> before deletion. Describe how you would <strong>tag systems</strong>, <strong>freeze backups</strong> appropriately, and <strong>escalate</strong> without tipping external actors.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l1-20":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L1-20: Shadow IT and acceptable use in plain language</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-20</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Why unsanctioned SaaS breaks DLP and incident response.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Self-service approved catalog vs blocking alone.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Write a one-page “sanctioned tools” list for a fictional 200-person company.</p>\n<h2>Level 2 extensions</h2>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-20</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Expect “which control type?” questions—administrative vs technical vs physical—tied to realistic workplace moments like contractor onboarding.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 1 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>DNS</strong></dt><dd>Name resolution is a trust anchor—DNSSEC, cache poisoning, and malicious resolutions are classic abuse paths; log resolver anomalies.</dd><dt><strong>Encryption at rest / in transit</strong></dt><dd>KMS/HSM-backed keys, envelope encryption, and TLS everywhere for administrative and user paths.</dd><dt><strong>Collision (hash)</strong></dt><dd>Two inputs produce same hash—breaks integrity assumptions; choose strong hash families for security use.</dd><dt><strong>Risk</strong></dt><dd>The intersection of threat, vulnerability, and impact—often assessed qualitatively (high/medium/low) or with scoring frameworks.</dd><dt><strong>PKI</strong></dt><dd>Public Key Infrastructure—CAs, RAs, CRL/OCSP, and certificate lifecycle; mis-issuance or weak validation breaks trust chains.</dd><dt><strong>Metrics that matter</strong></dt><dd>Mean time to detect/remediate with quality, coverage of critical assets, and control effectiveness—not vanity ticket counts.</dd><dt><strong>WAF vs IPS</strong></dt><dd>WAF focuses on application-layer attacks; IPS often line-rate network signatures—overlap exists but priorities differ.</dd><dt><strong>PII</strong></dt><dd>Personally identifiable information—names, government IDs, biometrics, account numbers; triggers handling, retention, and breach rules.</dd><dt><strong>Security headers</strong></dt><dd>HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options/Frame-ancestors, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy—reduce browser-driven attack surface.</dd><dt><strong>SOC triage order</strong></dt><dd>Scope → impact → evidence → containment hypothesis; avoid fixing symptoms before you know blast radius.</dd><dt><strong>Kill chain / cyber kill chain</strong></dt><dd>Stages of intrusion—mapping controls and detections to stages clarifies coverage gaps.</dd><dt><strong>DDoS</strong></dt><dd>Distributed denial of service—volumetric, protocol, or application-layer floods; mitigations include scrubbing, anycast, rate limits, and architecture elasticity.</dd><dt><strong>Shared responsibility model</strong></dt><dd>Cloud provider secures the platform; customer secures configuration, identities, data, and app code in their scope.</dd><dt><strong>CRL</strong></dt><dd>Certificate Revocation List—signed list of revoked serials; size/latency issues drove OCSP adoption.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li><li>S3 bucket policies and ACLs layer with IAM—effective permissions require understanding intersection.</li><li>ISO 27001 is an ISMS standard; it emphasizes risk treatment and continual improvement, not a product checklist.</li><li>Immutable backups mitigate ransomware that tries to delete online copies—air-gapped or WORM patterns.</li><li>Admission controllers can block privileged pods—policy-as-code integrates with GitOps reviews.</li><li>UDP-based protocols can be abused for amplification DDoS—patch open resolvers and monitor volumetric baselines.</li><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L1-20: Shadow IT and acceptable use in plain language</em>:</strong> Cryptojacking still appears: high CPU, unexpected mining pools, and cloud billing spikes—detection plus credential hygiene beats chasing miner signatures alone.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L1-20: Shadow IT and acceptable use in plain language</em>:</strong> Identity is the new perimeter: credentials, tokens, and sessions are stolen more often than novel zero-days are burned. Expect Security+ items on MFA bypass awareness, phishing-resistant factors, and why <strong>authorization</strong> must be enforced server-side.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L1-20: Shadow IT and acceptable use in plain language</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L1-20: Shadow IT and acceptable use in plain language</em>:</strong> Cryptography questions reward vocabulary precision: hashing vs encryption vs encoding; symmetric vs asymmetric roles in TLS; what signatures prove; and why key management is usually harder than picking an algorithm. If an answer sounds magical, it is probably wrong.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L1-20: Shadow IT and acceptable use in plain language</em>:</strong> SAST finds issues early but produces false positives; <strong>triage workflows</strong> and developer feedback loops are part of a mature program, not “run tool once.”</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L1-20: Shadow IT and acceptable use in plain language</em>:</strong> Application security scenarios often test whether you know <strong>where</strong> enforcement belongs—browser controls supplement but do not replace server-side checks. SameSite cookies, CSP, and HttpOnly mitigate classes of issues; they do not fix broken object-level authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L1-20: Shadow IT and acceptable use in plain language</em>:</strong> DAST exercises running apps but misses authz logic without credentials; combine with <strong>manual review</strong> for business-rule flaws.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L1-20: Shadow IT and acceptable use in plain language</em>:</strong> Vulnerability management is a lifecycle: scanners find candidates, analysts prioritize with exploitability and business context, owners remediate, and verification closes the loop. “Patch everything immediately” is rarely operational; <strong>risk-based SLAs</strong> are the adult answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L1-20: Shadow IT and acceptable use in plain language</em>:</strong> Penetration tests require <strong>written authorization</strong>, defined scope, and rules of engagement—even in internal labs for professional conduct.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L1-20: Shadow IT and acceptable use in plain language</em>:</strong> Incident response questions probe containment vs evidence preservation tension, legal escalation, and communication discipline. The exam rewards knowing when to isolate systems, when to involve counsel, and why mass log deletion is catastrophic.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Legal asks whether “L1-20: Shadow IT and acceptable use in plain language” artifacts require <strong>hold</strong> before deletion. Describe how you would <strong>tag systems</strong>, <strong>freeze backups</strong> appropriately, and <strong>escalate</strong> without tipping external actors.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l2-16":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L2-16: Server-side request forgery (SSRF) — defender view</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-16</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Why allowlists beat blocklists for outbound fetchers; metadata cloud attacks (concept).<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> AppSec review checklist item for “URL fetch” features.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Pseudocode <code>fetchUserSuppliedUrl(url)</code> with <strong>scheme/host allowlist</strong> and DNS rebinding note (no exploit).</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-16</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Level 2 tracks Security+ <strong>architecture and hybrid environments</strong>: trust boundaries, TLS/certificates, DNS/email controls, VPN caveats, and headline application flaws. Explain <em>why</em> a control exists and <em>what misconfiguration breaks</em>.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 2 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Digital signature</strong></dt><dd>Proves origin and integrity using private key to sign and public key to verify—non-repudiation when keys are well governed.</dd><dt><strong>Supply chain security</strong></dt><dd>SBOM, provenance signing (SLSA-style thinking), and dependency pinning reduce “update from upstream” surprises.</dd><dt><strong>Proxy vs reverse proxy</strong></dt><dd>Forward proxy represents clients outbound; reverse proxy fronts servers—different trust and logging points.</dd><dt><strong>Privacy</strong></dt><dd>Protection of personal information and individual rights—overlaps with security but adds legal/regulatory obligations (GDPR-style).</dd><dt><strong>IDOR</strong></dt><dd>Insecure direct object reference—missing object-level authorization; test horizontal/vertical access with different accounts.</dd><dt><strong>Business continuity testing</strong></dt><dd>Tabletops and technical failover drills reveal gaps in comms, dependencies, and vendor SLAs.</dd><dt><strong>Diamond model</strong></dt><dd>Adversary, infrastructure, capability, victim—useful for pivoting investigations and intel fusion.</dd><dt><strong>NAT (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Rewrites addresses/ports for traversal—security relevance includes logging visibility, port forwarding risks, and split tunnel implications for inspection.</dd><dt><strong>Chain of custody</strong></dt><dd>Documented handling of evidence from collection through presentation—hashing, write blockers, and access logs support admissibility.</dd><dt><strong>OCSP stapling (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Server sends fresh revocation info with handshake—reduces client privacy leaks and lookup failures.</dd><dt><strong>Asset</strong></dt><dd>Anything of value to the organization—data, systems, people, reputation, or services—that security controls protect.</dd><dt><strong>Certificate pinning (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Client remembers expected server key material—reduces MITM from rogue CAs but complicates rotation; mostly seen in mobile/API hardening patterns.</dd><dt><strong>Third-party risk</strong></dt><dd>Vendor access expands attack surface—DPAs, SOC reports, and continuous monitoring for critical suppliers.</dd><dt><strong>Diffie-Hellman (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Key agreement over insecure channel—combine with authentication to prevent MITM.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Typical exam angle</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Confidentiality</strong></td><td>Who may read? Encryption, ACLs, DLP, classification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Integrity</strong></td><td>Was it modified? Hashing, signatures, change control, backups.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Availability</strong></td><td>Can authorized users work? HA, patching windows, DDoS defense, DR.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authenticity / non-repudiation</strong></td><td>Prove source and intent—signatures, strong issuance, tamper-evident logs.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>S3 bucket policies and ACLs layer with IAM—effective permissions require understanding intersection.</li><li>OAuth access tokens are not a replacement for server-side authorization checks on every sensitive action.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>Bug bounty scope must exclude destructive testing—safe harbor language still needs legal review.</li><li>Sigma rules are vendor-agnostic detection snippets—tuning required per log source fields.</li><li>Admission controllers can block privileged pods—policy-as-code integrates with GitOps reviews.</li><li>PCI DSS scope reduction via segmentation is a recurring theme—if it is not in scope, it cannot drag you into assessment.</li><li>DNS over HTTPS changes visibility for some networks—understand resolver policy and logging tradeoffs.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L2-16: Server-side request forgery (SSRF) — defender view</em>:</strong> Vulnerability management is a lifecycle: scanners find candidates, analysts prioritize with exploitability and business context, owners remediate, and verification closes the loop. “Patch everything immediately” is rarely operational; <strong>risk-based SLAs</strong> are the adult answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L2-16: Server-side request forgery (SSRF) — defender view</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L2-16: Server-side request forgery (SSRF) — defender view</em>:</strong> Ransomware stems often pair encryption with <strong>exfiltration</strong>—the correct answer may include legal/notification obligations, not only restoring from backup.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L2-16: Server-side request forgery (SSRF) — defender view</em>:</strong> Certificate pinning failures during rotation teach why <strong>key continuity strategy</strong> must be planned before mobile releases.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L2-16: Server-side request forgery (SSRF) — defender view</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L2-16: Server-side request forgery (SSRF) — defender view</em>:</strong> Advanced topics still return to fundamentals: least privilege, segmentation, logging, and tested recovery. When you see Zero Trust or PQC buzzwords, map them back to concrete controls and threat models rather than treating them as magic shields.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L2-16: Server-side request forgery (SSRF) — defender view</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L2-16: Server-side request forgery (SSRF) — defender view</em>:</strong> DAST exercises running apps but misses authz logic without credentials; combine with <strong>manual review</strong> for business-rule flaws.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L2-16: Server-side request forgery (SSRF) — defender view</em>:</strong> Honeypots can generate high-signal alerts but carry <strong>legal and operational</strong> risk if touched by real users; scope carefully.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L2-16: Server-side request forgery (SSRF) — defender view</em>:</strong> Security operations value <strong>repeatable evidence</strong>: timestamps, authoritative configuration sources, and tamper-aware logs beat heroic memory after an incident. Many exam questions hinge on whether an action preserves integrity and accountability rather than whether it feels fast.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> During a tabletop, the CFO asks how “L2-16: Server-side request forgery (SSRF) — defender view” could become a material incident. Answer with <strong>one plausible attack path</strong>, <strong>one detective control</strong> you already have, and <strong>one preventive gap</strong> you would fund next quarter.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l2-17":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L2-17: XXE and unsafe deserialization (recognition only)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-17</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> XML external entities; never deserialize untrusted objects.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Serialization bombs and gadget chains in Java/.NET/Python ecosystems.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Find your language’s official safe XML/deserialization guidance — 5 bullet summary + URLs.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-17</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Application-layer stems sneak in early: know where <strong>authorization</strong> must be enforced even if TLS is perfect.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 2 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>DevSecOps</strong></dt><dd>Embed security gates in CI/CD with fast feedback—policy-as-code, secret scanning, and SBOMs support supply-chain resilience.</dd><dt><strong>Authenticity</strong></dt><dd>Verifies that users, devices, or data are genuine—cryptographic identity, attestation, and strong issuance processes matter.</dd><dt><strong>TLS</strong></dt><dd>Encrypts data in motion and authenticates endpoints when certificates and hostnames are validated; termination points affect trust boundaries.</dd><dt><strong>Security misconfiguration</strong></dt><dd>Default creds, debug features on in prod, verbose errors, open directory listings—hardening baselines and drift detection reduce this class.</dd><dt><strong>Shared responsibility model</strong></dt><dd>Cloud provider secures the platform; customer secures configuration, identities, data, and app code in their scope.</dd><dt><strong>Attack surface</strong></dt><dd>The sum of exposure—every service, API, integration, and human workflow that can be reached by a threat; reduction beats perfect monitoring alone.</dd><dt><strong>Downgrade attack</strong></dt><dd>Forcing weaker crypto or protocols—HSTS and modern TLS config reduce browser downgrade paths.</dd><dt><strong>Proxy vs reverse proxy</strong></dt><dd>Forward proxy represents clients outbound; reverse proxy fronts servers—different trust and logging points.</dd><dt><strong>Data residency</strong></dt><dd>Legal requirement for where data lives—impacts cloud region selection and key custody.</dd><dt><strong>Vulnerability</strong></dt><dd>A weakness in design, implementation, configuration, or process that could be exploited to violate a security policy.</dd><dt><strong>Authorization</strong></dt><dd>What an authenticated subject is allowed to do—RBAC/ABAC, scopes, and server-side checks enforce least privilege.</dd><dt><strong>Perfect forward secrecy (PFS)</strong></dt><dd>Ephemeral key exchange means past session keys are not compromised if long-term keys leak later—TLS cipher suites can offer this property.</dd><dt><strong>Security headers</strong></dt><dd>HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options/Frame-ancestors, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy—reduce browser-driven attack surface.</dd><dt><strong>Serverless blast radius</strong></dt><dd>One broad execution role affects every invocation—scope IAM per function and watch environment variable leaks.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Typical exam angle</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Confidentiality</strong></td><td>Who may read? Encryption, ACLs, DLP, classification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Integrity</strong></td><td>Was it modified? Hashing, signatures, change control, backups.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Availability</strong></td><td>Can authorized users work? HA, patching windows, DDoS defense, DR.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authenticity / non-repudiation</strong></td><td>Prove source and intent—signatures, strong issuance, tamper-evident logs.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Immutable backups mitigate ransomware that tries to delete online copies—air-gapped or WORM patterns.</li><li>PCI DSS scope reduction via segmentation is a recurring theme—if it is not in scope, it cannot drag you into assessment.</li><li>Azure AD / Entra conditional access is analogous to risk-based policies—device compliance signals matter.</li><li>Certificate pinning misconfigurations can brick apps—plan rotation and emergency releases.</li><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li><li>Bug bounty scope must exclude destructive testing—safe harbor language still needs legal review.</li><li>Race conditions in web apps can undermine authorization—sequential logic tests in secure design reviews.</li><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L2-17: XXE and unsafe deserialization (recognition only)</em>:</strong> Governance and awareness questions tie policy to behavior: acceptable use, clean desk, travel security, and vendor due diligence. Pick answers that reduce <strong>realistic</strong> human failure modes, not answers that maximize surveillance without process support.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L2-17: XXE and unsafe deserialization (recognition only)</em>:</strong> Wireless assessments should mention <strong>rogue AP</strong> discovery, client isolation, and guest segmentation—not just “use WPA2” as a slogan. Exam writers like the distinction between personal and enterprise authentication modes at a conceptual level.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L2-17: XXE and unsafe deserialization (recognition only)</em>:</strong> SAST finds issues early but produces false positives; <strong>triage workflows</strong> and developer feedback loops are part of a mature program, not “run tool once.”</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L2-17: XXE and unsafe deserialization (recognition only)</em>:</strong> TACACS+ vs RADIUS separation of duties in device admin access—exams may contrast accounting granularity.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L2-17: XXE and unsafe deserialization (recognition only)</em>:</strong> Defense in depth is not “more products,” it is <strong>independent mechanisms</strong>—if one layer is bypassed, another still limits movement, slows the adversary, or preserves evidence. Be ready to explain why network controls alone cannot compensate for missing app-layer authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L2-17: XXE and unsafe deserialization (recognition only)</em>:</strong> Wireless and mobility items reward knowing basics: WPA3 improvements conceptually, evil twin risks, captive portals, and why client isolation matters on guest networks—without memorizing obsolete WEP details unless explicitly historical.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L2-17: XXE and unsafe deserialization (recognition only)</em>:</strong> When logs “mysteriously stop,” think <strong>time sync failure</strong>, collector saturation, retention misconfiguration, or attacker tampering—in that diagnostic order for a fair exam narrative.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L2-17: XXE and unsafe deserialization (recognition only)</em>:</strong> Evidence bags and write blockers signal <strong>forensics awareness</strong>; touching disks before imaging is a classic wrong answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L2-17: XXE and unsafe deserialization (recognition only)</em>:</strong> Virtualization risks include <strong>snapshot sprawl</strong> containing secrets and stale VM images drifting from hardened baselines.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L2-17: XXE and unsafe deserialization (recognition only)</em>:</strong> Cryptography questions reward vocabulary precision: hashing vs encryption vs encoding; symmetric vs asymmetric roles in TLS; what signatures prove; and why key management is usually harder than picking an algorithm. If an answer sounds magical, it is probably wrong.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Marketing launches a campaign referencing “L2-17: XXE and unsafe deserialization (recognition only)” with a new subdomain. Security review finds DNS delegated to an unknown party. Explain <strong>trust chain</strong> risks and the <strong>minimum fixes</strong> before go-live.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l2-18":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L2-18: Path traversal and unsafe file upload handling</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-18</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Canonicalize paths; store uploads outside web root; content-type vs content sniffing.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Ticket triage for “arbitrary file read” findings.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> On paper, show why <code>GET /download?file=....//....//etc/passwd</code> is blocked by basename + root jail.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-18</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Level 2 tracks Security+ <strong>architecture and hybrid environments</strong>: trust boundaries, TLS/certificates, DNS/email controls, VPN caveats, and headline application flaws. Explain <em>why</em> a control exists and <em>what misconfiguration breaks</em>.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 2 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Confidentiality</strong></dt><dd>Assures that information is not disclosed to unauthorized subjects—encryption, access control, and data minimization support it.</dd><dt><strong>SPF / DKIM / DMARC</strong></dt><dd>Email authenticity stack—SPF authorizes senders, DKIM signs messages, DMARC aligns policies and reporting for abuse handling.</dd><dt><strong>CVE</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures identifier for a specific flaw—pairs with CVSS severity and vendor advisories for prioritization.</dd><dt><strong>Metrics that matter</strong></dt><dd>Mean time to detect/remediate with quality, coverage of critical assets, and control effectiveness—not vanity ticket counts.</dd><dt><strong>Salt (crypto)</strong></dt><dd>Random input to a password hash to defeat rainbow tables—must be unique per password.</dd><dt><strong>OODA loop (IR)</strong></dt><dd>Observe-orient-decide-act—adversary and defender both iterate; faster, accurate decisions beat hoarding data.</dd><dt><strong>Threat</strong></dt><dd>Any circumstance or actor with the potential to cause harm by exploiting a vulnerability (malware, insider, natural disaster).</dd><dt><strong>SSO</strong></dt><dd>Single sign-on federates trust to an IdP—misconfigured SAML/OIDC trusts are high-impact; validate metadata and signing keys.</dd><dt><strong>Security misconfiguration</strong></dt><dd>Default creds, debug features on in prod, verbose errors, open directory listings—hardening baselines and drift detection reduce this class.</dd><dt><strong>Serverless blast radius</strong></dt><dd>One broad execution role affects every invocation—scope IAM per function and watch environment variable leaks.</dd><dt><strong>Mandatory vacation</strong></dt><dd>Forces handover and review of another employee’s work—can uncover fraud or backdoors.</dd><dt><strong>WAF vs IPS</strong></dt><dd>WAF focuses on application-layer attacks; IPS often line-rate network signatures—overlap exists but priorities differ.</dd><dt><strong>CSRF</strong></dt><dd>Cross-site request forgery rides ambient auth—anti-CSRF tokens, SameSite cookies, and re-auth for sensitive actions help.</dd><dt><strong>Privacy</strong></dt><dd>Protection of personal information and individual rights—overlaps with security but adds legal/regulatory obligations (GDPR-style).</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>IR phase</th><th>What you do there (exam shorthand)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Prepare</strong></td><td>Playbooks, contacts, tooling, baseline logging—before the pager fires.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detect &amp; analyze</strong></td><td>Scope, timelines, hypotheses—preserve volatile evidence early.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Contain</strong></td><td>Stop spread with minimal evidence damage—network isolation variants matter.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Eradicate &amp; recover</strong></td><td>Remove persistence, patch root cause, restore with verification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Lessons learned</strong></td><td>Metrics, control changes, and communication improvements—close the loop.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authorization</strong></td><td>Server-side object checks—headers and TLS do not replace this.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>S3 bucket policies and ACLs layer with IAM—effective permissions require understanding intersection.</li><li>UDP-based protocols can be abused for amplification DDoS—patch open resolvers and monitor volumetric baselines.</li><li>ATT&CK technique IDs are stable references for detection content—good for purple team reporting.</li><li>JWT alg:none historical vulnerability class—always validate algorithm and signature keys explicitly.</li><li>GCP service account keys are long-lived secrets—prefer workload identity federation from CI where possible.</li><li>PCI DSS scope reduction via segmentation is a recurring theme—if it is not in scope, it cannot drag you into assessment.</li><li>Linux auth.log style entries pair with SSH brute-force detection patterns—velocity and geo anomalies.</li><li>Race conditions in web apps can undermine authorization—sequential logic tests in secure design reviews.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L2-18: Path traversal and unsafe file upload handling</em>:</strong> Tabletop exercises test <strong>comms trees</strong>, legal escalation, and customer notification templates—not only technical runbooks.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L2-18: Path traversal and unsafe file upload handling</em>:</strong> Certificate pinning failures during rotation teach why <strong>key continuity strategy</strong> must be planned before mobile releases.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L2-18: Path traversal and unsafe file upload handling</em>:</strong> Virtualization risks include <strong>snapshot sprawl</strong> containing secrets and stale VM images drifting from hardened baselines.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L2-18: Path traversal and unsafe file upload handling</em>:</strong> For the Security+ mindset, translate every control into <strong>who</strong> it protects, <strong>what</strong> asset is at risk, and <strong>how</strong> you would detect failure. Interview and exam items often reward practical prioritization over buzzwords—choose the mitigation that reduces realistic loss first.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L2-18: Path traversal and unsafe file upload handling</em>:</strong> Application security scenarios often test whether you know <strong>where</strong> enforcement belongs—browser controls supplement but do not replace server-side checks. SameSite cookies, CSP, and HttpOnly mitigate classes of issues; they do not fix broken object-level authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L2-18: Path traversal and unsafe file upload handling</em>:</strong> Access control stems frequently mix <strong>role</strong> vs <strong>attribute</strong> vs <strong>rule</strong> models; pick the answer that matches the scenario’s constraints (temporary contractor, cross-department data, dynamic tags on resources).</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L2-18: Path traversal and unsafe file upload handling</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L2-18: Path traversal and unsafe file upload handling</em>:</strong> When logs “mysteriously stop,” think <strong>time sync failure</strong>, collector saturation, retention misconfiguration, or attacker tampering—in that diagnostic order for a fair exam narrative.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L2-18: Path traversal and unsafe file upload handling</em>:</strong> Cryptojacking still appears: high CPU, unexpected mining pools, and cloud billing spikes—detection plus credential hygiene beats chasing miner signatures alone.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L2-18: Path traversal and unsafe file upload handling</em>:</strong> Multicloud complexity increases <strong>identity sprawl</strong>; centralized IdP and consistent conditional access policies reduce human error.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Junior staff proposes a quick fix for “L2-18: Path traversal and unsafe file upload handling” that disables logging on a noisy host. Walk through why that is unacceptable and propose a <strong>tuning</strong> path that preserves <strong>integrity and retention</strong> commitments.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l2-19":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L2-19: HTTP request smuggling (awareness for architects)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-19</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Conflicting Content-Length/Transfer-Encoding parsing between front proxy and origin.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Why standardized reverse proxy configs and patch velocity matter.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Read PortSwigger or RFC-level summary; write 6-sentence executive brief for architects.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-19</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>TLS questions separate <strong>confidentiality channel</strong> from <strong>server authentication</strong>—certificate validation and hostname checks matter in the answer set.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 2 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>TTP</strong></dt><dd>Tactics, techniques, and procedures—behavioral patterns; harder to change than IOCs, better for resilient detection.</dd><dt><strong>Authenticity</strong></dt><dd>Verifies that users, devices, or data are genuine—cryptographic identity, attestation, and strong issuance processes matter.</dd><dt><strong>Key management</strong></dt><dd>Generation, storage, rotation, and destruction—HSM/KMS patterns reduce exposure compared to software-only secrets.</dd><dt><strong>Security awareness</strong></dt><dd>Training plus culture—measure reporting rates, not shame metrics; phishing simulations should reinforce reporting.</dd><dt><strong>Block cipher vs stream</strong></dt><dd>Block operates on fixed-size chunks; stream on bits/bytes—misuse modes (e.g., ECB) create patterns.</dd><dt><strong>Firewall</strong></dt><dd>Enforces allow/deny rules on traffic—stateful inspection tracks sessions; default-deny with explicit permits is the secure baseline.</dd><dt><strong>FIDO2 / WebAuthn</strong></dt><dd>Phishing-resistant possession factors using asymmetric crypto and origin binding; preferred where supported.</dd><dt><strong>IDOR</strong></dt><dd>Insecure direct object reference—missing object-level authorization; test horizontal/vertical access with different accounts.</dd><dt><strong>PQC</strong></dt><dd>Post-quantum cryptography migration—hybrid schemes and crypto-agility for long-lived secrets exposed to harvest-now/decrypt-later risk.</dd><dt><strong>Jump server / bastion</strong></dt><dd>Hardened administrative entry point—centralizes session recording and access policy for admins.</dd><dt><strong>Compensating control</strong></dt><dd>Alternative control that meets intent when primary control cannot be implemented—must provide equivalent or greater assurance with documentation.</dd><dt><strong>SIEM</strong></dt><dd>Security information and event management—centralize logs, parse fields, correlate alerts; tuning reduces false positives and fatigue.</dd><dt><strong>Separation of duties (SoD)</strong></dt><dd>No single person can complete a sensitive transaction alone—classic finance control that also limits insider abuse.</dd><dt><strong>RPO / RTO recap</strong></dt><dd>RPO = max acceptable data loss time; RTO = max acceptable outage—drive backup frequency and HA design.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Cloud responsibility</th><th>Who typically owns it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Patching the hypervisor</strong></td><td>Provider responsibility in major IaaS models—customer still patches guests.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>IAM policy and keys</strong></td><td>Customer-owned configuration—misconfigurations dominate incidents.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Data encryption at rest</strong></td><td>Often customer-controlled keys/KMS policies with provider primitives.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Network exposure (SGs/NACLs)</strong></td><td>Customer configures; default-deny patterns are exam favorites.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Application vulnerabilities</strong></td><td>Customer code and dependencies—shared model does not absolve secure SDLC.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>GraphQL batching can amplify complexity attacks—depth and cost limits are first-class controls.</li><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li><li>Certificate pinning misconfigurations can brick apps—plan rotation and emergency releases.</li><li>AES-128 is not “half as strong” as AES-256 in practical threat models for many cases—key management quality dominates.</li><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li><li>SLSA levels describe increasing supply-chain assurance—useful vocabulary in modern governance questions.</li><li>Linux auth.log style entries pair with SSH brute-force detection patterns—velocity and geo anomalies.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L2-19: HTTP request smuggling (awareness for architects)</em>:</strong> When logs “mysteriously stop,” think <strong>time sync failure</strong>, collector saturation, retention misconfiguration, or attacker tampering—in that diagnostic order for a fair exam narrative.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L2-19: HTTP request smuggling (awareness for architects)</em>:</strong> Vulnerability management is a lifecycle: scanners find candidates, analysts prioritize with exploitability and business context, owners remediate, and verification closes the loop. “Patch everything immediately” is rarely operational; <strong>risk-based SLAs</strong> are the adult answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L2-19: HTTP request smuggling (awareness for architects)</em>:</strong> RADIUS is still referenced for <strong>network access control</strong> integrations; know it as a AAA component in enterprise Wi-Fi contexts.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L2-19: HTTP request smuggling (awareness for architects)</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L2-19: HTTP request smuggling (awareness for architects)</em>:</strong> Incident response questions probe containment vs evidence preservation tension, legal escalation, and communication discipline. The exam rewards knowing when to isolate systems, when to involve counsel, and why mass log deletion is catastrophic.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L2-19: HTTP request smuggling (awareness for architects)</em>:</strong> TACACS+ vs RADIUS separation of duties in device admin access—exams may contrast accounting granularity.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L2-19: HTTP request smuggling (awareness for architects)</em>:</strong> Container escape questions hinge on <strong>kernel boundary</strong> and misconfigured capabilities—namespaces are helpful but not a complete trust boundary without seccomp, AppArmor, and least-privileged service accounts.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L2-19: HTTP request smuggling (awareness for architects)</em>:</strong> Cloud items assume you can articulate <strong>shared responsibility</strong>: what the provider patches vs what the customer must configure (IAM, encryption, network exposure). Misconfiguration beats novel cloud exploits in real incidents and on the exam.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L2-19: HTTP request smuggling (awareness for architects)</em>:</strong> Honeypots can generate high-signal alerts but carry <strong>legal and operational</strong> risk if touched by real users; scope carefully.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L2-19: HTTP request smuggling (awareness for architects)</em>:</strong> Serverless cold start is not a security control; <strong>per-function IAM</strong> and least-privilege API scopes are. Watch for attractive nonsense distractors tied to performance tuning.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> You are the on-call analyst reviewing an alert tied to “L2-19: HTTP request smuggling (awareness for architects)”. Leadership wants a <strong>60-second</strong> brief: business impact, evidence gaps, and the <strong>first</strong> containment step that preserves logs. No tool-specific jargon—prioritize scope, evidence, blast radius, then root-cause remediation under change control.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l2-20":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L2-20: WebSockets — origin checks, auth, and message framing</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-20</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> WS is not “just another socket”; session binding and rate limits still apply.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Real-time dashboards, chat, collaborative editors.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>curl -i -N -H &#39;Connection: Upgrade&#39; -H &#39;Upgrade: websocket&#39; https://example.com 2&gt;/dev/null | head</code> — explain why handshake failed without proper headers (read-only).</p>\n<h2>Level 3 extensions</h2>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-20</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>TLS questions separate <strong>confidentiality channel</strong> from <strong>server authentication</strong>—certificate validation and hostname checks matter in the answer set.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 2 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Full packet capture</strong></dt><dd>High fidelity evidence for investigations—storage, privacy, and legal review constraints apply.</dd><dt><strong>Input validation vs output encoding</strong></dt><dd>Validation rejects bad input early; encoding neutralizes dangerous characters in the right output context—both are needed across HTML, SQL, OS, and LDAP channels.</dd><dt><strong>Control</strong></dt><dd>Administrative, technical, or physical safeguards that reduce likelihood or impact of a security event (prevent, detect, correct).</dd><dt><strong>FIDO2 / WebAuthn</strong></dt><dd>Phishing-resistant possession factors using asymmetric crypto and origin binding; preferred where supported.</dd><dt><strong>Symmetric encryption</strong></dt><dd>Same key encrypts and decrypts—fast for bulk data (AES-GCM); key distribution is the hard problem.</dd><dt><strong>DevSecOps</strong></dt><dd>Embed security gates in CI/CD with fast feedback—policy-as-code, secret scanning, and SBOMs support supply-chain resilience.</dd><dt><strong>GRC</strong></dt><dd>Governance, risk, and compliance—align security decisions with law, policy, and business appetite; audits test design and operation.</dd><dt><strong>Business continuity testing</strong></dt><dd>Tabletops and technical failover drills reveal gaps in comms, dependencies, and vendor SLAs.</dd><dt><strong>Block cipher vs stream</strong></dt><dd>Block operates on fixed-size chunks; stream on bits/bytes—misuse modes (e.g., ECB) create patterns.</dd><dt><strong>Warm site / cold site</strong></dt><dd>Warm has partial hardware ready; cold is space only—cost vs recovery speed tradeoff.</dd><dt><strong>IDOR</strong></dt><dd>Insecure direct object reference—missing object-level authorization; test horizontal/vertical access with different accounts.</dd><dt><strong>Confidentiality</strong></dt><dd>Assures that information is not disclosed to unauthorized subjects—encryption, access control, and data minimization support it.</dd><dt><strong>DDoS</strong></dt><dd>Distributed denial of service—volumetric, protocol, or application-layer floods; mitigations include scrubbing, anycast, rate limits, and architecture elasticity.</dd><dt><strong>Key management</strong></dt><dd>Generation, storage, rotation, and destruction—HSM/KMS patterns reduce exposure compared to software-only secrets.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authorization</strong></td><td>Server-side object checks—headers and TLS do not replace this.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>HttpOnly does not stop CSRF; it reduces token theft from XSS reading document.cookie in many setups.</li><li>Linux auth.log style entries pair with SSH brute-force detection patterns—velocity and geo anomalies.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>Admission controllers can block privileged pods—policy-as-code integrates with GitOps reviews.</li><li>SBOM formats (CycloneDX/SPDX) help inventory components for incident response and licensing—not only security.</li><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li><li>Immutable backups mitigate ransomware that tries to delete online copies—air-gapped or WORM patterns.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L2-20: WebSockets — origin checks, auth, and message framing</em>:</strong> KMS keys are not “magic secrecy dust”—<strong>who can invoke decrypt</strong> and from which contexts (VPC endpoint policies, IAM conditions) is what exams probe.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L2-20: WebSockets — origin checks, auth, and message framing</em>:</strong> RADIUS is still referenced for <strong>network access control</strong> integrations; know it as a AAA component in enterprise Wi-Fi contexts.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L2-20: WebSockets — origin checks, auth, and message framing</em>:</strong> Identity is the new perimeter: credentials, tokens, and sessions are stolen more often than novel zero-days are burned. Expect Security+ items on MFA bypass awareness, phishing-resistant factors, and why <strong>authorization</strong> must be enforced server-side.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L2-20: WebSockets — origin checks, auth, and message framing</em>:</strong> Engineers often optimize for speed; attackers optimize for <strong>cheap reuse</strong> of stolen creds and known exploits. The winning answer bridges both: ship fast with guardrails—feature flags, staged rollouts, and automated security checks in CI.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L2-20: WebSockets — origin checks, auth, and message framing</em>:</strong> Penetration tests require <strong>written authorization</strong>, defined scope, and rules of engagement—even in internal labs for professional conduct.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L2-20: WebSockets — origin checks, auth, and message framing</em>:</strong> TPM-backed BitLocker keys illustrate <strong>key protection</strong> binding to platform state—recovery keys must be guarded like crown jewels.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L2-20: WebSockets — origin checks, auth, and message framing</em>:</strong> Advanced topics still return to fundamentals: least privilege, segmentation, logging, and tested recovery. When you see Zero Trust or PQC buzzwords, map them back to concrete controls and threat models rather than treating them as magic shields.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L2-20: WebSockets — origin checks, auth, and message framing</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L2-20: WebSockets — origin checks, auth, and message framing</em>:</strong> Subresource integrity protects against <strong>CDN compromise</strong> but requires operational discipline when vendors rotate files.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L2-20: WebSockets — origin checks, auth, and message framing</em>:</strong> Defense in depth is not “more products,” it is <strong>independent mechanisms</strong>—if one layer is bypassed, another still limits movement, slows the adversary, or preserves evidence. Be ready to explain why network controls alone cannot compensate for missing app-layer authorization.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> A vendor integration project mentions “L2-20: WebSockets — origin checks, auth, and message framing” as out-of-scope for pen testing. Explain what <strong>residual risk</strong> remains, what <strong>compensating monitoring</strong> you would demand, and how you would <strong>document acceptance</strong>.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l3-16":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L3-16: Vulnerability scan vs credentialed scan vs pentest vs red team</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-16</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Scope, depth, business risk; what each can and cannot prove.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Contract SoW language; avoid “scan = secure.”<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Write a 1-page SoW outline for a <strong>credentialed</strong> internal scan with stop conditions.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-16</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>IR stems test <strong>containment vs evidence</strong> tension—choose actions that preserve hashes and legal escalation paths.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 3 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Due diligence</strong></dt><dd>Investigation and verification before decisions (vendor risk, M&amp;A) to ensure claims about controls are credible.</dd><dt><strong>Certificate pinning (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Client remembers expected server key material—reduces MITM from rogue CAs but complicates rotation; mostly seen in mobile/API hardening patterns.</dd><dt><strong>Logging &amp; monitoring</strong></dt><dd>CloudTrail-style management events differ from data-plane logs—enable central export, immutability, and alerting.</dd><dt><strong>Data loss prevention (DLP)</strong></dt><dd>Content-aware controls to block or alert on sensitive data movement—policy + tech, tuned to avoid blocking work.</dd><dt><strong>MTTD / MTTR</strong></dt><dd>Mean time to detect / remediate—quality matters; gaming metrics by closing tickets inflates false success.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>IR phase</th><th>What you do there (exam shorthand)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Prepare</strong></td><td>Playbooks, contacts, tooling, baseline logging—before the pager fires.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detect &amp; analyze</strong></td><td>Scope, timelines, hypotheses—preserve volatile evidence early.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Contain</strong></td><td>Stop spread with minimal evidence damage—network isolation variants matter.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Eradicate &amp; recover</strong></td><td>Remove persistence, patch root cause, restore with verification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Lessons learned</strong></td><td>Metrics, control changes, and communication improvements—close the loop.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>UDP-based protocols can be abused for amplification DDoS—patch open resolvers and monitor volumetric baselines.</li><li>HttpOnly does not stop CSRF; it reduces token theft from XSS reading document.cookie in many setups.</li><li>Linux auth.log style entries pair with SSH brute-force detection patterns—velocity and geo anomalies.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>Admission controllers can block privileged pods—policy-as-code integrates with GitOps reviews.</li><li>SBOM formats (CycloneDX/SPDX) help inventory components for incident response and licensing—not only security.</li><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L3-16: Vulnerability scan vs credentialed scan vs pentest vs red team</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L3-16: Vulnerability scan vs credentialed scan vs pentest vs red team</em>:</strong> Advanced topics still return to fundamentals: least privilege, segmentation, logging, and tested recovery. When you see Zero Trust or PQC buzzwords, map them back to concrete controls and threat models rather than treating them as magic shields.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L3-16: Vulnerability scan vs credentialed scan vs pentest vs red team</em>:</strong> RADIUS is still referenced for <strong>network access control</strong> integrations; know it as a AAA component in enterprise Wi-Fi contexts.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L3-16: Vulnerability scan vs credentialed scan vs pentest vs red team</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L3-16: Vulnerability scan vs credentialed scan vs pentest vs red team</em>:</strong> Controls fail in three predictable ways: <strong>misconfiguration</strong>, <strong>missing coverage</strong> (gaps between tools), and <strong>human process</strong> breakdown (exceptions, shared accounts, emergency access). When you read a scenario, ask which failure mode is most plausible before picking an answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L3-16: Vulnerability scan vs credentialed scan vs pentest vs red team</em>:</strong> DAST exercises running apps but misses authz logic without credentials; combine with <strong>manual review</strong> for business-rule flaws.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L3-16: Vulnerability scan vs credentialed scan vs pentest vs red team</em>:</strong> Access control stems frequently mix <strong>role</strong> vs <strong>attribute</strong> vs <strong>rule</strong> models; pick the answer that matches the scenario’s constraints (temporary contractor, cross-department data, dynamic tags on resources).</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L3-16: Vulnerability scan vs credentialed scan vs pentest vs red team</em>:</strong> Honeypots can generate high-signal alerts but carry <strong>legal and operational</strong> risk if touched by real users; scope carefully.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L3-16: Vulnerability scan vs credentialed scan vs pentest vs red team</em>:</strong> Email security stems often combine SPF alignment failures with <strong>look-alike domains</strong>. The best answer addresses user training plus technical authenticity controls, not only one or the other.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L3-16: Vulnerability scan vs credentialed scan vs pentest vs red team</em>:</strong> Security operations value <strong>repeatable evidence</strong>: timestamps, authoritative configuration sources, and tamper-aware logs beat heroic memory after an incident. Many exam questions hinge on whether an action preserves integrity and accountability rather than whether it feels fast.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> During a tabletop, the CFO asks how “L3-16: Vulnerability scan vs credentialed scan vs pentest vs red team” could become a material incident. Answer with <strong>one plausible attack path</strong>, <strong>one detective control</strong> you already have, and <strong>one preventive gap</strong> you would fund next quarter.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l3-17":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L3-17: OpenVAS/Greenbone-style workflow without firing bullets</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-17</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Policy templates, false positives, authenticated checks, change windows.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> VM team coordination; snapshot before intrusive plugins.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> If Greenbone installed in lab: explore UI <strong>read-only</strong>; export a CSV header row only and describe fields.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-17</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Threat modeling at this level stays <strong>STRIDE-shaped</strong>—name the abuse, then map a proportional control.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 3 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>SOC triage order</strong></dt><dd>Scope → impact → evidence → containment hypothesis; avoid fixing symptoms before you know blast radius.</dd><dt><strong>Right to be forgotten (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Privacy request to delete data—may conflict with legal hold; counsel resolves precedence.</dd><dt><strong>Firewall</strong></dt><dd>Enforces allow/deny rules on traffic—stateful inspection tracks sessions; default-deny with explicit permits is the secure baseline.</dd><dt><strong>GRC</strong></dt><dd>Governance, risk, and compliance—align security decisions with law, policy, and business appetite; audits test design and operation.</dd><dt><strong>Proxy vs reverse proxy</strong></dt><dd>Forward proxy represents clients outbound; reverse proxy fronts servers—different trust and logging points.</dd><dt><strong>Integrity</strong></dt><dd>Assures accuracy and trustworthiness—hashing, signatures, change control, and backups protect against unauthorized modification.</dd><dt><strong>Secure SDLC</strong></dt><dd>Requirements, threat modeling, secure design, code review, SAST/DAST, dependency scanning, and hardened deployment pipelines.</dd><dt><strong>Replay attack</strong></dt><dd>Valid data maliciously re-sent—nonces, timestamps, and session freshness mitigate.</dd><dt><strong>IDOR</strong></dt><dd>Insecure direct object reference—missing object-level authorization; test horizontal/vertical access with different accounts.</dd><dt><strong>Perfect forward secrecy (PFS)</strong></dt><dd>Ephemeral key exchange means past session keys are not compromised if long-term keys leak later—TLS cipher suites can offer this property.</dd><dt><strong>Metrics that matter</strong></dt><dd>Mean time to detect/remediate with quality, coverage of critical assets, and control effectiveness—not vanity ticket counts.</dd><dt><strong>RPO / RTO recap</strong></dt><dd>RPO = max acceptable data loss time; RTO = max acceptable outage—drive backup frequency and HA design.</dd><dt><strong>Authentication</strong></dt><dd>Proving identity—something you know, have, or are; combine factors for MFA; never equate login with authorization alone.</dd><dt><strong>MITRE ATT&amp;CK</strong></dt><dd>Tactics (why) and techniques (how) adversaries operate—use for detection engineering, gap analysis, and purple team scenarios.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>IR phase</th><th>What you do there (exam shorthand)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Prepare</strong></td><td>Playbooks, contacts, tooling, baseline logging—before the pager fires.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detect &amp; analyze</strong></td><td>Scope, timelines, hypotheses—preserve volatile evidence early.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Contain</strong></td><td>Stop spread with minimal evidence damage—network isolation variants matter.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Eradicate &amp; recover</strong></td><td>Remove persistence, patch root cause, restore with verification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Lessons learned</strong></td><td>Metrics, control changes, and communication improvements—close the loop.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authorization</strong></td><td>Server-side object checks—headers and TLS do not replace this.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Server-side template injection is distinct from XSS—context and sinks differ.</li><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li><li>Admission controllers can block privileged pods—policy-as-code integrates with GitOps reviews.</li><li>S3 bucket policies and ACLs layer with IAM—effective permissions require understanding intersection.</li><li>Azure AD / Entra conditional access is analogous to risk-based policies—device compliance signals matter.</li><li>Terraform state can hold secrets—remote secure backend and scanning are baseline hygiene.</li><li>SLSA levels describe increasing supply-chain assurance—useful vocabulary in modern governance questions.</li><li>Responsible disclosure timelines balance vendor patch readiness with public safety—coordinate, don’t surprise.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L3-17: OpenVAS/Greenbone-style workflow without firing bullets</em>:</strong> Controls fail in three predictable ways: <strong>misconfiguration</strong>, <strong>missing coverage</strong> (gaps between tools), and <strong>human process</strong> breakdown (exceptions, shared accounts, emergency access). When you read a scenario, ask which failure mode is most plausible before picking an answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L3-17: OpenVAS/Greenbone-style workflow without firing bullets</em>:</strong> KMS keys are not “magic secrecy dust”—<strong>who can invoke decrypt</strong> and from which contexts (VPC endpoint policies, IAM conditions) is what exams probe.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L3-17: OpenVAS/Greenbone-style workflow without firing bullets</em>:</strong> Defense in depth is not “more products,” it is <strong>independent mechanisms</strong>—if one layer is bypassed, another still limits movement, slows the adversary, or preserves evidence. Be ready to explain why network controls alone cannot compensate for missing app-layer authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L3-17: OpenVAS/Greenbone-style workflow without firing bullets</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L3-17: OpenVAS/Greenbone-style workflow without firing bullets</em>:</strong> Security operations value <strong>repeatable evidence</strong>: timestamps, authoritative configuration sources, and tamper-aware logs beat heroic memory after an incident. Many exam questions hinge on whether an action preserves integrity and accountability rather than whether it feels fast.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L3-17: OpenVAS/Greenbone-style workflow without firing bullets</em>:</strong> Ransomware stems often pair encryption with <strong>exfiltration</strong>—the correct answer may include legal/notification obligations, not only restoring from backup.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L3-17: OpenVAS/Greenbone-style workflow without firing bullets</em>:</strong> Risk decisions are economic: organizations <strong>accept</strong>, <strong>mitigate</strong>, <strong>transfer</strong> (insurance, outsourcing with contracts), or <strong>avoid</strong> (stop the activity). Controls change likelihood or impact; residual risk should be explicit, not invisible.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L3-17: OpenVAS/Greenbone-style workflow without firing bullets</em>:</strong> Cryptojacking still appears: high CPU, unexpected mining pools, and cloud billing spikes—detection plus credential hygiene beats chasing miner signatures alone.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L3-17: OpenVAS/Greenbone-style workflow without firing bullets</em>:</strong> Identity is the new perimeter: credentials, tokens, and sessions are stolen more often than novel zero-days are burned. Expect Security+ items on MFA bypass awareness, phishing-resistant factors, and why <strong>authorization</strong> must be enforced server-side.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L3-17: OpenVAS/Greenbone-style workflow without firing bullets</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Junior staff proposes a quick fix for “L3-17: OpenVAS/Greenbone-style workflow without firing bullets” that disables logging on a noisy host. Walk through why that is unacceptable and propose a <strong>tuning</strong> path that preserves <strong>integrity and retention</strong> commitments.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l3-18":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L3-18: WAF value, limits, and tuning partnership with devs</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-18</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Virtual patching vs root-cause fix; false positive burnout.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Block mode vs detect mode during rollout.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> List 5 attack classes a WAF helps with and 3 it often misses (logic bugs, stolen sessions…).</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-18</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>IR stems test <strong>containment vs evidence</strong> tension—choose actions that preserve hashes and legal escalation paths.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 3 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Network segmentation</strong></dt><dd>VLANs, micro-segmentation, and east-west controls limit lateral movement after an initial foothold.</dd><dt><strong>Input validation vs output encoding</strong></dt><dd>Validation rejects bad input early; encoding neutralizes dangerous characters in the right output context—both are needed across HTML, SQL, OS, and LDAP channels.</dd><dt><strong>CVSS</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerability Scoring System—base metrics describe technical severity; environmental and temporal modifiers refine priority.</dd><dt><strong>Encryption at rest / in transit</strong></dt><dd>KMS/HSM-backed keys, envelope encryption, and TLS everywhere for administrative and user paths.</dd><dt><strong>Metrics that matter</strong></dt><dd>Mean time to detect/remediate with quality, coverage of critical assets, and control effectiveness—not vanity ticket counts.</dd><dt><strong>SOC triage order</strong></dt><dd>Scope → impact → evidence → containment hypothesis; avoid fixing symptoms before you know blast radius.</dd><dt><strong>CRL</strong></dt><dd>Certificate Revocation List—signed list of revoked serials; size/latency issues drove OCSP adoption.</dd><dt><strong>MITM</strong></dt><dd>Man-in-the-middle intercepts or alters traffic—TLS with proper validation mitigates; corporate SSL inspection is its own trust zone.</dd><dt><strong>Warm site / cold site</strong></dt><dd>Warm has partial hardware ready; cold is space only—cost vs recovery speed tradeoff.</dd><dt><strong>NAT (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Rewrites addresses/ports for traversal—security relevance includes logging visibility, port forwarding risks, and split tunnel implications for inspection.</dd><dt><strong>Compensating control</strong></dt><dd>Alternative control that meets intent when primary control cannot be implemented—must provide equivalent or greater assurance with documentation.</dd><dt><strong>Policy vs standard vs procedure</strong></dt><dd>Policy states intent; standards define mandatory requirements; procedures are step-by-step how-to for operators.</dd><dt><strong>MFA</strong></dt><dd>Multi-factor authentication—requires two or more independent factors; push fatigue and MFA phishing are real bypass paths.</dd><dt><strong>DNS</strong></dt><dd>Name resolution is a trust anchor—DNSSEC, cache poisoning, and malicious resolutions are classic abuse paths; log resolver anomalies.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>IR phase</th><th>What you do there (exam shorthand)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Prepare</strong></td><td>Playbooks, contacts, tooling, baseline logging—before the pager fires.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detect &amp; analyze</strong></td><td>Scope, timelines, hypotheses—preserve volatile evidence early.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Contain</strong></td><td>Stop spread with minimal evidence damage—network isolation variants matter.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Eradicate &amp; recover</strong></td><td>Remove persistence, patch root cause, restore with verification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Lessons learned</strong></td><td>Metrics, control changes, and communication improvements—close the loop.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Admission controllers can block privileged pods—policy-as-code integrates with GitOps reviews.</li><li>UDP-based protocols can be abused for amplification DDoS—patch open resolvers and monitor volumetric baselines.</li><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li><li>AES-128 is not “half as strong” as AES-256 in practical threat models for many cases—key management quality dominates.</li><li>ATT&CK technique IDs are stable references for detection content—good for purple team reporting.</li><li>Server-side template injection is distinct from XSS—context and sinks differ.</li><li>Bug bounty scope must exclude destructive testing—safe harbor language still needs legal review.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L3-18: WAF value, limits, and tuning partnership with devs</em>:</strong> Identity is the new perimeter: credentials, tokens, and sessions are stolen more often than novel zero-days are burned. Expect Security+ items on MFA bypass awareness, phishing-resistant factors, and why <strong>authorization</strong> must be enforced server-side.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L3-18: WAF value, limits, and tuning partnership with devs</em>:</strong> Multicloud complexity increases <strong>identity sprawl</strong>; centralized IdP and consistent conditional access policies reduce human error.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L3-18: WAF value, limits, and tuning partnership with devs</em>:</strong> Third-party and supply chain answers should emphasize <strong>contracts</strong>, <strong>evidence</strong>, and <strong>continuous monitoring</strong>—not “trust the SOC 2 logo” without scope review.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L3-18: WAF value, limits, and tuning partnership with devs</em>:</strong> BIOS/UEFI passwords and secure boot reduce some pre-boot attacks but do not stop <strong>evil maid</strong> classes without additional controls.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L3-18: WAF value, limits, and tuning partnership with devs</em>:</strong> Serverless cold start is not a security control; <strong>per-function IAM</strong> and least-privilege API scopes are. Watch for attractive nonsense distractors tied to performance tuning.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L3-18: WAF value, limits, and tuning partnership with devs</em>:</strong> Application security scenarios often test whether you know <strong>where</strong> enforcement belongs—browser controls supplement but do not replace server-side checks. SameSite cookies, CSP, and HttpOnly mitigate classes of issues; they do not fix broken object-level authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L3-18: WAF value, limits, and tuning partnership with devs</em>:</strong> GraphQL introspection risk is about <strong>schema discovery</strong> aiding attackers—rate limits, authz on fields, and disabling introspection in prod are common answers.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L3-18: WAF value, limits, and tuning partnership with devs</em>:</strong> Data handling questions often hinge on <strong>classification</strong>, <strong>least data</strong>, and <strong>retention</strong>: collect only what you need, keep it only as long as allowed, and destroy securely when done.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L3-18: WAF value, limits, and tuning partnership with devs</em>:</strong> Sanitization vs wiping vs destruction: exams like knowing which media needs <strong>degaussing, shredding, or crypto erase</strong> per policy.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L3-18: WAF value, limits, and tuning partnership with devs</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> A cloud bill spike correlates with traffic about “L3-18: WAF value, limits, and tuning partnership with devs”. Differentiate <strong>misconfiguration</strong> vs <strong>abuse</strong> in your first triage questions and what logs prove each hypothesis.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l3-19":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L3-19: Reverse shell vs bind shell — what SOC sees</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-19</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Outbound C2 vs inbound listener; beaconing jitter (concept).<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Firewall egress allowlisting; proxy logs.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>ss -tn state established | head</code> — explain tuple fields for anomaly hunting (no C2).</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-19</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Threat modeling at this level stays <strong>STRIDE-shaped</strong>—name the abuse, then map a proportional control.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 3 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Encryption at rest / in transit</strong></dt><dd>KMS/HSM-backed keys, envelope encryption, and TLS everywhere for administrative and user paths.</dd><dt><strong>Collision (hash)</strong></dt><dd>Two inputs produce same hash—breaks integrity assumptions; choose strong hash families for security use.</dd><dt><strong>Risk</strong></dt><dd>The intersection of threat, vulnerability, and impact—often assessed qualitatively (high/medium/low) or with scoring frameworks.</dd><dt><strong>PKI</strong></dt><dd>Public Key Infrastructure—CAs, RAs, CRL/OCSP, and certificate lifecycle; mis-issuance or weak validation breaks trust chains.</dd><dt><strong>Metrics that matter</strong></dt><dd>Mean time to detect/remediate with quality, coverage of critical assets, and control effectiveness—not vanity ticket counts.</dd><dt><strong>WAF vs IPS</strong></dt><dd>WAF focuses on application-layer attacks; IPS often line-rate network signatures—overlap exists but priorities differ.</dd><dt><strong>PII</strong></dt><dd>Personally identifiable information—names, government IDs, biometrics, account numbers; triggers handling, retention, and breach rules.</dd><dt><strong>Security headers</strong></dt><dd>HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options/Frame-ancestors, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy—reduce browser-driven attack surface.</dd><dt><strong>SOC triage order</strong></dt><dd>Scope → impact → evidence → containment hypothesis; avoid fixing symptoms before you know blast radius.</dd><dt><strong>Kill chain / cyber kill chain</strong></dt><dd>Stages of intrusion—mapping controls and detections to stages clarifies coverage gaps.</dd><dt><strong>DDoS</strong></dt><dd>Distributed denial of service—volumetric, protocol, or application-layer floods; mitigations include scrubbing, anycast, rate limits, and architecture elasticity.</dd><dt><strong>Shared responsibility model</strong></dt><dd>Cloud provider secures the platform; customer secures configuration, identities, data, and app code in their scope.</dd><dt><strong>CRL</strong></dt><dd>Certificate Revocation List—signed list of revoked serials; size/latency issues drove OCSP adoption.</dd><dt><strong>Threat</strong></dt><dd>Any circumstance or actor with the potential to cause harm by exploiting a vulnerability (malware, insider, natural disaster).</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Typical exam angle</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Confidentiality</strong></td><td>Who may read? Encryption, ACLs, DLP, classification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Integrity</strong></td><td>Was it modified? Hashing, signatures, change control, backups.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Availability</strong></td><td>Can authorized users work? HA, patching windows, DDoS defense, DR.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authenticity / non-repudiation</strong></td><td>Prove source and intent—signatures, strong issuance, tamper-evident logs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>KMS key policies can deny even root in AWS when configured—explicit deny wins.</li><li>DNS over HTTPS changes visibility for some networks—understand resolver policy and logging tradeoffs.</li><li>HttpOnly does not stop CSRF; it reduces token theft from XSS reading document.cookie in many setups.</li><li>SLSA levels describe increasing supply-chain assurance—useful vocabulary in modern governance questions.</li><li>Server-side template injection is distinct from XSS—context and sinks differ.</li><li>Sigma rules are vendor-agnostic detection snippets—tuning required per log source fields.</li><li>UDP-based protocols can be abused for amplification DDoS—patch open resolvers and monitor volumetric baselines.</li><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L3-19: Reverse shell vs bind shell — what SOC sees</em>:</strong> Clean desk pairs with <strong>screen privacy</strong> and <strong>clear desk checks</strong> for regulated spaces—physical + procedural controls together.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L3-19: Reverse shell vs bind shell — what SOC sees</em>:</strong> Identity is the new perimeter: credentials, tokens, and sessions are stolen more often than novel zero-days are burned. Expect Security+ items on MFA bypass awareness, phishing-resistant factors, and why <strong>authorization</strong> must be enforced server-side.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L3-19: Reverse shell vs bind shell — what SOC sees</em>:</strong> Advanced topics still return to fundamentals: least privilege, segmentation, logging, and tested recovery. When you see Zero Trust or PQC buzzwords, map them back to concrete controls and threat models rather than treating them as magic shields.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L3-19: Reverse shell vs bind shell — what SOC sees</em>:</strong> Business continuity answers should reference <strong>RTO/RPO</strong>, <strong>workarounds</strong>, and <strong>tested restores</strong>; DR without practiced failover is wishful thinking, and exam writers know it.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L3-19: Reverse shell vs bind shell — what SOC sees</em>:</strong> Industrial and OT adjacent questions reward knowing <strong>safety vs security</strong> tension: availability may trump confidentiality; testing must avoid breaking physical processes.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L3-19: Reverse shell vs bind shell — what SOC sees</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L3-19: Reverse shell vs bind shell — what SOC sees</em>:</strong> Tabletop exercises test <strong>comms trees</strong>, legal escalation, and customer notification templates—not only technical runbooks.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L3-19: Reverse shell vs bind shell — what SOC sees</em>:</strong> Certificate pinning failures during rotation teach why <strong>key continuity strategy</strong> must be planned before mobile releases.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L3-19: Reverse shell vs bind shell — what SOC sees</em>:</strong> Virtualization risks include <strong>snapshot sprawl</strong> containing secrets and stale VM images drifting from hardened baselines.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L3-19: Reverse shell vs bind shell — what SOC sees</em>:</strong> For the Security+ mindset, translate every control into <strong>who</strong> it protects, <strong>what</strong> asset is at risk, and <strong>how</strong> you would detect failure. Interview and exam items often reward practical prioritization over buzzwords—choose the mitigation that reduces realistic loss first.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Purple team wants to simulate abuse of “L3-19: Reverse shell vs bind shell — what SOC sees” next Friday. List <strong>safety gates</strong> (scope, rollback, monitoring) you require before authorizing the exercise.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l3-20":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L3-20: YARA and file classification at scale</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-20</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Rules, strings, false positives; hunting vs blocking.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Threat intel feeds feeding EDR/SOAR.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Author a benign YARA rule matching <code>LearnHub</code> in <code>~/rules/hello.yar</code>; run <code>yarac</code> if installed or document install step.</p>\n<h2>Level 4 extensions</h2>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-20</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Detection engineering stems want you to connect <strong>data sources</strong> to <strong>hypothesis</strong>—what log field proves the story?</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 3 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Integrity</strong></dt><dd>Assures accuracy and trustworthiness—hashing, signatures, change control, and backups protect against unauthorized modification.</dd><dt><strong>Password policy</strong></dt><dd>Modern guidance favors long passphrases, breach-banned lists, and vaults over rotation-for-its-own-sake complexity theater.</dd><dt><strong>SPF / DKIM / DMARC</strong></dt><dd>Email authenticity stack—SPF authorizes senders, DKIM signs messages, DMARC aligns policies and reporting for abuse handling.</dd><dt><strong>Key management</strong></dt><dd>Generation, storage, rotation, and destruction—HSM/KMS patterns reduce exposure compared to software-only secrets.</dd><dt><strong>DevSecOps</strong></dt><dd>Embed security gates in CI/CD with fast feedback—policy-as-code, secret scanning, and SBOMs support supply-chain resilience.</dd><dt><strong>Logging &amp; monitoring</strong></dt><dd>CloudTrail-style management events differ from data-plane logs—enable central export, immutability, and alerting.</dd><dt><strong>Data retention</strong></dt><dd>Shorter retention reduces exposure and cost—legal holds override routine deletion when investigations require preservation.</dd><dt><strong>Forensics basics</strong></dt><dd>Volatile vs non-volatile collection, order of volatility, hashing, and legal escalation paths before deep technical work.</dd><dt><strong>Certificate transparency (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Public logs of issued certs help detect mis-issued certificates for your domains.</dd><dt><strong>HMAC</strong></dt><dd>Keyed hash construction—common for API authenticity when symmetric secret is shared out-of-band.</dd><dt><strong>BGP prefix hijack</strong></dt><dd>Unauthorized route advertisement—RPKI ROV reduces impact but does not replace monitoring.</dd><dt><strong>Data residency</strong></dt><dd>Legal requirement for where data lives—impacts cloud region selection and key custody.</dd><dt><strong>Compensating control</strong></dt><dd>Alternative control that meets intent when primary control cannot be implemented—must provide equivalent or greater assurance with documentation.</dd><dt><strong>Policy vs standard vs procedure</strong></dt><dd>Policy states intent; standards define mandatory requirements; procedures are step-by-step how-to for operators.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>GCP service account keys are long-lived secrets—prefer workload identity federation from CI where possible.</li><li>ATT&CK technique IDs are stable references for detection content—good for purple team reporting.</li><li>S3 bucket policies and ACLs layer with IAM—effective permissions require understanding intersection.</li><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li><li>OAuth access tokens are not a replacement for server-side authorization checks on every sensitive action.</li><li>Server-side template injection is distinct from XSS—context and sinks differ.</li><li>ISO 27001 is an ISMS standard; it emphasizes risk treatment and continual improvement, not a product checklist.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L3-20: YARA and file classification at scale</em>:</strong> GraphQL introspection risk is about <strong>schema discovery</strong> aiding attackers—rate limits, authz on fields, and disabling introspection in prod are common answers.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L3-20: YARA and file classification at scale</em>:</strong> Honeypots can generate high-signal alerts but carry <strong>legal and operational</strong> risk if touched by real users; scope carefully.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L3-20: YARA and file classification at scale</em>:</strong> Social engineering callbacks to <strong>pretexting</strong>, <strong>baiting</strong>, and <strong>vishing</strong>—name the subtype when the stem describes the tactic.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L3-20: YARA and file classification at scale</em>:</strong> Risk decisions are economic: organizations <strong>accept</strong>, <strong>mitigate</strong>, <strong>transfer</strong> (insurance, outsourcing with contracts), or <strong>avoid</strong> (stop the activity). Controls change likelihood or impact; residual risk should be explicit, not invisible.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L3-20: YARA and file classification at scale</em>:</strong> Governance and awareness questions tie policy to behavior: acceptable use, clean desk, travel security, and vendor due diligence. Pick answers that reduce <strong>realistic</strong> human failure modes, not answers that maximize surveillance without process support.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L3-20: YARA and file classification at scale</em>:</strong> Third-party and supply chain answers should emphasize <strong>contracts</strong>, <strong>evidence</strong>, and <strong>continuous monitoring</strong>—not “trust the SOC 2 logo” without scope review.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L3-20: YARA and file classification at scale</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L3-20: YARA and file classification at scale</em>:</strong> KMS keys are not “magic secrecy dust”—<strong>who can invoke decrypt</strong> and from which contexts (VPC endpoint policies, IAM conditions) is what exams probe.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L3-20: YARA and file classification at scale</em>:</strong> Penetration tests require <strong>written authorization</strong>, defined scope, and rules of engagement—even in internal labs for professional conduct.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L3-20: YARA and file classification at scale</em>:</strong> Subresource integrity protects against <strong>CDN compromise</strong> but requires operational discipline when vendors rotate files.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> A vendor integration project mentions “L3-20: YARA and file classification at scale” as out-of-scope for pen testing. Explain what <strong>residual risk</strong> remains, what <strong>compensating monitoring</strong> you would demand, and how you would <strong>document acceptance</strong>.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l4-16":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L4-16: Identity protection signals (Impossible travel, unfamiliar properties)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-16</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Reduce false positives with graph and HR context.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Privacy review for location signals; union rules.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Mock CSV of 10 sign-ins; mark 2 suspicious with reasons (velocity, ASN, device).</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-16</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Vendor risk items reward <strong>continuous monitoring</strong> and <strong>contractual evidence</strong>, not one-time PDF collection.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 4 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Data classification</strong></dt><dd>Labels (public, internal, confidential, restricted) drive storage, encryption, sharing, and disposal requirements.</dd><dt><strong>CWE</strong></dt><dd>Common Weakness Enumeration—taxonomy of software weakness types that help root-cause fixes beyond one CVE instance.</dd><dt><strong>Certificate transparency (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Public logs of issued certs help detect mis-issued certificates for your domains.</dd><dt><strong>PKI</strong></dt><dd>Public Key Infrastructure—CAs, RAs, CRL/OCSP, and certificate lifecycle; mis-issuance or weak validation breaks trust chains.</dd><dt><strong>Zero Trust (headline)</strong></dt><dd>Assume breach; verify explicitly per request using identity, device posture, and least privilege—not “trust the LAN.”</dd><dt><strong>Security awareness</strong></dt><dd>Training plus culture—measure reporting rates, not shame metrics; phishing simulations should reinforce reporting.</dd><dt><strong>WAF vs IPS</strong></dt><dd>WAF focuses on application-layer attacks; IPS often line-rate network signatures—overlap exists but priorities differ.</dd><dt><strong>Confidentiality</strong></dt><dd>Assures that information is not disclosed to unauthorized subjects—encryption, access control, and data minimization support it.</dd><dt><strong>CSRF</strong></dt><dd>Cross-site request forgery rides ambient auth—anti-CSRF tokens, SameSite cookies, and re-auth for sensitive actions help.</dd><dt><strong>Job rotation</strong></dt><dd>Reduces collusion and fraud risk; also surfaces “tribal knowledge” silos before an employee leaves.</dd><dt><strong>Right to be forgotten (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Privacy request to delete data—may conflict with legal hold; counsel resolves precedence.</dd><dt><strong>DDoS</strong></dt><dd>Distributed denial of service—volumetric, protocol, or application-layer floods; mitigations include scrubbing, anycast, rate limits, and architecture elasticity.</dd><dt><strong>Encryption at rest / in transit</strong></dt><dd>KMS/HSM-backed keys, envelope encryption, and TLS everywhere for administrative and user paths.</dd><dt><strong>MAC</strong></dt><dd>Message authentication code—integrity with a secret key; differs from digital signature which uses asymmetric keys.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>AEAD</strong></td><td>Confidentiality + integrity together—misuse of IV/nonce still breaks security.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li><li>Responsible disclosure timelines balance vendor patch readiness with public safety—coordinate, don’t surprise.</li><li>CVSS base does not include your asset criticality—environmental metrics exist for a reason.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>GCP service account keys are long-lived secrets—prefer workload identity federation from CI where possible.</li><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li><li>Admission controllers can block privileged pods—policy-as-code integrates with GitOps reviews.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L4-16: Identity protection signals (Impossible travel, unfamiliar properties)</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L4-16: Identity protection signals (Impossible travel, unfamiliar properties)</em>:</strong> Physical security is still on the exam: tailgating, visitor escorts, locks, destruction of media, and environmental controls (fire, HVAC) as availability/confidentiality supports.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L4-16: Identity protection signals (Impossible travel, unfamiliar properties)</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L4-16: Identity protection signals (Impossible travel, unfamiliar properties)</em>:</strong> TACACS+ vs RADIUS separation of duties in device admin access—exams may contrast accounting granularity.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L4-16: Identity protection signals (Impossible travel, unfamiliar properties)</em>:</strong> Cryptography questions reward vocabulary precision: hashing vs encryption vs encoding; symmetric vs asymmetric roles in TLS; what signatures prove; and why key management is usually harder than picking an algorithm. If an answer sounds magical, it is probably wrong.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L4-16: Identity protection signals (Impossible travel, unfamiliar properties)</em>:</strong> Help desk scenarios test whether you know <strong>identity proofing</strong> vs <strong>account recovery</strong> abuse. The secure path verifies the human through out-of-band channels without teaching attackers how to bypass your process in the stem text.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L4-16: Identity protection signals (Impossible travel, unfamiliar properties)</em>:</strong> Tabletop exercises test <strong>comms trees</strong>, legal escalation, and customer notification templates—not only technical runbooks.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L4-16: Identity protection signals (Impossible travel, unfamiliar properties)</em>:</strong> Sanitization vs wiping vs destruction: exams like knowing which media needs <strong>degaussing, shredding, or crypto erase</strong> per policy.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L4-16: Identity protection signals (Impossible travel, unfamiliar properties)</em>:</strong> Logging questions often test whether you understand <strong>what to log</strong> (who, what, when, where, outcome), <strong>time sync</strong> for correlation, and <strong>tamper resistance</strong> for evidentiary value—not whether you can collect infinite bytes.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L4-16: Identity protection signals (Impossible travel, unfamiliar properties)</em>:</strong> Container escape questions hinge on <strong>kernel boundary</strong> and misconfigured capabilities—namespaces are helpful but not a complete trust boundary without seccomp, AppArmor, and least-privileged service accounts.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Legal asks whether “L4-16: Identity protection signals (Impossible travel, unfamiliar properties)” artifacts require <strong>hold</strong> before deletion. Describe how you would <strong>tag systems</strong>, <strong>freeze backups</strong> appropriately, and <strong>escalate</strong> without tipping external actors.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l4-17":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L4-17: Kubernetes RBAC, service accounts, and token projection</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-17</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Default SA risks; least privilege for controllers.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Namespace isolation is not security boundary alone.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> If minikube/k3s in lab: <code>kubectl auth can-i --list --as=system:serviceaccount:default:default</code> — interpret danger.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-17</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Purple team references test <strong>authorization to simulate</strong> and <strong>logging of exercises</strong>—safety and auditability matter.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 4 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Compensating control</strong></dt><dd>Alternative control that meets intent when primary control cannot be implemented—must provide equivalent or greater assurance with documentation.</dd><dt><strong>Policy vs standard vs procedure</strong></dt><dd>Policy states intent; standards define mandatory requirements; procedures are step-by-step how-to for operators.</dd><dt><strong>MFA</strong></dt><dd>Multi-factor authentication—requires two or more independent factors; push fatigue and MFA phishing are real bypass paths.</dd><dt><strong>DNS</strong></dt><dd>Name resolution is a trust anchor—DNSSEC, cache poisoning, and malicious resolutions are classic abuse paths; log resolver anomalies.</dd><dt><strong>PKI</strong></dt><dd>Public Key Infrastructure—CAs, RAs, CRL/OCSP, and certificate lifecycle; mis-issuance or weak validation breaks trust chains.</dd><dt><strong>Security headers</strong></dt><dd>HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options/Frame-ancestors, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy—reduce browser-driven attack surface.</dd><dt><strong>Shared responsibility model</strong></dt><dd>Cloud provider secures the platform; customer secures configuration, identities, data, and app code in their scope.</dd><dt><strong>Security awareness</strong></dt><dd>Training plus culture—measure reporting rates, not shame metrics; phishing simulations should reinforce reporting.</dd><dt><strong>Purple teaming</strong></dt><dd>Collaborative attack/defense exercises to validate detections without surprise production harm—scope and safety first.</dd><dt><strong>Replay attack</strong></dt><dd>Valid data maliciously re-sent—nonces, timestamps, and session freshness mitigate.</dd><dt><strong>IV / nonce</strong></dt><dd>Initialization vector or number-used-once—must be unique per encryption under a key for many modes.</dd><dt><strong>Sinkhole (DNS)</strong></dt><dd>Controlled resolution for malicious domains—intel and disruption technique with legal process considerations.</dd><dt><strong>SOAR</strong></dt><dd>Security orchestration, automation, response—playbooks must have human gates for destructive actions.</dd><dt><strong>CASB / SaaS governance</strong></dt><dd>Visibility and policy for sanctioned vs shadow SaaS—OAuth consent attacks and guest sharing are common gaps.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>GCP service account keys are long-lived secrets—prefer workload identity federation from CI where possible.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>CVSS base does not include your asset criticality—environmental metrics exist for a reason.</li><li>Responsible disclosure timelines balance vendor patch readiness with public safety—coordinate, don’t surprise.</li><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li><li>Linux auth.log style entries pair with SSH brute-force detection patterns—velocity and geo anomalies.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L4-17: Kubernetes RBAC, service accounts, and token projection</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L4-17: Kubernetes RBAC, service accounts, and token projection</em>:</strong> Air gapped networks still need <strong>patching via sneaker-net</strong> and insider controls—physical isolation is not logical isolation.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L4-17: Kubernetes RBAC, service accounts, and token projection</em>:</strong> Incident response questions probe containment vs evidence preservation tension, legal escalation, and communication discipline. The exam rewards knowing when to isolate systems, when to involve counsel, and why mass log deletion is catastrophic.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L4-17: Kubernetes RBAC, service accounts, and token projection</em>:</strong> Industrial and OT adjacent questions reward knowing <strong>safety vs security</strong> tension: availability may trump confidentiality; testing must avoid breaking physical processes.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L4-17: Kubernetes RBAC, service accounts, and token projection</em>:</strong> API keys in mobile apps are often extractable—prefer <strong>short-lived tokens</strong> and server-mediated access to backends.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L4-17: Kubernetes RBAC, service accounts, and token projection</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L4-17: Kubernetes RBAC, service accounts, and token projection</em>:</strong> Physical security is still on the exam: tailgating, visitor escorts, locks, destruction of media, and environmental controls (fire, HVAC) as availability/confidentiality supports.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L4-17: Kubernetes RBAC, service accounts, and token projection</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L4-17: Kubernetes RBAC, service accounts, and token projection</em>:</strong> TACACS+ vs RADIUS separation of duties in device admin access—exams may contrast accounting granularity.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L4-17: Kubernetes RBAC, service accounts, and token projection</em>:</strong> Cryptography questions reward vocabulary precision: hashing vs encryption vs encoding; symmetric vs asymmetric roles in TLS; what signatures prove; and why key management is usually harder than picking an algorithm. If an answer sounds magical, it is probably wrong.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> During a tabletop, the CFO asks how “L4-17: Kubernetes RBAC, service accounts, and token projection” could become a material incident. Answer with <strong>one plausible attack path</strong>, <strong>one detective control</strong> you already have, and <strong>one preventive gap</strong> you would fund next quarter.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l4-18":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L4-18: Serverless (Lambda/Functions) IAM blast radius</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-18</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> One overly broad execution role affects all invocations.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Per-function roles; environment variable leaks in console.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Draw IAM policy JSON for read-only S3 prefix + <code>kms:Decrypt</code> for one CMK only.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-18</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>SaaS governance (CASB-style thinking) pairs technical visibility with <strong>OAuth consent</strong> and <strong>guest sharing</strong> policy.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 4 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Exploit</strong></dt><dd>A technique or code that takes advantage of a vulnerability to achieve an attacker goal (exfiltration, persistence, disruption).</dd><dt><strong>Input validation vs output encoding</strong></dt><dd>Validation rejects bad input early; encoding neutralizes dangerous characters in the right output context—both are needed across HTML, SQL, OS, and LDAP channels.</dd><dt><strong>Business continuity testing</strong></dt><dd>Tabletops and technical failover drills reveal gaps in comms, dependencies, and vendor SLAs.</dd><dt><strong>Data residency</strong></dt><dd>Legal requirement for where data lives—impacts cloud region selection and key custody.</dd><dt><strong>TLS</strong></dt><dd>Encrypts data in motion and authenticates endpoints when certificates and hostnames are validated; termination points affect trust boundaries.</dd><dt><strong>BCP / DR</strong></dt><dd>Business continuity and disaster recovery—RTO/RPO drive architecture; test restores, not just backups on paper.</dd><dt><strong>WAF vs IPS</strong></dt><dd>WAF focuses on application-layer attacks; IPS often line-rate network signatures—overlap exists but priorities differ.</dd><dt><strong>Non-repudiation</strong></dt><dd>Prevents a party from credibly denying an action—digital signatures, tamper-evident logs, and time-stamping support it.</dd><dt><strong>CVSS</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerability Scoring System—base metrics describe technical severity; environmental and temporal modifiers refine priority.</dd><dt><strong>OCSP stapling (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Server sends fresh revocation info with handshake—reduces client privacy leaks and lookup failures.</dd><dt><strong>Compensating control</strong></dt><dd>Alternative control that meets intent when primary control cannot be implemented—must provide equivalent or greater assurance with documentation.</dd><dt><strong>Digital signature</strong></dt><dd>Proves origin and integrity using private key to sign and public key to verify—non-repudiation when keys are well governed.</dd><dt><strong>Confidential computing</strong></dt><dd>Use of hardware enclaves/TEEs to reduce exposure to privileged operators—threat model still required.</dd><dt><strong>Kill chain / cyber kill chain</strong></dt><dd>Stages of intrusion—mapping controls and detections to stages clarifies coverage gaps.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Typical exam angle</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Confidentiality</strong></td><td>Who may read? Encryption, ACLs, DLP, classification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Integrity</strong></td><td>Was it modified? Hashing, signatures, change control, backups.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Availability</strong></td><td>Can authorized users work? HA, patching windows, DDoS defense, DR.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authenticity / non-repudiation</strong></td><td>Prove source and intent—signatures, strong issuance, tamper-evident logs.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Terraform state can hold secrets—remote secure backend and scanning are baseline hygiene.</li><li>EPSS (concept) scores exploitation probability—useful alongside CVSS for prioritization in mature programs.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li><li>PCI DSS scope reduction via segmentation is a recurring theme—if it is not in scope, it cannot drag you into assessment.</li><li>Certificate pinning misconfigurations can brick apps—plan rotation and emergency releases.</li><li>Bug bounty scope must exclude destructive testing—safe harbor language still needs legal review.</li><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li><li>S3 bucket policies and ACLs layer with IAM—effective permissions require understanding intersection.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L4-18: Serverless (Lambda/Functions) IAM blast radius</em>:</strong> Deception tech is not a replacement for <strong>baselines and patching</strong>; it augments detection when mature processes exist.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L4-18: Serverless (Lambda/Functions) IAM blast radius</em>:</strong> Cloud items assume you can articulate <strong>shared responsibility</strong>: what the provider patches vs what the customer must configure (IAM, encryption, network exposure). Misconfiguration beats novel cloud exploits in real incidents and on the exam.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L4-18: Serverless (Lambda/Functions) IAM blast radius</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L4-18: Serverless (Lambda/Functions) IAM blast radius</em>:</strong> LDAP vs Active Directory questions test directory concepts at a high level—binding, searches, and secure transport (LDAPS) appear often.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L4-18: Serverless (Lambda/Functions) IAM blast radius</em>:</strong> Cryptography questions reward vocabulary precision: hashing vs encryption vs encoding; symmetric vs asymmetric roles in TLS; what signatures prove; and why key management is usually harder than picking an algorithm. If an answer sounds magical, it is probably wrong.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L4-18: Serverless (Lambda/Functions) IAM blast radius</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L4-18: Serverless (Lambda/Functions) IAM blast radius</em>:</strong> GraphQL introspection risk is about <strong>schema discovery</strong> aiding attackers—rate limits, authz on fields, and disabling introspection in prod are common answers.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L4-18: Serverless (Lambda/Functions) IAM blast radius</em>:</strong> Defense in depth is not “more products,” it is <strong>independent mechanisms</strong>—if one layer is bypassed, another still limits movement, slows the adversary, or preserves evidence. Be ready to explain why network controls alone cannot compensate for missing app-layer authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L4-18: Serverless (Lambda/Functions) IAM blast radius</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L4-18: Serverless (Lambda/Functions) IAM blast radius</em>:</strong> Tabletop exercises test <strong>comms trees</strong>, legal escalation, and customer notification templates—not only technical runbooks.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Marketing launches a campaign referencing “L4-18: Serverless (Lambda/Functions) IAM blast radius” with a new subdomain. Security review finds DNS delegated to an unknown party. Explain <strong>trust chain</strong> risks and the <strong>minimum fixes</strong> before go-live.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l4-19":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L4-19: CASB and SaaS governance (sanction vs monitor vs block)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-19</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> API vs reverse-proxy modes; OAuth app consent attacks.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Google Workspace / Microsoft 365 risky OAuth apps workflow.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Checklist of 12 SaaS settings (MFA, session length, guest access, sharing links).</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-19</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Cloud answers should articulate <strong>shared responsibility</strong> boundaries without blaming the provider for customer IAM mistakes.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 4 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Certificate transparency (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Public logs of issued certs help detect mis-issued certificates for your domains.</dd><dt><strong>RPO / RTO recap</strong></dt><dd>RPO = max acceptable data loss time; RTO = max acceptable outage—drive backup frequency and HA design.</dd><dt><strong>Asset</strong></dt><dd>Anything of value to the organization—data, systems, people, reputation, or services—that security controls protect.</dd><dt><strong>Session management</strong></dt><dd>Server-side session IDs or tokens must rotate on privilege change, bind to channel, and expire predictably.</dd><dt><strong>Input validation vs output encoding</strong></dt><dd>Validation rejects bad input early; encoding neutralizes dangerous characters in the right output context—both are needed across HTML, SQL, OS, and LDAP channels.</dd><dt><strong>Container security</strong></dt><dd>Image provenance, non-root users, read-only roots, seccomp/AppArmor, and admission control for risky capabilities.</dd><dt><strong>Job rotation</strong></dt><dd>Reduces collusion and fraud risk; also surfaces “tribal knowledge” silos before an employee leaves.</dd><dt><strong>Proxy vs reverse proxy</strong></dt><dd>Forward proxy represents clients outbound; reverse proxy fronts servers—different trust and logging points.</dd><dt><strong>SIEM</strong></dt><dd>Security information and event management—centralize logs, parse fields, correlate alerts; tuning reduces false positives and fatigue.</dd><dt><strong>PII</strong></dt><dd>Personally identifiable information—names, government IDs, biometrics, account numbers; triggers handling, retention, and breach rules.</dd><dt><strong>Asymmetric encryption</strong></dt><dd>Key pairs for key agreement/signing—RSA/ECC; hybrid TLS uses asymmetric to establish symmetric session keys.</dd><dt><strong>IR phases</strong></dt><dd>Prepare, detect, analyze, contain, eradicate, recover, and lessons learned—legal hold and evidence integrity matter throughout.</dd><dt><strong>Threat modeling (STRIDE)</strong></dt><dd>Spoofing, tampering, repudiation, information disclosure, denial of service, elevation of privilege—drive controls early.</dd><dt><strong>IV / nonce</strong></dt><dd>Initialization vector or number-used-once—must be unique per encryption under a key for many modes.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li><li>SLSA levels describe increasing supply-chain assurance—useful vocabulary in modern governance questions.</li><li>Split tunnel VPN can exfil corporate data outside inspection if misconfigured—policy and routing matter.</li><li>UDP-based protocols can be abused for amplification DDoS—patch open resolvers and monitor volumetric baselines.</li><li>GraphQL batching can amplify complexity attacks—depth and cost limits are first-class controls.</li><li>OAuth access tokens are not a replacement for server-side authorization checks on every sensitive action.</li><li>Admission controllers can block privileged pods—policy-as-code integrates with GitOps reviews.</li><li>EPSS (concept) scores exploitation probability—useful alongside CVSS for prioritization in mature programs.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L4-19: CASB and SaaS governance (sanction vs monitor vs block)</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L4-19: CASB and SaaS governance (sanction vs monitor vs block)</em>:</strong> Incident response questions probe containment vs evidence preservation tension, legal escalation, and communication discipline. The exam rewards knowing when to isolate systems, when to involve counsel, and why mass log deletion is catastrophic.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L4-19: CASB and SaaS governance (sanction vs monitor vs block)</em>:</strong> TACACS+ vs RADIUS separation of duties in device admin access—exams may contrast accounting granularity.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L4-19: CASB and SaaS governance (sanction vs monitor vs block)</em>:</strong> Container escape questions hinge on <strong>kernel boundary</strong> and misconfigured capabilities—namespaces are helpful but not a complete trust boundary without seccomp, AppArmor, and least-privileged service accounts.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L4-19: CASB and SaaS governance (sanction vs monitor vs block)</em>:</strong> Cloud items assume you can articulate <strong>shared responsibility</strong>: what the provider patches vs what the customer must configure (IAM, encryption, network exposure). Misconfiguration beats novel cloud exploits in real incidents and on the exam.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L4-19: CASB and SaaS governance (sanction vs monitor vs block)</em>:</strong> Honeypots can generate high-signal alerts but carry <strong>legal and operational</strong> risk if touched by real users; scope carefully.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L4-19: CASB and SaaS governance (sanction vs monitor vs block)</em>:</strong> Serverless cold start is not a security control; <strong>per-function IAM</strong> and least-privilege API scopes are. Watch for attractive nonsense distractors tied to performance tuning.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L4-19: CASB and SaaS governance (sanction vs monitor vs block)</em>:</strong> Governance and awareness questions tie policy to behavior: acceptable use, clean desk, travel security, and vendor due diligence. Pick answers that reduce <strong>realistic</strong> human failure modes, not answers that maximize surveillance without process support.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L4-19: CASB and SaaS governance (sanction vs monitor vs block)</em>:</strong> Deception tech is not a replacement for <strong>baselines and patching</strong>; it augments detection when mature processes exist.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L4-19: CASB and SaaS governance (sanction vs monitor vs block)</em>:</strong> KMS keys are not “magic secrecy dust”—<strong>who can invoke decrypt</strong> and from which contexts (VPC endpoint policies, IAM conditions) is what exams probe.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Purple team wants to simulate abuse of “L4-19: CASB and SaaS governance (sanction vs monitor vs block)” next Friday. List <strong>safety gates</strong> (scope, rollback, monitoring) you require before authorizing the exercise.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l4-20":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L4-20: M&amp;A technical due diligence security checklist</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-20</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> AD forest trusts, legacy VPNs, undisclosed SaaS, license compliance vs security.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Day-one identity cutover risks.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> 2-page checklist template with owners (IT, Legal, Security, Finance).</p>\n<h2>Level 5 extensions</h2>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-20</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Evidence handling in regulated orgs may invoke <strong>legal hold</strong>—do not pick answers that “clean up” data prematurely.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 4 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Job rotation</strong></dt><dd>Reduces collusion and fraud risk; also surfaces “tribal knowledge” silos before an employee leaves.</dd><dt><strong>MAC</strong></dt><dd>Message authentication code—integrity with a secret key; differs from digital signature which uses asymmetric keys.</dd><dt><strong>Diamond model</strong></dt><dd>Adversary, infrastructure, capability, victim—useful for pivoting investigations and intel fusion.</dd><dt><strong>Network segmentation</strong></dt><dd>VLANs, micro-segmentation, and east-west controls limit lateral movement after an initial foothold.</dd><dt><strong>Authenticity</strong></dt><dd>Verifies that users, devices, or data are genuine—cryptographic identity, attestation, and strong issuance processes matter.</dd><dt><strong>TLS</strong></dt><dd>Encrypts data in motion and authenticates endpoints when certificates and hostnames are validated; termination points affect trust boundaries.</dd><dt><strong>Security misconfiguration</strong></dt><dd>Default creds, debug features on in prod, verbose errors, open directory listings—hardening baselines and drift detection reduce this class.</dd><dt><strong>Shared responsibility model</strong></dt><dd>Cloud provider secures the platform; customer secures configuration, identities, data, and app code in their scope.</dd><dt><strong>Attack surface</strong></dt><dd>The sum of exposure—every service, API, integration, and human workflow that can be reached by a threat; reduction beats perfect monitoring alone.</dd><dt><strong>Downgrade attack</strong></dt><dd>Forcing weaker crypto or protocols—HSTS and modern TLS config reduce browser downgrade paths.</dd><dt><strong>Proxy vs reverse proxy</strong></dt><dd>Forward proxy represents clients outbound; reverse proxy fronts servers—different trust and logging points.</dd><dt><strong>Data residency</strong></dt><dd>Legal requirement for where data lives—impacts cloud region selection and key custody.</dd><dt><strong>Vulnerability</strong></dt><dd>A weakness in design, implementation, configuration, or process that could be exploited to violate a security policy.</dd><dt><strong>Authorization</strong></dt><dd>What an authenticated subject is allowed to do—RBAC/ABAC, scopes, and server-side checks enforce least privilege.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>SBOM formats (CycloneDX/SPDX) help inventory components for incident response and licensing—not only security.</li><li>OAuth access tokens are not a replacement for server-side authorization checks on every sensitive action.</li><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li><li>Responsible disclosure timelines balance vendor patch readiness with public safety—coordinate, don’t surprise.</li><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li><li>DNS over HTTPS changes visibility for some networks—understand resolver policy and logging tradeoffs.</li><li>S3 bucket policies and ACLs layer with IAM—effective permissions require understanding intersection.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L4-20: M&amp;A technical due diligence security checklist</em>:</strong> Wireless assessments should mention <strong>rogue AP</strong> discovery, client isolation, and guest segmentation—not just “use WPA2” as a slogan. Exam writers like the distinction between personal and enterprise authentication modes at a conceptual level.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L4-20: M&amp;A technical due diligence security checklist</em>:</strong> For the Security+ mindset, translate every control into <strong>who</strong> it protects, <strong>what</strong> asset is at risk, and <strong>how</strong> you would detect failure. Interview and exam items often reward practical prioritization over buzzwords—choose the mitigation that reduces realistic loss first.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L4-20: M&amp;A technical due diligence security checklist</em>:</strong> SAST finds issues early but produces false positives; <strong>triage workflows</strong> and developer feedback loops are part of a mature program, not “run tool once.”</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L4-20: M&amp;A technical due diligence security checklist</em>:</strong> Logging questions often test whether you understand <strong>what to log</strong> (who, what, when, where, outcome), <strong>time sync</strong> for correlation, and <strong>tamper resistance</strong> for evidentiary value—not whether you can collect infinite bytes.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L4-20: M&amp;A technical due diligence security checklist</em>:</strong> TACACS+ vs RADIUS separation of duties in device admin access—exams may contrast accounting granularity.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L4-20: M&amp;A technical due diligence security checklist</em>:</strong> Industrial and OT adjacent questions reward knowing <strong>safety vs security</strong> tension: availability may trump confidentiality; testing must avoid breaking physical processes.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L4-20: M&amp;A technical due diligence security checklist</em>:</strong> Defense in depth is not “more products,” it is <strong>independent mechanisms</strong>—if one layer is bypassed, another still limits movement, slows the adversary, or preserves evidence. Be ready to explain why network controls alone cannot compensate for missing app-layer authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L4-20: M&amp;A technical due diligence security checklist</em>:</strong> Penetration tests require <strong>written authorization</strong>, defined scope, and rules of engagement—even in internal labs for professional conduct.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L4-20: M&amp;A technical due diligence security checklist</em>:</strong> Wireless and mobility items reward knowing basics: WPA3 improvements conceptually, evil twin risks, captive portals, and why client isolation matters on guest networks—without memorizing obsolete WEP details unless explicitly historical.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L4-20: M&amp;A technical due diligence security checklist</em>:</strong> Deception tech is not a replacement for <strong>baselines and patching</strong>; it augments detection when mature processes exist.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> A vendor integration project mentions “L4-20: M&amp;A technical due diligence security checklist” as out-of-scope for pen testing. Explain what <strong>residual risk</strong> remains, what <strong>compensating monitoring</strong> you would demand, and how you would <strong>document acceptance</strong>.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l5-16":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L5-16: HSMs, key ceremonies, and dual control</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-16</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Root of trust for PKI and payment keys; split knowledge.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> FIPS 140-2/3 awareness; cloud CloudHSM vs managed KMS.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Compare table: software keys vs KMS vs HSM for 6 attributes (cost, latency, assurance…).</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-16</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Zero Trust answers should emphasize <strong>continuous verification</strong> and <strong>policy enforcement points</strong>, not removing all network security.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 5 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Sinkhole (DNS)</strong></dt><dd>Controlled resolution for malicious domains—intel and disruption technique with legal process considerations.</dd><dt><strong>Threat</strong></dt><dd>Any circumstance or actor with the potential to cause harm by exploiting a vulnerability (malware, insider, natural disaster).</dd><dt><strong>TLS</strong></dt><dd>Encrypts data in motion and authenticates endpoints when certificates and hostnames are validated; termination points affect trust boundaries.</dd><dt><strong>Vulnerability management</strong></dt><dd>Discover, prioritize, remediate, verify, and report—SLAs differ by exposure, exploitability, and asset criticality.</dd><dt><strong>Forensics basics</strong></dt><dd>Volatile vs non-volatile collection, order of volatility, hashing, and legal escalation paths before deep technical work.</dd><dt><strong>Full packet capture</strong></dt><dd>High fidelity evidence for investigations—storage, privacy, and legal review constraints apply.</dd><dt><strong>Quantitative vs qualitative risk</strong></dt><dd>Qualitative uses scales (high/medium/low); quantitative uses dollar or probability estimates—both need consistent assumptions and reviewer judgment.</dd><dt><strong>Defense in depth</strong></dt><dd>Layered controls so one failure does not equal total failure—network, host, app, identity, and monitoring each contribute.</dd><dt><strong>CVSS</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerability Scoring System—base metrics describe technical severity; environmental and temporal modifiers refine priority.</dd><dt><strong>Purple teaming</strong></dt><dd>Collaborative attack/defense exercises to validate detections without surprise production harm—scope and safety first.</dd><dt><strong>Proxy vs reverse proxy</strong></dt><dd>Forward proxy represents clients outbound; reverse proxy fronts servers—different trust and logging points.</dd><dt><strong>Security control categories</strong></dt><dd>Technical (firewalls, encryption), administrative (policies, training), and physical (badges, locks)—exam items often ask which category fits a scenario.</dd><dt><strong>NAT (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Rewrites addresses/ports for traversal—security relevance includes logging visibility, port forwarding risks, and split tunnel implications for inspection.</dd><dt><strong>DevSecOps</strong></dt><dd>Embed security gates in CI/CD with fast feedback—policy-as-code, secret scanning, and SBOMs support supply-chain resilience.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Linux auth.log style entries pair with SSH brute-force detection patterns—velocity and geo anomalies.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>Admission controllers can block privileged pods—policy-as-code integrates with GitOps reviews.</li><li>SBOM formats (CycloneDX/SPDX) help inventory components for incident response and licensing—not only security.</li><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li><li>Immutable backups mitigate ransomware that tries to delete online copies—air-gapped or WORM patterns.</li><li>JWT alg:none historical vulnerability class—always validate algorithm and signature keys explicitly.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L5-16: HSMs, key ceremonies, and dual control</em>:</strong> Governance and awareness questions tie policy to behavior: acceptable use, clean desk, travel security, and vendor due diligence. Pick answers that reduce <strong>realistic</strong> human failure modes, not answers that maximize surveillance without process support.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L5-16: HSMs, key ceremonies, and dual control</em>:</strong> Third-party and supply chain answers should emphasize <strong>contracts</strong>, <strong>evidence</strong>, and <strong>continuous monitoring</strong>—not “trust the SOC 2 logo” without scope review.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L5-16: HSMs, key ceremonies, and dual control</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L5-16: HSMs, key ceremonies, and dual control</em>:</strong> KMS keys are not “magic secrecy dust”—<strong>who can invoke decrypt</strong> and from which contexts (VPC endpoint policies, IAM conditions) is what exams probe.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L5-16: HSMs, key ceremonies, and dual control</em>:</strong> Penetration tests require <strong>written authorization</strong>, defined scope, and rules of engagement—even in internal labs for professional conduct.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L5-16: HSMs, key ceremonies, and dual control</em>:</strong> Subresource integrity protects against <strong>CDN compromise</strong> but requires operational discipline when vendors rotate files.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L5-16: HSMs, key ceremonies, and dual control</em>:</strong> Air gapped networks still need <strong>patching via sneaker-net</strong> and insider controls—physical isolation is not logical isolation.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L5-16: HSMs, key ceremonies, and dual control</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L5-16: HSMs, key ceremonies, and dual control</em>:</strong> Cryptography questions reward vocabulary precision: hashing vs encryption vs encoding; symmetric vs asymmetric roles in TLS; what signatures prove; and why key management is usually harder than picking an algorithm. If an answer sounds magical, it is probably wrong.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L5-16: HSMs, key ceremonies, and dual control</em>:</strong> Logging questions often test whether you understand <strong>what to log</strong> (who, what, when, where, outcome), <strong>time sync</strong> for correlation, and <strong>tamper resistance</strong> for evidentiary value—not whether you can collect infinite bytes.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Legal asks whether “L5-16: HSMs, key ceremonies, and dual control” artifacts require <strong>hold</strong> before deletion. Describe how you would <strong>tag systems</strong>, <strong>freeze backups</strong> appropriately, and <strong>escalate</strong> without tipping external actors.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l5-17":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L5-17: BGP hijacking and RPKI (operator-level awareness)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-17</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Route leaks vs malicious origination; ROV.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Why SaaS uptime ties to routing hygiene.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Read MANRS or ARIN RPKI intro; 10-bullet briefing for executives.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-17</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Architecture tradeoff prompts want <strong>explicit assumptions</strong>—availability vs cost vs complexity, stated cleanly.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 5 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Perfect forward secrecy (PFS)</strong></dt><dd>Ephemeral key exchange means past session keys are not compromised if long-term keys leak later—TLS cipher suites can offer this property.</dd><dt><strong>Residual risk</strong></dt><dd>Risk remaining after controls are applied; organizations accept, transfer, mitigate, or avoid it explicitly.</dd><dt><strong>Kerberos (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Ticket-based enterprise auth—TGT vs service tickets; golden/silver ticket classes of abuse appear in advanced IR.</dd><dt><strong>Key management</strong></dt><dd>Generation, storage, rotation, and destruction—HSM/KMS patterns reduce exposure compared to software-only secrets.</dd><dt><strong>Chain of custody</strong></dt><dd>Documented handling of evidence from collection through presentation—hashing, write blockers, and access logs support admissibility.</dd><dt><strong>Zero Trust architecture</strong></dt><dd>Identity-centric access with continuous verification—policy enforcement points for users, devices, and workloads.</dd><dt><strong>CRL</strong></dt><dd>Certificate Revocation List—signed list of revoked serials; size/latency issues drove OCSP adoption.</dd><dt><strong>Sinkhole (routing)</strong></dt><dd>Different meaning in BGP—be careful with homonyms on exams; read the stem’s context.</dd><dt><strong>Digital signature</strong></dt><dd>Proves origin and integrity using private key to sign and public key to verify—non-repudiation when keys are well governed.</dd><dt><strong>Integrity</strong></dt><dd>Assures accuracy and trustworthiness—hashing, signatures, change control, and backups protect against unauthorized modification.</dd><dt><strong>TLS</strong></dt><dd>Encrypts data in motion and authenticates endpoints when certificates and hostnames are validated; termination points affect trust boundaries.</dd><dt><strong>Injection</strong></dt><dd>Untrusted input becomes part of a command or query—parameterized queries, input validation, and context escaping are core defenses.</dd><dt><strong>Encryption at rest / in transit</strong></dt><dd>KMS/HSM-backed keys, envelope encryption, and TLS everywhere for administrative and user paths.</dd><dt><strong>Purple / red / blue</strong></dt><dd>Red emulates adversaries, blue defends, purple bridges—authorization and logging are mandatory for any simulation.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Typical exam angle</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Confidentiality</strong></td><td>Who may read? Encryption, ACLs, DLP, classification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Integrity</strong></td><td>Was it modified? Hashing, signatures, change control, backups.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Availability</strong></td><td>Can authorized users work? HA, patching windows, DDoS defense, DR.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authenticity / non-repudiation</strong></td><td>Prove source and intent—signatures, strong issuance, tamper-evident logs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>AEAD</strong></td><td>Confidentiality + integrity together—misuse of IV/nonce still breaks security.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li><li>HttpOnly does not stop CSRF; it reduces token theft from XSS reading document.cookie in many setups.</li><li>Responsible disclosure timelines balance vendor patch readiness with public safety—coordinate, don’t surprise.</li><li>Admission controllers can block privileged pods—policy-as-code integrates with GitOps reviews.</li><li>Split tunnel VPN can exfil corporate data outside inspection if misconfigured—policy and routing matter.</li><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li><li>AES-128 is not “half as strong” as AES-256 in practical threat models for many cases—key management quality dominates.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L5-17: BGP hijacking and RPKI (operator-level awareness)</em>:</strong> Access control stems frequently mix <strong>role</strong> vs <strong>attribute</strong> vs <strong>rule</strong> models; pick the answer that matches the scenario’s constraints (temporary contractor, cross-department data, dynamic tags on resources).</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L5-17: BGP hijacking and RPKI (operator-level awareness)</em>:</strong> BIOS/UEFI passwords and secure boot reduce some pre-boot attacks but do not stop <strong>evil maid</strong> classes without additional controls.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L5-17: BGP hijacking and RPKI (operator-level awareness)</em>:</strong> Cryptojacking still appears: high CPU, unexpected mining pools, and cloud billing spikes—detection plus credential hygiene beats chasing miner signatures alone.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L5-17: BGP hijacking and RPKI (operator-level awareness)</em>:</strong> Wireless and mobility items reward knowing basics: WPA3 improvements conceptually, evil twin risks, captive portals, and why client isolation matters on guest networks—without memorizing obsolete WEP details unless explicitly historical.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L5-17: BGP hijacking and RPKI (operator-level awareness)</em>:</strong> TPM-backed BitLocker keys illustrate <strong>key protection</strong> binding to platform state—recovery keys must be guarded like crown jewels.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L5-17: BGP hijacking and RPKI (operator-level awareness)</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L5-17: BGP hijacking and RPKI (operator-level awareness)</em>:</strong> Physical security is still on the exam: tailgating, visitor escorts, locks, destruction of media, and environmental controls (fire, HVAC) as availability/confidentiality supports.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L5-17: BGP hijacking and RPKI (operator-level awareness)</em>:</strong> Sanitization vs wiping vs destruction: exams like knowing which media needs <strong>degaussing, shredding, or crypto erase</strong> per policy.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L5-17: BGP hijacking and RPKI (operator-level awareness)</em>:</strong> SAST finds issues early but produces false positives; <strong>triage workflows</strong> and developer feedback loops are part of a mature program, not “run tool once.”</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L5-17: BGP hijacking and RPKI (operator-level awareness)</em>:</strong> Patching and change management appear as <strong>risk tradeoffs</strong>: emergency patches vs testing rings; compensating monitoring when patching lags; and documenting exceptions for auditors.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> A vendor integration project mentions “L5-17: BGP hijacking and RPKI (operator-level awareness)” as out-of-scope for pen testing. Explain what <strong>residual risk</strong> remains, what <strong>compensating monitoring</strong> you would demand, and how you would <strong>document acceptance</strong>.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l5-18":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L5-18: Rowhammer / RAMBleed class issues (hardware-software boundary)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-18</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Why ECC matters for high-assurance; isolation limits.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Cloud shared host risk vs dedicated; browser mitigations over time.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Summarize one CVE in plain language with attacker model (local vs remote).</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-18</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Advanced IR/intel questions still punish <strong>evidence destruction</strong> and <strong>unscoped testing</strong>—professional ethics are in scope.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 5 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>XSS</strong></dt><dd>Cross-site scripting injects script in a victim context—CSP, output encoding, HttpOnly cookies, and DOM hygiene reduce blast radius.</dd><dt><strong>Misconfiguration</strong></dt><dd>Top cloud incident driver—public buckets, open security groups, permissive trust policies; IaC scanning catches drift early.</dd><dt><strong>Confidential computing</strong></dt><dd>Use of hardware enclaves/TEEs to reduce exposure to privileged operators—threat model still required.</dd><dt><strong>CRL</strong></dt><dd>Certificate Revocation List—signed list of revoked serials; size/latency issues drove OCSP adoption.</dd><dt><strong>NetFlow / IPFIX</strong></dt><dd>Flow metadata for volume and anomaly detection—lighter than PCAP but less payload visibility.</dd><dt><strong>Compensating control</strong></dt><dd>Alternative control that meets intent when primary control cannot be implemented—must provide equivalent or greater assurance with documentation.</dd><dt><strong>Privacy</strong></dt><dd>Protection of personal information and individual rights—overlaps with security but adds legal/regulatory obligations (GDPR-style).</dd><dt><strong>VPN</strong></dt><dd>Creates an encrypted tunnel; split tunneling can bypass corporate inspection; VPN is not anonymity or a substitute for app-layer auth.</dd><dt><strong>Injection</strong></dt><dd>Untrusted input becomes part of a command or query—parameterized queries, input validation, and context escaping are core defenses.</dd><dt><strong>Logging &amp; monitoring</strong></dt><dd>CloudTrail-style management events differ from data-plane logs—enable central export, immutability, and alerting.</dd><dt><strong>PQC</strong></dt><dd>Post-quantum cryptography migration—hybrid schemes and crypto-agility for long-lived secrets exposed to harvest-now/decrypt-later risk.</dd><dt><strong>OCSP stapling (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Server sends fresh revocation info with handshake—reduces client privacy leaks and lookup failures.</dd><dt><strong>Full packet capture</strong></dt><dd>High fidelity evidence for investigations—storage, privacy, and legal review constraints apply.</dd><dt><strong>Security control categories</strong></dt><dd>Technical (firewalls, encryption), administrative (policies, training), and physical (badges, locks)—exam items often ask which category fits a scenario.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Typical exam angle</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Confidentiality</strong></td><td>Who may read? Encryption, ACLs, DLP, classification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Integrity</strong></td><td>Was it modified? Hashing, signatures, change control, backups.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Availability</strong></td><td>Can authorized users work? HA, patching windows, DDoS defense, DR.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authenticity / non-repudiation</strong></td><td>Prove source and intent—signatures, strong issuance, tamper-evident logs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>AEAD</strong></td><td>Confidentiality + integrity together—misuse of IV/nonce still breaks security.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Azure AD / Entra conditional access is analogous to risk-based policies—device compliance signals matter.</li><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li><li>UDP-based protocols can be abused for amplification DDoS—patch open resolvers and monitor volumetric baselines.</li><li>Race conditions in web apps can undermine authorization—sequential logic tests in secure design reviews.</li><li>CVSS base does not include your asset criticality—environmental metrics exist for a reason.</li><li>Terraform state can hold secrets—remote secure backend and scanning are baseline hygiene.</li><li>Split tunnel VPN can exfil corporate data outside inspection if misconfigured—policy and routing matter.</li><li>ISO 27001 is an ISMS standard; it emphasizes risk treatment and continual improvement, not a product checklist.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L5-18: Rowhammer / RAMBleed class issues (hardware-software boundary)</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L5-18: Rowhammer / RAMBleed class issues (hardware-software boundary)</em>:</strong> When logs “mysteriously stop,” think <strong>time sync failure</strong>, collector saturation, retention misconfiguration, or attacker tampering—in that diagnostic order for a fair exam narrative.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L5-18: Rowhammer / RAMBleed class issues (hardware-software boundary)</em>:</strong> Sanitization vs wiping vs destruction: exams like knowing which media needs <strong>degaussing, shredding, or crypto erase</strong> per policy.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L5-18: Rowhammer / RAMBleed class issues (hardware-software boundary)</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L5-18: Rowhammer / RAMBleed class issues (hardware-software boundary)</em>:</strong> Virtualization risks include <strong>snapshot sprawl</strong> containing secrets and stale VM images drifting from hardened baselines.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L5-18: Rowhammer / RAMBleed class issues (hardware-software boundary)</em>:</strong> Engineers often optimize for speed; attackers optimize for <strong>cheap reuse</strong> of stolen creds and known exploits. The winning answer bridges both: ship fast with guardrails—feature flags, staged rollouts, and automated security checks in CI.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L5-18: Rowhammer / RAMBleed class issues (hardware-software boundary)</em>:</strong> Honeypots can generate high-signal alerts but carry <strong>legal and operational</strong> risk if touched by real users; scope carefully.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L5-18: Rowhammer / RAMBleed class issues (hardware-software boundary)</em>:</strong> Business continuity answers should reference <strong>RTO/RPO</strong>, <strong>workarounds</strong>, and <strong>tested restores</strong>; DR without practiced failover is wishful thinking, and exam writers know it.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L5-18: Rowhammer / RAMBleed class issues (hardware-software boundary)</em>:</strong> LDAP vs Active Directory questions test directory concepts at a high level—binding, searches, and secure transport (LDAPS) appear often.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L5-18: Rowhammer / RAMBleed class issues (hardware-software boundary)</em>:</strong> Physical security is still on the exam: tailgating, visitor escorts, locks, destruction of media, and environmental controls (fire, HVAC) as availability/confidentiality supports.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Internal audit samples “L5-18: Rowhammer / RAMBleed class issues (hardware-software boundary)” controls and finds screenshots instead of config exports. Explain why <strong>authoritative evidence</strong> matters and what you would collect instead.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l5-19":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L5-19: Fuzzing for developers (AFL++, libFuzzer, sanitizers)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-19</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Coverage-guided fuzzing finds parser bugs before attackers.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> CI integration with timeouts and crash triage.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>apt-cache show afl++ 2&gt;/dev/null | head -n 20</code> or document building a trivial harness for <code>atoi</code>-style parser.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-19</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Architecture tradeoff prompts want <strong>explicit assumptions</strong>—availability vs cost vs complexity, stated cleanly.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 5 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>PKI</strong></dt><dd>Public Key Infrastructure—CAs, RAs, CRL/OCSP, and certificate lifecycle; mis-issuance or weak validation breaks trust chains.</dd><dt><strong>MITRE ATT&amp;CK</strong></dt><dd>Tactics (why) and techniques (how) adversaries operate—use for detection engineering, gap analysis, and purple team scenarios.</dd><dt><strong>Threat intelligence lifecycle</strong></dt><dd>Planning, collection, processing, analysis, dissemination, feedback—intel must change detections or posture or it is shelf-ware.</dd><dt><strong>Certificate transparency (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Public logs of issued certs help detect mis-issued certificates for your domains.</dd><dt><strong>NetFlow / IPFIX</strong></dt><dd>Flow metadata for volume and anomaly detection—lighter than PCAP but less payload visibility.</dd><dt><strong>Vulnerability management</strong></dt><dd>Discover, prioritize, remediate, verify, and report—SLAs differ by exposure, exploitability, and asset criticality.</dd><dt><strong>Integrity</strong></dt><dd>Assures accuracy and trustworthiness—hashing, signatures, change control, and backups protect against unauthorized modification.</dd><dt><strong>TLS</strong></dt><dd>Encrypts data in motion and authenticates endpoints when certificates and hostnames are validated; termination points affect trust boundaries.</dd><dt><strong>Injection</strong></dt><dd>Untrusted input becomes part of a command or query—parameterized queries, input validation, and context escaping are core defenses.</dd><dt><strong>Encryption at rest / in transit</strong></dt><dd>KMS/HSM-backed keys, envelope encryption, and TLS everywhere for administrative and user paths.</dd><dt><strong>Purple / red / blue</strong></dt><dd>Red emulates adversaries, blue defends, purple bridges—authorization and logging are mandatory for any simulation.</dd><dt><strong>Block cipher vs stream</strong></dt><dd>Block operates on fixed-size chunks; stream on bits/bytes—misuse modes (e.g., ECB) create patterns.</dd><dt><strong>OODA loop (IR)</strong></dt><dd>Observe-orient-decide-act—adversary and defender both iterate; faster, accurate decisions beat hoarding data.</dd><dt><strong>Quantitative vs qualitative risk</strong></dt><dd>Qualitative uses scales (high/medium/low); quantitative uses dollar or probability estimates—both need consistent assumptions and reviewer judgment.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li><li>EPSS (concept) scores exploitation probability—useful alongside CVSS for prioritization in mature programs.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>Azure AD / Entra conditional access is analogous to risk-based policies—device compliance signals matter.</li><li>ISO 27001 is an ISMS standard; it emphasizes risk treatment and continual improvement, not a product checklist.</li><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li><li>Server-side template injection is distinct from XSS—context and sinks differ.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L5-19: Fuzzing for developers (AFL++, libFuzzer, sanitizers)</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L5-19: Fuzzing for developers (AFL++, libFuzzer, sanitizers)</em>:</strong> Multicloud complexity increases <strong>identity sprawl</strong>; centralized IdP and consistent conditional access policies reduce human error.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L5-19: Fuzzing for developers (AFL++, libFuzzer, sanitizers)</em>:</strong> BIOS/UEFI passwords and secure boot reduce some pre-boot attacks but do not stop <strong>evil maid</strong> classes without additional controls.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L5-19: Fuzzing for developers (AFL++, libFuzzer, sanitizers)</em>:</strong> Application security scenarios often test whether you know <strong>where</strong> enforcement belongs—browser controls supplement but do not replace server-side checks. SameSite cookies, CSP, and HttpOnly mitigate classes of issues; they do not fix broken object-level authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L5-19: Fuzzing for developers (AFL++, libFuzzer, sanitizers)</em>:</strong> Data handling questions often hinge on <strong>classification</strong>, <strong>least data</strong>, and <strong>retention</strong>: collect only what you need, keep it only as long as allowed, and destroy securely when done.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L5-19: Fuzzing for developers (AFL++, libFuzzer, sanitizers)</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L5-19: Fuzzing for developers (AFL++, libFuzzer, sanitizers)</em>:</strong> Subresource integrity protects against <strong>CDN compromise</strong> but requires operational discipline when vendors rotate files.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L5-19: Fuzzing for developers (AFL++, libFuzzer, sanitizers)</em>:</strong> Clean desk pairs with <strong>screen privacy</strong> and <strong>clear desk checks</strong> for regulated spaces—physical + procedural controls together.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L5-19: Fuzzing for developers (AFL++, libFuzzer, sanitizers)</em>:</strong> Governance and awareness questions tie policy to behavior: acceptable use, clean desk, travel security, and vendor due diligence. Pick answers that reduce <strong>realistic</strong> human failure modes, not answers that maximize surveillance without process support.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L5-19: Fuzzing for developers (AFL++, libFuzzer, sanitizers)</em>:</strong> Wireless assessments should mention <strong>rogue AP</strong> discovery, client isolation, and guest segmentation—not just “use WPA2” as a slogan. Exam writers like the distinction between personal and enterprise authentication modes at a conceptual level.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> A vendor integration project mentions “L5-19: Fuzzing for developers (AFL++, libFuzzer, sanitizers)” as out-of-scope for pen testing. Explain what <strong>residual risk</strong> remains, what <strong>compensating monitoring</strong> you would demand, and how you would <strong>document acceptance</strong>.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l5-20":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L5-20: Legal preservation and law-enforcement interaction (non-legal advice)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-20</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Know when to call counsel; preserve vs spoliation; scope documentation.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> “No one investigates alone” — IR + legal + HR.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Draft internal “first hour” bullets: who to call, what not to do (no mass delete).</p>\n<hr>\n<h2>Supplemental question banks (Q21–30 per level)</h2>\n<h3>Level 1 — Q21–30</h3>\n<p><strong>Q21.</strong> Shadow IT increases risk mainly because: (a) it is always faster (b) data leaves approved controls and visibility (c) it improves MFA.<br><strong>Q22.</strong> Secure disposal “destroy” intent is to: (a) hide icons (b) make recovery infeasible with reasonable resources (c) improve Wi-Fi.<br><strong>Q23.</strong> BYOD containerization tries to: (a) merge personal and work data freely (b) isolate work data and policies (c) remove encryption.<br><strong>Q24.</strong> Travel laptop programs reduce: (a) need for encryption (b) exposure of crown-jewel data at borders/theft (c) DNS TTL.<br><strong>Q25.</strong> Awareness “reporting rate” measures: (a) how many users fail tests only (b) users reporting suspicious messages upward (c) GPU usage.<br><strong>Q26.</strong> MDM can enforce: (a) patch levels and encryption policies on managed devices (b) BGP (c) SQL indexes.<br><strong>Q27.</strong> Acceptable use policies primarily: (a) set expected behavior and prohibitions (b) replace firewalls (c) eliminate audits.<br><strong>Q28.</strong> Punishing users who fail phishing sims tends to: (a) increase concealment and reduce reporting culture (b) improve TLS (c) fix SQLi.<br><strong>Q29.</strong> Inventory before disposal supports: (a) chain of custody and verification (b) faster games (c) weaker passwords.<br><strong>Q30.</strong> “Clean desk” pairs best with: (a) screen privacy filters + lock screens (b) posting passwords (c) disabling backups.</p>\n<h3>Answer key — Level 1 Q21–30</h3>\n<p>21–30: B/B/B/B/B/A/A/A/A/A</p>\n<h3>Level 2 — Q21–30</h3>\n<p><strong>Q21.</strong> SSRF defenses often emphasize: (a) allowlisted destinations (b) longer passwords only (c) disabling TLS.<br><strong>Q22.</strong> XXE primarily abuses: (a) XML parsers resolving external entities (b) RAID (c) HDMI-CEC.<br><strong>Q23.</strong> Unsafe deserialization risks: (a) remote code execution gadgets (b) slower DNS only (c) monitor brightness.<br><strong>Q24.</strong> Path traversal targets: (a) file system boundaries (b) TLS handshakes (c) TPM PCRs only.<br><strong>Q25.</strong> Request smuggling arises from: (a) inconsistent HTTP parsing between proxies and origins (b) weak Wi-Fi (c) SHA-1 in DNS.<br><strong>Q26.</strong> Upload safety includes: (a) store outside web root + randomize names + scan (b) trust browser MIME only (c) chmod 777 always.<br><strong>Q27.</strong> WebSockets still require: (a) authentication/authorization and abuse controls (b) nothing (c) RAID 0.<br><strong>Q28.</strong> DNS rebinding can hurt: (a) browser-based network attackers against internal IPs (b) RAID parity (c) printer DPI.<br><strong>Q29.</strong> SSRF to cloud metadata services is a risk when: (a) apps fetch URLs without strict controls on cloud instances (b) users use MFA (c) HSTS enabled.<br><strong>Q30.</strong> Deserialization safest stance: (a) never deserialize untrusted data (b) always pickle (c) trust CDN headers only.</p>\n<h3>Answer key — Level 2 Q21–30</h3>\n<p>21–30: A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A</p>\n<h3>Level 3 — Q21–30</h3>\n<p><strong>Q21.</strong> Credentialed scanning improves: (a) visibility into patch state from inside the OS (b) BGP (c) printer alignment.<br><strong>Q22.</strong> Pentest differs from vulnerability scan mainly by: (a) human chaining and business impact validation (b) always being cheaper (c) replacing SIEM.<br><strong>Q23.</strong> WAF “virtual patch”: (a) hot rule blocking exploit pattern while code fix ships (b) replaces SSD (c) removes MFA.<br><strong>Q24.</strong> Reverse shells often appear as: (a) outbound connections from victim to attacker (b) inbound only always (c) DHCP offers.<br><strong>Q25.</strong> YARA is used for: (a) content-based matching of files/memory strings (b) routing (c) disk partitioning.<br><strong>Q26.</strong> Greenbone/OpenVAS policies should be: (a) tuned to environment and maintenance windows (b) max aggressive always on prod without notice (c) disabled always.<br><strong>Q27.</strong> WAF false positives can cause: (a) alert fatigue and business disruption (b) stronger AES (c) automatic PQC.<br><strong>Q28.</strong> Outbound firewall egress control helps against: (a) post-exploitation C2 (b) SQL collation only (c) VGA theft.<br><strong>Q29.</strong> <code>yarac</code> compiles: (a) YARA rules to bytecode for engines (b) TLS certs (c) Dockerfile layers.<br><strong>Q30.</strong> Scan “authentication” typically needs: (a) least-privilege scan account and coordination (b) domain admin always (c) BIOS password.</p>\n<h3>Answer key — Level 3 Q21–30</h3>\n<p>21–30: A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A</p>\n<h3>Level 4 — Q21–30</h3>\n<p><strong>Q21.</strong> Impossible travel detections need: (a) tuning to reduce HR false positives (b) RAID 6 (c) disabling logs.<br><strong>Q22.</strong> K8s default service account over-permission is risky because: (a) compromised pod may inherit broad token (b) it speeds BGP (c) it removes TLS.<br><strong>Q23.</strong> Per-function IAM roles in serverless reduce: (a) blast radius (b) need for logging (c) need for TLS.<br><strong>Q24.</strong> CASB helps with: (a) visibility and policy for SaaS usage (b) CPU overclocking (c) HDMI-CEC.<br><strong>Q25.</strong> Risky OAuth consent in SaaS can: (a) grant third-party apps access to mail/files (b) improve RAID (c) fix XSS.<br><strong>Q26.</strong> M&amp;A security asks often include: (a) unknown trust relationships and shadow admin paths (b) monitor Hz only (c) SMTP banners only.<br><strong>Q27.</strong> Token projection in Kubernetes aims to: (a) short-lived scoped tokens (b) remove network policies (c) disable audit logs.<br><strong>Q28.</strong> SaaS guest access risks include: (a) overshared links and stale accounts (b) faster RAM (c) ASLR disable.<br><strong>Q29.</strong> Namespace alone is: (a) not a full security boundary without controls (b) equal to HSM (c) always sufficient.<br><strong>Q30.</strong> M&amp;A day-one identity risks include: (a) duplicate UPNs and trust abuse (b) GPU brand (c) printer DPI.</p>\n<h3>Answer key — Level 4 Q21–30</h3>\n<p>21–30: A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A</p>\n<h3>Level 5 — Q21–30</h3>\n<p><strong>Q21.</strong> HSMs are often used when: (a) high-assurance key operations and compliance drive hardware protection (b) replacing MFA apps (c) fixing XSS.<br><strong>Q22.</strong> RPKI ROV helps reduce: (a) bogus route origination impact (b) SQLi (c) weak USB cables.<br><strong>Q23.</strong> Key ceremony dual control means: (a) no single person can misuse root material alone (b) two monitors required (c) two Wi-Fi bands.<br><strong>Q24.</strong> Rowhammer class issues relate to: (a) repeated DRAM access patterns causing bit flips (b) SMTP (c) RAID stripe width.<br><strong>Q25.</strong> Fuzzing in CI should include: (a) timeouts, crash dedup, owner routing (b) unlimited prod runs (c) deleting unit tests.<br><strong>Q26.</strong> Legal hold means: (a) preserve relevant data per counsel instruction (b) delete faster (c) disable EDR always.<br><strong>Q27.</strong> Spoliation refers to: (a) improper destruction of evidence (b) VLAN tagging (c) AES-GCM nonce.<br><strong>Q28.</strong> MANRS promotes: (a) routing security good practices (b) MFA for printers only (c) SQL indexes.<br><strong>Q29.</strong> Cloud KMS vs CloudHSM tradeoff often balances: (a) ops burden vs assurance level (b) monitor refresh vs RAID (c) DHCP vs DNS only.<br><strong>Q30.</strong> Executive BGP briefing should emphasize: (a) business downtime and third-party dependency (b) GPU shader cores (c) cookie flags only.</p>\n<h3>Answer key — Level 5 Q21–30</h3>\n<p>21–30: A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A</p>\n<hr>\n<h2>Additional lab sequences (multi-hour)</h2>\n<p><strong>Lab sequence A — “SOC analyst day zero” (Kali + local VMs you own)</strong>  </p>\n<ol>\n<li>Normalize time and verify log sources (<code>journalctl</code>, file <code>/var/log/auth.log</code>).  </li>\n<li>Build 10-line timeline from 5 synthetic log lines you fabricate with realistic timestamps.  </li>\n<li>Write triage notes: benign vs suspicious vs malicious for each line.  </li>\n<li>Escalation template: severity, affected assets, evidence hashes, open questions.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Lab sequence B — “AppSec code review sprint”</strong>  </p>\n<ol>\n<li>Pick an open-source tiny web app in lab.  </li>\n<li>Run dependency audit (<code>npm audit</code>, <code>pip-audit</code>, or OSV-Scanner) — document one finding’s reachability.  </li>\n<li>STRIDE one feature end-to-end.  </li>\n<li>Propose three fixes prioritized by exploitability and impact.</li>\n</ol>\n<p><strong>Lab sequence C — “Cloud logging detective” (personal/sandbox tenant only)</strong>  </p>\n<ol>\n<li>Enable a read-only audit log export or portal view you are allowed to use.  </li>\n<li>Map three activities: IAM change, login risk, resource creation.  </li>\n<li>Write one detection rule pseudo-snippet per activity.</li>\n</ol>\n<hr>\n<h1>Capstone — Part 2 (Q61–80)</h1>\n<p><strong>Q61.</strong> A healthy security culture rewards: (a) reporting near-misses (b) hiding mistakes (c) disabling MFA for VIPs.<br><strong>Q62.</strong> Separation of duties for payments typically prevents: (a) single-person fraud (b) TLS (c) RAID 1.<br><strong>Q63.</strong> <code>SameSite=Strict</code> is stricter than <code>Lax</code> for: (a) cross-site cookie sends on navigations (b) SQL performance (c) BIOS.<br><strong>Q64.</strong> OAuth <code>state</code> parameter mitigates: (a) CSRF on authorization endpoint (b) SQLi (c) BGP leaks.<br><strong>Q65.</strong> Refresh token rotation detects: (a) token theft/replay (b) RAID degradation (c) weak VGA.<br><strong>Q66.</strong> Content-Type sniffing defenses include: (a) <code>X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff</code> (b) disabling HTTPS (c) chmod 777.<br><strong>Q67.</strong> Subresource Integrity (SRI) helps when: (a) loading scripts from CDNs (b) configuring RAID (c) SMTP STARTTLS only.<br><strong>Q68.</strong> <code>Referrer-Policy</code> can reduce: (a) sensitive URL leakage in Referer headers (b) SQL index size (c) TPM PCR count.<br><strong>Q69.</strong> <code>Permissions-Policy</code> (Feature-Policy) limits: (a) powerful browser APIs (b) disk encryption (c) BGP communities.<br><strong>Q70.</strong> Rate limiting and CAPTCHA address: (a) credential stuffing and automated abuse (b) RAID 5 write hole (c) DNSSEC only.<br><strong>Q71.</strong> <code>ssh-ed25519</code> vs RSA4096 debate in 2026 often favors: (a) modern Ed25519 for performance/security balance when supported (b) telnet (c) FTP cleartext.<br><strong>Q72.</strong> <code>Fail2ban</code>-style controls are: (a) reactive/shallow ban based on logs (b) replacement for secure coding (c) guaranteed APT stopper.<br><strong>Q73.</strong> SOAR playbooks automate: (a) enrichment + repeatable IR steps (b) BGP origination (c) BIOS updates only.<br><strong>Q74.</strong> MITRE D3FEND relates to: (a) defensive countermeasures mapping (b) JavaScript minification (c) HDMI version.<br><strong>Q75.</strong> Cyber insurance questionnaires push: (a) evidence of controls and maturity (b) removal of MFA (c) weaker passwords.<br><strong>Q76.</strong> “Assume breach” implies: (a) interior segmentation and detection matter (b) perimeter is perfect (c) no logging needed.<br><strong>Q77.</strong> Zero-day handling often prioritizes: (a) exposure analysis, temporary mitigations, vendor tracking (b) deleting SIEM (c) public exploit posting first.<br><strong>Q78.</strong> Bug bounty differs from pentest partly by: (a) continuous crowdsourced testing scope (b) no rules (c) replaces internal QA always.<br><strong>Q79.</strong> Secure SDLC “shift left” means: (a) earlier security testing and design (b) deploy Friday 5pm always (c) remove code review.<br><strong>Q80.</strong> Post-incident “lessons learned” should produce: (a) tracked remediation items and metrics (b) blame-only sessions (c) deleted tickets.</p>\n<h3>Capstone Part 2 answer key</h3>\n<p>61–70: A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A<br>71–80: A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A</p>\n<hr>\n<h2>Appendix A — Glossary (compact)</h2>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Term</th>\n<th>Plain meaning</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>AAA</strong></td>\n<td>Authentication, authorization, accounting (audit).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>ABAC</strong></td>\n<td>Access from attributes (department, clearance, tags).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>AEAD</strong></td>\n<td>Authenticated encryption with associated data (confidentiality + integrity).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>ASLR</strong></td>\n<td>Randomizes memory layout to hinder exploitation.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>ATT&amp;CK</strong></td>\n<td>MITRE knowledge base of adversary tactics and techniques.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>BEC</strong></td>\n<td>Business email compromise — finance process fraud via email.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>C2</strong></td>\n<td>Command and control channel after compromise.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>CASB</strong></td>\n<td>Cloud access security broker — SaaS policy enforcement point.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>CAB</strong></td>\n<td>Change advisory board — governs production changes.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>CIA</strong></td>\n<td>Confidentiality, integrity, availability.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>CSP</strong></td>\n<td>Content Security Policy — reduces XSS impact.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>CSRF</strong></td>\n<td>Cross-site request forgery — forged actions using victim session.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>CVSS</strong></td>\n<td>Common Vulnerability Scoring System — severity snapshot.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>CWE</strong></td>\n<td>Weakness taxonomy (type of mistake).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>DLP</strong></td>\n<td>Data loss prevention — detect/block sensitive data movement.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>EDR</strong></td>\n<td>Endpoint detection and response — telemetry + response on hosts.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>FIDO2 / WebAuthn</strong></td>\n<td>Phishing-resistant MFA class.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>IAM</strong></td>\n<td>Identity and access management.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>IdP</strong></td>\n<td>Identity provider (issues tokens, authenticates users).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>IR</strong></td>\n<td>Incident response.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>JIT / PIM</strong></td>\n<td>Just-in-time / privileged identity management — time-bound admin.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>KMS</strong></td>\n<td>Key management service.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>mTLS</strong></td>\n<td>Mutual TLS — both sides present certificates.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>OIDC</strong></td>\n<td>OpenID Connect — identity layer on OAuth2.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>PEP / PDP</strong></td>\n<td>Policy enforcement / decision point (Zero Trust).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>PII</strong></td>\n<td>Personally identifiable information.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>PKCE</strong></td>\n<td>Proof Key for Code Exchange — OAuth public client protection.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>RPO / RTO</strong></td>\n<td>Recovery point / time objectives — data loss vs downtime budgets.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>RBAC</strong></td>\n<td>Role-based access control.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>RoE</strong></td>\n<td>Rules of engagement — legal/technical pentest boundaries.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>RPKI</strong></td>\n<td>Resource Public Key Infrastructure — cryptographically signed routing origination.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>SCP</strong></td>\n<td>Service control policy (AWS Organizations guardrail).</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>SIEM</strong></td>\n<td>Security information and event management — central correlation.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>SOAR</strong></td>\n<td>Security orchestration, automation, response.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>SSRF</strong></td>\n<td>Server-side request forgery — server tricked into fetching dangerous URLs.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>STRIDE</strong></td>\n<td>Spoofing, tampering, repudiation, info disclosure, DoS, elevation.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>TEE</strong></td>\n<td>Trusted execution environment.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>TLS</strong></td>\n<td>Transport Layer Security — encrypts channel; verifies identity if validated.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>TPM</strong></td>\n<td>Trusted Platform Module — hardware root for keys/measurements.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>WAF</strong></td>\n<td>Web application firewall — HTTP-layer policy engine.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>XSS</strong></td>\n<td>Cross-site scripting — attacker JS in victim browser context.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>ZT / ZTA</strong></td>\n<td>Zero Trust (Architecture).</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table>\n<hr>\n<h2>Appendix B — Kali Linux quick reference (lab-safe)</h2>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Task</th>\n<th>Example command</th>\n<th>Notes</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody><tr>\n<td>Who am I</td>\n<td><code>whoami</code> / <code>id</code></td>\n<td>Check privilege before risky commands.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Listening services</td>\n<td><code>ss -tuln</code></td>\n<td>Map attack surface of <strong>your</strong> VM.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Routes</td>\n<td><code>ip r</code></td>\n<td>Understand egress path; split tunnel awareness.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>DNS</td>\n<td><code>dig +short A example.com</code></td>\n<td>Use domains you are allowed to query.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>TLS peek</td>\n<td><code>openssl s_client -connect host:443 -servername host &lt;/dev/null</code></td>\n<td>Read-only to permitted hosts.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Recent auth</td>\n<td><code>journalctl -u ssh --since &quot;24 hours ago&quot;</code></td>\n<td>Tune unit name for your distro.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>File hash</td>\n<td><code>sha256sum file</code></td>\n<td>Evidence integrity.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Find SUID</td>\n<td><code>find / -perm -4000 -type f 2&gt;/dev/null | head</code></td>\n<td><strong>Read-only</strong> survey; expect noise.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Local vuln hints</td>\n<td><code>debsecan</code></td>\n<td>Match suite to your Debian/Kali base.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>Packet capture</td>\n<td><code>tcpdump -i any -c 20 -n</code></td>\n<td>Only on interfaces carrying <strong>your</strong> lab traffic.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table>\n<p><strong>Never:</strong> run exploit frameworks against networks without authorization; do not exfiltrate real customer data into Kali.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2>Appendix C — NIST CSF 2.0 functions → curriculum map (sample)</h2>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>CSF function</th>\n<th>Example lessons</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Govern (GV)</strong></td>\n<td>L1-15, L1-20, L4-20, L5-20</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Identify (ID)</strong></td>\n<td>L1-05, L1-06, L3-01, L3-11, L4-20</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Protect (PR)</strong></td>\n<td>L1-07–L1-14, L2-02–L2-03, L3-03–L3-04, L4-17–L4-19</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Detect (DE)</strong></td>\n<td>L3-07–L3-10, L3-19–L3-20, L4-09–L4-10, L4-16</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Respond (RS)</strong></td>\n<td>L3-15, L4-11, L5-20, Lab sequence A</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Recover (RC)</strong></td>\n<td>L1-13, L4-15, Lab sequence A</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table>\n<hr>\n<h2>Appendix D — Compliance one-liners (interview-safe)</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>GDPR:</strong> EU-focused privacy regulation; lawful basis, data subject rights, breach notification timelines matter operationally.  </li>\n<li><strong>HIPAA (US healthcare):</strong> PHI safeguards; BAAs with vendors; minimum necessary.  </li>\n<li><strong>PCI DSS:</strong> Cardholder data environment controls; segmentation and scanning expectations.  </li>\n<li><strong>SOC 2:</strong> Trust services criteria audit report; not a law but a customer assurance artifact.  </li>\n<li><strong>ISO 27001:</strong> ISMS certification framework; risk treatment and continual improvement.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Always defer specifics to your organization’s compliance team.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2>Appendix E — Behavioral interview hooks (STAR skeletons)</h2>\n<p>Prepare two stories each: <strong>(1)</strong> phishing or fraud attempt you reported or triaged, <strong>(2)</strong> vulnerability you prioritized against pushback, <strong>(3)</strong> outage or incident where you improved detection/response, <strong>(4)</strong> secure design tradeoff you negotiated with product.<br>Each story: <strong>S</strong>ituation → <strong>T</strong>ask → <strong>A</strong>ction (what <em>you</em> did) → <strong>R</strong>esult (metric or risk reduction).</p>\n<hr>\n<h1>Part 3 — Extended lessons (21–25 per level)</h1>\n<p>IDs: <code>lh-sec-l1-21</code> … <code>lh-sec-l5-25</code>. Use after Parts 1–2 or as specialization modules.</p>\n<h2>Level 1 — Part 3</h2>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-20</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Architecture tradeoff prompts want <strong>explicit assumptions</strong>—availability vs cost vs complexity, stated cleanly.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 5 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Asymmetric encryption</strong></dt><dd>Key pairs for key agreement/signing—RSA/ECC; hybrid TLS uses asymmetric to establish symmetric session keys.</dd><dt><strong>IR phases</strong></dt><dd>Prepare, detect, analyze, contain, eradicate, recover, and lessons learned—legal hold and evidence integrity matter throughout.</dd><dt><strong>Threat modeling (STRIDE)</strong></dt><dd>Spoofing, tampering, repudiation, information disclosure, denial of service, elevation of privilege—drive controls early.</dd><dt><strong>IV / nonce</strong></dt><dd>Initialization vector or number-used-once—must be unique per encryption under a key for many modes.</dd><dt><strong>UEBA</strong></dt><dd>User and entity behavior analytics—baseline deviations; tune to avoid HR/privacy backlash.</dd><dt><strong>Due care</strong></dt><dd>The effort a prudent person would take to meet a duty; in security, reasonable steps to protect assets and stakeholders.</dd><dt><strong>TLS</strong></dt><dd>Encrypts data in motion and authenticates endpoints when certificates and hostnames are validated; termination points affect trust boundaries.</dd><dt><strong>Security headers</strong></dt><dd>HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options/Frame-ancestors, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy—reduce browser-driven attack surface.</dd><dt><strong>Insider threat</strong></dt><dd>Malicious or negligent insiders—monitor with proportionality, separation of duties, and HR/legal partnership.</dd><dt><strong>Certificate transparency (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Public logs of issued certs help detect mis-issued certificates for your domains.</dd><dt><strong>RPO / RTO recap</strong></dt><dd>RPO = max acceptable data loss time; RTO = max acceptable outage—drive backup frequency and HA design.</dd><dt><strong>Compensating control</strong></dt><dd>Alternative control that meets intent when primary control cannot be implemented—must provide equivalent or greater assurance with documentation.</dd><dt><strong>FIDO2 / WebAuthn</strong></dt><dd>Phishing-resistant possession factors using asymmetric crypto and origin binding; preferred where supported.</dd><dt><strong>Key management</strong></dt><dd>Generation, storage, rotation, and destruction—HSM/KMS patterns reduce exposure compared to software-only secrets.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>IR phase</th><th>What you do there (exam shorthand)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Prepare</strong></td><td>Playbooks, contacts, tooling, baseline logging—before the pager fires.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detect &amp; analyze</strong></td><td>Scope, timelines, hypotheses—preserve volatile evidence early.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Contain</strong></td><td>Stop spread with minimal evidence damage—network isolation variants matter.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Eradicate &amp; recover</strong></td><td>Remove persistence, patch root cause, restore with verification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Lessons learned</strong></td><td>Metrics, control changes, and communication improvements—close the loop.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authorization</strong></td><td>Server-side object checks—headers and TLS do not replace this.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Immutable backups mitigate ransomware that tries to delete online copies—air-gapped or WORM patterns.</li><li>Terraform state can hold secrets—remote secure backend and scanning are baseline hygiene.</li><li>Sigma rules are vendor-agnostic detection snippets—tuning required per log source fields.</li><li>KMS key policies can deny even root in AWS when configured—explicit deny wins.</li><li>CVSS base does not include your asset criticality—environmental metrics exist for a reason.</li><li>Admission controllers can block privileged pods—policy-as-code integrates with GitOps reviews.</li><li>SameSite=Lax blocks many CSRF POSTs from cross-site contexts in modern browsers—know the nuance vs Strict.</li><li>Race conditions in web apps can undermine authorization—sequential logic tests in secure design reviews.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L5-20: Legal preservation and law-enforcement interaction (non-legal advice)</em>:</strong> LDAP vs Active Directory questions test directory concepts at a high level—binding, searches, and secure transport (LDAPS) appear often.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L5-20: Legal preservation and law-enforcement interaction (non-legal advice)</em>:</strong> Third-party and supply chain answers should emphasize <strong>contracts</strong>, <strong>evidence</strong>, and <strong>continuous monitoring</strong>—not “trust the SOC 2 logo” without scope review.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L5-20: Legal preservation and law-enforcement interaction (non-legal advice)</em>:</strong> RADIUS is still referenced for <strong>network access control</strong> integrations; know it as a AAA component in enterprise Wi-Fi contexts.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L5-20: Legal preservation and law-enforcement interaction (non-legal advice)</em>:</strong> Business continuity answers should reference <strong>RTO/RPO</strong>, <strong>workarounds</strong>, and <strong>tested restores</strong>; DR without practiced failover is wishful thinking, and exam writers know it.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L5-20: Legal preservation and law-enforcement interaction (non-legal advice)</em>:</strong> TACACS+ vs RADIUS separation of duties in device admin access—exams may contrast accounting granularity.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L5-20: Legal preservation and law-enforcement interaction (non-legal advice)</em>:</strong> Data handling questions often hinge on <strong>classification</strong>, <strong>least data</strong>, and <strong>retention</strong>: collect only what you need, keep it only as long as allowed, and destroy securely when done.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L5-20: Legal preservation and law-enforcement interaction (non-legal advice)</em>:</strong> Honeypots can generate high-signal alerts but carry <strong>legal and operational</strong> risk if touched by real users; scope carefully.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L5-20: Legal preservation and law-enforcement interaction (non-legal advice)</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L5-20: Legal preservation and law-enforcement interaction (non-legal advice)</em>:</strong> Deception tech is not a replacement for <strong>baselines and patching</strong>; it augments detection when mature processes exist.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L5-20: Legal preservation and law-enforcement interaction (non-legal advice)</em>:</strong> Engineers often optimize for speed; attackers optimize for <strong>cheap reuse</strong> of stolen creds and known exploits. The winning answer bridges both: ship fast with guardrails—feature flags, staged rollouts, and automated security checks in CI.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Purple team wants to simulate abuse of “L5-20: Legal preservation and law-enforcement interaction (non-legal advice)” next Friday. List <strong>safety gates</strong> (scope, rollback, monitoring) you require before authorizing the exercise.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l1-21":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L1-21: Data classification and handling labels</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-21</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Public / internal / confidential / restricted; labeling in email and tickets; retention.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> DLP policies map to labels; “restricted” may require encryption in transit and at rest.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Create <code>~/data-class-policy.md</code> with 4 tiers, one handling rule each, and one wrong example to fix.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-21</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Level 1 physical and operational items return to <strong>tailgating, visitor logs, and media destruction</strong>—do not skip them as “non-technical”; they are fair game.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 1 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>SSO</strong></dt><dd>Single sign-on federates trust to an IdP—misconfigured SAML/OIDC trusts are high-impact; validate metadata and signing keys.</dd><dt><strong>Certificate pinning (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Client remembers expected server key material—reduces MITM from rogue CAs but complicates rotation; mostly seen in mobile/API hardening patterns.</dd><dt><strong>XSS</strong></dt><dd>Cross-site scripting injects script in a victim context—CSP, output encoding, HttpOnly cookies, and DOM hygiene reduce blast radius.</dd><dt><strong>Chain of custody</strong></dt><dd>Documented handling of evidence from collection through presentation—hashing, write blockers, and access logs support admissibility.</dd><dt><strong>Insider threat</strong></dt><dd>Malicious or negligent insiders—monitor with proportionality, separation of duties, and HR/legal partnership.</dd><dt><strong>Business continuity testing</strong></dt><dd>Tabletops and technical failover drills reveal gaps in comms, dependencies, and vendor SLAs.</dd><dt><strong>Salt (crypto)</strong></dt><dd>Random input to a password hash to defeat rainbow tables—must be unique per password.</dd><dt><strong>Proxy vs reverse proxy</strong></dt><dd>Forward proxy represents clients outbound; reverse proxy fronts servers—different trust and logging points.</dd><dt><strong>IOC</strong></dt><dd>Indicator of compromise—often ephemeral (IPs, domains); pair with TTP-based detections for durability.</dd><dt><strong>Control</strong></dt><dd>Administrative, technical, or physical safeguards that reduce likelihood or impact of a security event (prevent, detect, correct).</dd><dt><strong>Data classification</strong></dt><dd>Labels (public, internal, confidential, restricted) drive storage, encryption, sharing, and disposal requirements.</dd><dt><strong>TLS</strong></dt><dd>Encrypts data in motion and authenticates endpoints when certificates and hostnames are validated; termination points affect trust boundaries.</dd><dt><strong>Encoding (e.g., Base64)</strong></dt><dd>Transforms representation without cryptographic protection—do not confuse with encryption or integrity.</dd><dt><strong>CVE</strong></dt><dd>Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures identifier for a specific flaw—pairs with CVSS severity and vendor advisories for prioritization.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>S3 bucket policies and ACLs layer with IAM—effective permissions require understanding intersection.</li><li>SameSite=Lax blocks many CSRF POSTs from cross-site contexts in modern browsers—know the nuance vs Strict.</li><li>GraphQL batching can amplify complexity attacks—depth and cost limits are first-class controls.</li><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li><li>GCP service account keys are long-lived secrets—prefer workload identity federation from CI where possible.</li><li>CVSS base does not include your asset criticality—environmental metrics exist for a reason.</li><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L1-21: Data classification and handling labels</em>:</strong> LDAP vs Active Directory questions test directory concepts at a high level—binding, searches, and secure transport (LDAPS) appear often.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L1-21: Data classification and handling labels</em>:</strong> Physical security is still on the exam: tailgating, visitor escorts, locks, destruction of media, and environmental controls (fire, HVAC) as availability/confidentiality supports.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L1-21: Data classification and handling labels</em>:</strong> CSP reporting helps tune policy but can leak URLs—<strong>privacy review</strong> of report endpoints matters in regulated environments.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L1-21: Data classification and handling labels</em>:</strong> Logging questions often test whether you understand <strong>what to log</strong> (who, what, when, where, outcome), <strong>time sync</strong> for correlation, and <strong>tamper resistance</strong> for evidentiary value—not whether you can collect infinite bytes.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L1-21: Data classification and handling labels</em>:</strong> Multicloud complexity increases <strong>identity sprawl</strong>; centralized IdP and consistent conditional access policies reduce human error.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L1-21: Data classification and handling labels</em>:</strong> Cloud items assume you can articulate <strong>shared responsibility</strong>: what the provider patches vs what the customer must configure (IAM, encryption, network exposure). Misconfiguration beats novel cloud exploits in real incidents and on the exam.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L1-21: Data classification and handling labels</em>:</strong> Penetration tests require <strong>written authorization</strong>, defined scope, and rules of engagement—even in internal labs for professional conduct.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L1-21: Data classification and handling labels</em>:</strong> Application security scenarios often test whether you know <strong>where</strong> enforcement belongs—browser controls supplement but do not replace server-side checks. SameSite cookies, CSP, and HttpOnly mitigate classes of issues; they do not fix broken object-level authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L1-21: Data classification and handling labels</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L1-21: Data classification and handling labels</em>:</strong> Risk decisions are economic: organizations <strong>accept</strong>, <strong>mitigate</strong>, <strong>transfer</strong> (insurance, outsourcing with contracts), or <strong>avoid</strong> (stop the activity). Controls change likelihood or impact; residual risk should be explicit, not invisible.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> A vendor integration project mentions “L1-21: Data classification and handling labels” as out-of-scope for pen testing. Explain what <strong>residual risk</strong> remains, what <strong>compensating monitoring</strong> you would demand, and how you would <strong>document acceptance</strong>.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l1-22":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L1-22: Security champions networks</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-22</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Embedded advocates per squad; office hours; secure release gates light enough to ship.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Champions feed AppSec backlog with context product security lacks.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Draft a 6-month champion charter: cadence, escalation path, recognition (non-monetary).</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-22</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Expect “which control type?” questions—administrative vs technical vs physical—tied to realistic workplace moments like contractor onboarding.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 1 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>CRL</strong></dt><dd>Certificate Revocation List—signed list of revoked serials; size/latency issues drove OCSP adoption.</dd><dt><strong>Zero Trust (headline)</strong></dt><dd>Assume breach; verify explicitly per request using identity, device posture, and least privilege—not “trust the LAN.”</dd><dt><strong>Perfect forward secrecy (PFS)</strong></dt><dd>Ephemeral key exchange means past session keys are not compromised if long-term keys leak later—TLS cipher suites can offer this property.</dd><dt><strong>Data retention</strong></dt><dd>Shorter retention reduces exposure and cost—legal holds override routine deletion when investigations require preservation.</dd><dt><strong>NetFlow / IPFIX</strong></dt><dd>Flow metadata for volume and anomaly detection—lighter than PCAP but less payload visibility.</dd><dt><strong>Availability</strong></dt><dd>Assures timely and reliable access—redundancy, patching, DDoS defenses, and DR planning keep services usable for authorized users.</dd><dt><strong>Security headers</strong></dt><dd>HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options/Frame-ancestors, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy—reduce browser-driven attack surface.</dd><dt><strong>Need to know</strong></dt><dd>Finer than least privilege for data—access only to the minimum subset required for the current task.</dd><dt><strong>DDoS</strong></dt><dd>Distributed denial of service—volumetric, protocol, or application-layer floods; mitigations include scrubbing, anycast, rate limits, and architecture elasticity.</dd><dt><strong>Firewall</strong></dt><dd>Enforces allow/deny rules on traffic—stateful inspection tracks sessions; default-deny with explicit permits is the secure baseline.</dd><dt><strong>Serverless blast radius</strong></dt><dd>One broad execution role affects every invocation—scope IAM per function and watch environment variable leaks.</dd><dt><strong>Diffie-Hellman (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Key agreement over insecure channel—combine with authentication to prevent MITM.</dd><dt><strong>Risk</strong></dt><dd>The intersection of threat, vulnerability, and impact—often assessed qualitatively (high/medium/low) or with scoring frameworks.</dd><dt><strong>Input validation vs output encoding</strong></dt><dd>Validation rejects bad input early; encoding neutralizes dangerous characters in the right output context—both are needed across HTML, SQL, OS, and LDAP channels.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>IR phase</th><th>What you do there (exam shorthand)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Prepare</strong></td><td>Playbooks, contacts, tooling, baseline logging—before the pager fires.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detect &amp; analyze</strong></td><td>Scope, timelines, hypotheses—preserve volatile evidence early.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Contain</strong></td><td>Stop spread with minimal evidence damage—network isolation variants matter.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Eradicate &amp; recover</strong></td><td>Remove persistence, patch root cause, restore with verification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Lessons learned</strong></td><td>Metrics, control changes, and communication improvements—close the loop.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Split tunnel VPN can exfil corporate data outside inspection if misconfigured—policy and routing matter.</li><li>KMS key policies can deny even root in AWS when configured—explicit deny wins.</li><li>PCI DSS scope reduction via segmentation is a recurring theme—if it is not in scope, it cannot drag you into assessment.</li><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li><li>Linux auth.log style entries pair with SSH brute-force detection patterns—velocity and geo anomalies.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L1-22: Security champions networks</em>:</strong> Evidence bags and write blockers signal <strong>forensics awareness</strong>; touching disks before imaging is a classic wrong answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L1-22: Security champions networks</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L1-22: Security champions networks</em>:</strong> Third-party and supply chain answers should emphasize <strong>contracts</strong>, <strong>evidence</strong>, and <strong>continuous monitoring</strong>—not “trust the SOC 2 logo” without scope review.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L1-22: Security champions networks</em>:</strong> SAST finds issues early but produces false positives; <strong>triage workflows</strong> and developer feedback loops are part of a mature program, not “run tool once.”</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L1-22: Security champions networks</em>:</strong> TPM-backed BitLocker keys illustrate <strong>key protection</strong> binding to platform state—recovery keys must be guarded like crown jewels.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L1-22: Security champions networks</em>:</strong> Access control stems frequently mix <strong>role</strong> vs <strong>attribute</strong> vs <strong>rule</strong> models; pick the answer that matches the scenario’s constraints (temporary contractor, cross-department data, dynamic tags on resources).</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L1-22: Security champions networks</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L1-22: Security champions networks</em>:</strong> Deception tech is not a replacement for <strong>baselines and patching</strong>; it augments detection when mature processes exist.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L1-22: Security champions networks</em>:</strong> Cloud items assume you can articulate <strong>shared responsibility</strong>: what the provider patches vs what the customer must configure (IAM, encryption, network exposure). Misconfiguration beats novel cloud exploits in real incidents and on the exam.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L1-22: Security champions networks</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Junior staff proposes a quick fix for “L1-22: Security champions networks” that disables logging on a noisy host. Walk through why that is unacceptable and propose a <strong>tuning</strong> path that preserves <strong>integrity and retention</strong> commitments.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l1-23":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L1-23: Third-party and vendor risk (questionnaires + evidence)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-23</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> SOC 2 report review vs questionnaire theater; subprocessors; exit plan.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Procurement gates; annual re-attestation.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Build a 15-row vendor checklist (encryption, SSO, logging, breach notice, DPA).</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-23</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>At Level 1, think like an analyst who must <strong>classify</strong> an event: asset, threat, vulnerability, control, residual risk. If you can narrate those five words for any headline topic, you are aligned with how writers build scenario questions.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 1 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Rainbow table</strong></dt><dd>Precomputed hash chains for fast password cracking—salting and modern KDFs are the defense.</dd><dt><strong>Diffie-Hellman (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Key agreement over insecure channel—combine with authentication to prevent MITM.</dd><dt><strong>NetFlow / IPFIX</strong></dt><dd>Flow metadata for volume and anomaly detection—lighter than PCAP but less payload visibility.</dd><dt><strong>OODA loop (IR)</strong></dt><dd>Observe-orient-decide-act—adversary and defender both iterate; faster, accurate decisions beat hoarding data.</dd><dt><strong>Data residency</strong></dt><dd>Legal requirement for where data lives—impacts cloud region selection and key custody.</dd><dt><strong>DNS</strong></dt><dd>Name resolution is a trust anchor—DNSSEC, cache poisoning, and malicious resolutions are classic abuse paths; log resolver anomalies.</dd><dt><strong>Quantitative vs qualitative risk</strong></dt><dd>Qualitative uses scales (high/medium/low); quantitative uses dollar or probability estimates—both need consistent assumptions and reviewer judgment.</dd><dt><strong>Residual risk</strong></dt><dd>Risk remaining after controls are applied; organizations accept, transfer, mitigate, or avoid it explicitly.</dd><dt><strong>Authenticity</strong></dt><dd>Verifies that users, devices, or data are genuine—cryptographic identity, attestation, and strong issuance processes matter.</dd><dt><strong>MFA</strong></dt><dd>Multi-factor authentication—requires two or more independent factors; push fatigue and MFA phishing are real bypass paths.</dd><dt><strong>DDoS</strong></dt><dd>Distributed denial of service—volumetric, protocol, or application-layer floods; mitigations include scrubbing, anycast, rate limits, and architecture elasticity.</dd><dt><strong>Zero Trust (headline)</strong></dt><dd>Assume breach; verify explicitly per request using identity, device posture, and least privilege—not “trust the LAN.”</dd><dt><strong>Digital signature</strong></dt><dd>Proves origin and integrity using private key to sign and public key to verify—non-repudiation when keys are well governed.</dd><dt><strong>OWASP Top 10</strong></dt><dd>High-prevalence web risks—broken access control and crypto failures often dominate; study each category with one workplace example.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li><li>Admission controllers can block privileged pods—policy-as-code integrates with GitOps reviews.</li><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>GCP service account keys are long-lived secrets—prefer workload identity federation from CI where possible.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>CVSS base does not include your asset criticality—environmental metrics exist for a reason.</li><li>Responsible disclosure timelines balance vendor patch readiness with public safety—coordinate, don’t surprise.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L1-23: Third-party and vendor risk (questionnaires + evidence)</em>:</strong> Evidence bags and write blockers signal <strong>forensics awareness</strong>; touching disks before imaging is a classic wrong answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L1-23: Third-party and vendor risk (questionnaires + evidence)</em>:</strong> LDAP vs Active Directory questions test directory concepts at a high level—binding, searches, and secure transport (LDAPS) appear often.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L1-23: Third-party and vendor risk (questionnaires + evidence)</em>:</strong> BIOS/UEFI passwords and secure boot reduce some pre-boot attacks but do not stop <strong>evil maid</strong> classes without additional controls.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L1-23: Third-party and vendor risk (questionnaires + evidence)</em>:</strong> Controls fail in three predictable ways: <strong>misconfiguration</strong>, <strong>missing coverage</strong> (gaps between tools), and <strong>human process</strong> breakdown (exceptions, shared accounts, emergency access). When you read a scenario, ask which failure mode is most plausible before picking an answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L1-23: Third-party and vendor risk (questionnaires + evidence)</em>:</strong> Vulnerability management is a lifecycle: scanners find candidates, analysts prioritize with exploitability and business context, owners remediate, and verification closes the loop. “Patch everything immediately” is rarely operational; <strong>risk-based SLAs</strong> are the adult answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L1-23: Third-party and vendor risk (questionnaires + evidence)</em>:</strong> Wireless and mobility items reward knowing basics: WPA3 improvements conceptually, evil twin risks, captive portals, and why client isolation matters on guest networks—without memorizing obsolete WEP details unless explicitly historical.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L1-23: Third-party and vendor risk (questionnaires + evidence)</em>:</strong> Engineers often optimize for speed; attackers optimize for <strong>cheap reuse</strong> of stolen creds and known exploits. The winning answer bridges both: ship fast with guardrails—feature flags, staged rollouts, and automated security checks in CI.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L1-23: Third-party and vendor risk (questionnaires + evidence)</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L1-23: Third-party and vendor risk (questionnaires + evidence)</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L1-23: Third-party and vendor risk (questionnaires + evidence)</em>:</strong> API keys in mobile apps are often extractable—prefer <strong>short-lived tokens</strong> and server-mediated access to backends.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Marketing launches a campaign referencing “L1-23: Third-party and vendor risk (questionnaires + evidence)” with a new subdomain. Security review finds DNS delegated to an unknown party. Explain <strong>trust chain</strong> risks and the <strong>minimum fixes</strong> before go-live.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l1-24":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L1-24: Home office and Wi-Fi hygiene</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-24</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> WPA3, router firmware, guest VLAN, IoT isolation; corporate device vs personal.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> “Split tunnel from home” risk acceptance documentation.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> <code>iwconfig 2&gt;/dev/null || nmcli dev wifi list 2&gt;/dev/null | head</code> — document your <strong>lab</strong> Wi-Fi security mode (no neighbor SSIDs in reports).</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-24</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Expect “which control type?” questions—administrative vs technical vs physical—tied to realistic workplace moments like contractor onboarding.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 1 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>PII</strong></dt><dd>Personally identifiable information—names, government IDs, biometrics, account numbers; triggers handling, retention, and breach rules.</dd><dt><strong>Security misconfiguration</strong></dt><dd>Default creds, debug features on in prod, verbose errors, open directory listings—hardening baselines and drift detection reduce this class.</dd><dt><strong>Supply chain security</strong></dt><dd>SBOM, provenance signing (SLSA-style thinking), and dependency pinning reduce “update from upstream” surprises.</dd><dt><strong>MAC</strong></dt><dd>Message authentication code—integrity with a secret key; differs from digital signature which uses asymmetric keys.</dd><dt><strong>Exploit</strong></dt><dd>A technique or code that takes advantage of a vulnerability to achieve an attacker goal (exfiltration, persistence, disruption).</dd><dt><strong>Zero Trust (headline)</strong></dt><dd>Assume breach; verify explicitly per request using identity, device posture, and least privilege—not “trust the LAN.”</dd><dt><strong>IAM least privilege</strong></dt><dd>Grant minimum API/console rights; prefer roles over long-lived keys; audit risky admin-equivalent paths regularly.</dd><dt><strong>Token replay</strong></dt><dd>Reusing a stolen token/session artifact—rotation, binding, and short TTLs reduce window.</dd><dt><strong>Kill chain / cyber kill chain</strong></dt><dd>Stages of intrusion—mapping controls and detections to stages clarifies coverage gaps.</dd><dt><strong>FIDO2 / WebAuthn</strong></dt><dd>Phishing-resistant possession factors using asymmetric crypto and origin binding; preferred where supported.</dd><dt><strong>IDOR</strong></dt><dd>Insecure direct object reference—missing object-level authorization; test horizontal/vertical access with different accounts.</dd><dt><strong>PQC</strong></dt><dd>Post-quantum cryptography migration—hybrid schemes and crypto-agility for long-lived secrets exposed to harvest-now/decrypt-later risk.</dd><dt><strong>Jump server / bastion</strong></dt><dd>Hardened administrative entry point—centralizes session recording and access policy for admins.</dd><dt><strong>Due diligence</strong></dt><dd>Investigation and verification before decisions (vendor risk, M&amp;A) to ensure claims about controls are credible.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>IR phase</th><th>What you do there (exam shorthand)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Prepare</strong></td><td>Playbooks, contacts, tooling, baseline logging—before the pager fires.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detect &amp; analyze</strong></td><td>Scope, timelines, hypotheses—preserve volatile evidence early.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Contain</strong></td><td>Stop spread with minimal evidence damage—network isolation variants matter.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Eradicate &amp; recover</strong></td><td>Remove persistence, patch root cause, restore with verification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Lessons learned</strong></td><td>Metrics, control changes, and communication improvements—close the loop.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>HttpOnly does not stop CSRF; it reduces token theft from XSS reading document.cookie in many setups.</li><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>GraphQL batching can amplify complexity attacks—depth and cost limits are first-class controls.</li><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li><li>Certificate pinning misconfigurations can brick apps—plan rotation and emergency releases.</li><li>AES-128 is not “half as strong” as AES-256 in practical threat models for many cases—key management quality dominates.</li><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L1-24: Home office and Wi-Fi hygiene</em>:</strong> Certificate pinning failures during rotation teach why <strong>key continuity strategy</strong> must be planned before mobile releases.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L1-24: Home office and Wi-Fi hygiene</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L1-24: Home office and Wi-Fi hygiene</em>:</strong> Governance and awareness questions tie policy to behavior: acceptable use, clean desk, travel security, and vendor due diligence. Pick answers that reduce <strong>realistic</strong> human failure modes, not answers that maximize surveillance without process support.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L1-24: Home office and Wi-Fi hygiene</em>:</strong> Virtualization risks include <strong>snapshot sprawl</strong> containing secrets and stale VM images drifting from hardened baselines.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L1-24: Home office and Wi-Fi hygiene</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L1-24: Home office and Wi-Fi hygiene</em>:</strong> Third-party and supply chain answers should emphasize <strong>contracts</strong>, <strong>evidence</strong>, and <strong>continuous monitoring</strong>—not “trust the SOC 2 logo” without scope review.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L1-24: Home office and Wi-Fi hygiene</em>:</strong> For the Security+ mindset, translate every control into <strong>who</strong> it protects, <strong>what</strong> asset is at risk, and <strong>how</strong> you would detect failure. Interview and exam items often reward practical prioritization over buzzwords—choose the mitigation that reduces realistic loss first.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L1-24: Home office and Wi-Fi hygiene</em>:</strong> API keys in mobile apps are often extractable—prefer <strong>short-lived tokens</strong> and server-mediated access to backends.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L1-24: Home office and Wi-Fi hygiene</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L1-24: Home office and Wi-Fi hygiene</em>:</strong> Application security scenarios often test whether you know <strong>where</strong> enforcement belongs—browser controls supplement but do not replace server-side checks. SameSite cookies, CSP, and HttpOnly mitigate classes of issues; they do not fix broken object-level authorization.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Internal audit samples “L1-24: Home office and Wi-Fi hygiene” controls and finds screenshots instead of config exports. Explain why <strong>authoritative evidence</strong> matters and what you would collect instead.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l1-25":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L1-25: Browser compartmentalization and extension risk</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-25</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Separate profiles for admin vs casual; least extensions; enterprise browser policy.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Managed browsers push blocklists and update cadence.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> List installed Firefox/Chromium extensions path on Kali; mark “high privilege” if any can read all tabs.</p>\n<h2>Level 2 — Part 3</h2>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l1-25</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>At Level 1, think like an analyst who must <strong>classify</strong> an event: asset, threat, vulnerability, control, residual risk. If you can narrate those five words for any headline topic, you are aligned with how writers build scenario questions.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 1 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>TTP</strong></dt><dd>Tactics, techniques, and procedures—behavioral patterns; harder to change than IOCs, better for resilient detection.</dd><dt><strong>Kerberos (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Ticket-based enterprise auth—TGT vs service tickets; golden/silver ticket classes of abuse appear in advanced IR.</dd><dt><strong>Logging &amp; monitoring</strong></dt><dd>CloudTrail-style management events differ from data-plane logs—enable central export, immutability, and alerting.</dd><dt><strong>ECB mode weakness</strong></dt><dd>Identical plaintext blocks yield identical ciphertext—leaks structure; prefer modes with IVs and authentication.</dd><dt><strong>Exploit</strong></dt><dd>A technique or code that takes advantage of a vulnerability to achieve an attacker goal (exfiltration, persistence, disruption).</dd><dt><strong>Key management</strong></dt><dd>Generation, storage, rotation, and destruction—HSM/KMS patterns reduce exposure compared to software-only secrets.</dd><dt><strong>Threat modeling (STRIDE)</strong></dt><dd>Spoofing, tampering, repudiation, information disclosure, denial of service, elevation of privilege—drive controls early.</dd><dt><strong>Diamond model</strong></dt><dd>Adversary, infrastructure, capability, victim—useful for pivoting investigations and intel fusion.</dd><dt><strong>Password policy</strong></dt><dd>Modern guidance favors long passphrases, breach-banned lists, and vaults over rotation-for-its-own-sake complexity theater.</dd><dt><strong>Chain of custody</strong></dt><dd>Documented handling of evidence from collection through presentation—hashing, write blockers, and access logs support admissibility.</dd><dt><strong>Rainbow table</strong></dt><dd>Precomputed hash chains for fast password cracking—salting and modern KDFs are the defense.</dd><dt><strong>Asset</strong></dt><dd>Anything of value to the organization—data, systems, people, reputation, or services—that security controls protect.</dd><dt><strong>Digital signature</strong></dt><dd>Proves origin and integrity using private key to sign and public key to verify—non-repudiation when keys are well governed.</dd><dt><strong>Zero Trust architecture</strong></dt><dd>Identity-centric access with continuous verification—policy enforcement points for users, devices, and workloads.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Terraform state can hold secrets—remote secure backend and scanning are baseline hygiene.</li><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>Immutable backups mitigate ransomware that tries to delete online copies—air-gapped or WORM patterns.</li><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li><li>Bug bounty scope must exclude destructive testing—safe harbor language still needs legal review.</li><li>HttpOnly does not stop CSRF; it reduces token theft from XSS reading document.cookie in many setups.</li><li>Split tunnel VPN can exfil corporate data outside inspection if misconfigured—policy and routing matter.</li><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L1-25: Browser compartmentalization and extension risk</em>:</strong> Wireless and mobility items reward knowing basics: WPA3 improvements conceptually, evil twin risks, captive portals, and why client isolation matters on guest networks—without memorizing obsolete WEP details unless explicitly historical.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L1-25: Browser compartmentalization and extension risk</em>:</strong> When logs “mysteriously stop,” think <strong>time sync failure</strong>, collector saturation, retention misconfiguration, or attacker tampering—in that diagnostic order for a fair exam narrative.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L1-25: Browser compartmentalization and extension risk</em>:</strong> Evidence bags and write blockers signal <strong>forensics awareness</strong>; touching disks before imaging is a classic wrong answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L1-25: Browser compartmentalization and extension risk</em>:</strong> Virtualization risks include <strong>snapshot sprawl</strong> containing secrets and stale VM images drifting from hardened baselines.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L1-25: Browser compartmentalization and extension risk</em>:</strong> Cryptography questions reward vocabulary precision: hashing vs encryption vs encoding; symmetric vs asymmetric roles in TLS; what signatures prove; and why key management is usually harder than picking an algorithm. If an answer sounds magical, it is probably wrong.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L1-25: Browser compartmentalization and extension risk</em>:</strong> Business continuity answers should reference <strong>RTO/RPO</strong>, <strong>workarounds</strong>, and <strong>tested restores</strong>; DR without practiced failover is wishful thinking, and exam writers know it.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L1-25: Browser compartmentalization and extension risk</em>:</strong> KMS keys are not “magic secrecy dust”—<strong>who can invoke decrypt</strong> and from which contexts (VPC endpoint policies, IAM conditions) is what exams probe.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L1-25: Browser compartmentalization and extension risk</em>:</strong> CSP reporting helps tune policy but can leak URLs—<strong>privacy review</strong> of report endpoints matters in regulated environments.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L1-25: Browser compartmentalization and extension risk</em>:</strong> Social engineering callbacks to <strong>pretexting</strong>, <strong>baiting</strong>, and <strong>vishing</strong>—name the subtype when the stem describes the tactic.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L1-25: Browser compartmentalization and extension risk</em>:</strong> Cloud items assume you can articulate <strong>shared responsibility</strong>: what the provider patches vs what the customer must configure (IAM, encryption, network exposure). Misconfiguration beats novel cloud exploits in real incidents and on the exam.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> A vendor integration project mentions “L1-25: Browser compartmentalization and extension risk” as out-of-scope for pen testing. Explain what <strong>residual risk</strong> remains, what <strong>compensating monitoring</strong> you would demand, and how you would <strong>document acceptance</strong>.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l2-21":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L2-21: JWTs — what breaks in production</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-21</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> <code>alg</code> confusion, weak HS256 shared secrets, missing <code>aud</code>/<code>iss</code>, clock skew, huge claims.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Prefer opaque server-side sessions or hardened JWT + JWKS rotation.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Decode a <strong>synthetic</strong> JWT at <a href=\"https://jwt.io\">https://jwt.io</a> with a <strong>fake</strong> secret you invent — never paste production tokens.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-21</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Hybrid identity and remote access scenarios appear here—know when <strong>split tunneling</strong> changes what your security tools can see.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 2 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Jump server / bastion</strong></dt><dd>Hardened administrative entry point—centralizes session recording and access policy for admins.</dd><dt><strong>Residual risk</strong></dt><dd>Risk remaining after controls are applied; organizations accept, transfer, mitigate, or avoid it explicitly.</dd><dt><strong>Network segmentation</strong></dt><dd>VLANs, micro-segmentation, and east-west controls limit lateral movement after an initial foothold.</dd><dt><strong>Shared responsibility model</strong></dt><dd>Cloud provider secures the platform; customer secures configuration, identities, data, and app code in their scope.</dd><dt><strong>Mandatory vacation</strong></dt><dd>Forces handover and review of another employee’s work—can uncover fraud or backdoors.</dd><dt><strong>RPO / RTO recap</strong></dt><dd>RPO = max acceptable data loss time; RTO = max acceptable outage—drive backup frequency and HA design.</dd><dt><strong>Non-repudiation</strong></dt><dd>Prevents a party from credibly denying an action—digital signatures, tamper-evident logs, and time-stamping support it.</dd><dt><strong>Encoding (e.g., Base64)</strong></dt><dd>Transforms representation without cryptographic protection—do not confuse with encryption or integrity.</dd><dt><strong>GRC</strong></dt><dd>Governance, risk, and compliance—align security decisions with law, policy, and business appetite; audits test design and operation.</dd><dt><strong>CRL</strong></dt><dd>Certificate Revocation List—signed list of revoked serials; size/latency issues drove OCSP adoption.</dd><dt><strong>SOAR</strong></dt><dd>Security orchestration, automation, response—playbooks must have human gates for destructive actions.</dd><dt><strong>Password policy</strong></dt><dd>Modern guidance favors long passphrases, breach-banned lists, and vaults over rotation-for-its-own-sake complexity theater.</dd><dt><strong>CSRF</strong></dt><dd>Cross-site request forgery rides ambient auth—anti-CSRF tokens, SameSite cookies, and re-auth for sensitive actions help.</dd><dt><strong>Threat intelligence lifecycle</strong></dt><dd>Planning, collection, processing, analysis, dissemination, feedback—intel must change detections or posture or it is shelf-ware.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authorization</strong></td><td>Server-side object checks—headers and TLS do not replace this.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>AES-128 is not “half as strong” as AES-256 in practical threat models for many cases—key management quality dominates.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>PCI DSS scope reduction via segmentation is a recurring theme—if it is not in scope, it cannot drag you into assessment.</li><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li><li>KMS key policies can deny even root in AWS when configured—explicit deny wins.</li><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li><li>SLSA levels describe increasing supply-chain assurance—useful vocabulary in modern governance questions.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L2-21: JWTs — what breaks in production</em>:</strong> Third-party and supply chain answers should emphasize <strong>contracts</strong>, <strong>evidence</strong>, and <strong>continuous monitoring</strong>—not “trust the SOC 2 logo” without scope review.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L2-21: JWTs — what breaks in production</em>:</strong> Clean desk pairs with <strong>screen privacy</strong> and <strong>clear desk checks</strong> for regulated spaces—physical + procedural controls together.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L2-21: JWTs — what breaks in production</em>:</strong> Penetration tests require <strong>written authorization</strong>, defined scope, and rules of engagement—even in internal labs for professional conduct.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L2-21: JWTs — what breaks in production</em>:</strong> Business continuity answers should reference <strong>RTO/RPO</strong>, <strong>workarounds</strong>, and <strong>tested restores</strong>; DR without practiced failover is wishful thinking, and exam writers know it.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L2-21: JWTs — what breaks in production</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L2-21: JWTs — what breaks in production</em>:</strong> Tabletop exercises test <strong>comms trees</strong>, legal escalation, and customer notification templates—not only technical runbooks.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L2-21: JWTs — what breaks in production</em>:</strong> Data handling questions often hinge on <strong>classification</strong>, <strong>least data</strong>, and <strong>retention</strong>: collect only what you need, keep it only as long as allowed, and destroy securely when done.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L2-21: JWTs — what breaks in production</em>:</strong> For the Security+ mindset, translate every control into <strong>who</strong> it protects, <strong>what</strong> asset is at risk, and <strong>how</strong> you would detect failure. Interview and exam items often reward practical prioritization over buzzwords—choose the mitigation that reduces realistic loss first.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L2-21: JWTs — what breaks in production</em>:</strong> Evidence bags and write blockers signal <strong>forensics awareness</strong>; touching disks before imaging is a classic wrong answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L2-21: JWTs — what breaks in production</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Purple team wants to simulate abuse of “L2-21: JWTs — what breaks in production” next Friday. List <strong>safety gates</strong> (scope, rollback, monitoring) you require before authorizing the exercise.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l2-22":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L2-22: GraphQL abuse (complexity, batching, introspection)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-22</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Depth/cost limits; disable introspection in prod; authz per field, not only per route.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Federation increases trust surface across subgraphs.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Write a GraphQL query with nested depth 6 — explain why a cost analyzer would block it.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-22</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>TLS questions separate <strong>confidentiality channel</strong> from <strong>server authentication</strong>—certificate validation and hostname checks matter in the answer set.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 2 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Kill chain / cyber kill chain</strong></dt><dd>Stages of intrusion—mapping controls and detections to stages clarifies coverage gaps.</dd><dt><strong>Integrity</strong></dt><dd>Assures accuracy and trustworthiness—hashing, signatures, change control, and backups protect against unauthorized modification.</dd><dt><strong>PKI</strong></dt><dd>Public Key Infrastructure—CAs, RAs, CRL/OCSP, and certificate lifecycle; mis-issuance or weak validation breaks trust chains.</dd><dt><strong>BCP / DR</strong></dt><dd>Business continuity and disaster recovery—RTO/RPO drive architecture; test restores, not just backups on paper.</dd><dt><strong>Rainbow table</strong></dt><dd>Precomputed hash chains for fast password cracking—salting and modern KDFs are the defense.</dd><dt><strong>Security misconfiguration</strong></dt><dd>Default creds, debug features on in prod, verbose errors, open directory listings—hardening baselines and drift detection reduce this class.</dd><dt><strong>Authorization</strong></dt><dd>What an authenticated subject is allowed to do—RBAC/ABAC, scopes, and server-side checks enforce least privilege.</dd><dt><strong>XSS</strong></dt><dd>Cross-site scripting injects script in a victim context—CSP, output encoding, HttpOnly cookies, and DOM hygiene reduce blast radius.</dd><dt><strong>Attack surface</strong></dt><dd>The sum of exposure—every service, API, integration, and human workflow that can be reached by a threat; reduction beats perfect monitoring alone.</dd><dt><strong>MITM</strong></dt><dd>Man-in-the-middle intercepts or alters traffic—TLS with proper validation mitigates; corporate SSL inspection is its own trust zone.</dd><dt><strong>DevSecOps</strong></dt><dd>Embed security gates in CI/CD with fast feedback—policy-as-code, secret scanning, and SBOMs support supply-chain resilience.</dd><dt><strong>DDoS</strong></dt><dd>Distributed denial of service—volumetric, protocol, or application-layer floods; mitigations include scrubbing, anycast, rate limits, and architecture elasticity.</dd><dt><strong>CWE</strong></dt><dd>Common Weakness Enumeration—taxonomy of software weakness types that help root-cause fixes beyond one CVE instance.</dd><dt><strong>Business continuity testing</strong></dt><dd>Tabletops and technical failover drills reveal gaps in comms, dependencies, and vendor SLAs.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Typical exam angle</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Confidentiality</strong></td><td>Who may read? Encryption, ACLs, DLP, classification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Integrity</strong></td><td>Was it modified? Hashing, signatures, change control, backups.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Availability</strong></td><td>Can authorized users work? HA, patching windows, DDoS defense, DR.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authenticity / non-repudiation</strong></td><td>Prove source and intent—signatures, strong issuance, tamper-evident logs.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li><li>EPSS (concept) scores exploitation probability—useful alongside CVSS for prioritization in mature programs.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>Azure AD / Entra conditional access is analogous to risk-based policies—device compliance signals matter.</li><li>ISO 27001 is an ISMS standard; it emphasizes risk treatment and continual improvement, not a product checklist.</li><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li><li>Server-side template injection is distinct from XSS—context and sinks differ.</li><li>SBOM formats (CycloneDX/SPDX) help inventory components for incident response and licensing—not only security.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L2-22: GraphQL abuse (complexity, batching, introspection)</em>:</strong> Email security stems often combine SPF alignment failures with <strong>look-alike domains</strong>. The best answer addresses user training plus technical authenticity controls, not only one or the other.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L2-22: GraphQL abuse (complexity, batching, introspection)</em>:</strong> Application security scenarios often test whether you know <strong>where</strong> enforcement belongs—browser controls supplement but do not replace server-side checks. SameSite cookies, CSP, and HttpOnly mitigate classes of issues; they do not fix broken object-level authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L2-22: GraphQL abuse (complexity, batching, introspection)</em>:</strong> LDAP vs Active Directory questions test directory concepts at a high level—binding, searches, and secure transport (LDAPS) appear often.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L2-22: GraphQL abuse (complexity, batching, introspection)</em>:</strong> When logs “mysteriously stop,” think <strong>time sync failure</strong>, collector saturation, retention misconfiguration, or attacker tampering—in that diagnostic order for a fair exam narrative.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L2-22: GraphQL abuse (complexity, batching, introspection)</em>:</strong> Vulnerability management is a lifecycle: scanners find candidates, analysts prioritize with exploitability and business context, owners remediate, and verification closes the loop. “Patch everything immediately” is rarely operational; <strong>risk-based SLAs</strong> are the adult answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L2-22: GraphQL abuse (complexity, batching, introspection)</em>:</strong> RADIUS is still referenced for <strong>network access control</strong> integrations; know it as a AAA component in enterprise Wi-Fi contexts.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L2-22: GraphQL abuse (complexity, batching, introspection)</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L2-22: GraphQL abuse (complexity, batching, introspection)</em>:</strong> Incident response questions probe containment vs evidence preservation tension, legal escalation, and communication discipline. The exam rewards knowing when to isolate systems, when to involve counsel, and why mass log deletion is catastrophic.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L2-22: GraphQL abuse (complexity, batching, introspection)</em>:</strong> TACACS+ vs RADIUS separation of duties in device admin access—exams may contrast accounting granularity.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L2-22: GraphQL abuse (complexity, batching, introspection)</em>:</strong> Container escape questions hinge on <strong>kernel boundary</strong> and misconfigured capabilities—namespaces are helpful but not a complete trust boundary without seccomp, AppArmor, and least-privileged service accounts.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> You are the on-call analyst reviewing an alert tied to “L2-22: GraphQL abuse (complexity, batching, introspection)”. Leadership wants a <strong>60-second</strong> brief: business impact, evidence gaps, and the <strong>first</strong> containment step that preserves logs. No tool-specific jargon—prioritize scope, evidence, blast radius, then root-cause remediation under change control.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l2-23":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L2-23: CSP reporting (`report-uri` / `report-to`)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-23</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Collect violations without blocking users during rollout; noise management.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Report-only mode before enforce.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Draft a CSP header string with <code>default-src &#39;self&#39;</code> and <code>report-uri</code> pointing to internal collector (placeholder URL).</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-23</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Email authenticity (SPF/DKIM/DMARC) is a frequent multi-part stem—read whether the failure is <strong>alignment</strong>, <strong>policy</strong>, or <strong>operator error</strong>.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 2 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>SIEM</strong></dt><dd>Security information and event management—centralize logs, parse fields, correlate alerts; tuning reduces false positives and fatigue.</dd><dt><strong>Metrics that matter</strong></dt><dd>Mean time to detect/remediate with quality, coverage of critical assets, and control effectiveness—not vanity ticket counts.</dd><dt><strong>Downgrade attack</strong></dt><dd>Forcing weaker crypto or protocols—HSTS and modern TLS config reduce browser downgrade paths.</dd><dt><strong>Full packet capture</strong></dt><dd>High fidelity evidence for investigations—storage, privacy, and legal review constraints apply.</dd><dt><strong>OWASP Top 10</strong></dt><dd>High-prevalence web risks—broken access control and crypto failures often dominate; study each category with one workplace example.</dd><dt><strong>Due diligence</strong></dt><dd>Investigation and verification before decisions (vendor risk, M&amp;A) to ensure claims about controls are credible.</dd><dt><strong>DDoS</strong></dt><dd>Distributed denial of service—volumetric, protocol, or application-layer floods; mitigations include scrubbing, anycast, rate limits, and architecture elasticity.</dd><dt><strong>Input validation vs output encoding</strong></dt><dd>Validation rejects bad input early; encoding neutralizes dangerous characters in the right output context—both are needed across HTML, SQL, OS, and LDAP channels.</dd><dt><strong>IAM least privilege</strong></dt><dd>Grant minimum API/console rights; prefer roles over long-lived keys; audit risky admin-equivalent paths regularly.</dd><dt><strong>Confidential computing</strong></dt><dd>Use of hardware enclaves/TEEs to reduce exposure to privileged operators—threat model still required.</dd><dt><strong>PBKDF2 / Argon2 (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Key derivation functions that slow brute force—work factors must track attacker economics.</dd><dt><strong>RPO / RTO recap</strong></dt><dd>RPO = max acceptable data loss time; RTO = max acceptable outage—drive backup frequency and HA design.</dd><dt><strong>Security headers</strong></dt><dd>HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options/Frame-ancestors, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy—reduce browser-driven attack surface.</dd><dt><strong>Authenticity</strong></dt><dd>Verifies that users, devices, or data are genuine—cryptographic identity, attestation, and strong issuance processes matter.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>IR phase</th><th>What you do there (exam shorthand)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Prepare</strong></td><td>Playbooks, contacts, tooling, baseline logging—before the pager fires.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detect &amp; analyze</strong></td><td>Scope, timelines, hypotheses—preserve volatile evidence early.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Contain</strong></td><td>Stop spread with minimal evidence damage—network isolation variants matter.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Eradicate &amp; recover</strong></td><td>Remove persistence, patch root cause, restore with verification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Lessons learned</strong></td><td>Metrics, control changes, and communication improvements—close the loop.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authorization</strong></td><td>Server-side object checks—headers and TLS do not replace this.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>UDP-based protocols can be abused for amplification DDoS—patch open resolvers and monitor volumetric baselines.</li><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li><li>Terraform state can hold secrets—remote secure backend and scanning are baseline hygiene.</li><li>EPSS (concept) scores exploitation probability—useful alongside CVSS for prioritization in mature programs.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li><li>PCI DSS scope reduction via segmentation is a recurring theme—if it is not in scope, it cannot drag you into assessment.</li><li>Certificate pinning misconfigurations can brick apps—plan rotation and emergency releases.</li><li>Bug bounty scope must exclude destructive testing—safe harbor language still needs legal review.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L2-23: CSP reporting (`report-uri` / `report-to`)</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L2-23: CSP reporting (`report-uri` / `report-to`)</em>:</strong> Advanced topics still return to fundamentals: least privilege, segmentation, logging, and tested recovery. When you see Zero Trust or PQC buzzwords, map them back to concrete controls and threat models rather than treating them as magic shields.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L2-23: CSP reporting (`report-uri` / `report-to`)</em>:</strong> RADIUS is still referenced for <strong>network access control</strong> integrations; know it as a AAA component in enterprise Wi-Fi contexts.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L2-23: CSP reporting (`report-uri` / `report-to`)</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L2-23: CSP reporting (`report-uri` / `report-to`)</em>:</strong> Controls fail in three predictable ways: <strong>misconfiguration</strong>, <strong>missing coverage</strong> (gaps between tools), and <strong>human process</strong> breakdown (exceptions, shared accounts, emergency access). When you read a scenario, ask which failure mode is most plausible before picking an answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L2-23: CSP reporting (`report-uri` / `report-to`)</em>:</strong> DAST exercises running apps but misses authz logic without credentials; combine with <strong>manual review</strong> for business-rule flaws.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L2-23: CSP reporting (`report-uri` / `report-to`)</em>:</strong> Access control stems frequently mix <strong>role</strong> vs <strong>attribute</strong> vs <strong>rule</strong> models; pick the answer that matches the scenario’s constraints (temporary contractor, cross-department data, dynamic tags on resources).</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L2-23: CSP reporting (`report-uri` / `report-to`)</em>:</strong> Honeypots can generate high-signal alerts but carry <strong>legal and operational</strong> risk if touched by real users; scope carefully.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L2-23: CSP reporting (`report-uri` / `report-to`)</em>:</strong> Email security stems often combine SPF alignment failures with <strong>look-alike domains</strong>. The best answer addresses user training plus technical authenticity controls, not only one or the other.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L2-23: CSP reporting (`report-uri` / `report-to`)</em>:</strong> Security operations value <strong>repeatable evidence</strong>: timestamps, authoritative configuration sources, and tamper-aware logs beat heroic memory after an incident. Many exam questions hinge on whether an action preserves integrity and accountability rather than whether it feels fast.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> An engineer wants emergency access to production to debug “L2-23: CSP reporting (`report-uri` / `report-to`)” during change freeze. Outline <strong>break-glass</strong> steps: who approves, how sessions are recorded, and how credentials are rotated after.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l2-24":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L2-24: Subresource Integrity (SRI) for third-party scripts</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-24</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> <code>integrity</code> + <code>crossorigin</code> attributes; hash rotation when vendor updates.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Supply chain: CDN compromise becomes non-executing if hash mismatches.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Use <code>openssl dgst -sha384 -binary file.js | openssl base64 -A</code> on a tiny local <code>file.js</code> you create; build the <code>sha384-...</code> attribute value.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-24</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>TLS questions separate <strong>confidentiality channel</strong> from <strong>server authentication</strong>—certificate validation and hostname checks matter in the answer set.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 2 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Certificate transparency (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Public logs of issued certs help detect mis-issued certificates for your domains.</dd><dt><strong>IOC</strong></dt><dd>Indicator of compromise—often ephemeral (IPs, domains); pair with TTP-based detections for durability.</dd><dt><strong>Confidentiality</strong></dt><dd>Assures that information is not disclosed to unauthorized subjects—encryption, access control, and data minimization support it.</dd><dt><strong>Asymmetric encryption</strong></dt><dd>Key pairs for key agreement/signing—RSA/ECC; hybrid TLS uses asymmetric to establish symmetric session keys.</dd><dt><strong>Encryption at rest / in transit</strong></dt><dd>KMS/HSM-backed keys, envelope encryption, and TLS everywhere for administrative and user paths.</dd><dt><strong>Replay attack</strong></dt><dd>Valid data maliciously re-sent—nonces, timestamps, and session freshness mitigate.</dd><dt><strong>Diamond model</strong></dt><dd>Adversary, infrastructure, capability, victim—useful for pivoting investigations and intel fusion.</dd><dt><strong>Due diligence</strong></dt><dd>Investigation and verification before decisions (vendor risk, M&amp;A) to ensure claims about controls are credible.</dd><dt><strong>Certificate pinning (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Client remembers expected server key material—reduces MITM from rogue CAs but complicates rotation; mostly seen in mobile/API hardening patterns.</dd><dt><strong>Logging &amp; monitoring</strong></dt><dd>CloudTrail-style management events differ from data-plane logs—enable central export, immutability, and alerting.</dd><dt><strong>Data loss prevention (DLP)</strong></dt><dd>Content-aware controls to block or alert on sensitive data movement—policy + tech, tuned to avoid blocking work.</dd><dt><strong>MTTD / MTTR</strong></dt><dd>Mean time to detect / remediate—quality matters; gaming metrics by closing tickets inflates false success.</dd><dt><strong>Residual risk</strong></dt><dd>Risk remaining after controls are applied; organizations accept, transfer, mitigate, or avoid it explicitly.</dd><dt><strong>Network segmentation</strong></dt><dd>VLANs, micro-segmentation, and east-west controls limit lateral movement after an initial foothold.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li><li>Linux auth.log style entries pair with SSH brute-force detection patterns—velocity and geo anomalies.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li><li>Sigma rules are vendor-agnostic detection snippets—tuning required per log source fields.</li><li>Race conditions in web apps can undermine authorization—sequential logic tests in secure design reviews.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L2-24: Subresource Integrity (SRI) for third-party scripts</em>:</strong> Cryptojacking still appears: high CPU, unexpected mining pools, and cloud billing spikes—detection plus credential hygiene beats chasing miner signatures alone.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L2-24: Subresource Integrity (SRI) for third-party scripts</em>:</strong> Social engineering callbacks to <strong>pretexting</strong>, <strong>baiting</strong>, and <strong>vishing</strong>—name the subtype when the stem describes the tactic.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L2-24: Subresource Integrity (SRI) for third-party scripts</em>:</strong> Data handling questions often hinge on <strong>classification</strong>, <strong>least data</strong>, and <strong>retention</strong>: collect only what you need, keep it only as long as allowed, and destroy securely when done.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L2-24: Subresource Integrity (SRI) for third-party scripts</em>:</strong> API keys in mobile apps are often extractable—prefer <strong>short-lived tokens</strong> and server-mediated access to backends.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L2-24: Subresource Integrity (SRI) for third-party scripts</em>:</strong> Identity is the new perimeter: credentials, tokens, and sessions are stolen more often than novel zero-days are burned. Expect Security+ items on MFA bypass awareness, phishing-resistant factors, and why <strong>authorization</strong> must be enforced server-side.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L2-24: Subresource Integrity (SRI) for third-party scripts</em>:</strong> When logs “mysteriously stop,” think <strong>time sync failure</strong>, collector saturation, retention misconfiguration, or attacker tampering—in that diagnostic order for a fair exam narrative.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L2-24: Subresource Integrity (SRI) for third-party scripts</em>:</strong> Honeypots can generate high-signal alerts but carry <strong>legal and operational</strong> risk if touched by real users; scope carefully.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L2-24: Subresource Integrity (SRI) for third-party scripts</em>:</strong> Logging questions often test whether you understand <strong>what to log</strong> (who, what, when, where, outcome), <strong>time sync</strong> for correlation, and <strong>tamper resistance</strong> for evidentiary value—not whether you can collect infinite bytes.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L2-24: Subresource Integrity (SRI) for third-party scripts</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L2-24: Subresource Integrity (SRI) for third-party scripts</em>:</strong> Clean desk pairs with <strong>screen privacy</strong> and <strong>clear desk checks</strong> for regulated spaces—physical + procedural controls together.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> A vendor integration project mentions “L2-24: Subresource Integrity (SRI) for third-party scripts” as out-of-scope for pen testing. Explain what <strong>residual risk</strong> remains, what <strong>compensating monitoring</strong> you would demand, and how you would <strong>document acceptance</strong>.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l2-25":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L2-25: CORS — preflight, credentials, and dangerous `*`</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-25</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> CORS is not a security boundary for server-side protection; mis-reflected origins hurt.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Internal APIs behind gateway + auth, not “security through CORS.”<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Table: scenario → safe <code>Access-Control-Allow-Origin</code> pattern (specific origin vs <code>*</code> with credentials).</p>\n<h2>Level 3 — Part 3</h2>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l2-25</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Email authenticity (SPF/DKIM/DMARC) is a frequent multi-part stem—read whether the failure is <strong>alignment</strong>, <strong>policy</strong>, or <strong>operator error</strong>.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 2 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>CSRF</strong></dt><dd>Cross-site request forgery rides ambient auth—anti-CSRF tokens, SameSite cookies, and re-auth for sensitive actions help.</dd><dt><strong>Need to know</strong></dt><dd>Finer than least privilege for data—access only to the minimum subset required for the current task.</dd><dt><strong>FIDO2 / WebAuthn</strong></dt><dd>Phishing-resistant possession factors using asymmetric crypto and origin binding; preferred where supported.</dd><dt><strong>Network segmentation</strong></dt><dd>VLANs, micro-segmentation, and east-west controls limit lateral movement after an initial foothold.</dd><dt><strong>Supply chain security</strong></dt><dd>SBOM, provenance signing (SLSA-style thinking), and dependency pinning reduce “update from upstream” surprises.</dd><dt><strong>BGP prefix hijack</strong></dt><dd>Unauthorized route advertisement—RPKI ROV reduces impact but does not replace monitoring.</dd><dt><strong>Authorization</strong></dt><dd>What an authenticated subject is allowed to do—RBAC/ABAC, scopes, and server-side checks enforce least privilege.</dd><dt><strong>IR phases</strong></dt><dd>Prepare, detect, analyze, contain, eradicate, recover, and lessons learned—legal hold and evidence integrity matter throughout.</dd><dt><strong>Collision (hash)</strong></dt><dd>Two inputs produce same hash—breaks integrity assumptions; choose strong hash families for security use.</dd><dt><strong>Exploit</strong></dt><dd>A technique or code that takes advantage of a vulnerability to achieve an attacker goal (exfiltration, persistence, disruption).</dd><dt><strong>Input validation vs output encoding</strong></dt><dd>Validation rejects bad input early; encoding neutralizes dangerous characters in the right output context—both are needed across HTML, SQL, OS, and LDAP channels.</dd><dt><strong>Business continuity testing</strong></dt><dd>Tabletops and technical failover drills reveal gaps in comms, dependencies, and vendor SLAs.</dd><dt><strong>Data residency</strong></dt><dd>Legal requirement for where data lives—impacts cloud region selection and key custody.</dd><dt><strong>TLS</strong></dt><dd>Encrypts data in motion and authenticates endpoints when certificates and hostnames are validated; termination points affect trust boundaries.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>UDP-based protocols can be abused for amplification DDoS—patch open resolvers and monitor volumetric baselines.</li><li>Bug bounty scope must exclude destructive testing—safe harbor language still needs legal review.</li><li>GCP service account keys are long-lived secrets—prefer workload identity federation from CI where possible.</li><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li><li>Race conditions in web apps can undermine authorization—sequential logic tests in secure design reviews.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L2-25: CORS — preflight, credentials, and dangerous `*`</em>:</strong> Tabletop exercises test <strong>comms trees</strong>, legal escalation, and customer notification templates—not only technical runbooks.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L2-25: CORS — preflight, credentials, and dangerous `*`</em>:</strong> Data handling questions often hinge on <strong>classification</strong>, <strong>least data</strong>, and <strong>retention</strong>: collect only what you need, keep it only as long as allowed, and destroy securely when done.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L2-25: CORS — preflight, credentials, and dangerous `*`</em>:</strong> For the Security+ mindset, translate every control into <strong>who</strong> it protects, <strong>what</strong> asset is at risk, and <strong>how</strong> you would detect failure. Interview and exam items often reward practical prioritization over buzzwords—choose the mitigation that reduces realistic loss first.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L2-25: CORS — preflight, credentials, and dangerous `*`</em>:</strong> Evidence bags and write blockers signal <strong>forensics awareness</strong>; touching disks before imaging is a classic wrong answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L2-25: CORS — preflight, credentials, and dangerous `*`</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L2-25: CORS — preflight, credentials, and dangerous `*`</em>:</strong> Controls fail in three predictable ways: <strong>misconfiguration</strong>, <strong>missing coverage</strong> (gaps between tools), and <strong>human process</strong> breakdown (exceptions, shared accounts, emergency access). When you read a scenario, ask which failure mode is most plausible before picking an answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L2-25: CORS — preflight, credentials, and dangerous `*`</em>:</strong> Multicloud complexity increases <strong>identity sprawl</strong>; centralized IdP and consistent conditional access policies reduce human error.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L2-25: CORS — preflight, credentials, and dangerous `*`</em>:</strong> Engineers often optimize for speed; attackers optimize for <strong>cheap reuse</strong> of stolen creds and known exploits. The winning answer bridges both: ship fast with guardrails—feature flags, staged rollouts, and automated security checks in CI.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L2-25: CORS — preflight, credentials, and dangerous `*`</em>:</strong> Defense in depth is not “more products,” it is <strong>independent mechanisms</strong>—if one layer is bypassed, another still limits movement, slows the adversary, or preserves evidence. Be ready to explain why network controls alone cannot compensate for missing app-layer authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L2-25: CORS — preflight, credentials, and dangerous `*`</em>:</strong> API keys in mobile apps are often extractable—prefer <strong>short-lived tokens</strong> and server-mediated access to backends.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> An engineer wants emergency access to production to debug “L2-25: CORS — preflight, credentials, and dangerous `*`” during change freeze. Outline <strong>break-glass</strong> steps: who approves, how sessions are recorded, and how credentials are rotated after.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l3-21":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L3-21: ATT&amp;CK procedures vs techniques (TTP nuance)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-21</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Procedures are actor-specific implementations; detection should focus on observable behaviors.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Intelligence-driven detection engineering.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Pick technique <code>T1566</code> (phishing); list 5 observables (email headers, attachments, user agent).</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-21</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Operations answers should show <strong>measurable process</strong>: SLAs, verification steps, and feedback loops—not heroic one-off fixes.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 3 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Chain of custody</strong></dt><dd>Documented handling of evidence from collection through presentation—hashing, write blockers, and access logs support admissibility.</dd><dt><strong>Threat intelligence lifecycle</strong></dt><dd>Planning, collection, processing, analysis, dissemination, feedback—intel must change detections or posture or it is shelf-ware.</dd><dt><strong>Replay attack</strong></dt><dd>Valid data maliciously re-sent—nonces, timestamps, and session freshness mitigate.</dd><dt><strong>Jump server / bastion</strong></dt><dd>Hardened administrative entry point—centralizes session recording and access policy for admins.</dd><dt><strong>UEBA</strong></dt><dd>User and entity behavior analytics—baseline deviations; tune to avoid HR/privacy backlash.</dd><dt><strong>Integrity</strong></dt><dd>Assures accuracy and trustworthiness—hashing, signatures, change control, and backups protect against unauthorized modification.</dd><dt><strong>Defense in depth</strong></dt><dd>Layered controls so one failure does not equal total failure—network, host, app, identity, and monitoring each contribute.</dd><dt><strong>AEAD</strong></dt><dd>Authenticated encryption with associated data—confidentiality plus integrity in one primitive (e.g., AES-GCM) when used correctly.</dd><dt><strong>IR phases</strong></dt><dd>Prepare, detect, analyze, contain, eradicate, recover, and lessons learned—legal hold and evidence integrity matter throughout.</dd><dt><strong>Metrics that matter</strong></dt><dd>Mean time to detect/remediate with quality, coverage of critical assets, and control effectiveness—not vanity ticket counts.</dd><dt><strong>Token replay</strong></dt><dd>Reusing a stolen token/session artifact—rotation, binding, and short TTLs reduce window.</dd><dt><strong>Port knocking (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Obscurity-based pre-auth to open firewall—weak alone; exam may present as non-primary control.</dd><dt><strong>SOAR</strong></dt><dd>Security orchestration, automation, response—playbooks must have human gates for destructive actions.</dd><dt><strong>Confidentiality</strong></dt><dd>Assures that information is not disclosed to unauthorized subjects—encryption, access control, and data minimization support it.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Cloud responsibility</th><th>Who typically owns it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Patching the hypervisor</strong></td><td>Provider responsibility in major IaaS models—customer still patches guests.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>IAM policy and keys</strong></td><td>Customer-owned configuration—misconfigurations dominate incidents.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Data encryption at rest</strong></td><td>Often customer-controlled keys/KMS policies with provider primitives.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Network exposure (SGs/NACLs)</strong></td><td>Customer configures; default-deny patterns are exam favorites.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Application vulnerabilities</strong></td><td>Customer code and dependencies—shared model does not absolve secure SDLC.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authorization</strong></td><td>Server-side object checks—headers and TLS do not replace this.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li><li>S3 bucket policies and ACLs layer with IAM—effective permissions require understanding intersection.</li><li>Split tunnel VPN can exfil corporate data outside inspection if misconfigured—policy and routing matter.</li><li>SameSite=Lax blocks many CSRF POSTs from cross-site contexts in modern browsers—know the nuance vs Strict.</li><li>SBOM formats (CycloneDX/SPDX) help inventory components for incident response and licensing—not only security.</li><li>GraphQL batching can amplify complexity attacks—depth and cost limits are first-class controls.</li><li>ATT&CK technique IDs are stable references for detection content—good for purple team reporting.</li><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L3-21: ATT&amp;CK procedures vs techniques (TTP nuance)</em>:</strong> Defense in depth is not “more products,” it is <strong>independent mechanisms</strong>—if one layer is bypassed, another still limits movement, slows the adversary, or preserves evidence. Be ready to explain why network controls alone cannot compensate for missing app-layer authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L3-21: ATT&amp;CK procedures vs techniques (TTP nuance)</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L3-21: ATT&amp;CK procedures vs techniques (TTP nuance)</em>:</strong> LDAP vs Active Directory questions test directory concepts at a high level—binding, searches, and secure transport (LDAPS) appear often.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L3-21: ATT&amp;CK procedures vs techniques (TTP nuance)</em>:</strong> Cloud items assume you can articulate <strong>shared responsibility</strong>: what the provider patches vs what the customer must configure (IAM, encryption, network exposure). Misconfiguration beats novel cloud exploits in real incidents and on the exam.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L3-21: ATT&amp;CK procedures vs techniques (TTP nuance)</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L3-21: ATT&amp;CK procedures vs techniques (TTP nuance)</em>:</strong> TPM-backed BitLocker keys illustrate <strong>key protection</strong> binding to platform state—recovery keys must be guarded like crown jewels.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L3-21: ATT&amp;CK procedures vs techniques (TTP nuance)</em>:</strong> Third-party and supply chain answers should emphasize <strong>contracts</strong>, <strong>evidence</strong>, and <strong>continuous monitoring</strong>—not “trust the SOC 2 logo” without scope review.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L3-21: ATT&amp;CK procedures vs techniques (TTP nuance)</em>:</strong> Evidence bags and write blockers signal <strong>forensics awareness</strong>; touching disks before imaging is a classic wrong answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L3-21: ATT&amp;CK procedures vs techniques (TTP nuance)</em>:</strong> Security operations value <strong>repeatable evidence</strong>: timestamps, authoritative configuration sources, and tamper-aware logs beat heroic memory after an incident. Many exam questions hinge on whether an action preserves integrity and accountability rather than whether it feels fast.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L3-21: ATT&amp;CK procedures vs techniques (TTP nuance)</em>:</strong> Industrial and OT adjacent questions reward knowing <strong>safety vs security</strong> tension: availability may trump confidentiality; testing must avoid breaking physical processes.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Legal asks whether “L3-21: ATT&amp;CK procedures vs techniques (TTP nuance)” artifacts require <strong>hold</strong> before deletion. Describe how you would <strong>tag systems</strong>, <strong>freeze backups</strong> appropriately, and <strong>escalate</strong> without tipping external actors.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l3-22":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L3-22: Threat intelligence pyramid (strategic / operational / tactical)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-22</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> IOCs expire fast; TTPs and strategic reports age better.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Feed quality into SOAR; avoid blocking on stale IPs forever.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Classify 10 indicators you invent (hash, domain, CVE narrative, country motive) into pyramid layers.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-22</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Level 3 aligns with Security+ <strong>operations and engineering</strong>: vuln management, logging/SIEM concepts, IAM patterns, threat modeling, and IR mechanics. Writers blend domains—patch urgency plus change window is a classic pair.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 3 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>CSRF</strong></dt><dd>Cross-site request forgery rides ambient auth—anti-CSRF tokens, SameSite cookies, and re-auth for sensitive actions help.</dd><dt><strong>IR phases</strong></dt><dd>Prepare, detect, analyze, contain, eradicate, recover, and lessons learned—legal hold and evidence integrity matter throughout.</dd><dt><strong>BCP / DR</strong></dt><dd>Business continuity and disaster recovery—RTO/RPO drive architecture; test restores, not just backups on paper.</dd><dt><strong>Confidential computing</strong></dt><dd>Use of hardware enclaves/TEEs to reduce exposure to privileged operators—threat model still required.</dd><dt><strong>Data loss prevention (DLP)</strong></dt><dd>Content-aware controls to block or alert on sensitive data movement—policy + tech, tuned to avoid blocking work.</dd><dt><strong>Block cipher vs stream</strong></dt><dd>Block operates on fixed-size chunks; stream on bits/bytes—misuse modes (e.g., ECB) create patterns.</dd><dt><strong>Full packet capture</strong></dt><dd>High fidelity evidence for investigations—storage, privacy, and legal review constraints apply.</dd><dt><strong>IOC</strong></dt><dd>Indicator of compromise—often ephemeral (IPs, domains); pair with TTP-based detections for durability.</dd><dt><strong>DNS</strong></dt><dd>Name resolution is a trust anchor—DNSSEC, cache poisoning, and malicious resolutions are classic abuse paths; log resolver anomalies.</dd><dt><strong>Exploit</strong></dt><dd>A technique or code that takes advantage of a vulnerability to achieve an attacker goal (exfiltration, persistence, disruption).</dd><dt><strong>Non-repudiation</strong></dt><dd>Prevents a party from credibly denying an action—digital signatures, tamper-evident logs, and time-stamping support it.</dd><dt><strong>Kerberos (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Ticket-based enterprise auth—TGT vs service tickets; golden/silver ticket classes of abuse appear in advanced IR.</dd><dt><strong>Perfect forward secrecy (PFS)</strong></dt><dd>Ephemeral key exchange means past session keys are not compromised if long-term keys leak later—TLS cipher suites can offer this property.</dd><dt><strong>Security misconfiguration</strong></dt><dd>Default creds, debug features on in prod, verbose errors, open directory listings—hardening baselines and drift detection reduce this class.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>DNS over HTTPS changes visibility for some networks—understand resolver policy and logging tradeoffs.</li><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li><li>GCP service account keys are long-lived secrets—prefer workload identity federation from CI where possible.</li><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li><li>SameSite=Lax blocks many CSRF POSTs from cross-site contexts in modern browsers—know the nuance vs Strict.</li><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li><li>Certificate pinning misconfigurations can brick apps—plan rotation and emergency releases.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L3-22: Threat intelligence pyramid (strategic / operational / tactical)</em>:</strong> Penetration tests require <strong>written authorization</strong>, defined scope, and rules of engagement—even in internal labs for professional conduct.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L3-22: Threat intelligence pyramid (strategic / operational / tactical)</em>:</strong> Deception tech is not a replacement for <strong>baselines and patching</strong>; it augments detection when mature processes exist.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L3-22: Threat intelligence pyramid (strategic / operational / tactical)</em>:</strong> Risk decisions are economic: organizations <strong>accept</strong>, <strong>mitigate</strong>, <strong>transfer</strong> (insurance, outsourcing with contracts), or <strong>avoid</strong> (stop the activity). Controls change likelihood or impact; residual risk should be explicit, not invisible.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L3-22: Threat intelligence pyramid (strategic / operational / tactical)</em>:</strong> Patching and change management appear as <strong>risk tradeoffs</strong>: emergency patches vs testing rings; compensating monitoring when patching lags; and documenting exceptions for auditors.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L3-22: Threat intelligence pyramid (strategic / operational / tactical)</em>:</strong> Container escape questions hinge on <strong>kernel boundary</strong> and misconfigured capabilities—namespaces are helpful but not a complete trust boundary without seccomp, AppArmor, and least-privileged service accounts.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L3-22: Threat intelligence pyramid (strategic / operational / tactical)</em>:</strong> API keys in mobile apps are often extractable—prefer <strong>short-lived tokens</strong> and server-mediated access to backends.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L3-22: Threat intelligence pyramid (strategic / operational / tactical)</em>:</strong> TPM-backed BitLocker keys illustrate <strong>key protection</strong> binding to platform state—recovery keys must be guarded like crown jewels.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L3-22: Threat intelligence pyramid (strategic / operational / tactical)</em>:</strong> Vulnerability management is a lifecycle: scanners find candidates, analysts prioritize with exploitability and business context, owners remediate, and verification closes the loop. “Patch everything immediately” is rarely operational; <strong>risk-based SLAs</strong> are the adult answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L3-22: Threat intelligence pyramid (strategic / operational / tactical)</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L3-22: Threat intelligence pyramid (strategic / operational / tactical)</em>:</strong> Ransomware stems often pair encryption with <strong>exfiltration</strong>—the correct answer may include legal/notification obligations, not only restoring from backup.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> During a tabletop, the CFO asks how “L3-22: Threat intelligence pyramid (strategic / operational / tactical)” could become a material incident. Answer with <strong>one plausible attack path</strong>, <strong>one detective control</strong> you already have, and <strong>one preventive gap</strong> you would fund next quarter.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l3-23":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L3-23: STIX / TAXII (interchange and sharing)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-23</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Objects, relationships, sharing communities; trust but verify.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> ISAC memberships; taxii 2.1 servers for sector sharing.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Read STIX 2.1 intro diagram; write JSON stub for <code>indicator</code> + <code>malware</code> <code>indicates</code> relationship (synthetic).</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-23</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Vulnerability prioritization is not “CVSS only”—think <strong>exposure</strong>, <strong>exploitability</strong>, and <strong>asset value</strong> together.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 3 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Confidentiality</strong></dt><dd>Assures that information is not disclosed to unauthorized subjects—encryption, access control, and data minimization support it.</dd><dt><strong>Data classification</strong></dt><dd>Labels (public, internal, confidential, restricted) drive storage, encryption, sharing, and disposal requirements.</dd><dt><strong>SSO</strong></dt><dd>Single sign-on federates trust to an IdP—misconfigured SAML/OIDC trusts are high-impact; validate metadata and signing keys.</dd><dt><strong>DNS</strong></dt><dd>Name resolution is a trust anchor—DNSSEC, cache poisoning, and malicious resolutions are classic abuse paths; log resolver anomalies.</dd><dt><strong>Symmetric encryption</strong></dt><dd>Same key encrypts and decrypts—fast for bulk data (AES-GCM); key distribution is the hard problem.</dd><dt><strong>AEAD</strong></dt><dd>Authenticated encryption with associated data—confidentiality plus integrity in one primitive (e.g., AES-GCM) when used correctly.</dd><dt><strong>IDOR</strong></dt><dd>Insecure direct object reference—missing object-level authorization; test horizontal/vertical access with different accounts.</dd><dt><strong>Vulnerability management</strong></dt><dd>Discover, prioritize, remediate, verify, and report—SLAs differ by exposure, exploitability, and asset criticality.</dd><dt><strong>Logging &amp; monitoring</strong></dt><dd>CloudTrail-style management events differ from data-plane logs—enable central export, immutability, and alerting.</dd><dt><strong>BCP / DR</strong></dt><dd>Business continuity and disaster recovery—RTO/RPO drive architecture; test restores, not just backups on paper.</dd><dt><strong>Threat intelligence lifecycle</strong></dt><dd>Planning, collection, processing, analysis, dissemination, feedback—intel must change detections or posture or it is shelf-ware.</dd><dt><strong>Purple / red / blue</strong></dt><dd>Red emulates adversaries, blue defends, purple bridges—authorization and logging are mandatory for any simulation.</dd><dt><strong>Need to know</strong></dt><dd>Finer than least privilege for data—access only to the minimum subset required for the current task.</dd><dt><strong>CRL</strong></dt><dd>Certificate Revocation List—signed list of revoked serials; size/latency issues drove OCSP adoption.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li><li>SameSite=Lax blocks many CSRF POSTs from cross-site contexts in modern browsers—know the nuance vs Strict.</li><li>Bug bounty scope must exclude destructive testing—safe harbor language still needs legal review.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li><li>HttpOnly does not stop CSRF; it reduces token theft from XSS reading document.cookie in many setups.</li><li>Responsible disclosure timelines balance vendor patch readiness with public safety—coordinate, don’t surprise.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L3-23: STIX / TAXII (interchange and sharing)</em>:</strong> KMS keys are not “magic secrecy dust”—<strong>who can invoke decrypt</strong> and from which contexts (VPC endpoint policies, IAM conditions) is what exams probe.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L3-23: STIX / TAXII (interchange and sharing)</em>:</strong> API keys in mobile apps are often extractable—prefer <strong>short-lived tokens</strong> and server-mediated access to backends.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L3-23: STIX / TAXII (interchange and sharing)</em>:</strong> Virtualization risks include <strong>snapshot sprawl</strong> containing secrets and stale VM images drifting from hardened baselines.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L3-23: STIX / TAXII (interchange and sharing)</em>:</strong> Risk decisions are economic: organizations <strong>accept</strong>, <strong>mitigate</strong>, <strong>transfer</strong> (insurance, outsourcing with contracts), or <strong>avoid</strong> (stop the activity). Controls change likelihood or impact; residual risk should be explicit, not invisible.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L3-23: STIX / TAXII (interchange and sharing)</em>:</strong> Wireless and mobility items reward knowing basics: WPA3 improvements conceptually, evil twin risks, captive portals, and why client isolation matters on guest networks—without memorizing obsolete WEP details unless explicitly historical.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L3-23: STIX / TAXII (interchange and sharing)</em>:</strong> Industrial and OT adjacent questions reward knowing <strong>safety vs security</strong> tension: availability may trump confidentiality; testing must avoid breaking physical processes.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L3-23: STIX / TAXII (interchange and sharing)</em>:</strong> SAST finds issues early but produces false positives; <strong>triage workflows</strong> and developer feedback loops are part of a mature program, not “run tool once.”</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L3-23: STIX / TAXII (interchange and sharing)</em>:</strong> LDAP vs Active Directory questions test directory concepts at a high level—binding, searches, and secure transport (LDAPS) appear often.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L3-23: STIX / TAXII (interchange and sharing)</em>:</strong> Clean desk pairs with <strong>screen privacy</strong> and <strong>clear desk checks</strong> for regulated spaces—physical + procedural controls together.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L3-23: STIX / TAXII (interchange and sharing)</em>:</strong> Incident response questions probe containment vs evidence preservation tension, legal escalation, and communication discipline. The exam rewards knowing when to isolate systems, when to involve counsel, and why mass log deletion is catastrophic.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> You are the on-call analyst reviewing an alert tied to “L3-23: STIX / TAXII (interchange and sharing)”. Leadership wants a <strong>60-second</strong> brief: business impact, evidence gaps, and the <strong>first</strong> containment step that preserves logs. No tool-specific jargon—prioritize scope, evidence, blast radius, then root-cause remediation under change control.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l3-24":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L3-24: Osquery and fleet visibility (SQL on endpoints)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-24</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Scheduled queries for drift, persistence, suspicious binaries.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Privacy impact assessment before wide deployment.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> If <code>osqueryi</code> installed: <code>.tables</code> then <code>SELECT * FROM os_version;</code> — else document install and one compliance query idea.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-24</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Detection engineering stems want you to connect <strong>data sources</strong> to <strong>hypothesis</strong>—what log field proves the story?</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 3 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>CRL</strong></dt><dd>Certificate Revocation List—signed list of revoked serials; size/latency issues drove OCSP adoption.</dd><dt><strong>SOAR</strong></dt><dd>Security orchestration, automation, response—playbooks must have human gates for destructive actions.</dd><dt><strong>Availability</strong></dt><dd>Assures timely and reliable access—redundancy, patching, DDoS defenses, and DR planning keep services usable for authorized users.</dd><dt><strong>Digital signature</strong></dt><dd>Proves origin and integrity using private key to sign and public key to verify—non-repudiation when keys are well governed.</dd><dt><strong>Serverless blast radius</strong></dt><dd>One broad execution role affects every invocation—scope IAM per function and watch environment variable leaks.</dd><dt><strong>Certificate transparency (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Public logs of issued certs help detect mis-issued certificates for your domains.</dd><dt><strong>IOC</strong></dt><dd>Indicator of compromise—often ephemeral (IPs, domains); pair with TTP-based detections for durability.</dd><dt><strong>Confidentiality</strong></dt><dd>Assures that information is not disclosed to unauthorized subjects—encryption, access control, and data minimization support it.</dd><dt><strong>Asymmetric encryption</strong></dt><dd>Key pairs for key agreement/signing—RSA/ECC; hybrid TLS uses asymmetric to establish symmetric session keys.</dd><dt><strong>Encryption at rest / in transit</strong></dt><dd>KMS/HSM-backed keys, envelope encryption, and TLS everywhere for administrative and user paths.</dd><dt><strong>Replay attack</strong></dt><dd>Valid data maliciously re-sent—nonces, timestamps, and session freshness mitigate.</dd><dt><strong>Diamond model</strong></dt><dd>Adversary, infrastructure, capability, victim—useful for pivoting investigations and intel fusion.</dd><dt><strong>Due diligence</strong></dt><dd>Investigation and verification before decisions (vendor risk, M&amp;A) to ensure claims about controls are credible.</dd><dt><strong>Certificate pinning (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Client remembers expected server key material—reduces MITM from rogue CAs but complicates rotation; mostly seen in mobile/API hardening patterns.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Property</th><th>Typical exam angle</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Confidentiality</strong></td><td>Who may read? Encryption, ACLs, DLP, classification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Integrity</strong></td><td>Was it modified? Hashing, signatures, change control, backups.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Availability</strong></td><td>Can authorized users work? HA, patching windows, DDoS defense, DR.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authenticity / non-repudiation</strong></td><td>Prove source and intent—signatures, strong issuance, tamper-evident logs.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Linux auth.log style entries pair with SSH brute-force detection patterns—velocity and geo anomalies.</li><li>Race conditions in web apps can undermine authorization—sequential logic tests in secure design reviews.</li><li>SLSA levels describe increasing supply-chain assurance—useful vocabulary in modern governance questions.</li><li>SameSite=Lax blocks many CSRF POSTs from cross-site contexts in modern browsers—know the nuance vs Strict.</li><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li><li>Admission controllers can block privileged pods—policy-as-code integrates with GitOps reviews.</li><li>AES-128 is not “half as strong” as AES-256 in practical threat models for many cases—key management quality dominates.</li><li>CVSS base does not include your asset criticality—environmental metrics exist for a reason.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L3-24: Osquery and fleet visibility (SQL on endpoints)</em>:</strong> Logging questions often test whether you understand <strong>what to log</strong> (who, what, when, where, outcome), <strong>time sync</strong> for correlation, and <strong>tamper resistance</strong> for evidentiary value—not whether you can collect infinite bytes.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L3-24: Osquery and fleet visibility (SQL on endpoints)</em>:</strong> GraphQL introspection risk is about <strong>schema discovery</strong> aiding attackers—rate limits, authz on fields, and disabling introspection in prod are common answers.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L3-24: Osquery and fleet visibility (SQL on endpoints)</em>:</strong> Access control stems frequently mix <strong>role</strong> vs <strong>attribute</strong> vs <strong>rule</strong> models; pick the answer that matches the scenario’s constraints (temporary contractor, cross-department data, dynamic tags on resources).</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L3-24: Osquery and fleet visibility (SQL on endpoints)</em>:</strong> CSP reporting helps tune policy but can leak URLs—<strong>privacy review</strong> of report endpoints matters in regulated environments.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L3-24: Osquery and fleet visibility (SQL on endpoints)</em>:</strong> Wireless and mobility items reward knowing basics: WPA3 improvements conceptually, evil twin risks, captive portals, and why client isolation matters on guest networks—without memorizing obsolete WEP details unless explicitly historical.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L3-24: Osquery and fleet visibility (SQL on endpoints)</em>:</strong> Subresource integrity protects against <strong>CDN compromise</strong> but requires operational discipline when vendors rotate files.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L3-24: Osquery and fleet visibility (SQL on endpoints)</em>:</strong> Physical security is still on the exam: tailgating, visitor escorts, locks, destruction of media, and environmental controls (fire, HVAC) as availability/confidentiality supports.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L3-24: Osquery and fleet visibility (SQL on endpoints)</em>:</strong> Certificate pinning failures during rotation teach why <strong>key continuity strategy</strong> must be planned before mobile releases.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L3-24: Osquery and fleet visibility (SQL on endpoints)</em>:</strong> Patching and change management appear as <strong>risk tradeoffs</strong>: emergency patches vs testing rings; compensating monitoring when patching lags; and documenting exceptions for auditors.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L3-24: Osquery and fleet visibility (SQL on endpoints)</em>:</strong> LDAP vs Active Directory questions test directory concepts at a high level—binding, searches, and secure transport (LDAPS) appear often.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Junior staff proposes a quick fix for “L3-24: Osquery and fleet visibility (SQL on endpoints)” that disables logging on a noisy host. Walk through why that is unacceptable and propose a <strong>tuning</strong> path that preserves <strong>integrity and retention</strong> commitments.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l3-25":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L3-25: TAP vs SPAN for network security monitoring</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-25</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Inline vs out-of-band; dropped packets under load; TLS visibility limits.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Appliance sizing; lawful intercept policies.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> ASCII diagram: switch SPAN port → IDS vs inline IPS path.</p>\n<h2>Level 4 — Part 3</h2>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l3-25</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Vulnerability prioritization is not “CVSS only”—think <strong>exposure</strong>, <strong>exploitability</strong>, and <strong>asset value</strong> together.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 3 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>VPN</strong></dt><dd>Creates an encrypted tunnel; split tunneling can bypass corporate inspection; VPN is not anonymity or a substitute for app-layer auth.</dd><dt><strong>SSO</strong></dt><dd>Single sign-on federates trust to an IdP—misconfigured SAML/OIDC trusts are high-impact; validate metadata and signing keys.</dd><dt><strong>DevSecOps</strong></dt><dd>Embed security gates in CI/CD with fast feedback—policy-as-code, secret scanning, and SBOMs support supply-chain resilience.</dd><dt><strong>Purple teaming</strong></dt><dd>Collaborative attack/defense exercises to validate detections without surprise production harm—scope and safety first.</dd><dt><strong>Full packet capture</strong></dt><dd>High fidelity evidence for investigations—storage, privacy, and legal review constraints apply.</dd><dt><strong>Threat</strong></dt><dd>Any circumstance or actor with the potential to cause harm by exploiting a vulnerability (malware, insider, natural disaster).</dd><dt><strong>Chain of custody</strong></dt><dd>Documented handling of evidence from collection through presentation—hashing, write blockers, and access logs support admissibility.</dd><dt><strong>Need to know</strong></dt><dd>Finer than least privilege for data—access only to the minimum subset required for the current task.</dd><dt><strong>OODA loop (IR)</strong></dt><dd>Observe-orient-decide-act—adversary and defender both iterate; faster, accurate decisions beat hoarding data.</dd><dt><strong>Policy vs standard vs procedure</strong></dt><dd>Policy states intent; standards define mandatory requirements; procedures are step-by-step how-to for operators.</dd><dt><strong>Hashing</strong></dt><dd>One-way fingerprint for integrity verification—SHA-256 family; not secrecy; used with HMAC for keyed integrity.</dd><dt><strong>CASB / SaaS governance</strong></dt><dd>Visibility and policy for sanctioned vs shadow SaaS—OAuth consent attacks and guest sharing are common gaps.</dd><dt><strong>Salt (crypto)</strong></dt><dd>Random input to a password hash to defeat rainbow tables—must be unique per password.</dd><dt><strong>Right to be forgotten (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Privacy request to delete data—may conflict with legal hold; counsel resolves precedence.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>IR phase</th><th>What you do there (exam shorthand)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Prepare</strong></td><td>Playbooks, contacts, tooling, baseline logging—before the pager fires.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detect &amp; analyze</strong></td><td>Scope, timelines, hypotheses—preserve volatile evidence early.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Contain</strong></td><td>Stop spread with minimal evidence damage—network isolation variants matter.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Eradicate &amp; recover</strong></td><td>Remove persistence, patch root cause, restore with verification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Lessons learned</strong></td><td>Metrics, control changes, and communication improvements—close the loop.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Bug bounty scope must exclude destructive testing—safe harbor language still needs legal review.</li><li>GCP service account keys are long-lived secrets—prefer workload identity federation from CI where possible.</li><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li><li>Race conditions in web apps can undermine authorization—sequential logic tests in secure design reviews.</li><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li><li>CVSS base does not include your asset criticality—environmental metrics exist for a reason.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L3-25: TAP vs SPAN for network security monitoring</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L3-25: TAP vs SPAN for network security monitoring</em>:</strong> Ransomware stems often pair encryption with <strong>exfiltration</strong>—the correct answer may include legal/notification obligations, not only restoring from backup.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L3-25: TAP vs SPAN for network security monitoring</em>:</strong> Certificate pinning failures during rotation teach why <strong>key continuity strategy</strong> must be planned before mobile releases.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L3-25: TAP vs SPAN for network security monitoring</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L3-25: TAP vs SPAN for network security monitoring</em>:</strong> Advanced topics still return to fundamentals: least privilege, segmentation, logging, and tested recovery. When you see Zero Trust or PQC buzzwords, map them back to concrete controls and threat models rather than treating them as magic shields.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L3-25: TAP vs SPAN for network security monitoring</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L3-25: TAP vs SPAN for network security monitoring</em>:</strong> DAST exercises running apps but misses authz logic without credentials; combine with <strong>manual review</strong> for business-rule flaws.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L3-25: TAP vs SPAN for network security monitoring</em>:</strong> Honeypots can generate high-signal alerts but carry <strong>legal and operational</strong> risk if touched by real users; scope carefully.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L3-25: TAP vs SPAN for network security monitoring</em>:</strong> Security operations value <strong>repeatable evidence</strong>: timestamps, authoritative configuration sources, and tamper-aware logs beat heroic memory after an incident. Many exam questions hinge on whether an action preserves integrity and accountability rather than whether it feels fast.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L3-25: TAP vs SPAN for network security monitoring</em>:</strong> Physical security is still on the exam: tailgating, visitor escorts, locks, destruction of media, and environmental controls (fire, HVAC) as availability/confidentiality supports.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Equating <strong>encoding</strong> with secrecy or integrity.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> You are the on-call analyst reviewing an alert tied to “L3-25: TAP vs SPAN for network security monitoring”. Leadership wants a <strong>60-second</strong> brief: business impact, evidence gaps, and the <strong>first</strong> containment step that preserves logs. No tool-specific jargon—prioritize scope, evidence, blast radius, then root-cause remediation under change control.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l4-21":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L4-21: CI/CD pipeline attackers care about (OIDC, runners, caches)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-21</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Short-lived cloud credentials via OIDC; runner isolation; poisoned cache risks.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> “Build from scratch” vs reused compromised workers.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Sketch GitHub Actions → AWS <code>role-to-assume</code> OIDC trust — 8-step sequence, no secrets in YAML.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-21</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Level 4 mirrors Security+ <strong>enterprise and cloud</strong>: identity governance, conditional access patterns, evidence handling, purple collaboration, and vendor/SaaS risk. Show you understand <strong>scope</strong> and <strong>blast radius</strong> across accounts and tenants.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 4 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Logging &amp; monitoring</strong></dt><dd>CloudTrail-style management events differ from data-plane logs—enable central export, immutability, and alerting.</dd><dt><strong>Threat modeling (STRIDE)</strong></dt><dd>Spoofing, tampering, repudiation, information disclosure, denial of service, elevation of privilege—drive controls early.</dd><dt><strong>Rainbow table</strong></dt><dd>Precomputed hash chains for fast password cracking—salting and modern KDFs are the defense.</dd><dt><strong>Warm site / cold site</strong></dt><dd>Warm has partial hardware ready; cold is space only—cost vs recovery speed tradeoff.</dd><dt><strong>Zero Trust (headline)</strong></dt><dd>Assume breach; verify explicitly per request using identity, device posture, and least privilege—not “trust the LAN.”</dd><dt><strong>Non-repudiation</strong></dt><dd>Prevents a party from credibly denying an action—digital signatures, tamper-evident logs, and time-stamping support it.</dd><dt><strong>SPF / DKIM / DMARC</strong></dt><dd>Email authenticity stack—SPF authorizes senders, DKIM signs messages, DMARC aligns policies and reporting for abuse handling.</dd><dt><strong>IDOR</strong></dt><dd>Insecure direct object reference—missing object-level authorization; test horizontal/vertical access with different accounts.</dd><dt><strong>CASB / SaaS governance</strong></dt><dd>Visibility and policy for sanctioned vs shadow SaaS—OAuth consent attacks and guest sharing are common gaps.</dd><dt><strong>SOC triage order</strong></dt><dd>Scope → impact → evidence → containment hypothesis; avoid fixing symptoms before you know blast radius.</dd><dt><strong>MAC</strong></dt><dd>Message authentication code—integrity with a secret key; differs from digital signature which uses asymmetric keys.</dd><dt><strong>IOC</strong></dt><dd>Indicator of compromise—often ephemeral (IPs, domains); pair with TTP-based detections for durability.</dd><dt><strong>Asset</strong></dt><dd>Anything of value to the organization—data, systems, people, reputation, or services—that security controls protect.</dd><dt><strong>Authorization</strong></dt><dd>What an authenticated subject is allowed to do—RBAC/ABAC, scopes, and server-side checks enforce least privilege.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Cloud responsibility</th><th>Who typically owns it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Patching the hypervisor</strong></td><td>Provider responsibility in major IaaS models—customer still patches guests.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>IAM policy and keys</strong></td><td>Customer-owned configuration—misconfigurations dominate incidents.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Data encryption at rest</strong></td><td>Often customer-controlled keys/KMS policies with provider primitives.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Network exposure (SGs/NACLs)</strong></td><td>Customer configures; default-deny patterns are exam favorites.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Application vulnerabilities</strong></td><td>Customer code and dependencies—shared model does not absolve secure SDLC.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li><li>PCI DSS scope reduction via segmentation is a recurring theme—if it is not in scope, it cannot drag you into assessment.</li><li>OAuth access tokens are not a replacement for server-side authorization checks on every sensitive action.</li><li>HttpOnly does not stop CSRF; it reduces token theft from XSS reading document.cookie in many setups.</li><li>CVSS base does not include your asset criticality—environmental metrics exist for a reason.</li><li>ATT&CK technique IDs are stable references for detection content—good for purple team reporting.</li><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L4-21: CI/CD pipeline attackers care about (OIDC, runners, caches)</em>:</strong> Identity is the new perimeter: credentials, tokens, and sessions are stolen more often than novel zero-days are burned. Expect Security+ items on MFA bypass awareness, phishing-resistant factors, and why <strong>authorization</strong> must be enforced server-side.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L4-21: CI/CD pipeline attackers care about (OIDC, runners, caches)</em>:</strong> Engineers often optimize for speed; attackers optimize for <strong>cheap reuse</strong> of stolen creds and known exploits. The winning answer bridges both: ship fast with guardrails—feature flags, staged rollouts, and automated security checks in CI.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L4-21: CI/CD pipeline attackers care about (OIDC, runners, caches)</em>:</strong> Penetration tests require <strong>written authorization</strong>, defined scope, and rules of engagement—even in internal labs for professional conduct.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L4-21: CI/CD pipeline attackers care about (OIDC, runners, caches)</em>:</strong> TPM-backed BitLocker keys illustrate <strong>key protection</strong> binding to platform state—recovery keys must be guarded like crown jewels.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L4-21: CI/CD pipeline attackers care about (OIDC, runners, caches)</em>:</strong> Advanced topics still return to fundamentals: least privilege, segmentation, logging, and tested recovery. When you see Zero Trust or PQC buzzwords, map them back to concrete controls and threat models rather than treating them as magic shields.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L4-21: CI/CD pipeline attackers care about (OIDC, runners, caches)</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L4-21: CI/CD pipeline attackers care about (OIDC, runners, caches)</em>:</strong> Subresource integrity protects against <strong>CDN compromise</strong> but requires operational discipline when vendors rotate files.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L4-21: CI/CD pipeline attackers care about (OIDC, runners, caches)</em>:</strong> Defense in depth is not “more products,” it is <strong>independent mechanisms</strong>—if one layer is bypassed, another still limits movement, slows the adversary, or preserves evidence. Be ready to explain why network controls alone cannot compensate for missing app-layer authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L4-21: CI/CD pipeline attackers care about (OIDC, runners, caches)</em>:</strong> Business continuity answers should reference <strong>RTO/RPO</strong>, <strong>workarounds</strong>, and <strong>tested restores</strong>; DR without practiced failover is wishful thinking, and exam writers know it.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L4-21: CI/CD pipeline attackers care about (OIDC, runners, caches)</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Junior staff proposes a quick fix for “L4-21: CI/CD pipeline attackers care about (OIDC, runners, caches)” that disables logging on a noisy host. Walk through why that is unacceptable and propose a <strong>tuning</strong> path that preserves <strong>integrity and retention</strong> commitments.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l4-22":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L4-22: Terraform / IaC security (state files, modules, drift)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-22</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Remote state encryption and locking; module pinning; policy-as-code (OPA/Sentinel/Conftest).<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Blast radius of <code>AdministratorAccess</code> in CI role.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> List 5 <code>terraform</code> anti-patterns (state in git, plaintext secrets, overly wide IAM) with fixes.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-22</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Purple team references test <strong>authorization to simulate</strong> and <strong>logging of exercises</strong>—safety and auditability matter.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 4 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>MAC</strong></dt><dd>Message authentication code—integrity with a secret key; differs from digital signature which uses asymmetric keys.</dd><dt><strong>Quantitative vs qualitative risk</strong></dt><dd>Qualitative uses scales (high/medium/low); quantitative uses dollar or probability estimates—both need consistent assumptions and reviewer judgment.</dd><dt><strong>Perfect forward secrecy (PFS)</strong></dt><dd>Ephemeral key exchange means past session keys are not compromised if long-term keys leak later—TLS cipher suites can offer this property.</dd><dt><strong>BCP / DR</strong></dt><dd>Business continuity and disaster recovery—RTO/RPO drive architecture; test restores, not just backups on paper.</dd><dt><strong>HMAC</strong></dt><dd>Keyed hash construction—common for API authenticity when symmetric secret is shared out-of-band.</dd><dt><strong>Asset</strong></dt><dd>Anything of value to the organization—data, systems, people, reputation, or services—that security controls protect.</dd><dt><strong>Certificate pinning (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Client remembers expected server key material—reduces MITM from rogue CAs but complicates rotation; mostly seen in mobile/API hardening patterns.</dd><dt><strong>Third-party risk</strong></dt><dd>Vendor access expands attack surface—DPAs, SOC reports, and continuous monitoring for critical suppliers.</dd><dt><strong>Diffie-Hellman (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Key agreement over insecure channel—combine with authentication to prevent MITM.</dd><dt><strong>Threat</strong></dt><dd>Any circumstance or actor with the potential to cause harm by exploiting a vulnerability (malware, insider, natural disaster).</dd><dt><strong>Symmetric encryption</strong></dt><dd>Same key encrypts and decrypts—fast for bulk data (AES-GCM); key distribution is the hard problem.</dd><dt><strong>Security awareness</strong></dt><dd>Training plus culture—measure reporting rates, not shame metrics; phishing simulations should reinforce reporting.</dd><dt><strong>MITM</strong></dt><dd>Man-in-the-middle intercepts or alters traffic—TLS with proper validation mitigates; corporate SSL inspection is its own trust zone.</dd><dt><strong>Vulnerability</strong></dt><dd>A weakness in design, implementation, configuration, or process that could be exploited to violate a security policy.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Cloud responsibility</th><th>Who typically owns it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Patching the hypervisor</strong></td><td>Provider responsibility in major IaaS models—customer still patches guests.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>IAM policy and keys</strong></td><td>Customer-owned configuration—misconfigurations dominate incidents.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Data encryption at rest</strong></td><td>Often customer-controlled keys/KMS policies with provider primitives.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Network exposure (SGs/NACLs)</strong></td><td>Customer configures; default-deny patterns are exam favorites.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Application vulnerabilities</strong></td><td>Customer code and dependencies—shared model does not absolve secure SDLC.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>AEAD</strong></td><td>Confidentiality + integrity together—misuse of IV/nonce still breaks security.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li><li>Azure AD / Entra conditional access is analogous to risk-based policies—device compliance signals matter.</li><li>EPSS (concept) scores exploitation probability—useful alongside CVSS for prioritization in mature programs.</li><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li><li>HttpOnly does not stop CSRF; it reduces token theft from XSS reading document.cookie in many setups.</li><li>Race conditions in file operations underpin some TOCTOU issues—exam may reference unsafe temp files.</li><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>GraphQL batching can amplify complexity attacks—depth and cost limits are first-class controls.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L4-22: Terraform / IaC security (state files, modules, drift)</em>:</strong> Certificate pinning failures during rotation teach why <strong>key continuity strategy</strong> must be planned before mobile releases.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L4-22: Terraform / IaC security (state files, modules, drift)</em>:</strong> Patching and change management appear as <strong>risk tradeoffs</strong>: emergency patches vs testing rings; compensating monitoring when patching lags; and documenting exceptions for auditors.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L4-22: Terraform / IaC security (state files, modules, drift)</em>:</strong> LDAP vs Active Directory questions test directory concepts at a high level—binding, searches, and secure transport (LDAPS) appear often.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L4-22: Terraform / IaC security (state files, modules, drift)</em>:</strong> Third-party and supply chain answers should emphasize <strong>contracts</strong>, <strong>evidence</strong>, and <strong>continuous monitoring</strong>—not “trust the SOC 2 logo” without scope review.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L4-22: Terraform / IaC security (state files, modules, drift)</em>:</strong> RADIUS is still referenced for <strong>network access control</strong> integrations; know it as a AAA component in enterprise Wi-Fi contexts.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L4-22: Terraform / IaC security (state files, modules, drift)</em>:</strong> Business continuity answers should reference <strong>RTO/RPO</strong>, <strong>workarounds</strong>, and <strong>tested restores</strong>; DR without practiced failover is wishful thinking, and exam writers know it.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L4-22: Terraform / IaC security (state files, modules, drift)</em>:</strong> TACACS+ vs RADIUS separation of duties in device admin access—exams may contrast accounting granularity.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L4-22: Terraform / IaC security (state files, modules, drift)</em>:</strong> Data handling questions often hinge on <strong>classification</strong>, <strong>least data</strong>, and <strong>retention</strong>: collect only what you need, keep it only as long as allowed, and destroy securely when done.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L4-22: Terraform / IaC security (state files, modules, drift)</em>:</strong> Honeypots can generate high-signal alerts but carry <strong>legal and operational</strong> risk if touched by real users; scope carefully.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L4-22: Terraform / IaC security (state files, modules, drift)</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Internal audit samples “L4-22: Terraform / IaC security (state files, modules, drift)” controls and finds screenshots instead of config exports. Explain why <strong>authoritative evidence</strong> matters and what you would collect instead.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l4-23":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L4-23: Secrets in engineering systems (Git, tickets, wikis, CI logs)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-23</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Secret scanning on push; pre-commit hooks; rotation when leaked.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> “One leaked key = assume lateral movement started.”<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Create dummy repo with fake <code>AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=AKIAIOSFODNN7EXAMPLE</code> in history; run <code>gitleaks detect --source . --no-git</code> or <code>trufflehog</code> if available — verify detection.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-23</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Vendor risk items reward <strong>continuous monitoring</strong> and <strong>contractual evidence</strong>, not one-time PDF collection.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 4 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>Scenario stems often hide <strong>two</strong> issues; the distractor is half-right. Read for the primary business harm first, then map to CIA or IR phase.</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Full packet capture</strong></dt><dd>High fidelity evidence for investigations—storage, privacy, and legal review constraints apply.</dd><dt><strong>IOC</strong></dt><dd>Indicator of compromise—often ephemeral (IPs, domains); pair with TTP-based detections for durability.</dd><dt><strong>MITRE ATT&amp;CK</strong></dt><dd>Tactics (why) and techniques (how) adversaries operate—use for detection engineering, gap analysis, and purple team scenarios.</dd><dt><strong>Risk</strong></dt><dd>The intersection of threat, vulnerability, and impact—often assessed qualitatively (high/medium/low) or with scoring frameworks.</dd><dt><strong>PII</strong></dt><dd>Personally identifiable information—names, government IDs, biometrics, account numbers; triggers handling, retention, and breach rules.</dd><dt><strong>DDoS</strong></dt><dd>Distributed denial of service—volumetric, protocol, or application-layer floods; mitigations include scrubbing, anycast, rate limits, and architecture elasticity.</dd><dt><strong>Symmetric encryption</strong></dt><dd>Same key encrypts and decrypts—fast for bulk data (AES-GCM); key distribution is the hard problem.</dd><dt><strong>Injection</strong></dt><dd>Untrusted input becomes part of a command or query—parameterized queries, input validation, and context escaping are core defenses.</dd><dt><strong>SIEM</strong></dt><dd>Security information and event management—centralize logs, parse fields, correlate alerts; tuning reduces false positives and fatigue.</dd><dt><strong>CASB / SaaS governance</strong></dt><dd>Visibility and policy for sanctioned vs shadow SaaS—OAuth consent attacks and guest sharing are common gaps.</dd><dt><strong>Zero Trust architecture</strong></dt><dd>Identity-centric access with continuous verification—policy enforcement points for users, devices, and workloads.</dd><dt><strong>Mandatory vacation</strong></dt><dd>Forces handover and review of another employee’s work—can uncover fraud or backdoors.</dd><dt><strong>Rainbow table</strong></dt><dd>Precomputed hash chains for fast password cracking—salting and modern KDFs are the defense.</dd><dt><strong>Proxy vs reverse proxy</strong></dt><dd>Forward proxy represents clients outbound; reverse proxy fronts servers—different trust and logging points.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>IR phase</th><th>What you do there (exam shorthand)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Prepare</strong></td><td>Playbooks, contacts, tooling, baseline logging—before the pager fires.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detect &amp; analyze</strong></td><td>Scope, timelines, hypotheses—preserve volatile evidence early.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Contain</strong></td><td>Stop spread with minimal evidence damage—network isolation variants matter.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Eradicate &amp; recover</strong></td><td>Remove persistence, patch root cause, restore with verification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Lessons learned</strong></td><td>Metrics, control changes, and communication improvements—close the loop.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>S3 bucket policies and ACLs layer with IAM—effective permissions require understanding intersection.</li><li>Sigma rules are vendor-agnostic detection snippets—tuning required per log source fields.</li><li>SBOM formats (CycloneDX/SPDX) help inventory components for incident response and licensing—not only security.</li><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li><li>JWT alg:none historical vulnerability class—always validate algorithm and signature keys explicitly.</li><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>What is the difference between <strong>vulnerability scan</strong>, <strong>credentialed scan</strong>, and <strong>penetration test</strong> in procurement language?</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L4-23: Secrets in engineering systems (Git, tickets, wikis, CI logs)</em>:</strong> Cloud items assume you can articulate <strong>shared responsibility</strong>: what the provider patches vs what the customer must configure (IAM, encryption, network exposure). Misconfiguration beats novel cloud exploits in real incidents and on the exam.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L4-23: Secrets in engineering systems (Git, tickets, wikis, CI logs)</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L4-23: Secrets in engineering systems (Git, tickets, wikis, CI logs)</em>:</strong> KMS keys are not “magic secrecy dust”—<strong>who can invoke decrypt</strong> and from which contexts (VPC endpoint policies, IAM conditions) is what exams probe.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L4-23: Secrets in engineering systems (Git, tickets, wikis, CI logs)</em>:</strong> API keys in mobile apps are often extractable—prefer <strong>short-lived tokens</strong> and server-mediated access to backends.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L4-23: Secrets in engineering systems (Git, tickets, wikis, CI logs)</em>:</strong> Virtualization risks include <strong>snapshot sprawl</strong> containing secrets and stale VM images drifting from hardened baselines.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L4-23: Secrets in engineering systems (Git, tickets, wikis, CI logs)</em>:</strong> Risk decisions are economic: organizations <strong>accept</strong>, <strong>mitigate</strong>, <strong>transfer</strong> (insurance, outsourcing with contracts), or <strong>avoid</strong> (stop the activity). Controls change likelihood or impact; residual risk should be explicit, not invisible.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L4-23: Secrets in engineering systems (Git, tickets, wikis, CI logs)</em>:</strong> Wireless and mobility items reward knowing basics: WPA3 improvements conceptually, evil twin risks, captive portals, and why client isolation matters on guest networks—without memorizing obsolete WEP details unless explicitly historical.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L4-23: Secrets in engineering systems (Git, tickets, wikis, CI logs)</em>:</strong> Industrial and OT adjacent questions reward knowing <strong>safety vs security</strong> tension: availability may trump confidentiality; testing must avoid breaking physical processes.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L4-23: Secrets in engineering systems (Git, tickets, wikis, CI logs)</em>:</strong> SAST finds issues early but produces false positives; <strong>triage workflows</strong> and developer feedback loops are part of a mature program, not “run tool once.”</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L4-23: Secrets in engineering systems (Git, tickets, wikis, CI logs)</em>:</strong> LDAP vs Active Directory questions test directory concepts at a high level—binding, searches, and secure transport (LDAPS) appear often.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> A cloud bill spike correlates with traffic about “L4-23: Secrets in engineering systems (Git, tickets, wikis, CI logs)”. Differentiate <strong>misconfiguration</strong> vs <strong>abuse</strong> in your first triage questions and what logs prove each hypothesis.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l4-24":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L4-24: Multi-region resilience and key management</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-24</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> KMS multi-region keys vs replicated; data sovereignty vs DR.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> RTO for crypto availability during regional outage.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Decision matrix: single-region KMS vs multi-region for 4 app tiers.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-24</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Evidence handling in regulated orgs may invoke <strong>legal hold</strong>—do not pick answers that “clean up” data prematurely.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 4 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>When asked for the <strong>first</strong> step, pick triage actions that preserve evidence and reduce spread—not deep malware reverse engineering.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>SOAR</strong></dt><dd>Security orchestration, automation, response—playbooks must have human gates for destructive actions.</dd><dt><strong>SSO</strong></dt><dd>Single sign-on federates trust to an IdP—misconfigured SAML/OIDC trusts are high-impact; validate metadata and signing keys.</dd><dt><strong>IAM least privilege</strong></dt><dd>Grant minimum API/console rights; prefer roles over long-lived keys; audit risky admin-equivalent paths regularly.</dd><dt><strong>Block cipher vs stream</strong></dt><dd>Block operates on fixed-size chunks; stream on bits/bytes—misuse modes (e.g., ECB) create patterns.</dd><dt><strong>Asset</strong></dt><dd>Anything of value to the organization—data, systems, people, reputation, or services—that security controls protect.</dd><dt><strong>Digital signature</strong></dt><dd>Proves origin and integrity using private key to sign and public key to verify—non-repudiation when keys are well governed.</dd><dt><strong>Zero Trust architecture</strong></dt><dd>Identity-centric access with continuous verification—policy enforcement points for users, devices, and workloads.</dd><dt><strong>Warm site / cold site</strong></dt><dd>Warm has partial hardware ready; cold is space only—cost vs recovery speed tradeoff.</dd><dt><strong>Data classification</strong></dt><dd>Labels (public, internal, confidential, restricted) drive storage, encryption, sharing, and disposal requirements.</dd><dt><strong>CWE</strong></dt><dd>Common Weakness Enumeration—taxonomy of software weakness types that help root-cause fixes beyond one CVE instance.</dd><dt><strong>Certificate transparency (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Public logs of issued certs help detect mis-issued certificates for your domains.</dd><dt><strong>PKI</strong></dt><dd>Public Key Infrastructure—CAs, RAs, CRL/OCSP, and certificate lifecycle; mis-issuance or weak validation breaks trust chains.</dd><dt><strong>Zero Trust (headline)</strong></dt><dd>Assume breach; verify explicitly per request using identity, device posture, and least privilege—not “trust the LAN.”</dd><dt><strong>Security awareness</strong></dt><dd>Training plus culture—measure reporting rates, not shame metrics; phishing simulations should reinforce reporting.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>IR phase</th><th>What you do there (exam shorthand)</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Prepare</strong></td><td>Playbooks, contacts, tooling, baseline logging—before the pager fires.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detect &amp; analyze</strong></td><td>Scope, timelines, hypotheses—preserve volatile evidence early.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Contain</strong></td><td>Stop spread with minimal evidence damage—network isolation variants matter.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Eradicate &amp; recover</strong></td><td>Remove persistence, patch root cause, restore with verification.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Lessons learned</strong></td><td>Metrics, control changes, and communication improvements—close the loop.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>AEAD</strong></td><td>Confidentiality + integrity together—misuse of IV/nonce still breaks security.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>CRL/OCSP failures can cause false negatives in validation—monitor PKI health proactively.</li><li>Azure AD / Entra conditional access is analogous to risk-based policies—device compliance signals matter.</li><li>ISO 27001 is an ISMS standard; it emphasizes risk treatment and continual improvement, not a product checklist.</li><li>Windows Event ID familiarity helps in hybrid SOC scenarios—Security log categories appear in stems.</li><li>Server-side template injection is distinct from XSS—context and sinks differ.</li><li>SBOM formats (CycloneDX/SPDX) help inventory components for incident response and licensing—not only security.</li><li>OAuth access tokens are not a replacement for server-side authorization checks on every sensitive action.</li><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L4-24: Multi-region resilience and key management</em>:</strong> Engineers often optimize for speed; attackers optimize for <strong>cheap reuse</strong> of stolen creds and known exploits. The winning answer bridges both: ship fast with guardrails—feature flags, staged rollouts, and automated security checks in CI.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L4-24: Multi-region resilience and key management</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L4-24: Multi-region resilience and key management</em>:</strong> GraphQL introspection risk is about <strong>schema discovery</strong> aiding attackers—rate limits, authz on fields, and disabling introspection in prod are common answers.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L4-24: Multi-region resilience and key management</em>:</strong> BIOS/UEFI passwords and secure boot reduce some pre-boot attacks but do not stop <strong>evil maid</strong> classes without additional controls.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L4-24: Multi-region resilience and key management</em>:</strong> Identity is the new perimeter: credentials, tokens, and sessions are stolen more often than novel zero-days are burned. Expect Security+ items on MFA bypass awareness, phishing-resistant factors, and why <strong>authorization</strong> must be enforced server-side.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L4-24: Multi-region resilience and key management</em>:</strong> Physical security is still on the exam: tailgating, visitor escorts, locks, destruction of media, and environmental controls (fire, HVAC) as availability/confidentiality supports.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L4-24: Multi-region resilience and key management</em>:</strong> Email security stems often combine SPF alignment failures with <strong>look-alike domains</strong>. The best answer addresses user training plus technical authenticity controls, not only one or the other.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L4-24: Multi-region resilience and key management</em>:</strong> DAST exercises running apps but misses authz logic without credentials; combine with <strong>manual review</strong> for business-rule flaws.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L4-24: Multi-region resilience and key management</em>:</strong> RADIUS is still referenced for <strong>network access control</strong> integrations; know it as a AAA component in enterprise Wi-Fi contexts.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L4-24: Multi-region resilience and key management</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>People:</strong> training, hiring checks, separation of duties—human failure modes dominate real incidents.</li>\n<li><strong>Process:</strong> change management, access reviews, vendor onboarding—repeatable procedures beat heroics.</li>\n<li><strong>Technology:</strong> encryption, firewalls, EDR—deployed with configuration management and drift detection.</li>\n<li><strong>Measurement:</strong> control effectiveness tests, purple findings, audit samples—prove controls operate, not only exist on paper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> During a tabletop, the CFO asks how “L4-24: Multi-region resilience and key management” could become a material incident. Answer with <strong>one plausible attack path</strong>, <strong>one detective control</strong> you already have, and <strong>one preventive gap</strong> you would fund next quarter.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l4-25":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L4-25: Board and executive reporting (risk in business terms)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-25</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Fewer heat maps, more “top 5 loss scenarios” with controls and trend.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Tie to insurance, revenue, regulatory deadlines.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> One-slide outline: title, risk statement, control, metric, owner, date.</p>\n<h2>Level 5 — Part 3</h2>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l4-25</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Level 4 mirrors Security+ <strong>enterprise and cloud</strong>: identity governance, conditional access patterns, evidence handling, purple collaboration, and vendor/SaaS risk. Show you understand <strong>scope</strong> and <strong>blast radius</strong> across accounts and tenants.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 4 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>For <strong>IoT</strong>, default passwords and unsegmented VLANs are common exam villains; change defaults and isolate.</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Authenticity</strong></dt><dd>Verifies that users, devices, or data are genuine—cryptographic identity, attestation, and strong issuance processes matter.</dd><dt><strong>TLS</strong></dt><dd>Encrypts data in motion and authenticates endpoints when certificates and hostnames are validated; termination points affect trust boundaries.</dd><dt><strong>Security misconfiguration</strong></dt><dd>Default creds, debug features on in prod, verbose errors, open directory listings—hardening baselines and drift detection reduce this class.</dd><dt><strong>Shared responsibility model</strong></dt><dd>Cloud provider secures the platform; customer secures configuration, identities, data, and app code in their scope.</dd><dt><strong>Attack surface</strong></dt><dd>The sum of exposure—every service, API, integration, and human workflow that can be reached by a threat; reduction beats perfect monitoring alone.</dd><dt><strong>Downgrade attack</strong></dt><dd>Forcing weaker crypto or protocols—HSTS and modern TLS config reduce browser downgrade paths.</dd><dt><strong>Proxy vs reverse proxy</strong></dt><dd>Forward proxy represents clients outbound; reverse proxy fronts servers—different trust and logging points.</dd><dt><strong>Data residency</strong></dt><dd>Legal requirement for where data lives—impacts cloud region selection and key custody.</dd><dt><strong>Vulnerability</strong></dt><dd>A weakness in design, implementation, configuration, or process that could be exploited to violate a security policy.</dd><dt><strong>Authorization</strong></dt><dd>What an authenticated subject is allowed to do—RBAC/ABAC, scopes, and server-side checks enforce least privilege.</dd><dt><strong>Perfect forward secrecy (PFS)</strong></dt><dd>Ephemeral key exchange means past session keys are not compromised if long-term keys leak later—TLS cipher suites can offer this property.</dd><dt><strong>Security headers</strong></dt><dd>HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options/Frame-ancestors, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy—reduce browser-driven attack surface.</dd><dt><strong>Serverless blast radius</strong></dt><dd>One broad execution role affects every invocation—scope IAM per function and watch environment variable leaks.</dd><dt><strong>Purple / red / blue</strong></dt><dd>Red emulates adversaries, blue defends, purple bridges—authorization and logging are mandatory for any simulation.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Split tunnel VPN can exfil corporate data outside inspection if misconfigured—policy and routing matter.</li><li>CSP default-src does not magically fix server-side SQLi—different layer.</li><li>AES-128 is not “half as strong” as AES-256 in practical threat models for many cases—key management quality dominates.</li><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li><li>DNS over HTTPS changes visibility for some networks—understand resolver policy and logging tradeoffs.</li><li>CVSS base does not include your asset criticality—environmental metrics exist for a reason.</li><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li><li>S3 bucket policies and ACLs layer with IAM—effective permissions require understanding intersection.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L4-25: Board and executive reporting (risk in business terms)</em>:</strong> Wireless and mobility items reward knowing basics: WPA3 improvements conceptually, evil twin risks, captive portals, and why client isolation matters on guest networks—without memorizing obsolete WEP details unless explicitly historical.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L4-25: Board and executive reporting (risk in business terms)</em>:</strong> Social engineering callbacks to <strong>pretexting</strong>, <strong>baiting</strong>, and <strong>vishing</strong>—name the subtype when the stem describes the tactic.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L4-25: Board and executive reporting (risk in business terms)</em>:</strong> Tabletop exercises test <strong>comms trees</strong>, legal escalation, and customer notification templates—not only technical runbooks.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L4-25: Board and executive reporting (risk in business terms)</em>:</strong> Engineers often optimize for speed; attackers optimize for <strong>cheap reuse</strong> of stolen creds and known exploits. The winning answer bridges both: ship fast with guardrails—feature flags, staged rollouts, and automated security checks in CI.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L4-25: Board and executive reporting (risk in business terms)</em>:</strong> Risk decisions are economic: organizations <strong>accept</strong>, <strong>mitigate</strong>, <strong>transfer</strong> (insurance, outsourcing with contracts), or <strong>avoid</strong> (stop the activity). Controls change likelihood or impact; residual risk should be explicit, not invisible.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L4-25: Board and executive reporting (risk in business terms)</em>:</strong> Certificate pinning failures during rotation teach why <strong>key continuity strategy</strong> must be planned before mobile releases.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L4-25: Board and executive reporting (risk in business terms)</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L4-25: Board and executive reporting (risk in business terms)</em>:</strong> Governance and awareness questions tie policy to behavior: acceptable use, clean desk, travel security, and vendor due diligence. Pick answers that reduce <strong>realistic</strong> human failure modes, not answers that maximize surveillance without process support.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L4-25: Board and executive reporting (risk in business terms)</em>:</strong> Virtualization risks include <strong>snapshot sprawl</strong> containing secrets and stale VM images drifting from hardened baselines.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L4-25: Board and executive reporting (risk in business terms)</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Junior staff proposes a quick fix for “L4-25: Board and executive reporting (risk in business terms)” that disables logging on a noisy host. Walk through why that is unacceptable and propose a <strong>tuning</strong> path that preserves <strong>integrity and retention</strong> commitments.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l5-21":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L5-21: Differential privacy vs “anonymization”</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-21</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Re-identification risk; epsilon budgets as governance topic.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Analytics on sensitive populations; legal review.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Three-sentence brief for legal: why aggregate tables still re-identify.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-21</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Zero Trust answers should emphasize <strong>continuous verification</strong> and <strong>policy enforcement points</strong>, not removing all network security.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 5 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>For crypto/TLS items, verify whether the question is about <strong>confidentiality</strong>, <strong>integrity</strong>, <strong>authentication</strong>, or <strong>non-repudiation</strong>—pick the property that actually matches the mechanism described.</li><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Non-repudiation</strong></dt><dd>Prevents a party from credibly denying an action—digital signatures, tamper-evident logs, and time-stamping support it.</dd><dt><strong>Encoding (e.g., Base64)</strong></dt><dd>Transforms representation without cryptographic protection—do not confuse with encryption or integrity.</dd><dt><strong>GRC</strong></dt><dd>Governance, risk, and compliance—align security decisions with law, policy, and business appetite; audits test design and operation.</dd><dt><strong>CRL</strong></dt><dd>Certificate Revocation List—signed list of revoked serials; size/latency issues drove OCSP adoption.</dd><dt><strong>SOAR</strong></dt><dd>Security orchestration, automation, response—playbooks must have human gates for destructive actions.</dd><dt><strong>Password policy</strong></dt><dd>Modern guidance favors long passphrases, breach-banned lists, and vaults over rotation-for-its-own-sake complexity theater.</dd><dt><strong>CSRF</strong></dt><dd>Cross-site request forgery rides ambient auth—anti-CSRF tokens, SameSite cookies, and re-auth for sensitive actions help.</dd><dt><strong>Threat intelligence lifecycle</strong></dt><dd>Planning, collection, processing, analysis, dissemination, feedback—intel must change detections or posture or it is shelf-ware.</dd><dt><strong>MAC</strong></dt><dd>Message authentication code—integrity with a secret key; differs from digital signature which uses asymmetric keys.</dd><dt><strong>Threat</strong></dt><dd>Any circumstance or actor with the potential to cause harm by exploiting a vulnerability (malware, insider, natural disaster).</dd><dt><strong>TLS</strong></dt><dd>Encrypts data in motion and authenticates endpoints when certificates and hostnames are validated; termination points affect trust boundaries.</dd><dt><strong>Vulnerability management</strong></dt><dd>Discover, prioritize, remediate, verify, and report—SLAs differ by exposure, exploitability, and asset criticality.</dd><dt><strong>Forensics basics</strong></dt><dd>Volatile vs non-volatile collection, order of volatility, hashing, and legal escalation paths before deep technical work.</dd><dt><strong>Full packet capture</strong></dt><dd>High fidelity evidence for investigations—storage, privacy, and legal review constraints apply.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Crypto concept</th><th>Precision the exam likes</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Hashing</strong></td><td>Integrity fingerprint—one-way; not secrecy; pair with keys for MACs.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetric</strong></td><td>Bulk encryption—key distribution is the hard part.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Asymmetric</strong></td><td>Key agreement/signing—watch performance and key lifecycle.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Digital signature</strong></td><td>Integrity + origin + non-repudiation when keys are governed.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Key management</strong></td><td>Generation, storage, rotation, destruction—often the real vulnerability.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>SameSite=Lax blocks many CSRF POSTs from cross-site contexts in modern browsers—know the nuance vs Strict.</li><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li><li>Admission controllers can block privileged pods—policy-as-code integrates with GitOps reviews.</li><li>AES-128 is not “half as strong” as AES-256 in practical threat models for many cases—key management quality dominates.</li><li>CVSS base does not include your asset criticality—environmental metrics exist for a reason.</li><li>Certificate pinning misconfigurations can brick apps—plan rotation and emergency releases.</li><li>KMS key policies can deny even root in AWS when configured—explicit deny wins.</li><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Pen test = prove we are secure.” → Right: Pen test = <strong>point-in-time</strong> risk snapshot under defined scope; continuous improvement follows.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>HIPAA Security Rule: administrative, physical, technical safeguards for PHI—BAA and minimum necessary appear often.</li><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>Describe how you would respond to a suspected <strong>credential stuffing</strong> wave against customer logins without locking out legitimate users entirely.</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L5-21: Differential privacy vs “anonymization”</em>:</strong> RADIUS is still referenced for <strong>network access control</strong> integrations; know it as a AAA component in enterprise Wi-Fi contexts.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L5-21: Differential privacy vs “anonymization”</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L5-21: Differential privacy vs “anonymization”</em>:</strong> Cloud items assume you can articulate <strong>shared responsibility</strong>: what the provider patches vs what the customer must configure (IAM, encryption, network exposure). Misconfiguration beats novel cloud exploits in real incidents and on the exam.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L5-21: Differential privacy vs “anonymization”</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L5-21: Differential privacy vs “anonymization”</em>:</strong> KMS keys are not “magic secrecy dust”—<strong>who can invoke decrypt</strong> and from which contexts (VPC endpoint policies, IAM conditions) is what exams probe.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L5-21: Differential privacy vs “anonymization”</em>:</strong> API keys in mobile apps are often extractable—prefer <strong>short-lived tokens</strong> and server-mediated access to backends.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L5-21: Differential privacy vs “anonymization”</em>:</strong> Virtualization risks include <strong>snapshot sprawl</strong> containing secrets and stale VM images drifting from hardened baselines.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L5-21: Differential privacy vs “anonymization”</em>:</strong> Risk decisions are economic: organizations <strong>accept</strong>, <strong>mitigate</strong>, <strong>transfer</strong> (insurance, outsourcing with contracts), or <strong>avoid</strong> (stop the activity). Controls change likelihood or impact; residual risk should be explicit, not invisible.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L5-21: Differential privacy vs “anonymization”</em>:</strong> Wireless and mobility items reward knowing basics: WPA3 improvements conceptually, evil twin risks, captive portals, and why client isolation matters on guest networks—without memorizing obsolete WEP details unless explicitly historical.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L5-21: Differential privacy vs “anonymization”</em>:</strong> Industrial and OT adjacent questions reward knowing <strong>safety vs security</strong> tension: availability may trump confidentiality; testing must avoid breaking physical processes.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Assuming <strong>TLS</strong> on a site proves the site is benign—TLS only protects the channel, not intent.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Believing <strong>obscurity</strong> (hidden URLs) is equivalent to <strong>authorization</strong>.</li><li>Confusing SPF/DKIM/DMARC purposes or DMARC alignment details.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Legal asks whether “L5-21: Differential privacy vs “anonymization”” artifacts require <strong>hold</strong> before deletion. Describe how you would <strong>tag systems</strong>, <strong>freeze backups</strong> appropriately, and <strong>escalate</strong> without tipping external actors.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l5-22":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L5-22: Homomorphic encryption (when it is worth the cost)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-22</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Compute on ciphertext classes; latency and limited operations today.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Regulated analytics partnerships.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Bullet list: 4 use cases where HE is plausible vs 4 where it is marketing-only today.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-22</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Architecture tradeoff prompts want <strong>explicit assumptions</strong>—availability vs cost vs complexity, stated cleanly.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 5 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>Expect <strong>“best”</strong> or <strong>“most appropriate”</strong> wording—eliminate absolutes (“always,” “never,” “eliminates all risk”) unless the statement is a definitional law like “encryption cannot fix broken authorization.”</li><li>When two answers sound equally secure, prefer the one with <strong>explicit accountability</strong> (logging, ownership, review) over anonymous magic.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>CWE</strong></dt><dd>Common Weakness Enumeration—taxonomy of software weakness types that help root-cause fixes beyond one CVE instance.</dd><dt><strong>CASB / SaaS governance</strong></dt><dd>Visibility and policy for sanctioned vs shadow SaaS—OAuth consent attacks and guest sharing are common gaps.</dd><dt><strong>Confidential computing</strong></dt><dd>Use of hardware enclaves/TEEs to reduce exposure to privileged operators—threat model still required.</dd><dt><strong>Replay attack</strong></dt><dd>Valid data maliciously re-sent—nonces, timestamps, and session freshness mitigate.</dd><dt><strong>HMAC</strong></dt><dd>Keyed hash construction—common for API authenticity when symmetric secret is shared out-of-band.</dd><dt><strong>Warm site / cold site</strong></dt><dd>Warm has partial hardware ready; cold is space only—cost vs recovery speed tradeoff.</dd><dt><strong>Defense in depth</strong></dt><dd>Layered controls so one failure does not equal total failure—network, host, app, identity, and monitoring each contribute.</dd><dt><strong>Vulnerability</strong></dt><dd>A weakness in design, implementation, configuration, or process that could be exploited to violate a security policy.</dd><dt><strong>Privacy</strong></dt><dd>Protection of personal information and individual rights—overlaps with security but adds legal/regulatory obligations (GDPR-style).</dd><dt><strong>Digital signature</strong></dt><dd>Proves origin and integrity using private key to sign and public key to verify—non-repudiation when keys are well governed.</dd><dt><strong>Secure SDLC</strong></dt><dd>Requirements, threat modeling, secure design, code review, SAST/DAST, dependency scanning, and hardened deployment pipelines.</dd><dt><strong>Misconfiguration</strong></dt><dd>Top cloud incident driver—public buckets, open security groups, permissive trust policies; IaC scanning catches drift early.</dd><dt><strong>Threat intelligence lifecycle</strong></dt><dd>Planning, collection, processing, analysis, dissemination, feedback—intel must change detections or posture or it is shelf-ware.</dd><dt><strong>Mandatory vacation</strong></dt><dd>Forces handover and review of another employee’s work—can uncover fraud or backdoors.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>KMS key policies can deny even root in AWS when configured—explicit deny wins.</li><li>Responsible disclosure timelines balance vendor patch readiness with public safety—coordinate, don’t surprise.</li><li>FIDO2 security keys resist phishing because the origin is bound cryptographically—unlike TOTP seeds typed into a page.</li><li>ATT&CK technique IDs are stable references for detection content—good for purple team reporting.</li><li>Split tunnel VPN can exfil corporate data outside inspection if misconfigured—policy and routing matter.</li><li>Race conditions in web apps can undermine authorization—sequential logic tests in secure design reviews.</li><li>Azure AD / Entra conditional access is analogous to risk-based policies—device compliance signals matter.</li><li>AES-128 is not “half as strong” as AES-256 in practical threat models for many cases—key management quality dominates.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “MFA means impossible to phish.” → Right: Push fatigue, proxied phishing, and session theft still exist—use phishing-resistant factors where possible.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS Controls: prioritized safeguards list—good for baseline gap conversations in interviews.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How would you explain <strong>IDOR</strong> to a product manager using a concrete object example (orders, invoices, documents)?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L5-22: Homomorphic encryption (when it is worth the cost)</em>:</strong> Cryptography questions reward vocabulary precision: hashing vs encryption vs encoding; symmetric vs asymmetric roles in TLS; what signatures prove; and why key management is usually harder than picking an algorithm. If an answer sounds magical, it is probably wrong.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L5-22: Homomorphic encryption (when it is worth the cost)</em>:</strong> Secrets in CI logs are a supply-chain class issue: the fix is <strong>redact</strong>, rotate, and add secret scanning gates—not “delete the repo history” as a first instinct unless counsel says so.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L5-22: Homomorphic encryption (when it is worth the cost)</em>:</strong> Deception tech is not a replacement for <strong>baselines and patching</strong>; it augments detection when mature processes exist.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L5-22: Homomorphic encryption (when it is worth the cost)</em>:</strong> Access control stems frequently mix <strong>role</strong> vs <strong>attribute</strong> vs <strong>rule</strong> models; pick the answer that matches the scenario’s constraints (temporary contractor, cross-department data, dynamic tags on resources).</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L5-22: Homomorphic encryption (when it is worth the cost)</em>:</strong> SAST finds issues early but produces false positives; <strong>triage workflows</strong> and developer feedback loops are part of a mature program, not “run tool once.”</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L5-22: Homomorphic encryption (when it is worth the cost)</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L5-22: Homomorphic encryption (when it is worth the cost)</em>:</strong> Engineers often optimize for speed; attackers optimize for <strong>cheap reuse</strong> of stolen creds and known exploits. The winning answer bridges both: ship fast with guardrails—feature flags, staged rollouts, and automated security checks in CI.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L5-22: Homomorphic encryption (when it is worth the cost)</em>:</strong> CSP reporting helps tune policy but can leak URLs—<strong>privacy review</strong> of report endpoints matters in regulated environments.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L5-22: Homomorphic encryption (when it is worth the cost)</em>:</strong> Application security scenarios often test whether you know <strong>where</strong> enforcement belongs—browser controls supplement but do not replace server-side checks. SameSite cookies, CSP, and HttpOnly mitigate classes of issues; they do not fix broken object-level authorization.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L5-22: Homomorphic encryption (when it is worth the cost)</em>:</strong> Container escape questions hinge on <strong>kernel boundary</strong> and misconfigured capabilities—namespaces are helpful but not a complete trust boundary without seccomp, AppArmor, and least-privileged service accounts.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Thinking CORS or browser policies substitute for server-side authorization.</li><li>Selecting <strong>security through long passwords only</strong> while ignoring MFA and phishing resistance.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> Purple team wants to simulate abuse of “L5-22: Homomorphic encryption (when it is worth the cost)” next Friday. List <strong>safety gates</strong> (scope, rollback, monitoring) you require before authorizing the exercise.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Draft five <strong>yes/no questions</strong> you would ask the system owner to decide whether this is containment-first or preserve-forensics-first.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l5-23":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L5-23: Secure multi-party computation (high-level)</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-23</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Parties compute joint function without revealing inputs to each other.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Fraud detection across banks without raw data sharing (concept).<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Compare MPC vs HE in one table (trust model, performance, maturity).</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-23</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Advanced IR/intel questions still punish <strong>evidence destruction</strong> and <strong>unscoped testing</strong>—professional ethics are in scope.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 5 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>Regulatory mentions (HIPAA-style, PCI) usually want <strong>least data</strong>, <strong>encryption</strong>, and <strong>access reviews</strong>—not “collect everything for analytics.”</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Integrity</strong></dt><dd>Assures accuracy and trustworthiness—hashing, signatures, change control, and backups protect against unauthorized modification.</dd><dt><strong>TLS</strong></dt><dd>Encrypts data in motion and authenticates endpoints when certificates and hostnames are validated; termination points affect trust boundaries.</dd><dt><strong>Injection</strong></dt><dd>Untrusted input becomes part of a command or query—parameterized queries, input validation, and context escaping are core defenses.</dd><dt><strong>Encryption at rest / in transit</strong></dt><dd>KMS/HSM-backed keys, envelope encryption, and TLS everywhere for administrative and user paths.</dd><dt><strong>Purple / red / blue</strong></dt><dd>Red emulates adversaries, blue defends, purple bridges—authorization and logging are mandatory for any simulation.</dd><dt><strong>Block cipher vs stream</strong></dt><dd>Block operates on fixed-size chunks; stream on bits/bytes—misuse modes (e.g., ECB) create patterns.</dd><dt><strong>OODA loop (IR)</strong></dt><dd>Observe-orient-decide-act—adversary and defender both iterate; faster, accurate decisions beat hoarding data.</dd><dt><strong>Security control categories</strong></dt><dd>Technical (firewalls, encryption), administrative (policies, training), and physical (badges, locks)—exam items often ask which category fits a scenario.</dd><dt><strong>PII</strong></dt><dd>Personally identifiable information—names, government IDs, biometrics, account numbers; triggers handling, retention, and breach rules.</dd><dt><strong>Network segmentation</strong></dt><dd>VLANs, micro-segmentation, and east-west controls limit lateral movement after an initial foothold.</dd><dt><strong>Secure SDLC</strong></dt><dd>Requirements, threat modeling, secure design, code review, SAST/DAST, dependency scanning, and hardened deployment pipelines.</dd><dt><strong>BCP / DR</strong></dt><dd>Business continuity and disaster recovery—RTO/RPO drive architecture; test restores, not just backups on paper.</dd><dt><strong>Job rotation</strong></dt><dd>Reduces collusion and fraud risk; also surfaces “tribal knowledge” silos before an employee leaves.</dd><dt><strong>Diffie-Hellman (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Key agreement over insecure channel—combine with authentication to prevent MITM.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Cloud responsibility</th><th>Who typically owns it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Patching the hypervisor</strong></td><td>Provider responsibility in major IaaS models—customer still patches guests.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>IAM policy and keys</strong></td><td>Customer-owned configuration—misconfigurations dominate incidents.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Data encryption at rest</strong></td><td>Often customer-controlled keys/KMS policies with provider primitives.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Network exposure (SGs/NACLs)</strong></td><td>Customer configures; default-deny patterns are exam favorites.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Application vulnerabilities</strong></td><td>Customer code and dependencies—shared model does not absolve secure SDLC.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>Split tunnel VPN can exfil corporate data outside inspection if misconfigured—policy and routing matter.</li><li>KMS key policies can deny even root in AWS when configured—explicit deny wins.</li><li>PCI DSS scope reduction via segmentation is a recurring theme—if it is not in scope, it cannot drag you into assessment.</li><li>Write blockers protect disk integrity during acquisition—first touch matters for admissibility narratives.</li><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li><li>Linux auth.log style entries pair with SSH brute-force detection patterns—velocity and geo anomalies.</li><li>Container image signing and digest pinning reduce supply-chain surprises in Kubernetes pulls.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Disable SELinux/AppArmor because it breaks things.” → Right: Tune profiles and fix policy; disabling removes mandatory access control value.</li><li>Wrong: “PQC means turn off classical crypto today.” → Right: Hybrid transition and inventory of long-lived secrets guide migration.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How do <strong>break-glass</strong> accounts stay secure while remaining usable in emergencies?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L5-23: Secure multi-party computation (high-level)</em>:</strong> Advanced topics still return to fundamentals: least privilege, segmentation, logging, and tested recovery. When you see Zero Trust or PQC buzzwords, map them back to concrete controls and threat models rather than treating them as magic shields.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L5-23: Secure multi-party computation (high-level)</em>:</strong> Air gapped networks still need <strong>patching via sneaker-net</strong> and insider controls—physical isolation is not logical isolation.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L5-23: Secure multi-party computation (high-level)</em>:</strong> BEC stems want <strong>out-of-band verification</strong> for payment changes, not “block all international email.”</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L5-23: Secure multi-party computation (high-level)</em>:</strong> Logging questions often test whether you understand <strong>what to log</strong> (who, what, when, where, outcome), <strong>time sync</strong> for correlation, and <strong>tamper resistance</strong> for evidentiary value—not whether you can collect infinite bytes.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L5-23: Secure multi-party computation (high-level)</em>:</strong> Virtualization risks include <strong>snapshot sprawl</strong> containing secrets and stale VM images drifting from hardened baselines.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L5-23: Secure multi-party computation (high-level)</em>:</strong> Ransomware stems often pair encryption with <strong>exfiltration</strong>—the correct answer may include legal/notification obligations, not only restoring from backup.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L5-23: Secure multi-party computation (high-level)</em>:</strong> Access control stems frequently mix <strong>role</strong> vs <strong>attribute</strong> vs <strong>rule</strong> models; pick the answer that matches the scenario’s constraints (temporary contractor, cross-department data, dynamic tags on resources).</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L5-23: Secure multi-party computation (high-level)</em>:</strong> BIOS/UEFI passwords and secure boot reduce some pre-boot attacks but do not stop <strong>evil maid</strong> classes without additional controls.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L5-23: Secure multi-party computation (high-level)</em>:</strong> Cryptojacking still appears: high CPU, unexpected mining pools, and cloud billing spikes—detection plus credential hygiene beats chasing miner signatures alone.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L5-23: Secure multi-party computation (high-level)</em>:</strong> Wireless and mobility items reward knowing basics: WPA3 improvements conceptually, evil twin risks, captive portals, and why client isolation matters on guest networks—without memorizing obsolete WEP details unless explicitly historical.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li><li>Choosing “disable antivirus” or “turn off firewall” as a troubleshooting first step.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> You are the on-call analyst reviewing an alert tied to “L5-23: Secure multi-party computation (high-level)”. Leadership wants a <strong>60-second</strong> brief: business impact, evidence gaps, and the <strong>first</strong> containment step that preserves logs. No tool-specific jargon—prioritize scope, evidence, blast radius, then root-cause remediation under change control.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Write three <strong>plausible wrong answers</strong> an exam might offer—each violating least privilege, logging integrity, or legal escalation—then pick the best remaining option in one sentence.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l5-24":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L5-24: Protocol composition failures</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-24</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Secure pieces, insecure system; downgrade glue between components.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Microservices auth between internal hops.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Story: “service A trusts mTLS from gateway; gateway trusts Internet” — draw trust failure.</p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-24</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Architecture tradeoff prompts want <strong>explicit assumptions</strong>—availability vs cost vs complexity, stated cleanly.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 5 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If the question references <strong>contractors</strong>, expect answers about temporary accounts, expiration, and scoped access—not permanent admin.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If “AI” appears, answers usually emphasize <strong>data governance</strong>, prompt injection class risks, and supply chain of models—not sci-fi.</li><li>For <strong>wireless</strong>, “disable SSID broadcast” is weak obscurity; stronger answers involve WPA enterprise, segmentation, and monitoring.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>users clicking links</strong>, combine awareness with <strong>technical controls</strong> (safe link rewriting, attachment sandboxing, MFA) rather than blaming training only.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Confidential computing</strong></dt><dd>Use of hardware enclaves/TEEs to reduce exposure to privileged operators—threat model still required.</dd><dt><strong>BGP prefix hijack</strong></dt><dd>Unauthorized route advertisement—RPKI ROV reduces impact but does not replace monitoring.</dd><dt><strong>Integrity</strong></dt><dd>Assures accuracy and trustworthiness—hashing, signatures, change control, and backups protect against unauthorized modification.</dd><dt><strong>OWASP Top 10</strong></dt><dd>High-prevalence web risks—broken access control and crypto failures often dominate; study each category with one workplace example.</dd><dt><strong>Threat modeling (STRIDE)</strong></dt><dd>Spoofing, tampering, repudiation, information disclosure, denial of service, elevation of privilege—drive controls early.</dd><dt><strong>RPO / RTO recap</strong></dt><dd>RPO = max acceptable data loss time; RTO = max acceptable outage—drive backup frequency and HA design.</dd><dt><strong>Availability</strong></dt><dd>Assures timely and reliable access—redundancy, patching, DDoS defenses, and DR planning keep services usable for authorized users.</dd><dt><strong>Injection</strong></dt><dd>Untrusted input becomes part of a command or query—parameterized queries, input validation, and context escaping are core defenses.</dd><dt><strong>Purple teaming</strong></dt><dd>Collaborative attack/defense exercises to validate detections without surprise production harm—scope and safety first.</dd><dt><strong>Warm site / cold site</strong></dt><dd>Warm has partial hardware ready; cold is space only—cost vs recovery speed tradeoff.</dd><dt><strong>Authenticity</strong></dt><dd>Verifies that users, devices, or data are genuine—cryptographic identity, attestation, and strong issuance processes matter.</dd><dt><strong>XSS</strong></dt><dd>Cross-site scripting injects script in a victim context—CSP, output encoding, HttpOnly cookies, and DOM hygiene reduce blast radius.</dd><dt><strong>Purple / red / blue</strong></dt><dd>Red emulates adversaries, blue defends, purple bridges—authorization and logging are mandatory for any simulation.</dd><dt><strong>MTTD / MTTR</strong></dt><dd>Mean time to detect / remediate—quality matters; gaming metrics by closing tickets inflates false success.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Split tunnel</strong></td><td>User traffic may bypass corporate inspection—policy and routing implications.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>SLSA levels describe increasing supply-chain assurance—useful vocabulary in modern governance questions.</li><li>Responsible disclosure timelines balance vendor patch readiness with public safety—coordinate, don’t surprise.</li><li>SHA-1 is deprecated for security-sensitive signatures; prefer SHA-256 family algorithms for new designs.</li><li>NIST CSF functions: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover—useful mental scaffold for mapping controls.</li><li>PCI DSS scope reduction via segmentation is a recurring theme—if it is not in scope, it cannot drag you into assessment.</li><li>OAuth access tokens are not a replacement for server-side authorization checks on every sensitive action.</li><li>HttpOnly does not stop CSRF; it reduces token theft from XSS reading document.cookie in many setups.</li><li>CVSS base does not include your asset criticality—environmental metrics exist for a reason.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “Encryption fixes data quality.” → Right: Encryption protects data; it does not validate correctness or authorization.</li><li>Wrong: “Zero Trust = no firewalls.” → Right: Zero Trust changes <strong>trust assumptions</strong>; network controls remain, differently applied.</li><li>Wrong: “NAT is a security feature.” → Right: NAT complicates addressing; it is not a substitute for firewall rules and host controls.</li><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>COBIT / ITIL touch governance and service management—sometimes appear as “process maturity” distractors vs technical fixes.</li><li>ISO 27005: risk assessment guidance—ties likelihood/impact treatment to management decisions.</li><li>PCI DSS: cardholder data environment controls—segmentation and PAN minimization are recurring exam neighbors.</li><li>SOC 2 Trust Services Criteria: security + availability/confidentiality/etc.—read exceptions in real reports.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>What logs would you want for detecting <strong>lateral movement</strong> in an AD environment at a high level?</li><li>How does <strong>DMARC alignment</strong> reduce business email spoofing—what breaks if SPF passes but DKIM fails?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L5-24: Protocol composition failures</em>:</strong> Vulnerability management is a lifecycle: scanners find candidates, analysts prioritize with exploitability and business context, owners remediate, and verification closes the loop. “Patch everything immediately” is rarely operational; <strong>risk-based SLAs</strong> are the adult answer.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L5-24: Protocol composition failures</em>:</strong> CSP reporting helps tune policy but can leak URLs—<strong>privacy review</strong> of report endpoints matters in regulated environments.</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L5-24: Protocol composition failures</em>:</strong> Auditors care about <strong>traceability</strong>: who approved an exception, when it expires, and what compensating control exists. When you answer exam questions about policy, pick the option that leaves an evidence trail, not the one that relies on informal verbal OKs.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L5-24: Protocol composition failures</em>:</strong> Social engineering callbacks to <strong>pretexting</strong>, <strong>baiting</strong>, and <strong>vishing</strong>—name the subtype when the stem describes the tactic.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L5-24: Protocol composition failures</em>:</strong> Ransomware stems often pair encryption with <strong>exfiltration</strong>—the correct answer may include legal/notification obligations, not only restoring from backup.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L5-24: Protocol composition failures</em>:</strong> Cloud items assume you can articulate <strong>shared responsibility</strong>: what the provider patches vs what the customer must configure (IAM, encryption, network exposure). Misconfiguration beats novel cloud exploits in real incidents and on the exam.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L5-24: Protocol composition failures</em>:</strong> Certificate pinning failures during rotation teach why <strong>key continuity strategy</strong> must be planned before mobile releases.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L5-24: Protocol composition failures</em>:</strong> Help desk scenarios test whether you know <strong>identity proofing</strong> vs <strong>account recovery</strong> abuse. The secure path verifies the human through out-of-band channels without teaching attackers how to bypass your process in the stem text.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L5-24: Protocol composition failures</em>:</strong> Travel security includes <strong>full-disk encryption</strong>, VPN hygiene on hotel Wi-Fi, and device never leaving sight—not “turn off MFA for convenience.”</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L5-24: Protocol composition failures</em>:</strong> Typosquatting and dependency confusion prey on <strong>human trust in package names</strong>; mitigations include private registries, pinning, and provenance verification.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Identify (CSF-style):</strong> asset inventory, risk framing, governance—know what you are protecting before buying tools.</li>\n<li><strong>Protect:</strong> IAM, data security, protective tech—make abuse expensive and visible.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> continuous monitoring, anomaly detection—assume some bypass succeeds.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond &amp; Recover:</strong> coordinated actions with communications, then verified restoration and lessons captured as tickets.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Assuming “air gap” or “encryption” alone removes need for monitoring and backups.</li><li>Believing <strong>MAC filtering</strong> is strong authentication for Wi-Fi.</li><li>Selecting “domain admin for scanning” as a default best practice.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> During a tabletop, the CFO asks how “L5-24: Protocol composition failures” could become a material incident. Answer with <strong>one plausible attack path</strong>, <strong>one detective control</strong> you already have, and <strong>one preventive gap</strong> you would fund next quarter.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> Explain the same scenario twice: once for a <strong>technical peer</strong>, once for a <strong>non-technical executive</strong>—no word overlap in the opening sentences.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>","lh-sec-l5-25":"<p class=\"lh-tg-source\"><strong>L5-25: ML supply chain and model / prompt abuse</strong> · <span class=\"lh-tg-chapter\">Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing)</span> · Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-25</code> · Source: <code>docs/SECURITY_CONCEPTS_WORKPLACE_CURRICULUM.md</code></p><hr class=\"teach-hr lh-md-start\"/><div class=\"lh-tg-root tech-prose lh-tg-markdown lh-chapter-markdown\"><p><strong>Outcomes:</strong> Training data poisoning, weight tampering, prompt injection as appsec class.<br><strong>Workplace:</strong> Separate LLM system prompt from untrusted document content; output filtering and grounding.<br><strong>Kali lab:</strong> Write 6 defensive controls for an internal “chat with PDF” feature (no live LLM keys).</p>\n<hr>\n<h2>Supplemental question banks — Part 2 (Q31–40 per level)</h2>\n<h3>Level 1 — Q31–40</h3>\n<p><strong>Q31.</strong> Data “restricted” tier usually implies: (a) public blog OK (b) strongest controls and handling (c) no encryption.<br><strong>Q32.</strong> Vendor SOC 2 Type II mainly shows: (a) point-in-time screenshot only always (b) controls operated over a period (Type II) per auditor testing (c) PCI scope.<br><strong>Q33.</strong> Security champions help mainly by: (a) replacing AppSec headcount entirely (b) embedding risk context in squads (c) deleting logs.<br><strong>Q34.</strong> Guest Wi-Fi isolation goal: (a) merge with corporate LAN freely (b) segment untrusted devices (c) disable DHCP.<br><strong>Q35.</strong> Browser extensions with “read all site data” are: (a) always safe (b) high abuse potential (c) required for TLS.<br><strong>Q36.</strong> Third-party DPA importance: (a) legal processing terms and liability allocation (b) replaces MFA (c) fixes BGP.<br><strong>Q37.</strong> Retention limits help: (a) reduce exposure and cost (b) increase breach impact (c) remove need for backups.<br><strong>Q38.</strong> Home router firmware updates address: (a) known exploitable bugs (b) monitor refresh rate (c) SQL collation.<br><strong>Q39.</strong> Labeling emails “confidential” without technical controls: (a) sufficient alone always (b) awareness aid, not technical control (c) replaces encryption.<br><strong>Q40.</strong> Vendor exit strategy should include: (a) data export and key custody (b) deleting backups always day one (c) ignoring logs.</p>\n<h3>Answer key — Level 1 Q31–40</h3>\n<p>31–40: B/B/B/B/B/A/A/A/B/A</p>\n<h3>Level 2 — Q31–40</h3>\n<p><strong>Q31.</strong> JWT <code>aud</code> (audience) claim helps: (a) bind token to intended relying party (b) replace TLS (c) configure RAID.<br><strong>Q32.</strong> GraphQL introspection in production risk: (a) aids attackers mapping schema (b) improves BGP (c) removes MFA.<br><strong>Q33.</strong> SRI fails when: (a) vendor file changes and hash not updated (b) HSTS enabled (c) RAID 1 healthy.<br><strong>Q34.</strong> CSP <code>default-src &#39;self&#39;</code> is: (a) baseline restrict origins (b) disk encryption (c) MFA type.<br><strong>Q35.</strong> CORS with <code>Access-Control-Allow-Credentials: true</code> and <code>*</code> origin is: (a) valid and safe always (b) invalid / browser-rejected pattern (c) required for PCI.<br><strong>Q36.</strong> JWT in <code>localStorage</code> vs HttpOnly cookie: (a) localStorage often worse XSS token theft (b) identical always (c) always better.<br><strong>Q37.</strong> GraphQL field-level authz matters because: (a) one resolver may expose sensitive nested data (b) DNS only (c) BIOS.<br><strong>Q38.</strong> CSP report-only mode helps: (a) tune policy before blocking (b) remove TLS (c) disable cookies.<br><strong>Q39.</strong> <code>crossorigin</code> on SRI script tags relates to: (a) CORS checks for integrity fetch (b) RAID (c) SMTP.<br><strong>Q40.</strong> “CORS fixes authz” is: (a) false — server must enforce authorization (b) true always (c) only for SOAP.</p>\n<h3>Answer key — Level 2 Q31–40</h3>\n<p>31–40: A/A/A/A/B/A/A/A/A/A</p>\n<h3>Level 3 — Q31–40</h3>\n<p><strong>Q31.</strong> STIX expresses: (a) structured threat intel objects (b) BIOS passwords (c) RAID levels.<br><strong>Q32.</strong> TAXII moves: (a) STIX over HTTP APIs (b) GPU firmware (c) TPM quotes only.<br><strong>Q33.</strong> Tactical intel often includes: (a) short-lived IOCs (b) 10-year strategy only (c) HR payroll formulas.<br><strong>Q34.</strong> Osquery’s value is: (a) fleet-wide SQL visibility with governance (b) replaces firewalls (c) fixes XSS.<br><strong>Q35.</strong> SPAN port risk: (a) dropped packets under load; not perfect copy (b) always inline block (c) encrypts disk.<br><strong>Q36.</strong> ATT&amp;CK “procedure” is: (a) actor-specific way to execute technique (b) CVE number (c) TLS cipher.<br><strong>Q37.</strong> Intelligence without <strong>feedback</strong> to detection engineering often: (a) becomes shelf-ware (b) automatically stops APT (c) replaces EDR.<br><strong>Q38.</strong> Network TAP typical benefit: (a) full fidelity copy for tools (b) terminates TLS always (c) patches Linux kernel.<br><strong>Q39.</strong> Pyramid base for defenders often emphasizes: (a) durable TTP-based detections over stale IPs only (b) ignoring logs (c) deleting endpoints.<br><strong>Q40.</strong> Sharing STIX without validation can: (a) spread false positives or poisoned intel (b) fix SQLi (c) remove MFA.</p>\n<h3>Answer key — Level 3 Q31–40</h3>\n<p>31–40: A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A</p>\n<h3>Level 4 — Q31–40</h3>\n<p><strong>Q31.</strong> CI OIDC to cloud reduces: (a) long-lived static keys in repos (b) need for code review (c) TLS need.<br><strong>Q32.</strong> Terraform state in plain git is: (a) dangerous (secrets, infra metadata leak) (b) best practice (c) required by PCI.<br><strong>Q33.</strong> Poisoned CI cache could: (a) inject malicious build artifacts (b) improve unit tests (c) enable RAID 6 on laptop.<br><strong>Q34.</strong> Policy-as-code for IaC catches: (a) risky IAM/SG rules pre-apply (b) BGP leaks (c) HDMI issues.<br><strong>Q35.</strong> Multi-region KMS planning ties to: (a) DR, latency, jurisdiction (b) printer DPI (c) SMTP banners only.<br><strong>Q36.</strong> Executive slide should avoid: (a) unexplained CVSS-only heat maps without business story (b) clear owners (c) dates.<br><strong>Q37.</strong> <code>gitleaks</code> / secret scanning goal: (a) detect credentials in repos and history (b) replace WAF (c) configure BIOS.<br><strong>Q38.</strong> Over-privileged CI role risk: (a) pipeline compromise becomes cloud admin (b) improves MFA (c) shrinks logs.<br><strong>Q39.</strong> IaC module pinning reduces: (a) surprise upstream supply chain changes (b) RAID 0 risk (c) DNS TTL.<br><strong>Q40.</strong> Board metrics should include: (a) trend and remediation SLA, not only counts (b) raw grep only (c) employee birthdays.</p>\n<h3>Answer key — Level 4 Q31–40</h3>\n<p>31–40: A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A</p>\n<h3>Level 5 — Q31–40</h3>\n<p><strong>Q31.</strong> Differential privacy uses: (a) calibrated noise for bounded disclosure (b) RAID striping (c) static NAT only.<br><strong>Q32.</strong> HE today often limited by: (a) performance and operation sets (b) lack of TLS (c) SMTP.<br><strong>Q33.</strong> MPC trust model differs from HE partly in: (a) parties and collusion assumptions (b) monitor Hz (c) VGA.<br><strong>Q34.</strong> Composition failures explain: (a) secure components, insecure system glue (b) faster RAM (c) DKIM alignment.<br><strong>Q35.</strong> Prompt injection is primarily: (a) untrusted instructions influencing model/tool use (b) SQLi (c) RAID 5.<br><strong>Q36.</strong> Model weights integrity matters for: (a) supply chain of ML artifacts (b) DHCP scope (c) printer DPI.<br><strong>Q37.</strong> “Aggregate is safe” is: (a) often false due to re-identification (b) always true (c) PCI requirement for cards in clear.<br><strong>Q38.</strong> HE for regulated analytics is: (a) sometimes viable with expert architecture (b) solved for arbitrary code at line-rate everywhere (c) illegal.<br><strong>Q39.</strong> ML observability for abuse includes: (a) rate limits, anomaly detection on prompts/outputs (b) disabling audit logs (c) BGP only.<br><strong>Q40.</strong> Protocol glue attacks target: (a) assumptions between components (b) ECC RAM only (c) HDMI-CEC only.</p>\n<h3>Answer key — Level 5 Q31–40</h3>\n<p>31–40: A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A</p>\n<hr>\n<h1>Capstone — Part 3 (Q81–100)</h1>\n<p><strong>Q81.</strong> Data classification drives: (a) control selection and handling (b) GPU clock (c) SMTP EHLO only.<br><strong>Q82.</strong> Vendor Type II report review should include: (a) exceptions and scope boundaries (b) ignoring caveats (c) deleting DPA.<br><strong>Q83.</strong> JWT validation must include: (a) signature, <code>exp</code>, <code>iss</code>, <code>aud</code> as applicable (b) color of logo (c) RAID level.<br><strong>Q84.</strong> GraphQL depth limits primarily mitigate: (a) DoS via expensive queries (b) BGP hijacks (c) BIOS passwords.<br><strong>Q85.</strong> SRI mitigates: (a) compromised CDN file substitution (b) SQLi only (c) DHCP starvation.<br><strong>Q86.</strong> CSP helps with: (a) XSS reduction and blast control (b) disk encryption always (c) Kerberos only.<br><strong>Q87.</strong> CORS is not a substitute for: (a) server-side authorization (b) TLS certificate pinning only (c) RAID 6.<br><strong>Q88.</strong> STIX without validation risks: (a) garbage or malicious intel propagation (b) faster CPU (c) WPA3.<br><strong>Q89.</strong> Osquery deployment needs: (a) privacy governance and query scope (b) no logging (c) domain admin for desktops only always.<br><strong>Q90.</strong> CI/CD OIDC reduces: (a) static cloud keys in repos (b) unit tests (c) MFA everywhere.<br><strong>Q91.</strong> Terraform state exposure is dangerous because: (a) may contain secrets and sensitive infra layout (b) improves BGP (c) required for DNS.<br><strong>Q92.</strong> Policy-as-code (e.g., OPA) applies checks: (a) pre-deploy on IaC plans (b) only post-breach (c) never on IAM.<br><strong>Q93.</strong> Executive reporting should emphasize: (a) material scenarios and remediation owners (b) raw grep (c) employee gossip.<br><strong>Q94.</strong> Differential privacy is about: (a) bounding individual influence on published stats (b) RAID 6 (c) DKIM.<br><strong>Q95.</strong> MPC allows: (a) joint compute without sharing raw inputs (under model) (b) infinite line-rate AES on laptop always (c) SMTP only.<br><strong>Q96.</strong> Prompt injection defenses include: (a) trust boundaries, tool allowlists, output validation (b) disabling HTTPS (c) chmod 777.<br><strong>Q97.</strong> HE is a silver bullet for all analytics: (a) true (b) false (c) legally banned.<br><strong>Q98.</strong> Network TAP vs SPAN: TAP often gives: (a) better fidelity under load than SPAN in many designs (b) always worse (c) encrypts TLS automatically.<br><strong>Q99.</strong> Threat intel operationalization means: (a) detection/response changes from intel (b) hoarding PDFs (c) deleting SIEM.<br><strong>Q100.</strong> Composition security means: (a) analyze whole system glue, not only parts (b) ignore microservices trust (c) trust LAN.</p>\n<h3>Capstone Part 3 answer key</h3>\n<p>81–90: A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A/A<br>91–100: A/A/A/A/A/A/B/A/A/A</p>\n<hr>\n<h2>Appendix F — OWASP API Security (2019) at a glance</h2>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Risk category</th>\n<th>One-line workplace meaning</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>API1 Broken object level authz</strong></td>\n<td>Users can access others’ objects by changing IDs.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>API2 Broken authentication</strong></td>\n<td>Weak tokens, bad MFA, credential stuffing on APIs.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>API3 Excessive data exposure</strong></td>\n<td>Mobile “convenience” responses leak extra fields.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>API4 Lack of resources and rate limits</strong></td>\n<td>Scraping, brute force, cost bombs.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>API5 Broken function level authz</strong></td>\n<td>Admin endpoints hidden but not protected.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>API6 Mass assignment</strong></td>\n<td>Client sets <code>role=admin</code> in JSON body.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>API7 Security misconfiguration</strong></td>\n<td>Debug stacks, default accounts, verbose errors.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>API8 Injection</strong></td>\n<td>SQL/NoSQL/OS command via parameters.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>API9 Improper assets management</strong></td>\n<td>Shadow APIs, old <code>/v1</code> still exposed.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>API10 Insufficient logging and monitoring</strong></td>\n<td>No trace for fraud or IR.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table>\n<p><strong>Kali lab (design):</strong> Pick one public API doc (authorized); list three tests your team would run in staging (no customer harm).</p>\n<hr>\n<h2>Appendix G — Sample weekly syllabus (24 weeks, 3 lessons/week)</h2>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Week</th>\n<th>Focus</th>\n<th>Suggested lessons</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody><tr>\n<td>1–2</td>\n<td>Foundations</td>\n<td>L1-01–L1-10</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>3–4</td>\n<td>Human + ops</td>\n<td>L1-11–L1-20</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>5–6</td>\n<td>Governance + home</td>\n<td>L1-21–L1-25 + Lab A start</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>7–8</td>\n<td>Web + TLS</td>\n<td>L2-01–L2-10</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9–10</td>\n<td>App flaws</td>\n<td>L2-11–L2-20</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>11–12</td>\n<td>Modern web</td>\n<td>L2-21–L2-25 + Lab B</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>13–14</td>\n<td>Vuln + logging</td>\n<td>L3-01–L3-10</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>15–16</td>\n<td>Intel + NSM</td>\n<td>L3-11–L3-25</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>17–18</td>\n<td>Enterprise ID + cloud</td>\n<td>L4-01–L4-10</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>19–20</td>\n<td>DevSecOps + exec</td>\n<td>L4-11–L4-25</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>21–22</td>\n<td>Architecture + crypto futures</td>\n<td>L5-01–L5-15</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>23–24</td>\n<td>Research edge + capstone</td>\n<td>L5-16–L5-25 + Parts 1–3 exams</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table>\n<p>Adjust pacing for cohort; add <strong>Lab sequence A–C</strong> between weeks.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2>Appendix H — Certification alignment (illustrative, not endorsements)</h2>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Credential</th>\n<th>This curriculum overlap (high level)</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>CompTIA Security+</strong></td>\n<td>L1–L2 bulk; parts of L3 logging/IR.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>CySA+</strong></td>\n<td>L3 SIEM, intel, IR; L4 SOC workflows.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>PenTest+</strong></td>\n<td>Ethical scope in L3/L5; <strong>only</strong> with legal lab RoE.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>CASP+ / CISSP (later)</strong></td>\n<td>L4–L5 architecture, risk, governance depth.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>CCSP</strong></td>\n<td>L4 cloud logging, IAM, DR when extended with vendor labs.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table>\n<p>Always use official exam objectives for gaps analysis.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2>Appendix I — Scenario pack (write-ups for triage drills)</h2>\n<p><strong>Scenario 1 — “Finance forwarded the CEO’s urgent wire”</strong><br>Indicators: domain look-alike, urgency, new account number, no phone callback culture violated.<br>Tasks: classify BEC vs account takeover; preserve headers; comms freeze; finance callback procedure.</p>\n<p><strong>Scenario 2 — “Spike in <code>kubectl</code> exec from CI service account”</strong><br>Indicators: non-human hours, new clusterRoleBinding, image pull from unknown registry.<br>Tasks: map blast radius; revoke tokens; check pipeline YAML history; incident commander checklist.</p>\n<p><strong>Scenario 3 — “Customer reports another user’s invoice in portal”</strong><br>Indicators: IDOR pattern; missing authz on object GET.<br>Tasks: hotfix pattern (feature flag off); forensic log of accessed IDs; customer notification policy consult.</p>\n<p><strong>Scenario 4 — “Security tool shows self-signed TLS on internal API”</strong><br>Indicators: missed cert rotation vs malicious MITM.<br>Tasks: validate config management drift; compare cert fingerprint to vault; out-of-band verify with second path.</p>\n<p><strong>Scenario 5 — “WAF blocked 90% traffic after deploy”</strong><br>Indicators: new JSON field tripping XSS rule; false positive surge.<br>Tasks: rollback vs detect-only; tune rule; postmortem on CSP vs WAF overlap.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2>Appendix J — Grading rubric (project: “Lab network dossier”)</h2>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Criterion</th>\n<th>Excellent</th>\n<th>Needs work</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>Scope &amp; ethics</strong></td>\n<td>Written RoE; only owned/lab targets</td>\n<td>Ambiguous or external targets</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Technical accuracy</strong></td>\n<td>Commands correct; concepts precise</td>\n<td>Major misconceptions</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Evidence</strong></td>\n<td>Hashes, timestamps, reproducible steps</td>\n<td>Assertions only</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Risk communication</strong></td>\n<td>Business impact + control mapping</td>\n<td>Jargon-only</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Remediation</strong></td>\n<td>Prioritized, feasible, owners</td>\n<td>Generic “patch everything”</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table>\n<p>Weight ethics and evidence highest; fail submissions that violate scope rules.</p>\n<hr>\n<h2>Appendix K — Glossary addendum (API, DevOps, intel)</h2>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Term</th>\n<th>Meaning</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody><tr>\n<td><strong>IDOR</strong></td>\n<td>Insecure direct object reference — missing object-level authz.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>OIDC federated trust</strong></td>\n<td>Trust chain between IdPs and SaaS via signed tokens/metadata.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>OPA / Conftest</strong></td>\n<td>Policy-as-code engines testing IaC JSON/YAML.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>OIDC in CI</strong></td>\n<td>Short-lived cloud creds from pipeline identity, not static keys.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>STIX bundle</strong></td>\n<td>Container of related intel objects for exchange.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>TAXII collection</strong></td>\n<td>Server-side grouping of objects clients poll or push.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Report-only CSP</strong></td>\n<td>Sends violations without blocking render.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><strong>Poisoned pipeline</strong></td>\n<td>CI compromise altering artifacts or stealing secrets.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table>\n<hr>\n<p><em>Document version: 1.2 — Part 3 (lessons 21–25), Q31–40 banks, capstone Q81–100, appendices F–K. Learn-Hub: split on <code>### Lx-yy</code> and <code>&lt;!-- id: lh-sec-* --&gt;</code>.</em></p>\n\n<section class=\"lh-sec-study-pack\" aria-label=\"Security+ expanded study notes\">\n<h2>Security+ prep — expanded study guide</h2>\n<p class=\"lh-sec-lede\">This block is generated to mirror <strong>CompTIA Security+ (SY0-701)</strong> study depth: definitions, exam psychology, and workplace application. It supplements the short curriculum bullets above—read both. Lesson <code>lh-sec-l5-25</code> · Level 1 — Foundations (CIA, risk language, safe computing). Sections below rotate per lesson so adjacent topics do not repeat the same blurbs.</p>\n\n<h3>Where this sits in the Security+ landscape</h3>\n<p>Advanced IR/intel questions still punish <strong>evidence destruction</strong> and <strong>unscoped testing</strong>—professional ethics are in scope.</p>\n\n<h3>How this lesson shows up on the exam</h3>\n<p>Security+ rewards <strong>vocabulary precision</strong> and <strong>scenario judgment</strong>. For Level 5 topics, expect paired questions that test whether you know the <em>definition</em>, the <em>correct control family</em>, and the <em>failure mode</em> when misapplied. Use the key terms below as a checklist: if you cannot explain a term in under 20 seconds, revisit the concept.</p>\n<ul><li>If the stem lists <strong>symptoms</strong> (latency, resets, odd DNS), separate network faults from malicious activity before choosing “block country X.”</li><li>If data crosses borders, answers may touch <strong>data residency</strong> and lawful access regimes—pick the legally grounded option.</li><li>If a stem mentions <strong>compliance</strong>, choose answers that show <strong>policy + technical evidence</strong> (audit logs, access reviews), not performative paperwork alone.</li><li>If the scenario is <strong>after hours</strong> admin login, think break-glass procedures, alerting, and dual approval—not “always allow.”</li><li>When controls overlap (WAF + secure coding, EDR + backups), choose the option that addresses the <strong>root cause</strong> first, then layering as secondary.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Key terms (memorize and be able to contrast)</h3>\n<dl class=\"lh-sec-dl\"><dt><strong>Symmetric encryption</strong></dt><dd>Same key encrypts and decrypts—fast for bulk data (AES-GCM); key distribution is the hard problem.</dd><dt><strong>Container security</strong></dt><dd>Image provenance, non-root users, read-only roots, seccomp/AppArmor, and admission control for risky capabilities.</dd><dt><strong>OCSP stapling (concept)</strong></dt><dd>Server sends fresh revocation info with handshake—reduces client privacy leaks and lookup failures.</dd><dt><strong>UEBA</strong></dt><dd>User and entity behavior analytics—baseline deviations; tune to avoid HR/privacy backlash.</dd><dt><strong>Privacy</strong></dt><dd>Protection of personal information and individual rights—overlaps with security but adds legal/regulatory obligations (GDPR-style).</dd><dt><strong>Input validation vs output encoding</strong></dt><dd>Validation rejects bad input early; encoding neutralizes dangerous characters in the right output context—both are needed across HTML, SQL, OS, and LDAP channels.</dd><dt><strong>Data retention</strong></dt><dd>Shorter retention reduces exposure and cost—legal holds override routine deletion when investigations require preservation.</dd><dt><strong>IV / nonce</strong></dt><dd>Initialization vector or number-used-once—must be unique per encryption under a key for many modes.</dd><dt><strong>CSRF</strong></dt><dd>Cross-site request forgery rides ambient auth—anti-CSRF tokens, SameSite cookies, and re-auth for sensitive actions help.</dd><dt><strong>Session management</strong></dt><dd>Server-side session IDs or tokens must rotate on privilege change, bind to channel, and expire predictably.</dd><dt><strong>Secure SDLC</strong></dt><dd>Requirements, threat modeling, secure design, code review, SAST/DAST, dependency scanning, and hardened deployment pipelines.</dd><dt><strong>Threat modeling (STRIDE)</strong></dt><dd>Spoofing, tampering, repudiation, information disclosure, denial of service, elevation of privilege—drive controls early.</dd><dt><strong>WAF vs IPS</strong></dt><dd>WAF focuses on application-layer attacks; IPS often line-rate network signatures—overlap exists but priorities differ.</dd><dt><strong>Asset</strong></dt><dd>Anything of value to the organization—data, systems, people, reputation, or services—that security controls protect.</dd></dl>\n\n<h3>Quick contrast table (recall drill)</h3>\n<div class=\"lh-sec-table-wrap\"><table class=\"lh-sec-recall\"><thead><tr><th>Control flavor</th><th>When exam writers pick it</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Preventive</strong></td><td>Stops incident before success—least privilege, secure defaults, MFA.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Detective</strong></td><td>Finds badness—SIEM rules, EDR alerts, integrity monitoring.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Corrective</strong></td><td>Fixes after detection—quarantine, reimage, rollback.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Deterrent</strong></td><td>Raises attacker cost—monitoring banners, legal warnings (not magic alone).</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Compensating</strong></td><td>Alternative when primary control infeasible—documented equivalence required.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Authorization</strong></td><td>Server-side object checks—headers and TLS do not replace this.</td></tr></tbody></table></div>\n\n<h3>Fact pack (high-signal trivia)</h3>\n<p>Short statements you can verify in official courseware—use them to catch “sounds right” distractors.</p>\n<ul><li>SLSA levels describe increasing supply-chain assurance—useful vocabulary in modern governance questions.</li><li>Server-side template injection is distinct from XSS—context and sinks differ.</li><li>Sigma rules are vendor-agnostic detection snippets—tuning required per log source fields.</li><li>UDP-based protocols can be abused for amplification DDoS—patch open resolvers and monitor volumetric baselines.</li><li>Cloud IAM policy wildcards are a frequent blast-radius multiplier—explicit ARNs beat star patterns.</li><li>Chain of custody forms tie who touched evidence to times and hashes—do not skip signatures on transfers.</li><li>OAuth access tokens are not a replacement for server-side authorization checks on every sensitive action.</li><li>Terraform state can hold secrets—remote secure backend and scanning are baseline hygiene.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Wrong vs right mental models</h3>\n<ul><li>Wrong: “We have logs, so we are secure.” → Right: Logs without <strong>tuning, retention, and review</strong> are decoration.</li><li>Wrong: “Share admin passwords in the vault ‘for emergencies.’” → Right: Break-glass accounts with logging, rotation, and dual control after use.</li><li>Wrong: “WAF replaces secure coding.” → Right: WAF buys time; <strong>root-cause fixes</strong> remove vulnerability classes.</li><li>Wrong: “SIEM bought = SOC mature.” → Right: Content engineering, runbooks, and staffing determine outcomes—not SKU count.</li><li>Wrong: “Block all ICMP for security.” → Right: ICMP is needed for path MTU discovery; filter thoughtfully, not blanket ban by myth.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Standards &amp; frameworks (one-liners)</h3>\n<ul><li>NIST SP 800-53: control catalog often mapped for federal and regulated industries—think “what control family applies?”</li><li>FedRAMP: standardized cloud security assessment for US government—continuous monitoring is a theme.</li><li>CIS benchmarks: hardened configuration guidance—know they exist for OS, cloud, and mobile stacks.</li><li>NIST IR 800-61 lineage informs incident handling structure—align your answers to prepare/detect/contain themes.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Interview-style prompts (say aloud)</h3>\n<ul><li>What is the role of <strong>change management</strong> during an active incident—when do you still need CAB vs emergency change?</li><li>How does <strong>shared responsibility</strong> change your logging strategy in IaaS vs PaaS vs SaaS?</li><li>Explain the difference between <strong>risk</strong>, <strong>threat</strong>, and <strong>vulnerability</strong> with one workplace example each.</li><li>Walk through how TLS provides both <strong>confidentiality</strong> and <strong>integrity</strong> for a browser session—where does authentication of the server happen?</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Deep explanation (read slowly)</h3>\n<p><strong>Depth 1 — lens on <em>L5-25: ML supply chain and model / prompt abuse</em>:</strong> Sanitization vs wiping vs destruction: exams like knowing which media needs <strong>degaussing, shredding, or crypto erase</strong> per policy.</p><p><strong>Depth 2 — lens on <em>L5-25: ML supply chain and model / prompt abuse</em>:</strong> Mainframe and legacy integration appears as “we cannot patch.” The Security+ answer is usually <strong>compensating controls</strong>, isolation, monitoring, and a documented risk acceptance—not “ignore CVEs.”</p><p><strong>Depth 3 — lens on <em>L5-25: ML supply chain and model / prompt abuse</em>:</strong> Virtualization risks include <strong>snapshot sprawl</strong> containing secrets and stale VM images drifting from hardened baselines.</p><p><strong>Depth 4 — lens on <em>L5-25: ML supply chain and model / prompt abuse</em>:</strong> Engineers often optimize for speed; attackers optimize for <strong>cheap reuse</strong> of stolen creds and known exploits. The winning answer bridges both: ship fast with guardrails—feature flags, staged rollouts, and automated security checks in CI.</p><p><strong>Depth 5 — lens on <em>L5-25: ML supply chain and model / prompt abuse</em>:</strong> Honeypots can generate high-signal alerts but carry <strong>legal and operational</strong> risk if touched by real users; scope carefully.</p><p><strong>Depth 6 — lens on <em>L5-25: ML supply chain and model / prompt abuse</em>:</strong> Business continuity answers should reference <strong>RTO/RPO</strong>, <strong>workarounds</strong>, and <strong>tested restores</strong>; DR without practiced failover is wishful thinking, and exam writers know it.</p><p><strong>Depth 7 — lens on <em>L5-25: ML supply chain and model / prompt abuse</em>:</strong> LDAP vs Active Directory questions test directory concepts at a high level—binding, searches, and secure transport (LDAPS) appear often.</p><p><strong>Depth 8 — lens on <em>L5-25: ML supply chain and model / prompt abuse</em>:</strong> Physical security is still on the exam: tailgating, visitor escorts, locks, destruction of media, and environmental controls (fire, HVAC) as availability/confidentiality supports.</p><p><strong>Depth 9 — lens on <em>L5-25: ML supply chain and model / prompt abuse</em>:</strong> CSP reporting helps tune policy but can leak URLs—<strong>privacy review</strong> of report endpoints matters in regulated environments.</p><p><strong>Depth 10 — lens on <em>L5-25: ML supply chain and model / prompt abuse</em>:</strong> Logging questions often test whether you understand <strong>what to log</strong> (who, what, when, where, outcome), <strong>time sync</strong> for correlation, and <strong>tamper resistance</strong> for evidentiary value—not whether you can collect infinite bytes.</p>\n\n<h3>Controls &amp; engineering habits</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Prevent:</strong> least privilege, secure defaults, hardened baselines, input validation, architecture that shrinks trust zones.</li>\n<li><strong>Detect:</strong> authoritative logging, correlation, integrity monitoring, tuned detections that reduce alert fatigue.</li>\n<li><strong>Respond:</strong> playbooks with legal/HR hooks, containment preserving evidence, comms that avoid tipping attackers.</li>\n<li><strong>Recover:</strong> tested restores, disaster runbooks, post-incident metrics that change systems—not blame individuals alone.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Common exam traps</h3>\n<ul><li>Picking “encrypt everything with AES” when the problem is <strong>broken access control</strong> on the API.</li><li>Treating CVSS as business impact score rather than technical severity snapshot.</li><li>Choosing “disable logging” or “delete evidence” in any IR scenario stem.</li><li>Believing VPNs grant anonymity by default or replace MFA.</li><li>Thinking <strong>snapshots alone</strong> satisfy backup requirements without restore testing.</li><li>Choosing <strong>anonymous FTP</strong> for “convenience” in any business context stem.</li></ul>\n\n<h3>Scenario practice</h3>\n<p><strong>Workplace scenario:</strong> A cloud bill spike correlates with traffic about “L5-25: ML supply chain and model / prompt abuse”. Differentiate <strong>misconfiguration</strong> vs <strong>abuse</strong> in your first triage questions and what logs prove each hypothesis.</p><p><strong>Follow-up drill:</strong> List <strong>four log fields</strong> you need minimum to reconstruct a timeline; explain what each field disambiguates.</p>\n\n<p class=\"msg info\"><strong>Lab ethics:</strong> Treat every command as if it were under a written Rules of Engagement. No probing of systems you do not own or lack authorization to test.</p>\n</section></div>"};
  window.LEARN_HUB_SECURITY_MD = window.LEARN_HUB_SECURITY_MD || {};
  for (var k in C) {
    if (Object.prototype.hasOwnProperty.call(C, k)) window.LEARN_HUB_SECURITY_MD[k] = C[k];
  }
})();
